<HEADLINE>
ARCHER SPREADING WORD ABOUT GRAND PRIX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever the spectator turnout for the inaugural Grand Prix of
Texas at Texas Motor Speedway this weekend, Bobby Archer is
confident it will either meet or exceed the fan-count compiled at
Lowe's Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 20 people at Charlotte. Maybe 25,'' said Archer,
referring to a similar American Le Mans Series-headlined program
staged in April at TMS's sister superspeedway in Concord, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlotte sucked,'' said Archer, succinctly sizing up his
weekend in the heart of NASCARland. ``I mean, we were up at this
race in podunk Ste. Croix (Quebec) earlier this month, and it was
15,000 people. It was SRO. Everybody was complaining about racing
up there, and I said, `Hey, remember Charlotte.' This is going to
be a very good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Bobby Archer's opinion, as reigning Speedvision World
Challenge GT champion: This weekend is a huge opportunity to
properly reintroduce sports car racing to the Fort Worth-Dallas
market ... if enough potential customers know about it.
</P>
<P>
   TMS and its various venues already have exposed motorsports fans
to stock cars, Indy cars, pickup trucks, flat-track motorcycles,
Sprint Cars, Late Models ... and Legends Cars. Archer believes the
wide array of recognizable machinery at the track in far north Fort
Worth will draw from the area's sports car-driving enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Bobby Archer's opinion, and I'd like to think I have a
pretty good clue,'' said Archer, whose business, German Motor
Works, caters to various sports car-oriented clientele. Wednesday,
the shop on North Henderson Street also played host to the
inaugural Bobby Archer Motorsports Open House. It was Archer's
attempt to get the word out, and by midafternoon, Archer said
approximately 200 fans had braved the afternoon heat to check out
the displays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just mystified there isn't more promotion for this event,
because these people are in a different group,'' said Archer,
referring to both the sanctioning body and the racetrack staff.
``It's been my contention all along that even the IRL doesn't
attract these people. They like to do things as a group. I know of
guys who are selling tickets for the race out of their homes. I
don't see that in other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I'm going to maintain that this is a brand new market _
unblemished, untapped _ and they need to pursue it. I just haven't
seen it (promoted) at the grass roots level. And you couldn't hit a
more direct bull's-eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Five separate series will compete on the track's new combined
oval/road-course. The ALMS Prototype, Grand Touring Sport and Grand
Touring cars are the acknowledged attractions for Saturday night's
2-hour, 45-minute main event.
</P>
<P>
   From Archer's position, that leaves the BFGoodrich Trans-Am
Series, World Challenge, Women's Global GT Series and Star Mazda
Series to argue over who's best of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm racing in the SCCA World Challenge, sponsored by
Speedvision,'' said Archer, a transplanted Minnesotan living in
Keller. ``And SCCA is not promoting it because they feel
Speedvision should be. And Speedvision is saying, `We're paying our
money, SCCA should be promoting.' There's a standoff. Meanwhile,
they've got one of the fastest growing series ... with over 100
cars entered for the two (World Challenge) classes here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost as though everybody is trying to keep it under
wraps. And from my standpoint, it almost makes it impossible to
sell a sponsor.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer's No. 32 ViperSpeed Dodge Viper, and the team he
relocated from Detroit over the winter, will begin the weekend
trailing Peter Cunningham and his BMW M3 by 11 points (117-106)
halfway through the World Challenge schedule. Archer has secured a
one-race sponsorship deal for TMS from Jack Farr, his friend and
founder of the Motorsports Ranch in Cresson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bar has been raised in this series,'' said Archer, whose
car is owned by Ben and Sandy Madey of Ingleside, Ill., only
because Archer has been unable to raise enough money to purchase
the team outright. ``Trying to get sponsors to do it properly has
been tough. I really thought we could have attracted a (seasonlong)
local sponsor at some level. We got the Motorsports Ranch, but it's
just for this race, which makes it hard to show a return on
investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to make this come across as a negative, because
by my own admission, this series is not Formula One. But this is a
series that gets a lot of recognition and air time. It deserves
some acknowledgement. There's probably going to be more people in
the stands that will know me than will know the winner of the ALMS
race.''
</P>
<P>
   With the word starting to get out, that number hopefully will
meet or exceed 20 fans. Maybe 25. Easy.
MOTORPLEX ATTEMPTING TO ADD MULDOWNEY
</P>
<P>
   Three-time NHRA Top Fuel champion Shirley Muldowney is scheduled
to make a one-race return to the series during the 46th annual U.S.
Nationals this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The six-day event at Indianapolis Raceway Park is the longest,
oldest and most prestigious stop on the National Hot Rod
Association Winston Drag Racing Series Tour. But officials of the
Texas Motorplex in Ennis will touch down at IRP on Thursday with
the idea of convincing Muldowney to add the O'Reilly Fall Nationals
in October to her 2000 schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Muldowney, 60, last competed in an NHRA-sanctioned race in 1997
at the Motorplex. She qualified 19th, three spots away from the
16-car ladder, with a top quarter-mile elapsed time of 4.882
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Muldowney is scheduled to drive the Goosehead.com Dragster,
tuned by husband Rahn Tobler, when professional qualifying begins
Friday at IRP.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked to the marketing and promotions people at
Goosehead.com and our understanding is that she'll be here in the
fall,'' said Elon Werner, Motorplex general manager. ``Shirley
loves racing here. It's a perfect track for her, because her
husband can generate more horsepower with less money than anyone
out there. Coming to a track like the Motorplex, which is
all-concrete and can hold all that horsepower, it's a perfect
match.''
</P>
<P>
   Muldowney's appearance behind the wheel of the Action-backed Top
Fueler in 1997 was her lone NHRA drive of that season.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had only four qualifying sessions in the car, and nearly
made it,'' Werner said. ``Getting some time in Indy ... I'll be
shocked if she doesn't qualify there. And I think they'll build on
that coming into Ennis.''
</P>
<P>
   As announced on Tuesday, the Oct. 19-22 event at the Motorplex
is scheduled to play host to the anticipated debut of George and
Hank Steinbrenner's Yankee Racing Top Fuel team run by Darrell
Gwynn and driven by Mike Dunn. The addition of Muldowney would make
the weekend a blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a good relationship with Shirley going back to
1997,'' Werner said, ``and I'll definitely touch base with her at
Indy.''
</P>
<P>
   The first woman licensed to drive a Top Fuel car, Muldowney
claimed her first championship in 1977 and added titles in 1980 and
1982. Muldowney scored her last NHRA top-10 points finish, 10th, in
1990, but has remained active with numerous match-race appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Muldowney also has competed in the rival International Hot Rod
Association circuit in recent seasons, clocking a top speed of 319
mph and elapsed time of 4.741 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Among her 18 career national event victories _ most by a woman
driver in NHRA history _ was the 1982 U.S. Nationals final over
Connie Kalitta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really looking forward to racing at Indy,'' said
Muldowney, a resident of Armada, Mich. ``There's no other place
like the NHRA U.S. Nationals, and I'm proud to have been the only
woman to have ever won a professional title there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rahn and I would like nothing better than to have an impact on
this year's points race. I think we can do that with a good showing
at Indy.''
</P>
<P>
   PIT STOPS MENARD STICKS WITH RAY
</P>
<P>
   Team-owner John Menard says Texan Greg Ray will return as his
Indy Racing Northern Light Series driver in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Menard squelched two rumors at Kentucky Speedway last weekend
during The Belterra Resort Indy 300: that he was moving to another
series, and that Ray _ the 1999 Indy Racing League champion _ was
jumping to NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, we're going to have an (Indy Racing League) team,''
said Menard, a charter member of Tony George's all-oval open-wheel
series. ``Greg now is in the second year of a five-year contract.
We'll keep on going with a one-car team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Greg would be a success in any series he'd run, but as
it stands now, he's given every indication of fulfilling the
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about Ray's future with Menard heightened after team
manager and confidant Thomas Knapp unexpectedly left the team in
August, shortly after Ray scored his only victory of the season at
Atlanta Motor Speedway. Ray is 11th in points with only the
season-ending Excite 500 at Texas Motor Speedway on Oct. 15
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Davis has replaced Knapp as team manager on Menard's No. 1
Conseco Dallara/Oldsmobile. TRUCK RACE GETS LONGER
</P>
<P>
   Looking to provide a better show and more ticket value, NASCAR
and Texas Motor Speedway officials have agreed to lengthen the
Craftsman Truck Series race on Oct. 13 by 100 kilometers to 400K.
</P>
<P>
   The O'Reilly 300K has been redubbed the O'Reilly 400K, which
figures out to an increase of 42 laps/62 miles (to 167 laps/248
miles) around the 1.5-mile quadoval. The fall race now is the same
distance of the June night event won by current points-leader Greg
Biffle.
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying for the O'Reilly 400K is scheduled Oct. 12 at 5:30
p.m., with the race the next day at 7 p.m. ATLANTA RETURNS TO IRL
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Motor Speedway will return to the Indy Racing Northern
Light Series in 2001 with a new date.
</P>
<P>
   The open-wheel series is scheduled to compete on the 1.5-mile
AMS trioval for the fourth time on Saturday night, April 28. The
series most recently competed at AMS under the lights on July 15.
In its new slot, the Atlanta race becomes the lead-in event to the
Indianapolis 500 on May 27.
</P>
<P>
   After competing with only nine events in 2000, IRL teams face a
13-race schedule in 2001. Included are stops at Texas Motor
Speedway on June 9, the first race after the Indy 500, and the
season-ender on Sept. 30. LAST LAPS
</P>
<P>
   _ CART's Team Kool Green has signed Paul Tracy to a contract
extension through the 2005 FedEx Championship Series season. In
addition, teammate Dario Franchitti, who tested with Jaguar's
Formula One team this summer, has decided to return to Barry
Green's lineup for the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rookie Jamie McMurray has scored two poles and three top-10
finishes in four starts for TKO Motorsports owner Mike Farris of
Fort Worth in the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
