<HEADLINE>
USC'S PALMER HEARS NEW FEEDBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the first time in his college career, Carson
Palmer is walking around the USC campus answering a tough question
instead of receiving an obligatory compliment.
</P>
<P>
   The usual ``good job'' has been replaced by ``What happened?''
as everyone analyzes his performance against Penn State on Sunday,
when he completed 10 of 20 passes for 87 yards with an
interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wonders what the deal was,'' Palmer said. ``It's
different. It's the first time I've felt that. I just tell them the
same thing I tell you guys. I didn't have a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer is still his unflappable self, relaxed and positive as he
prepares for USC's Sept. 9 game against Colorado. But he isn't
about to concede that fans should expect less of him as he regains
his sharpness following a year off with a broken collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still want people to expect a lot from me,'' Palmer said.
``I know I've got that game out of my system and I'll be ready to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he watched films of the Penn State game, Palmer hasn't
discovered any magical answers for his subpar opening effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt I wasn't in a rhythm with my footwork and I was a
little rusty,'' he said. ``The only way I'll get out of the rust
stage is more and more practice. Hopefully, it was a first-game
thing. I wish we did have another game this week. I can't wait.''
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett said Palmer's play might have been
attributed to playing against a defense other than the Trojans,
which is going out of its way to avoid hitting him hard in
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot different,'' Hackett said. ``But he has to get
playing. We're going to find out a lot about the guy. He's going to
grow and get better.''
</P>
<P>
   McGuire to play: Freshman offensive lineman Joe McGuire was used
in goal-line formations against Penn State, which would seem a
minor role to use up his redshirt year. However, Hackett said he
fully intends to play McGuire this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect him to play,'' Hackett said. ``If we redshirt him, it
would be a medical issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Which might not seem so far-fetched. McGuire missed Wednesday's
practice with a back injury suffered during an all-star game this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Plays of the game: Wide receiver Marcell Allmond made two of the
biggest plays of the game, but neither involved catching passes. He
recovered Mike McGillivray's blocked punt in the end zone, which
allowed Penn State to score a safety instead of a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ball just came to me, I didn't know what to do,'' Allmond
said. ``I thought about running with it, but then I knew it would
be better to take a safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Allmond also recovered Sultan McCullough's fumble at the USC
23-yard line in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just there at the right time. I saw the ball pop out and
went for it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Number change: Snapper Joe Boscovich of Westlake High has
changed from jersey No. 91 to 57. It means USC no longer has two
Westlake players wearing 91. Defensive tackle Bobby DeMars also
wears the number.
</P>
</TEXT>
