<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M COUNTING ON ATTITUDE ADJUSTMENT
</HEADLINE>
 12-REPORT-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Listen closely to coaches and players
and you get a sense that the puzzle pieces are finally fitting into
place for a Texas A&AMP;M offense in transition.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Farris, we're told, is The Man. He'll get first shot at
ending the Aggies' three-quarterback carousel in the season opener
at Notre Dame on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Robert Ferguson, from all indications, is The
Truth. The junior-college transfer, in the estimation of
overmatched defensive backs, is the game-breaker A&AMP;M has lacked
since Albert Connell took his pass-catching act to the NFL after
the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   But this offense is going nowhere without The Attitude
Adjustment. That's where fullback Ja'Mar Toombs enters the picture.
</P>
<P>
   The 275-pound fullback provided one of the few sparks in a
dismal ground game last season, leading the Aggies in rushing with
583 yards. It marked the lowest season total by A&AMP;M's top
ground-gainer since 1983, when Roger Vick netted 425 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Toombs' reward for setting the pace has been an increased role
as a blocker for unproven tailbacks Richard Whitaker and Joe Weber.
This might raise eyebrows among those who watched Toombs' matador
blocking skills result in the beating former A&AMP;M quarterback Randy
McCown took in last year's 24-0 loss to Penn State in the Alamo
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then. This is now. Toombs, after some
heart-to-heart talks with coaches during the off-season about
personal responsibility, sounds committed to his new role. The
junior expressed gratitude that, after two arrests since the
conclusion of his freshman season (one for marijuana possession,
one for driving while intoxicated), he still has a spot on the A&AMP;M
roster.
</P>
<P>
   Two years into a college career clearly at a crossroads, Toombs
finally shows signs of being a leader on an offense in dire need of
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of the old guys now,'' Toombs said. ``It's time for me
to take hold of the reins and do all the things the coaches
expected of me. To do the things they recruited me to do. Most guys
in college don't develop until their junior year. Now that I'm a
junior, it's time for me to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   After missing spring workouts because of a hamstring injury,
Toombs' recent actions have matched his determined words. Coach
R.C. Slocum said he has never seen Toombs work harder, or practice
with more intensity, than during fall drills.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining that focus will be crucial because Toombs, as a
blocker, will be integral in creating holes for A&AMP;M tailbacks and
providing Farris enough time to find receivers. If Toombs flops in
his new role, the A&AMP;M offense flops along with him. If Toombs'
selfless attitude proves genuine and rubs off on teammates, it will
raise the performance level of those around him.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum acknowledged that the stakes are high, adding that he is
betting on Toombs' turnaround to withstand the test of time. Toombs
said he does not plan to disappoint. The ``Big Rumble'' vows not to
grumble about a lack of carries. Instead, he is planning on
pounding linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've listened to a lot of criticism, most of it deserved,''
Toombs said. ``Every day, I keep thinking to myself, `I've got to
become a better blocker.' I'm not the best at it yet. But I know
what I'm supposed to be doing now. I'm working at it. I know my
role and my role has changed a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   From all indications, so has his attitude.
</P>
<P>
   That could be A&AMP;M's most significant change of the 2000 season.
LITTLE-KNOWN RECEIVER A KEY TO TEXAS OFFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Without question, the most glaring question marks on the Texas
depth chart involve the wide-receiver positions, where five
freshmen could earn playing time this season. Four of the five
spent last season playing high school football but arrived with
glittering resumes: B.J. Johnson, Roy Williams, Sloan Thomas and
Tony Jeffery.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Wednesday night's final scrimmage, Johnson and
Williams had made the biggest impression among the newcomers. But
all have had their moments while working against the first-team
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Artie Ellis, a redshirt freshman who has two things
the others do not: a year of experience in the Texas system and a
projected spot in the starting lineup. Teammates identify him as
the forgotten commodity in a receiver corps that could be better
than last season despite the departures of Kwame Cavil (100
catches, 1,188 yards) and Ryan Nunez (56 catches, 600 yards), the
Big 12's busiest pass-catchers in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect a big year from Artie,'' free safety Greg Brown said.
``He's been so overlooked, people don't take him into
consideration. But he's a big guy with good hands who can give you
a lot of moves. I think he'll be a big factor in what our offense
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Major Applewhite said Ellis (6-foot-4, 205 pounds)
has the ideal body type to play the position and understands some
techniques that the newcomers have yet to grasp. He also bowled
over free safety Phillip Geiggar to complete a 20-yard,
catch-and-run during one scrimmage session, drawing one of the
loudest cheers of the night from Texas fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artie really positions himself well to the ball. He catches
the ball well and runs good routes,'' Applewhite said. ``The
biggest thing I've seen in Artie, from spring until two-a-days, is
that he's become a whole lot more consistent. That's what you need
out there is a consistent guy with Artie's body type who can
perform.'' IMMEDIATE IMPACT
</P>
<P>
   Three of 10 junior-college players who signed in February have
moved into the starting lineup at Kansas: defensive tackle Ervin
Holloman, defensive end De'Nard Whitfield and wide receiver Roger
Ross. Defensive ends John Culp and Demond Benford also have cracked
the two-deep list heading into the season opener at SMU on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   For the Jayhawks, the influx of defensive linemen has been
crucial. The team had no returning starters from 1999. Coach Terry
Allen said Holloman has especially been impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``His motor has been running full speed. I'm delighted with the
way he's stepped up,'' Allen said. ``We have some proven players
among the new guys up front. I think we'll be much better there.''
</P>
<P>
   The influx is strong enough, Allen said, that the Jayhawks plan
to use more 4-3 alignments, rather than their base 3-4, to get
additional linemen on the field. TEXAS TIES
</P>
<P>
   Opening the season against Texas A&AMP;M offers special incentive to
a pair of Notre Dame offensive linemen from the Lone Star State.
Jordan Black, the starter at left tackle, is from Rowlett. Mike
Gandy, the first-team right guard, is from Garland.
</P>
<P>
   Black, who played at Dallas Christian, said he is ``good
friends'' with A&AMP;M quarterback Vance Smith, a Fort Worth Christian
graduate. He has received ample input in recent weeks from other
buddies with A&AMP;M connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was home over the summer, a lot of people told me, `I
can't wait to see Texas A&AMP;M whip up on you guys,' '' Black said.
``My response? I said, `Well, we'll see about that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gandy said he is excited about the noon matchup Saturday in
South Bend, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from Texas, it's good to play against teams you've
followed,'' Gandy said. ``Against A&AMP;M, it will be like any other
game. If we play bad, we'll lose. If we play good, we'll have a
chance to win.'' SIZING UP THE HYPE
</P>
<P>
   Is bigger really better when it comes to correlating the size of
a team's media guide with its on-field performance? Or, can a
school remain thin and still win?
</P>
<P>
   These questions are asked in response to Texas' unveiling of a
536-page guide for the 2000 season, by far the biggest in the Big
12. As a means of comparison, Kansas State has won 11 games in
three consecutive seasons while hyped by guides less than half that
size.
</P>
<P>
   Below is a look at how former Southwest Conference teams have
fattened records and media guides (or failed to do so) since
joining the Big 12. Under each season is listed the size, in pages,
of the school's annual media guide with its corresponding record:
School 1996 1997 1998 1999 2000 Texas 412 (8-5) 444 (4-7) 446 (9-3)
492 (9-5) 536 (TBD) Texas A&AMP;M 292 (6-6) 292 (9-4) 300 (11-3) 336
(8-4) 348 (TBD) Baylor 304 (4-7) 168 (2-9) 208 (2-9) 204 (1-10) 240
(TBD) Texas Tech 144 (7-5) 184 (6-5) 196 (7-5) 200 (6-5) 272 (TBD)
BURCH'S PICKS
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Burch picks (against the line) this week's Big 12 games:
</P>
<P>
   Baylor at North Texas (plus 51/2). Pick: Baylor. Greg Cicero
reintroduces the passing game, and the win column, to Baylor fans.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M (plus 21/2) at Notre Dame. Pick: Notre Dame. Aggies
struggle to win in Lubbock, much less in the intimidating presence
of Touchdown Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas at SMU (plus 41/2). Pick: Kansas. Jayhawks finally have
an act worth taking on the road.
</P>
<P>
   UTEP (plus 26) at Oklahoma. Pick: Oklahoma. Sooners air out,
then blow out, the outmanned Miners.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado vs. Colorado State (plus 41/2). Pick: Colorado. The
Buffs can't lose to their in-state rivals in consecutive seasons
... can they?
</P>
<P>
   Ohio (plus 131/2) at Iowa State. Pick: Iowa State. A soft
schedule has the Cyclones primed for another 3-0 burst from the
gate.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Tech at Kansas State (271/2). Pick: Kansas State. A
taste of Manhattan should cure the Wildcats' struggling offense.
</P>
<P>
   Western Illinois at Missouri (no line). Pick: Missouri. Tigers
capitalize on their only iron-clad opportunity to win this season.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose State (plus 50) at Nebraska. Pick: Nebraska.
Cornhuskers justify their top-ranked status with a thunderous romp
to start the season.
</P>
<P>
   Utah State (plus 21) at Texas Tech. Pick: Tech. High-flying
offense struggled in its debut but the Tech defense still looks
salty.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's record: 1-1. Season record: 1-1. nn
</P>
