<SLUG> BC-OLY-VOLLEYBALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. VOLLEYBALL WOMEN GAINING ON COURT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A few months ago, getting to the medal round - let
alone leaving Sydney with a medal - was considered a difficult
proposition for the United States women's volleyball team.
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans' chances of at least getting out of pool play
seem much better after what has transpired on and off the court.
</P>
<P>
   Team USA's pool includes lightly regarded Kenya and Australia,
ranked 27th and 29th, respectively, in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. also made big strides at the recently concluded FIVB
Grand Prix in Asia by beating several higher-ranked teams,
including a five-game upset of China, the world's fourth-ranked
team.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-28, 25-20, 22-25, 25-18, 15-12 win snapped a 10-game
losing streak to the Chinese dating back to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a great feeling to beat China,'' Robyn Ah Mow said. ``We
have had some great matches with them, but we have never pulled out
a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. also defeated fifth-ranked South Korea in the
preliminary rounds. But a loss to the Koreans in a rematch later in
the tournament exposed a continuing problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have won if we had played consistently, but we were
unable to execute when it mattered,'' U.S. outside hitter Tara
Cross-Battle said after the Americans were swept by Korea. ``This
problem needs to be fixed before the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are coming off a disappointing 1996 Olympics, when
they were a heavy medal favorite. Instead, the veteran U.S. team
finished a disappointing seventh. Afterward, the entire team
retired or played professionally overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Former Texas women's coach Mick Haley was hired to rebuild the
program. Haley has since been hired by USC as its women's coach,
beginning after the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   With most of its players just a year or two out of college, the
U.S. has struggled most of the past four years. But the Americans
got a boost when veterans Danielle Scott, who played in `96) and
Cross-Battle, a `92 and `96 Olympian, returned.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, an All-American basketball and volleyball player at Long
Beach State, considered a chance to play in the WNBA but opted for
the national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many things that Danielle does for us,'' Haley
said. ``First of all, she gives us confidence. She really takes a
lot of pressure off the other players. Second, she's experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on board are promising young players such as Ah Mow,
Heather Brown and Logan Tom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think right now we're making great strides from when I
joined the team until now. We know we can play well. If we can get
better results in terms of wins, that will help us in the future
and give us more confidence,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the way the (rally) scoring system is, it's up for
grabs for anyone. The team who makes less errors and has the heart
is going to be the victor.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Australia and Kenya are in the way of the Americans being
one of the top four in their pool and reaching the medal round.
</P>
<P>
   Getting past a potential quarterfinal matchup with a Russia or
Cuba is a longshot for a team lacking Olympic seasoning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
