<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7007 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-BAYLOR-TEX     08-31 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIGGER, STRONGER BAYLOR TEAM AIMS TO ERASE BAD MEMORIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Baylor football coach Kevin Steele, the most dismal sound in
a 1-10 inaugural season last year was a phrase that crept into his
headset with alarming regularity:
</P>
<P>
   ``They got us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a sound Steele frequently heard ``before'' the snap when
the Baylor offense lined up to run a play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It meant we were running a dead play,'' he said. ``A situation
where the opponent was in the perfect defense to stop it, and we
had no ability to check off and run a different play. We knew it
wasn't going to work before the ball was snapped, but there was
nothing we could do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding this woeful scenario is one of the chief goals in the
team's preparation for Steele's second season, which begins
Thursday night when the Bears visit North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year is a new year ... that's the great thing about
athletics,'' Steele said, tossing out a quick reminder about how
the St. Louis Rams went from 4-12 to 13-3 a year ago. Anything can
happen, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, almost everything that could have happened to the
Bears did happen _ from the infamous fumble return on the final
play that cost them the Nevada-Las Vegas game to being outscored,
347-61, in Big 12 play. But Steele's mood is optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a different team,'' he said. ``Bigger, stronger,
faster, working harder and with a different attitude. I know that
people outside the program look at it and say, `Wow, they were
1-10, how can they get this thing right this year?' But they don't
see the changes from within.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we were in a situation so destitute that it would
have been daunting for Tom Osborne, or Joe Paterno, or anyone else.
If `Bear' Bryant could have returned from the grave, he would have
looked around and shaken his head. But we started after the season
in January with an intense physical conditioning program, and we
have a lot of very young kids _ especially in the offensive line _
who are a year older and wiser and a lot bigger and stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, for the first time in 11 years, the Baylor coaching
staff returns intact.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Steele said, this means no more dead plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we got into it last year,'' he said, ``we extremely
simplified the offense. It was not our original plan to do that,
but the situation here dictated it. We had a lot of people trying
to learn a new system and, in the offensive line for instance, they
were almost all underclassmen. We decided out of necessity not to
give them too much to try and learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when we encountered that situation in games where the
normal headset conversation is `what's he going to?,' we had
nowhere to go.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Bears not only have somewhere to go, there is an
exciting new quarterback _ Greg Cicero _ ready to take them there.
</P>
<P>
   A second-team junior college All-American from Palomar (Calif.)
College, Cicero was once running neck-and-neck with Major
Applewhite for the starting job at Texas before he injured a knee.
</P>
<P>
   Cicero, who played at Servite High School in Anaheim, Calif.,
transferred to Palomar College and last season threw for 2,880
yards and 33 touchdowns. He signed with Baylor last December and
won the quarterback job in spring drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no savior,'' he said, ``but I'm glad to be back in the Big
12, and I think I can help this team.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Steele, who noted that along with his physical skills,
Cicero is accustomed to directing the far more diversified attack
Baylor will use this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a coach on the field,'' Steele said. ``He sees
things and instantly changes the play and comes up with something
that will work. Most important, perhaps, he's a leader who inspires
confidence in those around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be much improved. I know that at some point, we have
to start winning ... not so that someone can keep their job but
because people can only go so long working in a down environment.
They need the energy of success to keep going.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have that energy. I don't know when, but it'll
happen.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 0016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
