<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTRE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNTESTED QB READY TO LEAD NOTRE DAME
</HEADLINE>
 DAME-QB-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NCAA placed the program on probation in December.
</P>
<P>
   The head coach's status beyond this season remains a hot topic
for discussion, and the program will open the season unranked in
The Associated Press Top 25 for the first time since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and the quarterback can't throw, either.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame's Arnaz Battle heard it all this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, they say a lot of things about this team,'' Battle says.
``I really don't listen to it too much because I know what I can
do. The coaches have confidence in me. The players have confidence
in me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never really doubted my abilities. I've been playing
football too long to doubt myself like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Battle makes his first career start Saturday when the Fighting
Irish play Texas A&AMP;M at Notre Dame Stadium. How the junior from
Shreveport, La., reacts to replacing Jarious Jackson could well
determine Notre Dame's season.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our schedule, there is no honeymoon period for the
quarterback,'' said coach Bob Davie, whose Irish play A&AMP;M,
Nebraska, Purdue, Michigan State and Stanford in their first five
games. ``He's thrown into the fire right off the bat, but Arnaz had
the opportunity to learn from Jarious and watch Jarious _ and
that's invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of playing that position is what you do when something
bad happens. Is he going to be able to jump in there and get the
offense back on track? It's still hard to say how good he will be,
but from a talent standpoint, he's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   No one questions Battle's athletic talent or his ability to beat
a defense senseless with his speed. Battle's 74-yard touchdown run
against Kansas in the 1999 season-opener stood as the Irish's
longest play from scrimmage last year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, can a quarterback who attempted only 15 passes in seven
games as a reserve a year ago operate efficiently in the passing
game?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to come down to how good can Arnaz throw the
football,'' Davie said. ``Not that he can't go out there right now
and throw the football, but when it's third-and-10, are they up
there bluffing blitz or are they blitzing? How well is he going to
throw the football then?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think back to Jarious two years ago out here against
Michigan. The first half was frightening. I didn't know if we would
ever complete a pass, but the second half got a little bit better.
Then, we got a little bit better and a little bit better. So, how
quick is he going to settle in being comfortable throwing the
football? But I like him. He brings a lot of explosiveness to that
position, and I think he's going to be exciting to watch. I really
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame returns seven starters on offense, so Davie doesn't
envision Battle being forced to carry the weight of the offense as
did Jackson, who last year established Irish single-season records
for completions (184), attempts (316) and passing yards (2,753).
</P>
<P>
   Yet, ``being the Notre Dame quarterback, all eyes are on you,''
Battle said.
</P>
<P>
   Irish offensive coordinator Kevin Rogers senses his
inexperienced signal caller could ``shock some people'' this
season, but ``Arnaz also has to learn that he is `the man,'''
Rogers said. ``Jarious understood and relished that role and, as a
result, was a tremendous leader. We have to develop Arnaz as a
leader. He can be a dynamic player, but he needs to be a confident
player.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 0024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
