<HEADLINE>
FIRST IMPRESSION SHAKY FOR KARL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Anaheim Angels manager Mike Scioscia displayed
one more of his attributes Wednesday night: a remarkably keen eye.
</P>
<P>
   Asked before Wednesday's game about his pitcher from the
previous night, left-hander Scott Karl, Scioscia replied, ``We saw
some positive things.''
</P>
<P>
   Really? In his first start for the Angels after coming to
Anaheim in a deal last week with Colorado, Karl lasted all of 2
innings, yielded nine hits and left trailing by four.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's someone who can be a high pitch-count guy,'' Scioscia
said of Karl, who was around for just 50 pitches in his Angels
debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the ability to change speeds better than he did
(Tuesday night).''
</P>
<P>
   Karl, who admitted afterward he was on the jittery side as well
as a little rusty, will make his next start Monday night in
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   More rehab for Belcher: Right-hander Tim Belcher will not be
activated Friday, the day clubs expand their rosters, but will
pitch that night in his second rehab assignment with Single-A Lake
Elsinore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we'll see,'' Scioscia said. ``He'll throw 100 or so
pitches, then we'll have to decide if he's better off going back
into the rotation or will be used out of the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, 38, had elbow surgery in December, came back to make
four starts, then strained the elbow again July 2 and has been on
the disabled list since.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Belcher finally is activated he'll quickly be
deactivated; he still must serve a three-game suspension for
arguing a balk call during a 2-1 loss at Seattle on June 27.
</P>
<P>
   No cigar - yet: After extensive research the Angels' public
relations department has discovered that Darin Erstad's 109-point
leap in average - from .253 last year to .362 entering Wednesday's
game - would be the third-greatest increase in baseball were the
season to end. Thus far, it's the largest in 82 years.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 is George Burns, who jumped from .226 in 1917 to .352 in
1918, an increase of 126 points. George Davis' 110-point leap -
from .241 in 1982 to .355 in 1983 - was the second greatest.
</P>
<P>
   What the P.R. staff couldn't pin down was Burns' choice of
cigar.
</P>
<P>
   More pitching help: The Angels claimed right-hander Ben Weber
off waivers from San Francisco and assigned him to Triple-A
Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Weber, 30, was 0-1 in nine relief appearances with the Giants
and was 4-8 with seven saves in 38 appearances, including three
starts, for Triple-A Fresno of the Pacific Coast League.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
