<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7027 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CHENEY-1STLD-WRITETHR     08-31 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY CONTENDS THAT CLINTON HAS HANDLED MILITARY POORLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS 10th, 11th grafs with Gore's reaction)  
(ART ADV: Photos 46, 47 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dick Cheney, the Republican vice presidential
candidate and former defense secretary, delivered a harsh
assessment Wednesday of the condition of the armed forces under
President Clinton, accusing him of ``running down'' a military that
has succeeded in recent conflicts only because of the military
buildup of past Republican administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said the American military was stretched over too many
foreign theaters and hampered by low morale, low pay, inadequate
training and unreliable weapons and equipment. He accused Clinton,
and by association Vice President Al Gore, of neglecting the
national defense to the point where military planners were no
longer certain that the United States could meet its stated goals
of being prepared to fight two medium-sized conflicts at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Decisions made today shape the forces of tomorrow,'' he told
an audience of several hundred veterans and political supporters in
a hotel ballroom here. ``That is why we were able to win the Gulf
War _ because we were commanding a military that had been rebuilt
in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that is why the current administration has been able to
conduct its vast deployments, from Baghdad to Belgrade. The ships
and planes were ready. The pilots and crewmen were prepared. The
missiles, the ammunition, the equipment and the men and women to
use them were all there. That is the military they inherited. The
question today is what future presidents will inherit.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense analysts acknowledged several of Cheney's arguments, but
cautioned that he exaggerated some of the criticisms and ignored
positive trends in the military under the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot valid points in the speech _ things aren't
quite as good as they were under Cheney,'' said Michael O'Hanlon, a
defense policy specialist at the Brookings Institution in
Washington. ``But he greatly overstates the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's appearance, which was scheduled only in recent days,
seemed to signal a shift in tactics in the Bush campaign. Cheney's
aides had said he would spend the week talking about education. But
after more than a week in which the Bush campaign found itself
defending its policies on tax and health care, Cheney returned to
more familiar Republican ground with an appeal on national
security.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Cheney also seemed to be trying to play the role
that Republicans had hoped he would take in the campaign _ lending
his age, experience and authority as a former defense secretary to
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the Republican presidential nominee.
Indeed, Cheney not only framed his remarks as the words of the
defense secretary who helped defeat Iraq, but portrayed himself as
a man who had returned to public life in large part because of his
desire to repair the damage he said had been done to the military.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney offered few concrete proposals in his speech Wednesday.
But in the past the Bush campaign has called for a $20 billion
increase in the military budget for research and development from
2002 through 2006, for directing the Defense Department to spend a
fifth of its procurement budget on new technologies and for
increasing the recently enacted pay raise for members of the armed
services by $1 billion more a year.
</P>
<P>
   Gore responded Wednesday night to Cheney's criticisms. ``We have
the strongest military in the world by far, and we reversed the
decline that began in the Bush-Quayle years,'' Gore told reporters.
``And I have advocated additional steps to continue the rebuilding
and strengthen- ing to make sure it's always the best and always
more than adequate.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign has said that the vice president advocates a
10-year, $127 billion in- crease in spending on military salaries,
training and modernization, and that amount may in- crease when
Gore adjusts his budget propos- als to reflect a growing surplus. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Cheney also sought to counter the Democratic
response to the criticism directed by Bush at President Clinton's
military policies. Since those attacks began in recent weeks, Gore
and his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, accused
Bush and Cheney of denigrating the American military, which they
said sent a bad signal to allies and potential adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``To point out that our military has been overextended, taken
for granted, and neglected _ that is no criticism of the
military,'' Cheney said Wednesday. ``That is a criticism of a
president and a vice president, and the record they have built
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said that Gore had expressed concerns that criticism
about the military would send the wrong message to potential
adversaries, and he used it to make another dig at the Clinton
administration. ``If our potential adversaries have received any
`wrong messages' recently,'' he said, ``it was not from the
newspapers, but from the nuclear lab at Los Alamos. And what lesson
do they draw from the fact that this administration has failed to
safeguard our nation's most vital national secrets?''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney attributed the Clinton administration's recent military
successes, like the NATO bombing that led to the withdrawal of of
Serb forces from Kosovo and the air strikes on Iraq, to the
military build-up under Presidents Ronald Reagan and George Bush.
And he said that the Republicans in Congress deserved the credit
for recent increases in the defense budget.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While many of the examples Cheney cited echoed his past remarks
_ that fewer units are ready for combat, recruitment is down, aging
equipment poses a danger and low pay is damaging morale _ he cast
his criticisms in a much more partisan light.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the record of eight years of stewardship over the
American armed forces by President Clinton and Vice President
Gore,'' he said. ``Eight years of neglect and misplaced priorities.
Eight years of multiplying missions and unclear goals. Eight years
during which the enemies of freedom have not been idle. Eight years
is a long time _ and eight years is long enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our military today is overused and under-resourced,'' he said.
``All this has brought on serious problems of readiness,
recruiting, retention and morale.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   O'Hanlon, the Brookings Institution analyst, criticized Cheney
for not proposing a specific alternative for overseas commitments
or enlarging the military. ``As much as Cheney says we've
overdeployed and overcut, there's been no proposal by the campaign
to reverse either of those policies,'' O'Hanlon said. ``The idea
they'll review U.S. commitments and find any big cutbacks is
illusory.''
</P>
<P>
   A former national security budget specialist under Clinton,
Gordon Adams, said many of the problems Cheney cited, including
substandard military housing, was prevalent during the Bush
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's selectively culled barnicles of the readiness issue, but
many are out of context,'' said Adams, who now directs the security
policy studies program at George Washington University. ``This is
not neglect, I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams also said the former defense secretary was not giving the
military enough credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When called upon, this force has performed spectacularly
well,'' Adams said. ``He fails to note the question of readiness
for what? To the rest of the world, the U.S. military isn't just
the toughest kid on the block, it's the toughest by far.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Gore campaign echoed the criticism. ``By
twisting facts about our military for partisan gain, Governor Bush
has demonstrated that he is not ready to be America's
commander-in-chief,'' said the spokesman, Douglas Hattaway. ``Our
military is the strongest, most capable, most ready fighting force
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials have countered Cheney's assertion that morale
is declining, citing improvements in the number of troops
re-enlisting, which they attribute to two years of increases in pay
and benefits. They have also pointed to improvements this year in
recruiting, although reserve recruiting has declined and there has
been a shortage in commissioned officers, with a drastic increase
in the number of captains leaving the Army.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cheney offered few concrete proposals to bolster the nation's
military in his speech although he did say that a Bush-Cheney
administration would spend more money researching new technologies
and deploying missile defenses, that it would raise pay for the
troops and improve their housing and schools.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore the importance of what aides billed as a major
policy speech, Cheney's aides encouraged reporters to interview
another Gulf War colleague of Cheney's _ Colin Powell, the retired
general who led the joint chiefs of staff. ``I share his view,''
Powell said in a telephone interview. ``We still have a great
force, and I don't think anybody would say we don't. But we owe
them everything they need to get the jobs done.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., released a statement in support
of the speech. ``Congress deserves a share of the blame for this
problem for annually treating the defense budget as just another
pork barrel,'' he said. ``But the lion's share of our failure
belongs rightfully to the man honored to serve as
commander-in-chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Cheney's most pointed dig at the opposition came when he
quoted an ``observer of the military'' in his speech. ``One
observer of the military,'' he said. ``had this to say last year:
`Our military faces readiness problems,' he cautioned, `including
falling recruitment, and retention in critical skill areas; aging
equipment that costs more to keep operating at acceptable levels of
reliability; a need for more support services for a force with a
high percentage of married personnel; and frequent deployments.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a fair summary of the problem,'' Cheney said, ``and it
came from Senator Joseph Lieberman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 0055EDT &QL; 
