r a BC-JOB-RATINGS-2Takes-LA     08-31 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOB-RATINGS-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK DETAILS BEST AND WORST OCCUPATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DANA BARTHOLOMEW and ORITH GOLDBERG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Fishermen risk going overboard and have little job
security. Cowboys don't get paid much and get hurt a lot.
Lumberjacks face high risks and bone-wearying work.
</P>
<P>
   They are among the worst jobs America has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   But financial planners, Web site managers and computer systems
analysts they have the best jobs of all, according to the new
``Jobs Rated Almanac,'' which lists the best _ and lousiest _ jobs
for Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Buckets of cash, time to spend it and being your own boss have
propelled financial planner from No. 17 last year to America's top
gig, author Les Krantz said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby boomers are thinking about retirement and they need
professional advice,'' said the 57-year-old Krantz, in his fifth
year of rating jobs. ``The stock market is booming, and we see the
need for good financial planning.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Ortiz, a 33-year-old financial planner from Glendale whose
wife is pregnant with their first child, was elated at the
promising rank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awesome, good to hear that,'' said Ortiz of American Express
Financial Services in Glendale. ``I do enjoy what I do; you're
helping people all the time, it's the most rewarding part of my
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I always wanted to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mining data from the U.S. Department of Labor, trade
organizations and telephone interviews, Krantz ranks 250 jobs
according to six criteria: income; stress; work environment; job
outlook; job security; and physical demands.
</P>
<P>
   The top ranked jobs, like last year, were in math or
computer-related fields. Web site managers, top dogs last year,
slipped to No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a glut of people in computer jobs,'' Krantz said in
explaining the drop. ``A few years ago, computer jobs were not in
abundance, but today, even a dope can do it. You just have to know
how to type.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the almanac's rankings seem predictable. Got a yen to
be president of the United States? Better figure the highest stress
(No. 250) and worst working environment (No. 250), according to
Krantz, a Wisconsin author and journalist. Of course, the $400,000
salary and benefits provide a balance in the best paying category.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs with the most tedium were also least stressful: medical
records technician, janitor and musical instrument repairer to name
a few. ``Clarinets don't give you much guff when you're fixing
them,'' Krantz said.
</P>
<P>
   The Krantz almanac advised would-be teachers (No. 119) and cops
(No. 200) that such callings offered low pay, high stress and
less-than-desirable working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Krantz's advice for career cubs or job changers: Above all, find
out what a person does at the job all day. It's not what you see on
TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see Perry Mason and Johnny Cochran and think, Boy, what
a great way to make a living. In actual fact, that's not what
lawyers do every day _ being a lawyer is very tedious, (often)
filing forms.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the job-crud five, ranked at the bottom because of
long hours and poor working conditions: fisherman, oil field
roustabout, lumberjack, cowboy and ironworker, according to Krantz.
</P>
<P>
   Fisherman, besides being one of the most dangerous, is one of
the worst jobs. ``You're in the boat all day getting seasick with a
lot of smelly fish; it's not fun. And a lot of waters are getting
fished out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be a cowboy when I grew up _ I still want to be
one,'' Krantz said. ``But even cowboys get the blues. You're
stepping in cow s--- all day, it's raining, you're out there
punching cows.''
</P>
<P>
   While not many people would opt for a job in the worst-ranked
working environment, that of the president of the United States,
those toiling in the fifth-worst-ranked working environment, taxi
drivers, said they didn't have many complaints about their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Valley Cab driver Steve Froehlich, 51, who works the 4 p.m. to 3
a.m. shift, said based on his experience, he totally disagrees with
the ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to love what I'm doing,'' he said. ``It gives me
freedom to do what I want. I have no boss ... basically we are on
our own out there.'' Froehlich did acknowledge, however, that there
are inherent dangers on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was robbed a number of years ago driving a cab in New
York,'' he said. ``I didn't drive again for a while, but I went
back to it.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to earning an income, waiters and waitresses
ranked the lowest, followed by dishwashers, bartenders, dressmakers
and cashiers.
</P>
<P>
   Damon Tovar, a 26-year-old waiter at the TGI Friday's in
suburban Woodland Hills, said he didn't think that waiting tables
should have been ranked as the lowest-income job with an average
wage of $14,058 per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe most people make a little more than that, especially
at this TGI Friday's,'' Tovar said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the low ranking could be attributed to the uncertainty
attached with the varying tips.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   ``You might go through a week when you're not making a lot of
money,'' he said. ``One week you can make $600 to $700 and the next
only $300,'' he said, adding that about 90percent of his income is
from tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on the restaurant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The job of president of the United States also ranked as the
most stressful, followed by firefighters, senior corporate
executives, race car drivers and surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County fire Capt. Mark Savage, who works out of
Station 73 in Newhall, said he was not surprised by the ranking
firefighters received.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stress is something we don't think about,'' Savage said.
``We accept that it may shorten our life expectancy with the
exposure to the stress and the hazards we encounter ... but we
wouldn't trade it for anything because we enjoy what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lists such as Krantz's generate excitement and cause people to
think, career planners say. But they sometimes fail to guide
prospects to meaningful careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't talk about what people's skills are,'' Adele
Scheele, director of the Career Center at California State
University, Northridge, said of the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most meaningful type of career is what uses your best
talents and consumes your interest,'' Scheele said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet people still work terrible jobs, Krantz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as we complain, I think people love and take pride in
their jobs,'' Krantz said. ``The American worker takes the most
pride in even the worst job. I would say working is alive and
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
