<HEADER>
A7039 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BURNING-MAN-SFCHRON &LR;      08-31 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURNING-MAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BURNING MAN ORGANIZERS WANT TO PUT BREAKS ON `SPECTATORS'  &HT;     By JAMES SULLIVAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At Burning Man, the annual art carnival in the
Black Rock Desert of Nevada, strange behaviors are not just
tolerated, they're encouraged. Voyeurism, however, is not one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the festival's organizers have made some subtle
changes to discourage the ``spectators,'' last-minute visitors who
show up simply to gawk and party. Their numbers have been
increasing in recent years, to the chagrin of the artists, event
planners and self-proclaimed freaks who claim Burning Man as their
own.
</P>
<P>
   For many in the San Francisco Bay Area, Burning Man, the
fantastical celebration now in its 15th year, has made the Labor
Day weekend's traditional last gasp of summer more like a howl. The
event runs through Monday, and the annual ceremonial bonfire of the
50-foot man takes place Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, walkup tickets were available during the entire run
of the festival. This year, for the first time since Burning Man
moved to the desert 11 years ago, there is a cutoff: midnight
Thursday. No tickets will be sold during the last four days of the
festival.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance at the festival, once an improvisational gathering of
a few dozen friends on the beach in San Francisco, has been rising
sharply in recent years, from 15,000 in 1998 to 24,000 last year.
This year 28,000 are expected.
</P>
<P>
   For 2000, Burning Man founder Larry Harvey and his team decided
it was time to tap the brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Variously described as New Age, a space-age Woodstock and a
bacchanal, Burning Man attracts artists, performers and
exhibitionists who relish the opportunity to create a temporary
community from scratch each year. People set up cafes, radio
stations and galleries; real money is useless, but bartering with
candy or toys is encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   Prices this year are up considerably, to $200 for advance
tickets and up to $250 for those bought on-site before the cutoff.
Officially, the higher prices are attributed to higher fees imposed
by the federal Bureau of Land Management, which regulates Burning
Man's use of the dried-mud playa at Black Rock, 100 miles northeast
of Reno.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to abolish last-minute walkup tickets ``was to
discourage last-minute decision making,'' said Marian Goodell,
Burning Man's ``mistress of communication.'' ``We implemented the
policy to try and reduce the `looky-loo' factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Also this year, the festival entrance has been moved about nine
miles farther from Gerlach, the tiny town of 250, which represents
the closest thing to civilization at the barren festival scene.
</P>
<P>
   Goodell said that the event still has room to grow, provided it
happens through ``slow growth.'' There are resource issues to
consider _ ``the number of Porta Potties there are within several
hundred miles of the site,'' for instance. ``There are
infrastructural limits, but we haven't hit them yet. We're sort of
in a yellow zone.''
</P>
<P>
   For devotees, the policy changes are minor impediments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd travel further,'' said East Bay musician Ben Leinbach, 33,
who was a first-timer last year and left last night for his second
Burning Man experience. The effort involved in making your own
personal Burning Man a success, he said, is ``taxing, but I
definitely think it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Leinbach said he was well aware before he attended the event
last year that creative participation _ a costume, an art
installation, a fortune-telling tent _ was considered mandatory at
Burning Man. He and his friend, guitarist Chris Shot, made a mobile
percussion rack, and they strolled around, serenading camp sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a few posses of _ what do we call them? _ `yahoos,' ''
he said. ``There were a couple groups of rowdy, drunk people who
didn't seem to be offering anything.''
</P>
<P>
   For many, planning for Burning Man is a year-round proposition,
but August is especially hectic. In recent weeks, campers have been
raiding Bay Area suppliers for their Burning Man equipment _
coolers, tent stakes, solar showers, face paint and endless gallons
of water. Those who want to make the trip in recreational vehicles
rent them months in advance. The value of a solid, no-frills
bicycle out on the vast playa has made it nearly impossible to find
a used bike in the Bay Area in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty much everything gets sold,'' said Tony DeLeon, a
mechanic at Pedal Revolution in the Mission District of San
Francisco, which salvages old bike parts. People going to the
desert, he said, ``don't care what it is _ clunkers, 3-speeds _ as
long as it rolls and has air in the tires.''
</P>
<P>
   Planning a contribution _ your installation or your rave tent _
often takes months, too. Dan Das Mann, a San Francisco artist who
founded Headless Point Studios on Hunters Point, taught 36 people
how to weld this spring so they could work on his project.
</P>
<P>
   They built three 20-foot-tall masks made from copper, grass and
driftwood designed to suggest what the stick-figure man's face
might look like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `What is the man's face to us? Is it love? Hate? Is it
you or me?' '' said Das Mann, who is trained as a landscape
architect. ``I wanted it to be a completely collaborative
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as everyone understands that spirit of cooperation,
Burning Man's Goodell said, the more the merrier. As a temporary
community created entirely by its inhabitants, Burning Man is an
experiment in utopia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally we would like to affect as many people as possible,''
said Goodell. ``Through a slow-growth process, this event could
probably be 40,000 or 50,000 people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
