<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7042 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-LAZAROFF-CASINO-KAN &LR;      08-31 1390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAZAROFF-CASINO-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI GAMING COMMISSION VOTES TO REVOKE CASINO LICENSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Missouri Gaming
Commission moved Wednesday to strip Station Casinos Inc. of its
licenses to operate in Missouri after its executives boycotted a
public hearing into the activities of a St. Louis lawyer who once
represented Station.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, Station executives challenged the commission's
investigative authority and refused to honor subpoenas to testify
at the Kansas City hearing on the activities of attorney Michael
Lazaroff. They made good on that threat Wednesday, prompting a
unanimous commission vote to revoke the company's licenses to
operate in the state.
</P>
<P>
   A Station attorney said the company would appeal the hastily
prepared order. That will trigger a public hearing later this year
and probable lawsuits that could take years to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Station operates Kansas City's biggest and most lucrative casino
and another complex in St. Charles, Mo. Combined, the company's
Missouri casinos generate $288.4 million a year in gambling
revenues alone and employ 3,500 people. The casinos would continue
to operate while legal matters are resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Proposed revocation of its Missouri licenses could trigger a
similar inquiry in Nevada, where Station operates five casinos.
</P>
<P>
   One of the possible scenarios could see the commission allowing
Station to sell its Missouri riverboats, pay a fine and voluntarily
surrender its licenses, similar to the commission's decision in the
aftermath of a scandal that forced Hilton Hotels Corp. to sell its
Flamingo Hilton Casino in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Station already has proposed a $475 million sale of its
Missouri operations to a group of five company executives. Two of
those executives were subpoenaed to appear.
</P>
<P>
   One, William W. Warner, Station's vice president for finance,
refused to appear, prompting commission staff members to say they
would begin steps to bar Warner from receiving a Missouri license.
The other, Station's Midwest counsel Troy A. Stremming, is expected
to testify when the hearing resumes today.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's hearing examined the $500,000 in bonuses Station
paid Lazaroff over two years.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Lazaroff pleaded guilty in federal court in
St. Louis to multiple felonies, including misappropriation of more
than $800,000 in law-firm funds. That included $500,000 from
Station that rightly belonged to the firm.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed to cooperate in the commission probe while awaiting
sentencing in exchange for leniency consideration in his expected
prison sentence of 27 to 33 months.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury in Kansas City also is examining Lazaroff's
affairs. FBI agents monitored Wednesday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Commission officials were aware of at least $100,000 of
Station's payments since 1996 and questioned Lazaroff about the
money at the time. But only recently have questions been raised
about whether that money was used to improperly influence any
public officials to approve Station's St. Charles and Kansas City
casinos in 1994 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaroff testified that was ``absolutely not'' true. He said he
kept the money and spent it all on himself and his family. Federal
prosecutors who examined Lazaroff's bank records earlier this year
made no allegations of bribery of any public official.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's testimony focused tightly on Lazaroff's relationship
with Robert L. Wolfson, the Gaming Commission's chairman from its
inception in 1993 until February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Following several hours of testimony by Lazaroff, Wolfson
acknowledged improper contacts with Lazaroff over the years.
Wolfson said he used Lazaroff to obtain tickets to Las Vegas shows
for clients and family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was bad judgment,'' Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaroff characterized their relationship as an illicit and
``tacit understanding'' that each would provide the other with
useful information. ``I think we used each other,'' Lazaroff said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson responded that he was ``appalled by distortions'' in
Lazaroff's testimony. Wolfson said he typically tried to discourage
Lazaroff from initiating private conversations about casino
regulatory matters; such conversations are barred by the
commission's ethics rules.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazaroff produced documents he faxed to Wolfson that he said
painted a picture of a quid pro quo and a continuing flow of
information between the two men.
</P>
<P>
   In one 1996 example, Lazaroff said Wolfson detailed his concerns
about Station's plans for financing construction of its $300
million Kansas City casino. Lazaroff reported those concerns to
Station, which then shaped its financing plans to satisfy Wolfson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no such recollection,'' Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson repeatedly testified under oath that ``I have no
independent recollection'' of any sensitive information he
allegedly disclosed to the casino lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Under commission rules, all improper contacts must be reported
by the commissioner involved and also by the regulated casino, if
it is aware of the contact.
</P>
<P>
   But Wolfson told the commission he never reported any of his
contacts with Lazaroff. Office and residential phone records made
public by the commission document more than 200 calls between the
two men over six years.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaroff said there were many more than that from other phones.
During particularly controversial periods his contact with Wolfson
was ``daily,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   State law has no disciplinary sanctions against commissioners or
former commissioners. But failure by Station to report improper
contacts could bring further disciplinary actions _ including a
separate license revocation order.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaroff testified that Station executives were sometimes in the
room or in his car when he spoke by telephone with Wolfson, and
that Station executives frequently asked him to clear company
issues with Wolfson before they were made public.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Warner, the other Station executives who received
subpoenas to testify at Wednesday's hearing were: Frank J. Fertitta
III, chairman and chief executive; Glenn C. Christenson, executive
vice president and chief financial officer; Scott Nielson,
executive vice president and general counsel; Richard Haskins,
associate general counsel; John Pasqualotto, vice president of
regulatory compliance; and Marnie Hinrichs, executive secretary to
Nielson.
</P>
<P>
   At midday press conferences next door to the commission hearing
room at the Westin Crown Center hotel, Station lawyer Charles
German deflected Lazaroff's testimony, calling him a convicted
felon and a liar who is trying to shorten his prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   German acknowledged, however, that Station executives were aware
of Lazaroff's contacts with Wolfson, but depended on them to follow
the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``People hire lawyers like Mike Lazaroff and his law firm, which
is very well regarded in this state, to keep them out of trouble,
not to get them into trouble,'' German said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaroff refused all interview requests.
</P>
<P>
   Station's troubles had little impact on Wall Street Wednesday,
where its publicly traded stock closed at $14.81, down 6 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaroff was one of the principal forces who lobbied for
Missouri riverboat gambling in the early 1990s, and he represented
many Missouri casino firms over the years.
</P>
<P>
   His first client was the President Casino on the Admiral in St.
Louis, whose owners in the late 1980s pressed for riverboat
gambling in Iowa, where Lazaroff first made his reputation as a
gaming-industry lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   President executives who testified Wednesday said Lazaroff never
suggested to them he had any extraordinary relationship with
Wolfson, and they said they never pressed him to seek such
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson was appointed by Gov. Mel Carnahan and shaped the
development of casino gambling in Missouri until resigning the post
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson established Feld Chevrolet in 1947 and is a co-founder
and former officer of the St. Louis Blues National Hockey League
franchise. He also has established several banks, including Parkway
Bank and Progress Bank, which are now part of the Mercantile Bank
group.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaroff and Wolfson testified that they first became close
while serving as board members at a St. Louis country club. ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 0129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
