A7043 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-EBAY-MILESTONE-SFCHRO     08-31 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-MILESTONE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EBAY TURNING 5 YEARS OLD AS TOP AUCTION SITE  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's not much of a stretch to say that EBay
changed Michael Krasow's life.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of Pacific Loan &AMP; Jewelry Co., a pawn shop on Sixth
Street in San Francisco, gave his business a jump start by selling
items to EBay users throughout the world instead of over the
counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sold a Palm Pilot this week to a fellow in Germany,'' Krasow
said. ``I sold a guitar to a lady in Connecticut. I don't put a lot
of stuff out front in my store anymore. Now I just keep it in the
back and sell it online.''
</P>
<P>
   His experience mirrors that of millions of people who have
helped San Jose's EBay evolve from an electronic clearinghouse for
Pez dispensers and Beanie Babies to an economic juggernaut, with
the value of annual merchandise sales topping $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   EBay turns 5 years old Monday _ an eternity in Internet time but
a remarkably short period for a single company to both create and
thoroughly dominate an entire industry.
</P>
<P>
   That growth has not been without pitfalls. EBay has seen more
than its share of oddities and hoaxes _ items for sale have
included body parts, babies and even a teenager's virginity _ and
not all sellers have upheld the highest standards of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the FBI reported that online auctions far and away
account for the highest number of complaints relating to fraud on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Yet EBay continues to grow, with its roughly 16 million
registered users listing more than 5 million items for sale. Each
day, users add an additional 600,000 items to the site. A thousand
bids are entered every second.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become a global trading platform accessed by millions
each year,'' said Meg Whitman, the company's chief executive.
``Anything you're interested in is there.''
</P>
<P>
   In Whitman's case, her interests, when not overseeing the
planet's largest swap meet, stray toward fly fishing. It goes
without saying that she picks up much of her gear at
you-know-where.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately I've been looking for a collapsible fly rod of a
certain length,'' Whitman said. ``I couldn't find it retail. But I
found it online.''
</P>
<P>
   EBay was founded by Pierre Omidyar on Labor Day in 1995 after
his then-girlfriend, a collector of Pez dispensers, had commented
one day about how it would be nifty if she and like-minded Pez
enthusiasts could hook up via the Net to share their passion.
</P>
<P>
   The bell that went off in Omidyar's head still resonates today.
An early Internet geek, he acted on his girlfriend's suggestion by
creating a sort of virtual flea market where Pez-heads could buy
and sell dispensers to round out their collections.
</P>
<P>
   The rest, as they say, is history. EBay _ as in ``electronic
bay,'' a tip of the hat to the company's Bay Area home _ quickly
expanded its scope to embrace all manner of collectibles. The bull
market for Beanie Babies that emerged around the same time helped
fuel the site's growth.
</P>
<P>
   Today, users really can find almost anything on the site.
Sellers are charged a small fee per listing and then pay EBay a
variable commission, ranging from about 1 percent to 5 percent,
depending on the final sale price.
</P>
<P>
   By functioning in a classic middleman mode, EBay has pulled off
that rarest of tricks _ it is an Internet company that actually
makes money. Last month, the company reported a 159 percent
increase in quarterly earnings to $13.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``EBay has evolved so much over the past five years, you could
argue they've entered the level of AOL or Yahoo,'' said Michael
Cibula, an analyst at Robertson Stephens in San Francisco. ``They
dominate in the U.S., and according to our estimates, they dominate
in almost every international market they're in.''
</P>
<P>
   Those markets will grow by year's end when a French version of
the site debuts, joining EBay outposts in Australia, Britain,
Canada, Germany and Japan. An Italian site is expected next year.
</P>
<P>
   Cibula said EBay has achieved an almost unstoppable ``critical
mass'' among users of online auctions. As the biggest service, he
said, EBay attracts a greater number of would-be buyers and
sellers, which in turn only reinforces its position as the biggest
online auction house.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Cibula noted that technical glitches last
year, which caused prolonged outages and forced EBay to overhaul
its operation, ultimately served to make the company stronger. The
same applies to its handling of high-profile hoaxes and fraud
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've gone through growing pains,'' Cibula said. ``That's a
huge advantage over competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that EBay is completely out of the woods. Along with being
the biggest kid in the playground, EBay continues to attract more
than its fair share of charlatans and pranksters.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the company halted bidding on an auction in which six
people were offering to sell their votes in November's presidential
election. The bidding went as high as $10,100.
</P>
<P>
   Past items for sale _ legitimate and otherwise _ included
kidneys and other organs, Ku Klux Klan memorabilia and a raft that
the seller claimed Elian Gonzalez rode on from Cuba to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Bidding on a mysterious painting attributed to artist Richard
Diebenkorn soared from 25 cents to $135,805 in May before the
auction was halted. The work has since been discredited by art
experts.
</P>
<P>
   It comes as no surprise, then, that the FBI's new Internet Fraud
Complaint Center has found that almost half of all complaints from
Net users concern online auctions. Nondelivery of goods ordered
online was a distant second.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as EBay's reach grows, its user base has become
increasingly sophisticated. Whereas the typical EBay user several
years ago might have been someone cleaning out the basement or
attic, nowadays the site is overshadowed by entrepreneurs who in
essence use EBay as a virtual storefront.
</P>
<P>
   EBay calls them ``power sellers'' _ wholesalers, inventory
liquidators and wannabe e-commerce moguls who now account for the
majority of items listed on the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Auctions are not just a garage sale for consumers,'' said
Munjal Shah, CEO of Andale Inc., a Mountain View firm specializing
in technology for online auctions. ``They are a new sales channel
for small and medium businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   After closely examining EBay's listings, Shah said he discovered
that a mere 10 percent of the site's sellers account for 80 percent
of its sales. And because they generate so much in listing fees and
commissions, these power sellers have become one of EBay's primary
revenue generators.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Birnbaum is a good case in point. His New Jersey
company, WearAmerica.com, purchases excess designer goods from
retailers at below-wholesale prices and then resells them at a tidy
mark-up. He hopes to see about $2 million in sales this year.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half that amount, however, will come from hawking items
on EBay, where Birnbaum estimates he makes up to $100,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can acquire customers at a very low cost,'' he said.
``That's definitely the key. Nobody else can drive traffic like
EBay.''
</P>
<P>
   As an investment, EBay has richly rewarded those who got in
early. Omidyar, the founder, is now worth more than $4 billion
(and, unlike many other techno-riche, has vowed to give away the
bulk of his fortune).
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock, which slipped 6 cents yesterday to close at
$61.06, now trades at more than 1,000 times earnings _ a staggering
multiple.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't for the faint-hearted,'' observed Jeetil Patel, an
analyst with Deutsche Bank Alex. Brown in San Francisco. ``But over
the long haul, EBay is probably a very sound investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors circulated earlier this year that EBay may be an
acquisition target for Santa Clara's Yahoo, which has struggled to
carve out a piece of the online-auction pie. ``That's still within
the realm of possibility,'' Patel said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, EBay has set its sights on further expansion,
building on acquisitions like auction house Butterfield &AMP;
Butterfield and fixed-price online marketplace Half.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could scroll forward five years, you'd see us in many
more geographies and with many more categories,'' CEO Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect the company to significantly alter the way it
does business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to stay focused on the person-to-person and
small-business-to-person marketplace,'' Whitman said. ``That's what
we do best and that's what we'll keep doing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; dlazarus(AT)sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
