<SLUG> BC-CAMCORDER-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SONY CAMCORDER SEES ALL, DOES ALL  &HT;     By BECKY WARING 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you have been coveting a digital camcorder
but have hesitated to spend the big bucks (typically starting at
about $1,500) for a high-quality model, here's a reason to take the
plunge: Sony's DCR-TRV720.
</P>
<P>
   The TRV720 is the hottest addition to Sony's top-selling Digital
8 line. This $1,199 powerhouse boasts features usually seen in
$2,500 cameras, and is quite simply the best digital video camera
under $1,200 available.
</P>
<P>
   DV camcorders offer several big advantages over traditional
analog models (which use VHSC, 8mm or Hi-8 tape), such as higher
image quality and the ability to transfer footage directly to a
computer for editing (via an IEEE 1394 cable, also known as
FireWire or i.LINK). Digital also means that you can copy tapes
with practically no image degradation; with analog, you get cloudy,
noisy tapes after just a couple generations.
</P>
<P>
   While most consumer DV camcorders use MiniDV tape, the Digital 8
line uses regular Hi-8 tape, recorded digitally. If you already
have a Hi-8 camcorder, you can play back your old tapes with a
Digital 8 model, and re-record them digitally, a great feature.
Hi-8 tapes are about 30 percent cheaper than MiniDV, and easier to
find. Hi-8 tape mechanisms are also less costly than MiniDV, which
means Digital 8 cameras are less expensive too, starting at about
$799.
</P>
<P>
   So what's so great about the TRV720? In terms of size, it's a
handheld model, about 2.5 pounds. Perfectly portable, although not
palm size. A palm-size model would not be able to accommodate the
features this camera has, starting with a phenomenal 25X optical/
450X digital zoom lens, a big 4-inch LCD screen and an optional
13-hour battery.
</P>
<P>
   That zoom lens captures distant action, such as sports events
and concerts, as well as vacation shots of scenery and landmarks.
The TRV720 can shoot still images, too, and with such a long
optical zoom, it can beat many digital still cameras at their own
game. While still pictures from the camcorder are only 640x480,
most digital still cameras are limited to about 10X optical zoom,
so even at megapixel resolutions (1280x1024), they can't match a
close-up from the TRV720.
</P>
<P>
   The Sony also comes with a Memory Stick slot for storing stills.
I would prefer to see a more ubiquitous Compact Flash or SmartMedia
slot, but luckily a serial cable is provided for downloading, so
you don't have to buy yet another adapter to get the images into
the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's PictureGear software for the PC is bundled for
transferring images. There is no Mac version. Mac users can work
around the situation by copying Memory Stick images to tape, but
this is a hassle.
</P>
<P>
   The big LCD screen swivels, so it can be used to frame shots
above the head and below the waist easily, great for crowds and
kids. However, the TRV720 also boasts a flip-up color viewfinder
(most low-cost video cameras have monochrome viewfinders), so you
can have it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, amateur videographers will benefit greatly from
SteadyShot image stabilization, which eliminates handheld camera
shake. If you're going to shoot for a long time, a tripod is still
best, but the camera is light and easy to hold. Another cool
feature is the Super NightShot mode, which brightens images about
16X, and can even take footage in pitch-dark conditions by using
infrared light.
</P>
<P>
   Controls are placed well, with three operating modes: camera,
memory and VTR. The camera mode is for shooting video, memory is
for shooting stills onto the Memory Stick card and VTR is for
playback. A strap wrapped around the back of the hand lets you hold
the camera securely and shoot one-handed with the start/stop
button. VTR control buttons (Fast Forward/Rewind/Pause etc.) are
along the top of the camera, again for single-handed operation.
There's also a remote control that works in all three modes.
</P>
<P>
   Camera enthusiasts will also like features such as the ability
to adjust focus and exposure manually, add a light or microphone to
the front accessory shoe and add a time code to recordings.
</P>
<P>
   The TRV720 also includes in-camera special effects and titling
(such as movie credits), although they are elementary and
cumbersome compared with computer video editing packages. By all
means take advantage of the i.LINK port to transfer your footage to
a computer. Most current Mac models have built-in FireWire ports,
as do many consumer-level machines from Sony, Dell and Compaq. You
can also add an IEEE 1394 card to most PCs with PCI slots for less
than $100.
</P>
<P>
   With the TRV720, you can even convert old analog tapes into
digital by using the analog input port. This is a great way to edit
scenes from old home movies along with new ones on your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have gotten a video into the computer, you can use
software like Pinnacle's StudioDV, MGI's VideoWave or Apple's
iMovie to edit it, then send it back out to videotape. Or you can
save it in compressed formats for CD or Web playback.
</P>
<P>
   While its amazing zoom lens will be the key attraction for many,
the TRV720 is an all-around great value. It can take excellent
pictures in virtually any environment, and links up to your
computer for editing and sharing video with others.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Becky Waring at  &LR; becky(AT)waring.org &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
