<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAP-DECLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AUGUST DOLDRUMS FOR GAP  &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The back-to-school season came in with a pained
whimper at Gap Inc., as same-store sales at all four of the
company's divisions declined during August, the retailer reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Companywide, same-store sales, or sales at stores open at least
a year, plummeted 14 percent against August 1999, about twice the
shortfall expected by analysts. Leading the plunge was the
low-price Old Navy chain, which saw same-store sales tumble a
stunning 24 to 26 percent. (Gap provides ranges, rather than
specific numbers, for sales of its individual chains.)
</P>
<P>
   With the help of store openings, total sales rose 6 percent to
$1.09 billion compared with last August. The number of new stores
grew 22 percent to 3,348 worldwide during that period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the nature of these results and the uncertainties in the
retail environment and in consumer spending on apparel, we continue
to see risk and challenge in both the third and fourth quarters,''
Gap Chief Financial Officer Heidi Kunz said in a recorded message.
</P>
<P>
   Gap has suffered sales and earnings disappointments all year.
</P>
<P>
   At press time, shares of the onetime Wall Street darling had
skidded 16 percent to $22.50 in after-hours trading, near the
stock's 52-week low. The San Francisco company's sales announcement
was made after the end of the regular trading day.
</P>
<P>
   At the flagship Gap brand, which includes Gap adult, child and
baby stores, same-store sales declined 4 to 6 percent for the
month.
</P>
<P>
   The shortfall was blamed largely on an experiment in which the
Gap adult chain's high-profile television advertising was replaced
with in-store promotions, including a new discount card.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Shop Card program fell below our expectations and did not
provide a strong enough voice in the marketplace'' to boost sales
above last year's levels, Kunz said.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to step up television advertising leading into
the holiday shopping season, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Same-store sales at Banana Republic declined 1 to 3 percent
while the company's international division, comprising mostly Gap
stores in Europe and Japan, fell 7 to 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Old Navy continued to suffer from warehouse distribution snafus
that began in July. Fixing that problem is the company's top
priority and it expects to have the issue resolved by the end of
September, Kunz said.
</P>
<P>
   In every division, a highly promotional retail climate ``forced
us to take deeper markdowns that we would have liked to attract
customers and clear through inventory,'' Kunz said.
</P>
<P>
   She echoed complaints of other retailers that the beginning of
the back-to-school season, a crucial period for the Gap and Old
Navy chains, has been anemic.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of the typical ``sales build'' through the month of
August was largely responsible for lower-than-expected results, she
said. Already-declining foot traffic at Old Navy actually worsened
as the month progressed, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite weak sales, inventories companywide are currently at
expected levels. Also, consumers seem to like Old Navy's new
``techno chino'' merchandise and a ``cleaner'' fashion focus at Gap
stores, Kunz said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert(AT)sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
