<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 I WANDER AS I WONDER  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _  &UR; Marginal notes from the margins of my &LR; 
 &UR; margarine .. &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   --United has reached a tentative agreement with its pilots. Soon
the airline will get back to doing what it does best: Sending up a
lot of pilots working overtime.
</P>
<P>
   --Secret Source (OK, her name is Linda Robertson) leaks this: On
the Sheraton Palace's catering menu, a gallon of orange juice is
$77, including tax and tip.
</P>
<P>
   At my local Safeway, OJ is $4.79 per gallon. And this week it's
buy one, get one free.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the Safeway swill isn't fresh-squeezed by vestal
virgins.
</P>
<P>
   --New York City's main bus terminal has a new statue: Ralph
Kramden of the old ``Honeymooners'' TV show. You know, a salute to
the noble bus driver.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of a private firm's national program to promote
vintage TV re-runs, so they're planning other statues. What about
San Francisco?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a statue honoring Red Skelton's lovable homeless guy,
Freddie the Freeloader.
</P>
<P>
   --``Would you like to find out what makes Raiders fans tick?''
That's the press invitation to the annual Raiders Rally (Friday, 3
to 7 p.m., Jack London Square Meadow).
</P>
<P>
   I hope there's bus parking, 'cause I'm bringing 500
psychiatrists.
</P>
<P>
   --And about that Raider rally and its ticking fans: Is it BYO
bomb squad?
</P>
<P>
   --This is your captain speaking. Remember, in the unlikely event
of a water landing, our empty promises can be used as a flotation
device!
</P>
<P>
   --It's cruel what employees say behind their company's back.
</P>
<P>
   My spy deep inside Kaiser Medical Center sends these revised (by
employees) Kaiser slogans:
</P>
<P>
   Original: ``Good people. Good medicine.'' Now: ``Good people.
Good medicine. Good luck!''
</P>
<P>
   Original: ``Good people from the ground up.'' Now: ``Good people
ground up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rimshot, please.
</P>
<P>
   --Carl Nolte, his finger on the pulse of the pavement, says,
``You know times are good when the panhandler pitch is, `Gotta
spare dollar?' Happened on Market near Fourth, right where the
zillion-dollar condos are rising.''
</P>
<P>
   --I saw the same panhandler. Told him I was tapped, I'd catch
him tomorrow. He said he'd have to run a credit check.
</P>
<P>
   --The Tread Shed in Pittsburg reports that Pat W. does sell
Fire- &QL; 
stones. Easy shop name to remember, now that we know that
Firestones do shed tread.
</P>
<P>
   --Near-miss meeting of the minds at Aqua! Dining in this corner,
Bill Maher, wise-guy host of ABC's ``Politically Incorrect.'' In
that corner, the national poster boy for political incorrectness _
baseball pitcher John Rocker!
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Bill and John did not interact. Two great ships, passing
in the night. Would have been sweet. ``Nice to meet you. Your TV
show sucks!'' ``Thanks. You throw like a girl!''
</P>
<P>
   --Music In Schools Today held a fund-raising committee meeting
in the 23rd-floor conference room of the PG&AMP;E building on Mission.
Good meeting, except for the part where the lights went out. The
conference room is next door to PG&AMP;E's Energy Efficiency offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next time we'll bring candles,'' says Ed Moose.
</P>
<P>
   --Kultural note: The folks who run the big Friends &AMP; Foundation
of the S.F. Public Library book fair (Sept. 7-10, Ft. Mason, Herbst
Pavilion) just got a donation: 17 huge pallets of Pokemon books!
</P>
<P>
   Don't let the kiddies browse that stack alone. Interspersed are
some R-rated Japanese illustration books.
</P>
<P>
   So: Everything from Pikachu to peek-a-boo.
</P>
<P>
   --Reminds me of the SFO bookstore clerk I overheard ringing up a
Sunday paper and a Playboy mag: ``OK. Examiner ... and examine
'er.''
</P>
<P>
   --Filming this fall in S.F.: ``The Princess Diaries,'' starring
Julie Andrews and Anne Hathaway. It's about a San Francisco girl
who inherits the throne of a small European principality. And swaps
it for a fixer-upper in the Crocker Amazon. (Just kidding about
that last part.)
</P>
<P>
   They're filming in S.F. to save costs. Willie's going to loan
them his throne, crown and robe.
</P>
<P>
   --Two men with sandwich-board sermons pace in front of the old
Emporium on Market every day. ``Fallen, fallen is Babylon the
great!''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Alfred says, ``They're referring to the Planning
Commission's acceptance of the Bloomingdale's deal, right?''
</P>
<P>
   --Firestone and Ford have formed what they call a ``Joint
Defense Agreement.'' Their ``Star Wars'' missile system will shoot
down any incoming lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   But don't worry, Explorer drivers. As soon as Clinton tidies up
the poppies in Colombia, he's sending the Marines into Decatur to
get your new tires. Until then: Avoid paved roads.
</P>
<P>
   --By popular demand: More sidesplitting redundancies!
</P>
<P>
   ``Young rookie'' (Bob Hood) ... ``Crooked politician'' (Steve
Abney) ... ``Little Thai Restaurant _ We specialize in Thai food.''
(Christine) ... ``Reason why'' (Dario DiBenedictus) ... ``San
Francisco Zoo'' (Arlene Heath) ... ``Other alternative'' (Walter
Wohlfeiler) ... ``Fully engulfed'' (Me).
</P>
<P>
   --``Sorry, I can't hear you,'' said Assemblyman Kevin Shelley's
receptionist on the phone. ``All the lobbyists are making too much
noise.''
</P>
<P>
   She was kidding, sort of. Noisy lobbyists killed the
Shelley-sponsored bill that would have limited Big Insurance bribes
_ I mean, contributions _ to the insurance commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Possible solution: Convert all the lobbies in Sacramento to
homeless shelters.
</P>
<P>
   --I trash-can all spam jokes. But, ah, what the hell, just one.
From a list of real want-ads: ``Cow, calves, never bred. Also 1 gay
bull for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   --I'm worried. It's already Thursday and Tiger Woods hasn't won
anything this week.
</P>
<P>
   --From the full-page United Airlines ad (noted by reader Jerry
Ohm): ``(W)e're working tirelessly ...'' Wow, United can't get
Firestones either?
</P>
<P>
   --Evelyn Sanchez, &LR;  has no health insurance, so she had to pay
the total bill for her newborn delivery and a two-day stay at
Alameda Hospital. The tab was $48.35. Of that, the ambulance was $9
and medicine was 10 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn could have gotten off cheaper, but she blew $11.50 on
room service.
</P>
<P>
   This was in 1948. Evelyn is no longer with us, but Judi Sanchez
is, and let's hope she suffers no emotional scars because her birth
cost less than a gallon of orange juice at the Sheraton Palace.
</P>
</TEXT>
