<SLUG> BC-HOSTAGE-STANDOFF-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MEN HOLD WOMAN HOSTAGE IN HER CAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY BERRIOS and ANNE LAMOY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A 53-year-old Kansas
woman was snatched from her home early Wednesday, touching off a
three-county police chase and a desperate standoff with police that
dragged on into a second day.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early Thursday, police were still attempting to negotiate the
release of the hostage, See Vongphrachanh. She reportedly was
showing signs of heat-related illness brought on by more than 20
hours inside the sport-utility vehicle holding her and her two
armed captors.
</P>
<P>
   The SUV, disabled in Gladstone, Mo., after a chase that wound
through downtown Kansas City, was surrounded by a phalanx of police
and FBI agents as negotiations played out in hours of 100-degree
heat and then into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Police estimated that 70 to 100 officers were involved, and the
area was blocked off to the public for several blocks in each
direction. Residents from at least two homes were evacuated, others
were asked to stay inside at about a dozen homes, and 21 children
stayed home from school.
</P>
<P>
   The episode began about 3 a.m. Wednesday, when a man dialed 911
and said two intruders were in his house, holding his family
against their will. Inside the split-level house in the 5400 block
of Locust Avenue in Kansas City, Kan., were a woman and her three
grown sons.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City, Kan., police said they had no reason to suspect
that Wednesday's break-in was linked to a series of recent
incidents in which intruders have impersonated police officers or
sheriff's deputies. At least eight times since May, intruders
posing as police officers or sheriff's deputies have robbed and
intimidated people in Johnson and Wyandotte counties, most recently
on Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's break-in, police said, two white males took the
woman with them when they broke through the garage door of the home
in her Isuzu Rodeo at about 3:30 a.m.. The Rodeo hurtled backward
through the garage door, stopped briefly on a small hill in front
of the house, then slipped between a car and the mailbox before
speeding east on Locust.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City police officers picked up the chase when the vehicle
entered Kansas City on Southwest Boulevard just after 4 a.m.,
department spokesman Steve Young said.
</P>
<P>
   The men fired at police during the chase. Police did not fire
back, Young said.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle weaved through downtown and north on Interstate 35.
It ended up on Vivion Road and eventually got stuck in the back
yard of a house in the 5200 block of Old Pike Road in Gladstone.
Tactical teams from Gladstone and Kansas City surrounded the car.
</P>
<P>
   Then the waiting and negotiating began.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, tactical officers outfitted in black with
masks, helmets and bulletproof vests, with guns slung over their
shoulders, worked the area as temperatures reached 102 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   At first, negotiators communicated with the abductors using a
bullhorn and yelling. According to police, the abductors had
spray-painted the windows black and placed sheets or blankets
across its windows.
</P>
<P>
   The abductors demanded water, cigarettes and alcohol, police
said. Between 11 and 11:30 a.m., police said, they received water
in exchange for a weapon. Police said there was at least one more
gun in the car. The abductors also received cigarettes, and between
5:35 and 5:45 p.m., police delivered more water and a direct-line
phone to the vehicle by a mechanical robot.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle's air conditioning was being turned on and off
throughout the stifling heat of the day. The FBI had a doctor on
the scene from about 10:30 a.m. to monitor police and the vehicle's
occupants.
</P>
<P>
   Officers from the Gladstone and Kansas City police departments
worked the scene, along with the FBI. Spokesman Jeff Lanza said the
FBI had jurisdiction because of potential federal kidnapping
charges involving taking a person across state lines.
</P>
<P>
   Residents who live on Old Pike Road and on adjacent streets had
front-row seats as the drama unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Atlas Payne and his wife, Ora-D. Payne, were rousted out of bed
about 3:30 a.m. in their home at 301 N.W. 52nd Terrace. They were
waiting at the command post when police asked for a key to the
Paynes' house.
</P>
<P>
   Atlas Payne went to the house with police, and saw about 75
policemen in the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, the house was surrounded, and they were all behind my
trees,'' Payne said. ``I was over my shock by then.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne took the police to a second-story bathroom, which looked
out on the SUV.
</P>
<P>
   Police told him the bathroom would be a good spot for a sniper.
</P>
<P>
   Payne left with the police having taken over his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thoughts are with the lady in the car and what she's going
through,'' Payne said. ``It must be devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Corrigan, who said he wakes up at 4 a.m. every morning
to watch ``Cops'' and ``Real TV,'' opted for the real-life show
playing out in his front yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could hear the sirens blaring, and we saw the police
chasing him down Old Pike Road and into a driveway,'' Corrigan
said. ``Police told him to stop, but he turned around, and sparks
were flying everywhere because his tires were all flat.''
</P>
<P>
   Corrigan said his home looks down the street on the home where
the Rodeo finally stopped, stuck on the retaining wall of a garden.
</P>
<P>
   Several neighbors said they heard police yelling for the
abductors to leave the vehicle and get on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept saying to stop the vehicle because the engine kept
revving,'' resident Diane Hartley said. ``I was very concerned when
I saw the cops going at the car with their guns drawn. I have two
3-year-olds, and my only thought was to get them out of their
bedrooms and into the back of the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Hubbell said she and her family were asleep when her
doorbell rang at 4:45 a.m. at their house in the 5100 block of
North Washington Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first thought was, `Who...is ringing my doorbell at this
hour, what is going on?' &UR; '' Hubbell said.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be an officer dressed in solid black, who told
Hubbell and her husband, Todd, that there was a hostage situation
and that the area was being evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   At that hour, there weren't too many places open for the
Hubbells, their 13-year-old son, her brother and a cousin, who all
had been in the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to Home Depot and sat down for a while, and we've been
at the command post ever since,'' Susan Hubbell said. ``I'm ready
to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   However, police told the Hubbells they would be wise to find a
place to stay Wednesday, indicating the situation was nowhere near
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Three schools in the North Kansas City School District also were
affected.
</P>
<P>
   District spokeswoman Jo Burton said police prohibited the
district's buses from picking up students who live in that area.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Burns, who lives on Old Pike Road, said he hoped
everything would be resolved peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least it makes me feel better to think that everything
ended, rather than started, here in my neighborhood,'' he said. (
30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
