<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IPAQ-APPLIANCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 REVIEW: COMPAQ'S NET APPLIANCE NOT QUITE ALL IT COULD BE  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``Internet appliances'' are in danger of
becoming the Godot of the high-tech world.
</P>
<P>
   For years the industry has been promising such products _
stripped-down devices designed to make getting online as easy as
making toast. Market researchers studying the potential for such
products have egged the manufacturers on by conjuring up visions of
unit sales in the millions and revenues of billions.
</P>
<P>
   As the pundits see it, the half or so of U.S. households that
have so far resisted the siren song of the personal computer _ plus
countless customers in the rest of the world _ would take the
plunge once offered something smaller, cheaper and less
intimidating than full-blown PCs.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, there has been little reality to support the
hype. Microsoft's WebTV, a set-top box that puts the Net on the
tube, has sold slowly _ slightly more than a million units during
nearly four years on the market. The I-opener, a stand-alone
terminal introduced last fall by a Texas startup called Netpliance,
took off only when hackers figured out how to convert it into a
Linux computer, and now it's off the market while the company tries
to figure out how to price the product low enough to sell but high
enough to keep it afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, with a few even less significant exceptions, all the
announced appliances _ including a trio that Gateway is building
for America Online _ are still somewhere over the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Except one: Compaq's iPAQ Home Internet Appliance 1A-1, which is
supposed to reach most major electronics chains this week. This
could be the product that finally brings the appliance concept into
the mainstream, but my testing during the last few weeks suggests a
little more tweaking is required before it really takes off.
</P>
<P>
   The product's list price is $599, but you're eligible for a $400
rebate if you sign up for three years of Internet access from MSN,
the Microsoft Network, at $21.95 per month. Because the appliance
is useless without MSN _ it's the first in a class of products
called MSN Companions, which are based on software Microsoft
developed specifically for use with its service _ you would be a
fool to buy one without taking advantage of the rebate.
</P>
<P>
   (An aside on terminology: neither ``iPAQ'' nor ``MSN Companion''
refers exclusively to this particular product. A number of hardware
companies are expected to offer MSN Companions of their own design
in the future, and Compaq now applies the iPAQ brand to a whole
line of products, ranging from pagers and MP3 players to desktop
PCs. For this review, though, iPAQ means the Compaq MSN Companion.)
</P>
<P>
   Hardware Basics
</P>
<P>
   The iPAQ hardware consists of two cables (one that you plug into
an AC outlet, the other into a phone jack), a keyboard and a main
unit that includes a 10.1-inch display (measured diagonally) and,
stretching out in a slightly bulbous base behind the screen, the
system's electronics.
</P>
<P>
   In back there's a jack for external speakers (not included) and
an Ethernet port, which currently isn't functional but will someday
allow the device to be connected to high-speed cable and DSL
modems. There are also four USB (Universal Serial Bus) ports, where
you can add a mouse and printer. (Neither is included, and for now
only one printer, the $99 Epson Stylus Color 740, works with the
iPAQ.)
</P>
<P>
   The compact keyboard communicates with the base unit wirelessly,
via infrared light, which works well as long as you keep the
keyboard pointed directly at the main unit and don't let anything
get in the way. The keyboard has a number of handy special keys
that take you directly to common Internet activities _ e-mail,
MSN's search page, the service's online shopping area, a special
Compaq support page, etc.
</P>
<P>
   At the front of the keyboard, below the space bar, is a floating
black button, the size of a quarter, that serves as the default
cursor-control device in the absence of a mouse. It works a little
like a miniature joystick: Press one edge of the button and the
onscreen pointer moves in the corresponding direction.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly there are people who will be comfortable with this
device, but my strong hunch is that they're few and far between; I
continued to find it a painfully slow and awkward way to work, even
after several weeks of daily use. Until Compaq replaces it, or at
least adds a mouse as standard equipment, I bet it's going to be a
real deterrent to the success of the product, especially among the
seniors, novices and computerphobes the company says are its target
market.
</P>
<P>
   The laptop-style screen could also be a problem for some of
these users. It's bright and crisp enough when you look at it
straight on, but it's based on a low-end display technology called
passive-matrix, which means you often see shadows and streaks on
the screen and the viewing angle is narrow _ if you look at it from
an angle, it's unreadably dark.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, the display has a fixed resolution of 800 by 600
pixels. It's easy to understand why Compaq chose that resolution _
it's the standard Web designers usually assume these days. But when
you pack that many pixels into a 10-inch screen, each pixel has to
be smaller, which in turn means everything on screen gets smaller,
and type in small point sizes can get difficult to read. Many
potential buyers would, I suspect, welcome an option to switch to a
resolution of 640 by 480 pixels, which would make text bigger and
much more legible.
</P>
<P>
   Making Toast
</P>
<P>
   The iPAQ tries to make Internet access easy in the same way
toasters make toasting easy: by not doing much else. All it's
capable of is Web browsing, e-mail and instant messaging. Since the
device has no hard drive, floppy drive or CD-ROM, there's no way
you can install or run additional software or even load browser
plug-ins. (There's room for cookies, though: they're stored in a
flash-memory buffer; if you collect so many that the buffer gets
full, the oldest cookie is automatically thrown away.)
</P>
<P>
   The developers did their best to make setting up the device and
connecting to the Internet as simple as possible. When you purchase
the iPAQ appliance, the dealer is supposed to enter your name and
address into a Microsoft database, so the system will know who you
are and have an e-mail account all set up for you the first time
you connect. All you have to do to get started _ in theory _ is
take the hardware out of the box, plug in the AC and phone cords,
hit the Connect button on the keyboard, and work through a few
simple setup screens.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it didn't work that way for me. The prototype
Microsoft sent me for evaluation arrived configured for the 415
area code, but during setup it gave me the opportunity to switch
the numbers, and since I live in the 510 area, I opted to do so,
picking a ``Berkley'' number (as Microsoft's list spells Berkeley,
Calif.) as my primary dial-in point and an Oakland, Calif., number
for backup.
</P>
<P>
   But when I then hit the Connect button, it proceeded to dial a
superfluous 510 in front of the seven-digit number, which of course
made it impossible to complete the local call. Eventually, after a
Microsoft support engineer had talked me through numerous attempts
to reconfigure the system, we got past that problem, and I managed
to get connected. But I continued to encounter a variety of
technical problems, including blank screens, half-drawn pages and
weird error messages.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, my friendly and helpful support engineer gave up and
sent me a second prototype. That one didn't work at all _ over and
over again, it dialed the right number, seemed to connect and then
disconnected. This time the engineer blamed unspecified ``server
problems,'' but they apparently turned out to be intractable; after
several days, he finally had me switch to a different dial-in
number.
</P>
<P>
   Thereafter, the iPAQ worked like a charm. I could connect every
time I tried. The Web looked and acted pretty much the way it does
from a PC or Mac, except that the device's browser has its
simplified toolbar and address field at the bottom instead of the
top of the screen. My MSN mail account, which uses Microsoft's
HotMail system, also worked reliably; you can even open and read
attached files, provided they were created in Microsoft Office or
saved in a few other common formats.
</P>
<P>
   But I did run up some important limitations with the browser. It
supports Flash, an animated graphics format that's common on the
Web, but not Shockwave, another common animation format. When I
went to the Shockwave Web site, the device froze. Likewise, it
handles audio and video in Microsoft's Windows Media format, but
not the Real Networks or Apple QuickTime formats. And you can't
read .pdf documents, the Adobe Acrobat format many sites use for
manuals and other documents where graphics and formatting are
important.
</P>
<P>
   I even had trouble with a Web site that runs entirely on
Microsoft software _ the Web site through which Chronicle employees
can check their e-mail from off-site. I could log in and see my
in-box, and even read messages, but when I tried to reply, all I
got was a blank screen. Microsoft said it's investigating.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's one very important issue that's inherent in the
hardware: The iPAQ doesn't give you any way to store documents. Old
mail is saved, for a while, on the HotMail server, but that's
accessible only when you're online. As for keeping information from
the Web, the best you can do is choose an option that's supposed to
let you mail a Web page and send it to yourself, but all it really
does is mail the URL, not the page's content.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bottom Line
</P>
<P>
   At its list price the iPAQ isn't a whole lot cheaper than a
full-fledged computer _ you can now get an Apple iMac for only
$799, or a low-end PC and monitor for less, maybe even less than
$599. If you're willing to sign up for three years of MSN, you can
get the same $400 rebate offered to iPAQ buyers.
</P>
<P>
   If you go that route, you'll get a much more versatile machine,
with floppy and hard drives for your data, plenty of room for
additional software when and if you want it, and ports where you
can add a wide variety of peripherals.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that would bring you up against the complexity that
Internet appliances are designed to avoid. But you don't have to
take advantage of all the flexibility a PC or Mac provides _ if you
wish, you could use it only for the same things an appliance does:
the Web, e-mail and instant messaging.
</P>
<P>
   If you're disciplined enough to stick to just those
applications, and you resist adding plug-ins, screensavers,
shareware utilities, additional programs or new hardware, odds are
your system will be just as easy to use as the current iPAQ _ maybe
even easier, because you'll have a better mouse, a bigger, more
adjustable screen, and plenty of room to store important
information where you can easily get at it. And you'll have the
option of changing Internet service providers or getting high-speed
Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Even assuming most users won't encounter the numerous setup
glitches I did, I just don't see a compelling advantage to the iPAQ
in its current form, even for the customers Compaq and Microsoft
are targeting. They'd be better off pitching it as a second (or
third) terminal to households that are already Net-savvy and simply
want a way for more family members to get online simultaneously.
But MSN's policies make that unlikely: Even if you're willing to
use MSN as the Internet provider for your PC or Mac, you have to
open a separate account, and pay an extra $21.95 per month, for the
iPAQ.
</P>
<P>
   I still believe Internet appliances have lots of potential, but
they're not there yet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
