<SLUG> BC-SEBASTIANI-SELLOFF-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WINEMAKER SEBASTIANI SELLING MOST OF ITS BRANDS  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sebastiani Vineyards of Sonoma, Calif.,
announced the sale Wednesday of the bulk of its business _ six
popular midprice wine labels and production facilities in San
Joaquin County, Calif. _ in a move to focus on high-price premium
brands bearing the Sebastiani name.
</P>
<P>
   The Wine Group, a San Francisco vendor best known for its
bag-in-the-box Franzia wine, was the buyer. No purchase price was
announced, but industry sources estimate that the Wine Group paid
more than $300 million for the brands and facilities that account
for about 7.8 million cases of Sebastiani's 8 million cases it
produces annually.
</P>
<P>
   Sebastiani sold its Turner Road Vintners division, which
includes Vendange, Talus, Farallon, Heritage, La Terre and
Nathanson Creek brands. It also sold two wineries and a
distribution center near Woodbridge, Calif., and its Humphrey &AMP;
Brown International wine marketing group.
</P>
<P>
   The winery deal is the third this week as a wave of
consolidations resculpts the wine country landscape.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Australia's Foster's Brewing Group agreed to buy
Beringer for $1.5 billion and Canada's Vincor agreed to buy R.H.
Phillips for $92 million.
</P>
<P>
   Vendange and Talus have been among California's fastest-growing
wine brands during the past decade. But Sebastiani Chairman Don
Sebastiani said the continuing wine industry consolidation made it
necessary for his privately owned winery to concentrate on just one
of its two businesses _ either the low-volume, high-price
ultra-premium niche or the high-volume, lower-margin $7 and $8
wines that require substantial ``marketing muscle'' to stay
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Sebastiani, which has been making wine in Sonoma since 1904,
chose to sell its high-volume operations, which employ about
two-thirds of its 380 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Wine Group was a logical buyer. Once part of the Coca-Cola
Co., the Wine Group began as a limited partnership in 1981 to buy
Franzia Bros., Mogen David and Tribuno brands. It also produces the
popular Corbett Canyon line of midprice varietal wines.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton(AT)sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
