<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-EINSTEIN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 COMPUTING Q&AMP;A: EXPECT TO PAY $1,500 FOR A DECENT LAPTOP COMPUTER  &HT;     By DAVID EINSTEIN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: What should be my top priorities when shopping for a notebook
computer? And what will I have to pay for a decent one?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Notebook PCs (also called laptops) can be had for less than
$1,000, but to get one that provides a satisfying computing
experience, you're probably looking at $1,500 minimum. The two
things that make the biggest difference between a good notebook and
a mediocre one are the technology used in the display, and the
weight of the computer. Notebooks costing less than $1,500
generally have dual-scan displays, while more expensive machines
have TFT active displays. The active display is clear and bright
regardless of the viewing angle. With a dual-scan display, you have
to look directly at the screen or else it fades.
</P>
<P>
   Weight is really important if you intend to haul your notebook
around _ and again, the more expensive the machine, the lighter
it's going to be. The trouble is that really light notebooks _ less
than 5 pounds _ usually cost more than $2,000. For $1,500, you'll
probably have to settle for 7 pounds including the battery (which
is the heaviest component).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Floppiless Tranfers
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: After purchasing a new PC, I'm trying to find a way to transfer
data files from my old computer to the new one without having to
use floppy disks. That would take a long time, plus, some of my
files are too large to put on a floppy. Someone mentioned a cable
that you can hook up to both machines.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Someone is absolutely right. The Direct Cable Connection feature
in Windows 98 lets you link two PCs together using either a
parallel cable, which attaches to the printer ports of both PCs, or
a serial cable that connects to the serial ports. Direct Cable
Connection should be located in the Start/Programs/Accessories
/Communications menu. (If it's not there, you can install it using
Windows Setup in the Add/Remove Programs option of the Windows
Control Panel.)
</P>
<P>
   When you start Direct Cable Connection, you'll see a Wizard that
will walk you through the process of getting your old and new PCs
to talk to each other and setting them up to share files. Keep in
mind, however, that while you can easily copy data files like Word
documents from one PC to the other, copying an actual program is a
tricky business and probably won't work. For that, you need to
install the program on the new PC.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Great 3-D Sans AGP
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I need to upgrade my computer with a 3-D video accelerator card,
but my motherboard doesn't have an AGP slot. I've been told that
all the hottest new cards are made for AGP. Am I out of luck, and
what are my options?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: AGP (accelerated graphics port) provides the fastest possible
graphics, but don't despair. If you have an open PCI slot
(peripheral component interconnect), you can still get great
explosions and other special effects. Just make sure to get a PCI
version of whatever card you decide on (my son just got a PCI
Voodoo 3 3000, and the 3-D is terrific).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Home Networking
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I'd like to set up a home network so that our daughter's PC can
share the high-speed DSL line that's connected to my computer. Is
this something I can do myself, or is it hopelessly technical?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Actually it's a piece of cake. Companies like Intel, S3
(Diamond) and 3Com offer easy-to-install network cards (and in some
cases even easier-to-install USB devices) that let you connect two
or more PCs via the telephone jacks in your house. They also
provide the software, although you won't even need it if you have
Windows 98 Second Edition, Windows NT 4 or Windows 2000 _ which
come with something called Internet Connection Sharing.
</P>
<P>
   Once your network is up and running, the PCs will be able to
share files, printers, and, of course, the Internet. And the best
part is that both you and your daughter can be online at the same
time, with no measurable loss of speed for either of you. Pretty
cool stuff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Need a quick dose of info on a stock you own _ or are
considering buying or selling? Three Web sites with lots of free
data for investors are  &LR; www.stockmaster.com &LR; ,
 &LR; moneycentral.msn.com/home.asp  &LR; and  &LR; www.marketguide.com &LR; . They
give you price quotes, charts, financials and background material,
along with the latest news headlines about the company you're
researching. Each site presents information differently, so check
them all out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
David Einstein is a columnist for Forbes Digital Tool. Got a
question about computing? E-mail it to
 &LR; computers(AT)sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
