<SLUG> BC-ITOKE-MARIJUANA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FOUNDERS DREAM OF HIGH DEMAND ON MARIJUANA NET SITE  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Call it a cross between Webvan and a cannabis
buyers club.
</P>
<P>
   Two budding entrepreneurs behind a firm descriptively named
IToke say they will launch a Web-based marijuana delivery service
in Amsterdam on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The e-commerce company promises to deliver orders within 30
minutes, using fast, friendly ``iTokkerista'' couriers astride a
fleet of green and white bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   The IToke Web site describes a service allowing customers to
place their orders by phone, fax or WAP-enabled wireless phones.
They pay for the pot with prepaid ``iToken'' smart cards that can
be refilled with cash online.
</P>
<P>
   Founders Tim Freccia and Mike Tucker, two Seattle natives, also
say they have plans to open a chain of ``toke style'' clubs in
London, New York and Tokyo that will ``celebrate a pastime that is
as American as Silicon Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business isn't different than any other business and had
its share of obstacles to overcome,'' Tucker said in a news
release. ``At the end of the day, who do you want to buy from? Some
guy in an alley in Barcelona, or from a company that not only
delivers premium products, but also shows an interest in the
community and its employees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``IToke is a vertical corporation,'' Freccia said. ``Think
Seattle. Think Starbucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Freccia and Tucker could not be reached for comment Wednesday to
determine whether the site is serious or just blowing smoke. The
online portal Yahoo listed the site,  &LR; www.itoke.co.uk, &LR;  under
``humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen St. Pierre of the National Organization for the Reform of
Marijuana Laws said IToke could run a legitimate business in
Amsterdam, where the laws and social mores regarding marijuana use
are less strict than in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds like all they need are the growers and the bike
riders,'' said St. Pierre, executive director of the NORML
Foundation, the nonprofit education and research arm of the
Washington, D.C., lobbying group that is trying to make marijuana
legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this service was available in an unfettered way in the
District of Columbia, they'd be zillionaires,'' St. Pierre said.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, though, Freccia and Tucker would be
considered major drug dealers and thrown in jail, St. Pierre said.
Pro- and anti-marijuana forces are battling over the question of
whether pot should be distributed for medicinal purposes.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the U.S. Supreme Court issued an emergency order
barring the Oakland (Calif.) Cannabis Buyers' Cooperative from
distributing marijuana to seriously ill patients.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Netherlands, marijuana can be sold legally in small
amounts from licensed coffee shops, although it remains to be seen
whether a fleet of ganja couriers runs afoul of those laws, St.
Pierre said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people who use marijuana (medicinally) are so physically
incapacitated that if they could call someone to have it delivered
to them, this would be a godsend,'' St. Pierre said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bevangelista(AT)sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
