<SLUG> BC-FORD-RECALL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FORD FACES RECALL OVER FAULTY IGNITION DEVICE  &HT;     By HENRY K. LEE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
OAKLAND, Calif. _ Lambasting Ford Motor Co. for deceiving
consumers, an Alameda County judge is poised to order an
unprecedented recall of up to 2 million Ford cars because of an
ignition device that allegedly causes stalling.
<P>
   The preliminary decision Tuesday by Superior Court Judge Michael
Ballachey was hailed Wednesday by attorneys who filed a
class-action lawsuit on behalf of 3 million current and former
owners of Ford, Lincoln and Mercury cars of model years 1983 to
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``It couldn't be better,'' said Jeff Fazio, an attorney for the
plaintiffs. ``This recall would be the first by a judge in United
States history _ it's a complete vindication of five years of very
hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed decision deals another blow to the Dearborn, Mich.,
automaker, which is embroiled in the recall of 6.5 million
Firestone tires used on its Explorer sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Krusel, a Ford spokeswoman, denied the allegations, saying
no plaintiffs in the suit have been injured or killed because the
ignition module was mounted on the distributor, which heats up
quickly, rather than on a cooler part of the engine.
</P>
<P>
   Krusel said Ford plans to ask the judge to reverse his decision
at a hearing on Sept. 28. If Ballachey finalizes his decision, the
automaker intends to appeal, she said.
</P>
<P>
   During the Alameda County trial, Ballachey said Ford officials
and witnesses provided evasive answers and used euphemisms in
attempting to explain why cars suddenly stalled, when in fact they
knew about problems associated with a part known as the ``thick
film ignition'' module.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ford's strategy, clearly established by the credible evidence,
was: `If you don't ask the right question, we don't have to answer
with what common sense tells us you want to know,' '' Ballachey
wrote in his 10-page tentative decision.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the proposed recall, the judge said he plans to order
Ford to pay full restitution to plaintiffs who paid to have their
modules replaced.
</P>
<P>
   But Krusel said the judge's ruling ``absolutely conflicts with
all of the real-world data and engineering analysis that was
presented in the case. The modules we're talking about lasted over
100,000 miles and performed as well as any alternative design
available at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling stems from a two-part trial before Ballachey, who was
called out of retirement to hear the case.
</P>
<P>
   The trial drew national attention not only because the
plaintiffs sought $3 billion in damages, but also because they
accused Ford of violating a state consumer law _ rather than a
product-liability statute _ by allegedly misleading the public, the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration and environmental
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase ended in a mistrial in November, when jurors
reported that they were deadlocked on whether Ford concealed
alleged problems with the module.
</P>
<P>
   In his written tentative ruling, Ballachey accused Ford
officials of selectively releasing information it was required to
release to the national highway safety agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ford presented a blizzard of unpersuasive statistical evidence
in an attempt to disprove the obvious: That TFI modules failed in
enormous numbers from the outset, that they continued to fail in
unacceptable numbers for many years before being replaced by
successor technology, and that they presented a serious safety risk
to its consumers,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   Ballachey also attacked the auto manufacturer's use of phrases
such as ``stop, won't start,'' ``quits on road'' as euphemisms that
were ``immersed in rhetoric claiming a multiplicity of causes for
stalling.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Nelson, a plaintiffs' attorney, said, ``They played word
games.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs said at trial that the module often failed at 257
degrees Fahrenheit &LR; , resulting in stalled engines. Ford decided to
save $4 per vehicle by mounting the device on the distributor
instead of on a cooler place on the engine, attorneys for the
plaintiffs said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said it did not have an estimate for the cost of any
recall.
</P>
<P>
   Krusel also sought to dispel concerns about public confidence in
Ford because of the tire recall and the recent trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always doing everything we can to assure the public that
Ford Motor Co. is doing the right thing,'' Krusel said. ``There
should be no decline in trust. We are committed to ensuring safe
products for our customers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
