 PERSONALS: Congress Is a Barrel of Monkeys 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news
file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
AWashingtonian magazine poll of congressional aides, culled by
Personals for mentions relevant to the presidential election or
morsels of gossip, found:
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate,  &UR; Joe Lieberman &LR;  was second least partisan and
second in the ``just plain nice'' category;  &UR; Barbara Boxer &LR;  took
the uncoveted third spot in the ``no rocket scientist'' category;
 &UR; John McCain &LR;  was No. 1 worst follower and No. 1 hottest temper.
</P>
<P>
   In the House,  &UR; Barney Frank &LR;  was both brainiest and funniest;
 &UR; Nancy Pelosi &LR;  was second-best-dressed; and although  &UR; Mary Bono &LR;  was
``best in a bathing suit,'' she also took second place in the ``no
rocket scientist'' category.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; HATCH'S MEMOIR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' champ  &UR; Richard Hatch &LR;  is about to close a $500,000
deal with St. Martin's Press to write his memoir, reports
Inside.com. The book is not only a memoir of the 39-year-old
corporate trainer's life but also a summary of his professional
advice, for those who might want to emulate him.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's 76-page proposal was with his agent,  &UR; Eric Simonoff &LR;  at
Janklow &AMP; Nesbit, before he was announced as winner of the show.
St. Martin's prevailed over Simon &AMP; Schuster and Pocket Books, both
of which are owned by Viacom, the parent company of the show's
broadcast network, CBS.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; NOW HEAR THIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The average American office worker, says Real Simple magazine,
receives 201 phone, paper and e-mail messages a day. Although the
magazine is aimed at making readers' lives more serene, this
information is cause for anxiety:
</P>
<P>
   Are you falling below average in the number of people contacting
you? Why does everyone else seem so busy and productive? Are you
becoming a loner? Will you grow old by yourself, sitting in some
room and staring at the walls while bristly hairs grow out of your
ears? Are you starting to look like Whistler's mother?
</P>
<P>
   There, you're not minding life's complications now, are you?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; REMEMBERING MATTHAU &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Herbert Ross &LR; , who directed  &UR; Walter Matthau &LR;  in ``The Sunshine
Boys'' and other movies, told Premiere magazine that he had first
met Matthau at a party in New York, where ``he was still a theater
actor, and not the most successful one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I met him and  &UR; Carol &LR;  ( &UR; Matthau &LR; ) at a party. She was angry at
him for gambling. And he was angry at her for being angry at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he took a match and burned a hundred-dollar bill in front
of her. It left this enormous impression on me. She just huffed and
walked away. They had a very fascinating relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
