<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, August 31.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-WORKERS (Tianjin, China) _ The Meite Packaging factory
here is nearly deserted now, its managers and machines all hastily
transferred over the last two days to an isolated development zone.
Although the closure had long been planned, the precipitous
departure was necessitated by an extraordinary event: Last week,
desperate Chinese workers fearing layoffs kept six foreign managers
from Meite's U.S. parent company hostage in the factory for 40
hours. The workers' frustrations that sparked this unusual incident
are extremely commonplace, leading to hundreds of worker protests
in the last 3 years. By Elisabeth Rosenthal. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SOMALIA-POLITICS (Mogadishu, Somalia) _ Somalia finally has a
government, and its first president in nearly a decade arrived here
escorted by at least 120 pickup trucks carrying more than 1,000
militiamen armed with rifles, rocket launchers, even
double-barreled antiaircraft guns. And just to be on the safe side,
the president wore a bullet-proof vest. By Ian Fisher. (The story
has moved in ``i'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos, NYT18,19,20 are being sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
