   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ROBOTS-REPRODUCE (Undated) _ For the first time, computer
scientists have created a robot that designs and builds other
robots, almost entirely without human help or expertise. In the
short run, this advance could lead to a new industry of inexpensive
robots customized for specific tasks. In the long run _ decades at
least _ robots may one day be truly regarded as ``artificial life''
_ able to reproduce and evolve, building improved versions of
themselves. By Kenneth Chang.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT19 is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ORE-CHINESE-DEPORT (Portland) _ Portland is being called
De-Portland by some people because of the way officials from the
Immigration and Naturalization Service treat Chinese tourists. By
Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-VEEPS (Undated) _ Joseph Lieberman and Dick Cheney are
waging starkly different campaigns as they strike out on their own
for the first time since each party's national convention. Cheney
has largely kept a low profile, staging small events, sticking to a
safe speech script, generally staying clear of reporters from
national news organizations. Lieberman has been a more active
campaigner, drawing far larger crowds and attracting _ indeed
courting _ more media coverage. By David Barstow. 1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-PRIMARY (New York) _ It is a primary race that has spawned a
soap opera-like drama. The bitterness of a feud between two
Democrats in the 11th Congressional District in Brooklyn has not
only torn apart a longstanding relationship but has delivered some
of that anguish to the doorstep of other politicians and voters in
the borough. But it is also a race that has brought to the surface
simmering _ and often unspoken _ unease between black New Yorkers
whose roots are in the United States and those with Caribbean
heritage. By Jonathan P. Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CNN-FUTURE (Undated) _ In 1997, CNN's executives were looking
for something to make it the news outlet of record all of the time.
So they hired Richard N. Kaplan, an ABC News producer, in the hope
that as the president of their U.S. operation, he would bring to
CNN what the broadcast networks already had: highly produced news
programming so compelling that millions of people would tune in
regularly whether there is big news or not. The dual announcements
Wednesday that Kaplan was resigning and that CNN's entire executive
structure was being revamped, were accompanied by admissions that
the strategy did not work. By Jim Rutenberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   FORD (Washington) _ Federal regulators trying to determine how
much the Ford Motor Co. knew about defective tires used on its
Explorers expanded their investigation Wednesday by demanding that
the company provide detailed information of any tire problems in 16
countries outside the United States. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   BANKS-TAKEOVERS (New York) _ Now that the acquisition of
Donaldson, Lufkin and Jenrette promises to put Credit Suisse First
Boston in the ``bulge bracket'' of Wall Street firms, how do
also-rans like Merrill Lynch, JP Morgan and Chase Manhattan
respond? Do Lehman Brothers, Prudential Securities and even Bear
Stearns now become more attractive takeover targets? By Patrick
McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIACAMP-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ The concept of summer camp
normally conjures up images of kayaks and campfires. But at a new
two-week day camp, children instead find story boards, video
cameras and even the ingredients food stylists use to prepare prop
ice cream cones. The camp, called Club Media, is designed to teach
children how to be more aware of the persuasion techniques used in
marketing. By Allison Fass.
</P>
<P>
   INCOME-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ Make no mistake about how good the
last five years have been to Americans. But what is too often
ignored is that this remarkable economic performance has not yet
compensated for the persistent erosion of the income of male
workers since the early 1970s. And this goes a long way toward
explaining why Al Gore's message at the Democratic convention to
help working families seems to have caught on. By Jeff Madrick.
</P>
<P>
   KIDNAP-TAX (Undated) _ A legal memo from the Internal Revenue
Service says that if a child is kidnapped, taxpayers who claimed
that child as a deduction can take a deduction only for the year of
the kidnapping and not for subsequent years even if they maintain a
room for the child or otherwise spend money on the child. This is
apparently because the law makes the kidnappers eligible to deduct
the cost of caring for the child. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
