<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKERS IN PARADISE FEEL PINCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   You know the local job market is
painfully tight when you get a heartfelt yelp for help from
paradise.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Paradise'' may be stretching it, but all those ``best places
to work'' lists over the years have lionized Southwest Airlines for
its employee benefits, work atmosphere and job satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of companies and business professors have visited its
Dallas headquarters to divine its hiring, retention and customer
satisfaction secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Now at Kansas City International Airport (MCI in airline code),
the workplace blossom has wilted along with the energy and morale
of Southwest ground crews.
</P>
<P>
   Read excerpts from a letter that short-staffed, overtime-weary
MCI customer service and ramp agents wrote to headquarters this
summer:
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty, we are extremely exhausted by our jobs. The
amount of hours that we are putting in individually is unrealistic
and inhumane. ... Customers are suffering through long lines, and
being given a level of customer service that is far below our
standards...
</P>
<P>
   ``We all love our jobs; otherwise we wouldn't be here. Many
outsiders would view our situation and say we should find another
job, but that is the last thing in the world we want to do. This
Company holds a very special place in all of our hearts. We are
just at the end of our rope.''
</P>
<P>
   Colleen Barrett, Southwest executive vice president, answered
the plea with a seven-page, single-spaced letter and ``game plan''
on staffing strategies for MCI and two other staff-stressed
stations (Baltimore and San Jose, Calif.).
</P>
<P>
   First, she commiserated with workers' pain. But, she wrote,
``Unfortunately, there are no `miracle cures' to the cumulative
effect of three years of virtually no unemployment in the MCI
area.''
</P>
<P>
   The overall economy, competitive salary offers from high-tech
companies and the location of the airport make it difficult to
attract employees to MCI, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest is trying to add 20 percent more ground workers at MCI
by holding job fairs, advertising in movie theaters, operating a
toll-free hot line for job applicants, operating a 1-800-SWA-JOBS
(1-800-792-5627) hot line, using the Monster.com resume database,
giving $500 referral bonuses to employees who suggest new hires,
recruiting at colleges and high schools, and paying some moving
expenses that the airline otherwise wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it has scheduled more job fairs and interviews between now
and November, hired a commercial staffing company to help find job
candidates, arranged for ``loaners'' from other airports,
temporarily relaxed its high school diploma requirement, and
streamlined interview and hiring processes for the short-staffed
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Other remedies are in mind, Barrett said, ``all the while
realizing that some of them will fail and that some will be more
effective//successful than others. The bottom-line objective is to
have each Station across our system fully staffed ASAP and to have
our short-staffed Stations (with MCI as our first priority) fully
staffed.''
</P>
<P>
   The tight job market has put Southwest's famed reputation at
stake _ and its staff, top officers and customers know it. ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
