<SLUG> BC-NJ-FIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE IN NEW JERSEY RAZES APARTMENT COMPLEX NEAR HUDSON
</HEADLINE>
  By ANDY NEWMAN and ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A spectacular and suspicious fire Wednesday night consumed a
sprawling apartment complex under construction near the Hudson
River in Edgewater, N.J., destroyed an occupied apartment building
and eight homes across the street, and sent columns of flame 200
feet into the air.
</P>
<P>
   There were no serious injuries, but dozens of people lost their
homes, said the Edgewater Fire Chief, Sam DeNorchia Several
firefighters were treated for heat exhaustion and smoke inhalation.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after midnight, fire officials said they had contained
the blaze but could not put it out, partly because it was being fed
by a ruptured gas line in the apartment complex. Public Service
Electric and Gas was unable to get to the valves to shut off the
line, said the Edgewater fire chief, Sam DeNorchia. Another gas
line, on Undercliff Avenue, where the occupied dwellings burned,
also ruptured, the chief said.
</P>
<P>
   From the Palisades, the cliffs that overlook Edgewater, the
scene of the blaze, resembled a lake of fire. Homeowners on top of
the Palisades in the town of Cliffside Park doused their lawns to
keep the fire from spreading to them, and firefighters stood near
the cliff's edge and shot water 150 feet down onto the flames.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the top of the cliff, the heat was so intense that
firefighters had to hose down the firefighters working closest to
the cliff.
</P>
<P>
   The fire began around 8:15 p.m. at Avalon River Mews, a 400-unit
complex consisting of an H-shaped, seven-story structure and seven
other buildings under construction on the inland side of River
Road. Within minutes, it was as if a curtain of flame had been
drawn across the waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   On Undercliff Avenue, just west of the complex, residents
described a huge fireball shooting up the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's windows went red,'' said Debbie Bonhan, a
resident. ``The whole sky was illuminated, the power went out.
People were running around because they didn't know where the fire
was.'' Hundreds of homes surrounding the fire lost power.
</P>
<P>
   DeNorchia said that the first of the more than 150 firefighters
who eventually arrived on the scene did not know where to begin.
``When you pulled up, it was, `I got a fire here, I got a fire here
and I've got another fire here,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials were especially concerned because Avalon River
Mews, built on the site of an old Alcoa aluminum plant, is only
about a hundred yards from a tank farm _ a field of giant tanks
filled with gasoline. Only an empty warehouse stands between the
condominium complex and the tanks. Officials said they were taking
steps to protect the tank farm from the flames.
</P>
<P>
   The fire began in the southeast corner of the H-shaped structure
and spread at a furious speed. One witness, Jeff Louisot, 24, said
that in no more than 10 minutes the entire structure was aflame.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the blaze was not immediately determined, but
DeNorchia said, ``Anything that burns that quickly has got to be
suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   As the fire consumed Avalon River Mews, it jumped across
Undercliff Avenue, which runs parallel to River Road west of the
complex, and began chewing its way through the houses and a 25-unit
apartment building there.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:15 p.m., Edgewater's mayor, Bryan Christiansen, stood on
Undercliff Avenue watching firefighters from more than 20 towns
struggle to save more houses.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, a three-story house nearby collapsed. ``There goes
that one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many cars along Undercliff Avenue exploded from the heat of the
fire, Chief DeNorchia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The radiant heat it generated was tremendous,'' he said. ``It
was the worst fire I've encountered outside a building in 20
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Across River Road, Edgewater's main thoroughfare, a shopping
center parking lot filled with people who came to watch the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds of smoke and ash filled the air, lighted from beneath by
the orange flame. Periodically, chunks of Avalon River Mews broke
off or collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was also watched by thousands of Manhattan residents _
Avalon River Mews is across the Hudson River from about 125th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Bourdain, who watched from the windows of his apartment
on Riverside Drive, said, ``It looks like an oil field fire, with
periodic explosions of pressurized flame that extend higher than
the Palisades.''
</P>
<P>
   Avalon River Mews is part of the transformation of the Hudson
riverfront from factories and rail yards into some of the most
desirable residential real estate in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Before beginning construction, the developer and Alcoa had to
spend millions to clean up PCBs and other contaminants.
</P>
<P>
   Construction on the 408-unit complex began last September, said
Gary Steinfield, the vice president for development of the
complex's owner, Avalon Bay Communities, which is based in Iselin
N.J. The first apartment were going to be occupied in December, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   As he watched the $70 million project go up in flames,
Steinfield tried to be philosophical.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day,'' he said, the most important thing is
life and safety.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
