<HEADER>
A7067 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-MATRINERS-N     08-31 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MATRINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANDAGES AND BRACES AND A CURE FROM CONE
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The New York Yankees lead the American League East in
victories and perhaps all of baseball in medical implements. David
Justice's uniform is stretched by the extra wrapping he wears to
protect a strained groin muscle. A brace houses the right knee of
Glenallen Hill. Tino Martinez played Wednesday night's game with
his left foot enveloped by gauze.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of their lineup are slowed by nagging injuries and
others are just slow, but in their deliberate way, the Yankees
dumped the Seattle Mariners Wednesday night, 5-4, to finish their
six-game road trip with four victories. David Cone improved his
record to 4-11; Dwight Gooden relieved and pitched out of a pivotal
seventh-inning jam.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch's sore elbow is preventing him from playing now
and may prevent him from playing second base the rest of the
season, depriving the Yankees of one of their few speedy everyday
players. Derek Jeter, who will replace Knoblauch as the leadoff
hitter on most days, is fast, and once Bernie Williams gets a
couple of strides, he moves well; Paul O'Neill is capable of taking
an extra base, when healthy.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neill played Wednesday night's game with a hip pointer,
his right side flushed crimson because of a cortisone shot.
Justice's injury has bothered him since he joined the Yankees, and
when he is hurting, he strides with his feet splayed uncomfortably.
Hill and Jose Canseco are cautious rounding bases, gaining speed
when moving in a straight line. Martinez's injury is not considered
serious, but he is not speedy when fully healthy; nor is Jorge
Posada or Luis Sojo or Scott Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are a slow team, and that won't change before the
postseason, the tradeoff for fielding a lineup stocked with big
bangers. But the Yankees are compensating for that by reverting to
the patient style they thrived with in 1998 and 1999, drawing walks
and flooding the base paths with runners and creating a steady
stream of runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees led Seattle and Aaron Sele, 1-0, in the fourth
inning, having stranded runners in scoring position in the second
and third innings. Williams singled through the middle leading off
the fourth, and Justice walked on five pitches. Before the Yankees
traded for Justice on June 29, they had collected 245 walks in 74
games, an average of 3.3 walks a game. Since then, they have 273
walks in 55 games, an average of five a game. Martinez chopped a
grounder toward first, where Raul Ibanez was playing in place of
John Olerud, who was with his wife as she gave birth to their
second child. The ball took a kangaroo hop over Ibanez's glove,
Martinez had a double and each runner advanced two bases, Williams
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Sele hit Hill in the hand with a fastball, loading the bases.
The right-handed-hitting Sojo, falling toward third base as he
reached for an outside pitch, slapped it to the right side _ just
inside first base, the ball rolling toward the corner. Justice and
Martinez scored, Hill steadily made his way toward third and Sojo
had a double. Yankees 4, Seattle 0.
</P>
<P>
   The lead must have pleased Cone, although he would probably have
preferred the Yankees' at-bats to move a little more quickly, to
help him keep loose. Cone likes to pitch in hot weather, and
Wednesday night, Seattle was cool and clear and he wore long
sleeves, stretching his arm after warm-up pitches and his first
offerings of each inning. His first fastballs in each inning
invariably reached about 87 mph, and as his arm loosened, he threw
harder, some fastballs clocking in at 91 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Cone lasted just three innings in his previous start, against
Oakland last Friday, and came away second-guessing much of what he
did. Kevin Appier, the pitcher who faced Cone that day, digs huge
holes in the mound when he pitches, and Cone had trouble landing
properly. Rather than summon a member of the grounds crew to fill
the holes _ or fill them in himself _ Cone simply shifted to the
opposite side of the rubber for the third inning, and he was
knocked out after allowing five runs.
</P>
<P>
   Cone also lamented that he didn't use his fastball more
aggressively, and Wednesday night, he changed that. He threw a
fastball on the first or second pitch to every Seattle hitter the
first time through the lineup, and finished off the Mariners when
he got ahead in the count. Cone struck out six in 5 2/3 innings,
allowing five hits and a run and walking four.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle scored a run in the fifth, reducing the Yankees' lead to
4-1. With his pitch count mounting, Cone was relieved after
allowing a two-out single in the sixth. The left-hander Randy
Choate, who is building a case to be part of the postseason roster,
retired the only batter he faced.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden took over in the top of the seventh, and after allowing a
walk and a single to start the inning, he got Alex Rodriguez to pop
out. Edgar Martinez, who beat the Yankees on Tuesday with a
late-inning three-run homer, came to the plate as the potential
tying run. He chopped a double-play grounder to Jeter _ and Jeter
fumbled it, and fumbled it again while trying to pick it up.
Everybody was safe. But Gooden struck out Al Martin and retired
Mike Cameron on a fly to deep right-center, where Justice caught
the ball for the last out of the inning, faked as if he were going
to flip the ball to jeering fans and then kept it for himself.
</P>
<P>
   The next game the Yankees play will be in September, at Yankee
Stadium, their magic number for clinching the AL East at 28. The
Yankees are expected to add a little more speed for their bench _
Ryan Thompson will most likely be in uniform Friday, to be followed
by Alfonso Soriano and perhaps Knoblauch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
