<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALDES COULD GO TO BULLPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ While Los Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said
he wouldn't go to a four-man rotation in the season's final few
weeks even if it meant making a playoff push, the starting rotation
issue is far from settled.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are getting production from Kevin Brown, Chan Ho
Park and Darren Dreifort, but quality outings and wins beyond that
have been few.
</P>
<P>
   That stated, right-hander Ismael Valdes' time in the starting
rotation could be running out, and club officials have talked about
making a change if Valdes doesn't pitch well Friday against
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes has been awful since joining the club in late July in a
trade the Dodgers made the same day Arizona acquired Curt Schilling
from Philadelphia. In 18 games, Valdes is 2-6 with a 5.94 ERA this
season, including going 0-2 with a 7.33 ERA in seven games with the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers pitching coach Clause Osteen is hopeful Valdes can turn
around his dismal season with a strong month. Osteen said Valdes'
20-minute bullpen session Tuesday was his best since being
reacquired.
</P>
<P>
   But Osteen added that one of the reasons Valdes hasn't pitched
well is because he's still feeling the effects of a shoulder injury
that landed him on the disabled list to start the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think it's going to take him a little bit of time to
get his strength back, and I think it will come as his timing and
rhythm get better,'' Osteen said. ``His timing has not been good.
(Tuesday) night was probably the closest he's come to doing it
right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers can still turn to right-hander Matt Herges, who made
four starts after lefty Carlos Perez was yanked from the rotation
in early August. Herges went 0-3 with a 5.25 ERA as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Praising Park: The moment catcher Chad Kreuter arrived at spring
training, he began asking about right-hander Chan Ho Park, and what
made a pitcher of his talent have a 5.23 ERA in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Trusting his ability to throw any pitch at any time in the count
was something Park lacked, but working exclusively with Kreuter for
the past three months has changed that approach. And it's made Park
one of the top young pitchers in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Park had the most dominating performance of his
career when he struck out 14 and allowed one hit in eight innings
Tuesday against Milwaukee. Park (14-8) leads the Dodgers in wins
and is 5-2 with a 2.48 ERA since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the spring, it was a must to have Chan Ho,'' Johnson said.
`He's pitched like a No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was strictly a thrower last year, and overthrew a lot. This
year, he's been pitching. This year, with the help of Kreuter, he's
a complete pitcher. When he's in that groove and makes good
pitches, he gets good hitters out.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Dodgers utility outfielder F.P. Santangelo said
team doctors told him his season is all but over. Santangelo, who
tore a ligament in his left thumb Aug. 22, is expected to be in a
cast for another two weeks. However, Santangelo said he's hopeful
he can return for the last week of the season. ... Dodgers center
fielder Devon White played for the first time since straining his
left quadricep Friday. White pinch hit in the ninth and grounded
out, though he had trouble running because the leg is not 100
percent. ... Left fielder Bruce Aven's strained left oblique muscle
continues to give him trouble, and he was unavailable for the third
straight day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
