<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-EARTHQUAKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VORBE'S LATE GOAL LIFTS GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The San Jose Earthquakes couldn't rattle
anything or anyone Wednesday night. Especially not starting
goalkeeper Kevin Hartman, who could have taken a nap in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   But the Los Angeles Galaxy has found ways to miss a sure thing
this season and it nearly did it again.
</P>
<P>
   The Earthquakes, whose only previous shot came in the 74th
minute, evened the match 1-1 on a penalty kick by Dario Brose in
the 88th minute after Galaxy defender Danny Califf pulled down
Wojtek Krakowiak in the penalty area.
</P>
<P>
   However, substitute Sebastian Vorbe came to the rescue, scoring
in the 93rd minute - three minutes into injury time - to help the
Galaxy escape with a much-needed 2-1 victory in front of 11,974 at
the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved the Galaxy (14-8-8, 50 points) into a share of
the Western Division lead with Kansas City (14-7-8, 50 points),
which was idle on Wednesday. The Wizards have three games remaining
while the Galaxy has two.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, K.C. will look in the paper today and see that
we're even,'' said Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid. ``I think anything can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not only a good night for Vorbe, but also Seth George.
Both strikers are fighting for the starting spot that will be left
by Sasha Victorine during the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   In his previous four starts and 11 appearances, George logged
252 minutes, but had more offsides (seven) than shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   Starting his fifth game in typical George fashion, the former
UCLA striker was whistled offside three times in the first half and
had missed two easy shots before breaking through in the 40th
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Elliott sent a pass right of San Jose's goal for
Victorine. Victorine headed the ball down to George streaking in
the penalty area. George wasted no time, sending a one-touch shot
to the left corner for a 1-0 lead and his first goal and points of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Mauricio Cienfuegos (El Salvador), Cobi Jones (U.S.) and Luis
Hernandez (Mexico) all missed Wednesday's match because of World
Cup qualifiers Sunday. Ezra Hendrickson (St. Vincent &AMP; the
Grenadines) also has a qualifier Sunday, but his federation allowed
him to stay.
</P>
<P>
   With the playoffs looming, the Galaxy is keeping close tabs on
El Salvador and St. Vincent &AMP; the Grenadines, which are both at the
bottom of CONCACAF Group D.
</P>
<P>
   Neither country can afford another loss if it hopes to advance
to the next round. On the flip side, Schmid would have Cienfuegos
and Hendrickson the remainder of the season if they do lose,
prompting a reporter to ask Schmid if he would light any candles
this weekend hoping for that outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of St. Vincent, I don't think I have to light any
candles for that to happen,'' joked Schmid. ``I don't want to
disappoint Ezra, but, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Schmid would love for those countries to lose, he
won't root against his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have tremendous respect for Mauricio and I know it means a
lot for him to have his country qualify,'' said Schmid.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, if Mexico wins on Sunday against Panama, it all but
assures Mexico a berth in the next round of qualifying. If that
happens, Schmid said Hernandez may not be called for Mexico's last
two qualifiers, one of which is during the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had informal conversations with Mexico,'' said Schmid.
``They said if they win this game they won't call Luis for the next
game. We just hope that's the case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 0236EDT &QL; 
