<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-BLUEJAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS POUNDED BY BLUE JAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Angels failed to add to their
American League-leading number of home victories Wednesday night,
absorbing an 11-2 thrashing by the Toronto Blue Jays and David
Wells, and now they head back out on the road where life so far in
2000 has been far from blissful.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to get to where we want to be,'' said manager Mike
Scioscia, who clearly wants to get to the top, ``then, obviously,
we've got to win on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously.
</P>
<P>
   Of their remaining 29 games, 20 are on the road and only nine -
nine - at Edison Field, where 19,653 fans showed up Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels begin a seven-game trip Friday night in Chicago, then
move on to Detroit, remarkably, for the only time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to be a good club, you have to play well on
the road,'' said Scioscia, well aware the Angels, who are 41-31 at
home, are just 27-34 on the road. That's by far the poorest road
record of any of the AL wild-card contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This season we've hit some stretches on the road when we
haven't played well, we've had some tough spells, and we've hit
some hot clubs on the road,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now all they've got coming up is the winningest team in the
league, the White Sox, and then the hottest, the Tigers, who have
rebounded from a 9-23 start to climb into wild-card contention.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Angels are through with the Blue Jays, who won
seven of the 12 meetings with Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays unloaded on three Angels pitchers for 19 hits,
four of them home runs. A dozen hits came off of rookie starter
Matt Wise (3-2), including three of the homers, and he was gone
after only 4 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just pounded the ball,'' Scioscia said. ``Every mistake
(Wise) made, they were on.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Wells breezed to his career-best - and
major-league-leading - 19th win.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, pitching in his 300th game as a Blue Jay, left after five
innings because of what was described as tightness in his left
shoulder. He also left with an 8-0 lead. Wells threw only 61
pitches, little more than a workout, and gave up just three hits,
all singles.
</P>
<P>
   While the Angels may have their troubles on the road, not so for
the 6-foot-4, 235-pound Wells. He's 11-1 this season away from the
SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   For the second successive night, the Angels spotted the Blue
Jays a 4-0 lead. But unlike Tuesday night, when they stormed back
to win 9-5, this one only got worse. Toronto added single runs in
the second and third innings, then two in the sixth and one in the
seventh against reliever Derrick Turnbow, plus two more in the
ninth off of Mark Petkovsek.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good-hitting team, and I made mistakes,'' Wise said,
``... the change I hung to Fullmer (in the first inning).'' It
wasn't until the eighth that the Angels finally retired the Blue
Jays 1-2-3 in an inning.
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter Brad Fullmer slugged two home runs, his 27th
and 28th, and drove in four runs; third baseman Tony Batista hit
his 37th home run to reach 100 runs batted in, and catcher Darrin
Fletcher hit his 17th home run.
</P>
<P>
   That gave the Blue Jays a major-league-leading 221 homers for
the season, which tied the Toronto franchise record.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Carlos Delgado drove in four runs, giving him 124
for the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays' Dave Martinez had two of the Blue Jays' 19 hits,
a single and a double, to extend his hitting streak to 20 games, a
career high and the longest current streak in the AL.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were shut out until the seventh, when Mo Vaughn
opened the inning with his 33rd home run off of reliever John
Frascatore. It was good for his 100th RBI. Vaughn is just the
second Angels player with back-to-back 100 RBI seasons (Wally
Joyner did it in 1986-87).
</P>
<P>
   Ron Gant homered in the ninth, the Angels' 123rd homer at Edison
Field, breaking the franchise record for most homers at home. The
previous mark of 122 was established in the Angels' first season,
1961, when they played in cozy Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels ended August at 11-15, their first losing month all
season.
</P>
<P>
   But, all was not bad. In the past month they still managed to
gain a game on first-place Seattle in the AL West.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 0238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
