<HEADER>
A7075 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-BREWERS-L     08-31 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-BREWERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH ONE TO SWALLOW FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE -- Eight marvelous innings and 106 pitches by Darren
Dreifort was wasted as the result of five pitches by Terry Adams
and an errant throw by young shortstop Alex Cora.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the predominant topic in the Los Angeles Dodgers'
clubhouse - after Milwaukee's Richie Sexson singled in the winning
run with none out in the ninth inning to give the Brewers a 3-2
victory Wednesday at County Stadium - was a controversial call back
in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dodgers leading 1-0 with runners on second and third
and two out, Adrian Beltre hit a sharp single a few steps to the
left of Brewers shortstop Mark Loretta. Mark Grudzielanek scored
and a throw home allowed Beltre to move to second while Shawn Green
stopped at third.
</P>
<P>
   However, second base umpire Jeff Kellogg ruled the ball glanced
off Green's heel and called him out, which ended the inning. The
run didn't count.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely brutal call,'' Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros
said. ``That's not an interpretive call. It's not like, `Well,
maybe it was a ball, maybe it was a strike.' It either hit him or
it didn't hit him. To make a call like that, you would think you
would have to see it. My understanding is he heard it, and the
shortstop, who has the play right there, didn't get up and argue.
Just a brutal call. There's no reason to make that call. None.
Zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Green said the ball was a few feet behind him and initially was
confused as to why he was called out. Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
argued and Kellogg asked home plate umpire Eric Cooper for help.
Cooper didn't overturn the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Kellogg) said he didn't see it, but he thought he heard it,''
Johnson said. ``The only thing I don't like about that call is you
have to see it and it's got to change direction. You can't hear
something and assume that it nicked him. Greenie said it didn't
come close.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential for a big inning existed, especially since
Milwaukee starter Jamey Wright walked the first three batters.
However, to what extent the Dodgers suffered is debatable.
</P>
<P>
   Though it clearly altered the game, the Dodgers had other
chances to get to Wright, who survived eight innings. Wright wasn't
as dominating as Dreifort but struck out a career high 11 and -
even though he's without a decision in his last three starts - he
got the Brewers to the ninth inning tied 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee's first two runs came via homers. Geoff Jenkins tied
it 1-1 with a two-out shot in the first inning and Tyler Houston
made it 2-1 in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The winning run was the result of a mistake. Jenkins led off
against reliever Adams (6-7) with a bloop single to left field.
Cora, who almost came up with the catch, grabbed the ball on one
hop, spun and threw wildly to second thinking Jenkins was heading
there. However, Jenkins didn't move up a base until Cora's throw
sailed well over Grudzielanek's head.
</P>
<P>
   Sexson then hit the second pitch he saw from Adams into center
field to knock in Jenkins and hand the Dodgers their second loss in
10 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a stupid play, that's it,'' Cora said. ``I tried to
make the catch and sometimes, defensively, I try to be too
aggressive. I thought he was going to try to go to second and I
threw it away. Cost us the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Green had a chance to make the first-inning call a little less
relevant, but with the bases loaded and two outs in the fifth
inning, he tapped weakly in front of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers did tie it 2-2 on Jim Leyritz's RBI double in the
sixth, but another opportunity was lost in the seventh when Karros
grounded into a double play with two runners on and one out. Wright
got his third double play in the eighth when Leyritz grounded to
third to start it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had (Wright) on the ropes. Who knows what we would have
ended up getting in that (first) inning,'' said Dreifort, who
allowed four hits. ``You end up losing by one run in the bottom of
the ninth and you definitely look back on it and it makes a
difference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
