<HEADER>
A7141 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-INJURIES-B     08-31 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INJURIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUBACH, MERLONI TOOK THEIR LUMPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ With his injured left arm dangling
awkwardly at his side, Brian Daubach abruptly rushed out of the Red
Sox clubhouse Wednesday for an unscheduled trip to Boston that will
determine if the team's second-leading home run hitter will play
again this season.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a woozy Lou Merloni sat in front of his locker, trying
to sift through the wreckage of his short memory to piece together
the events the night before that also knocked him out of the Sox
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   And all around there was the lingering tension from Tuesday
night's Bean Brawl by the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all things, they embarrassed themselves,'' Sox catcher
Jason Varitek said of a Tampa Bay team that had eight members
ejected, five of them in connection with their game-long war
against Daubach.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly angry, right fielder Trot Nixon said, ``I'm not even
going to waste my breath talking about that team over there.''
</P>
<P>
   And reliever Derek Lowe, noting that the Red Sox finish the
regular season with three games against Tampa Bay, said that could
be the time when Boston exacts its payback for the Daubach fiasco.
He said the Sox cannot risk losing a key pitcher to a possible
suspension in their race for a playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   But the team might not mind losing a pitcher who is called up
from the minors in September and does not factor into postseason
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have come out on top last night in hitting guys,''
Lowe said, ``but there's September, when you have September
call-ups, and then you can do the same thing. It might be a totally
different situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams continued to defend their actions as the
commissioner's office began an investigation. Major League
officials received videotapes of the game and spoke with Red Sox
general manager Dan Duquette and his Devil Rays counterpart, Chuck
LaMar.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams, who was ejected in the first inning, is
expected to be suspended not only for charging the mound but for
briefly returning to the field when both benches emptied again in
the seventh inning. He was quickly ushered back to the Tampa Bay
clubhouse by teammates.
</P>
<P>
   LaMar said he expects the league to act swiftly in suspending
Williams. But he argued that Williams charged Pedro Martinez in
self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no retaliation an opposing team can have against a
pitcher,'' LaMar said, citing the designated hitter rule. ``So
you're going to have hitters trying to protect themselves, and in
Gerald Williams's case, whether we condone it or not, he went out
there because he thought he was right.''
</P>
<P>
   LaMar also insisted that Tampa Bay was justified in sending out
three pitchers to try to hit Daubach with pitches. Two succeeded
and a third came dangerously close. All three were ejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tampa Bay Devil Rays feel strongly that Brian Daubach did
not conduct himself in a professional manner when the fight broke
out,'' LaMar sid. ``Our actions throughout the rest of the night
indicate that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rays believe Daubach threw ``cheap shots'' in the pile of
players on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no place in baseball for what he did,'' said Devil
Rays closer Roberto Hernandez, who gave Daubach a two-handed shove
in the back following the pileup.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Martinez insisted his pitch to Williams was about
establishing control of the inside of the plate, LaMar said, ``We
spent the rest of the game trying to establish the inside part of
the plate against Brian Daubach.''
</P>
<P>
   His regret? ``In our pursuit of trying to establish the inside
part of the plate, we could have done a better job.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they should have hit him more often.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach was headed back to Boston for more tests on his arm.
Before he left, he said preliminary X-rays determined the arm was
not fractured. The Sox listed the injury as a hyperextended left
elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all I know,'' Daubach said, declining further comment
until he returns to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach's loss comes at crucial time for the Sox, as they brace
for the September stretch drive. He was the team's hottest hitter
on the seven-game road trip that ended Wednesday and one of the
only power threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to play with what we've got,'' Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams said. ``We've got to keep going. No excuses, no sour
grapes, no nothing. We go play.''
</P>
<P>
   But Daubach's teammates were still hot over the ongoing effort
by the Rays to hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk about cheap shots,'' Merloni said. ``I didn't see
any cheap shots. When you have a guy charging Pedro Martinez, you
do everything you can to prevent anything from happening to him.
Daubach just came in to try to get him out of there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, a very important part of our team could be
out for a while for something that never should have happened in
the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Varitek, who was near Merloni at the bottom of the pile, agreed
that Daubach acted appropriately. The corroboration is important
because Merloni may have been fuzzy at the time. Daubach had just
dived onto Merloni, causing his head and neck injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Merloni spent Tuesday night in Bayfront Medical Center after
suffering a mild concussion. He said he continued to suffer
headaches and a stiff neck Wednesday but hoped to be able to play
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   When Merloni beat out an infield hit with two outs in the second
inning Tuesday night, he said he ``felt weird and just kind of shut
down. I don't remember how we got the third out.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was a game anyone else who was there will not soon
forget.
</P>
<P>
   Said Tampa Bay coach Jose Cardenal, who was ejected, ``It was a
wild and crazy night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 0912EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
