<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 09:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7160 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-COMMENT-BO     08-31 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDRO'S REPUTATION HAS PRECEDED HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes two Pedro hit-by-pitch text tables.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has gone on too long unpunished. His identity is known to
everyone in both leagues, this righthanded Red Sox pitcher from a
Latin country who is hitting batters at an alarming rate. Two years
ago, he hit more batters in a season than any pitcher in the '90s.
Nineteen batters felt his wrath in 1998. This season, he's leading
the major leagues again.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Robinson, how much longer are you going to let Rolando
Arrojo get away with such reckless behavior? That's right, our
newest Cuban import leads the majors with 16 hit batsmen, 12 while
he was with the Colorado Rockies, four since joining the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, you thought we were talking about the little Dominicano?
</P>
<P>
   That's how reputation intrudes on reality. When have you ever
heard Arrojo described as a headhunter? But Pedro Martinez, who
thought he'd left that all behind him in Montreal, when manager
Felipe Alou and pitching coach Joe Kerrigan went to the league
president to plead his case for him, is now back to being Public
Enemy No. 1 among opposing hitters.
</P>
<P>
   True, Martinez has hit 14 batters this season, most in the
American League. But in the previous four seasons, he hasn't come
close to leading the league: 3 in 1996, 9 in '97, 8 in '98, and 9
in '99.
</P>
<P>
   Gentleman Jim Lonborg hit 19 men in the Impossible Dream year of
1967. Compared with Lonborg, Martinez has been a prince.
</P>
<P>
   But all it has taken is a few pitches for Martinez to be saddled
with his previous reputation, and this time it may be tougher to
shake. I am in no way an apologist for Martinez. He is not afraid
to go up and in on a hitter, especially one with whom he has an
issue.
</P>
<P>
   He buzzed Einar Diaz after the Indians' backup catcher hit two
doubles off him on that May day when he later hit Robbie Alomar as
payback for Charles Nagy hitting Jose Offerman, leading to
Martinez's five-game suspension. He drilled Matt Lawton of the
Twins last year for stepping out of the box one too many times. And
yes, he went upstairs on Gerald Williams of the Devil Rays Tuesday
night, delivering a message to the first batter of the game that he
was not letting the expansion team have its way with him again,
like it did two weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   And if a batter doesn't know how to spin away, like Diaz of the
Tribe, or should happen to be plunked, like Williams, Martinez
isn't the type to offer apologies.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had a right to be upset. The fastball from Martinez
could have broken his hand. But even one of the Devil Rays' own,
catcher John Flaherty, admitted he was embarrassed at the clumsy
way in which the Devil Rays tried to even the score, with a parade
of pitchers taking aim (and generally missing) Brian Daubach.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach remained a target Wednesday, the Devil Rays making a
show of how they had sent a tape to the commissioner's office,
which they claim proves Daubach had performed dirty deeds while in
the scrum created when Williams charged the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Globe assistant sports editor Joe Sullivan, who confesses to
having once covered the Yankees, pondered what the Devil Rays hoped
to accomplish. ``What are they going to show,'' he asked, ``that
Daubach was fighting during a fight?''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach may have paid a high price for his part in the brawl. He
flew back to Boston to have an MRI taken of his sore left elbow.
But what of the future cost to Martinez, because of his reputation
for extracting retribution.
</P>
<P>
   That reputation has gotten so large, when his brother Ramon hit
Oakland's Olmedo Saenz with a pitch the day after Saenz had taken
Pedro deep, Saenz blamed Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   Review the batters Martinez has hit with pitches this season,
and it becomes obvious there was no malice aforethought. Miguel
Tejada of the A's hit a big homer off Martinez last season, but
when Pedro hit him in April, Tejada absolved the pitcher, saying
his good buddy from the Dominican would never intentionally hit
him.
</P>
<P>
   Royce Clayton of the Rangers was plunked with two outs and a
runner already on first. Chuck Knoblauch and Jorge Posada of the
Yankees both had two strikes on them when they were hit with
pitches in the ninth in Yankee Stadium, when Martinez was trying to
hold onto the 2-0 lead Trot Nixon had given him in the top of the
inning against Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   On June 14 in Fenway Park, Martinez hit Bernie Williams of the
Yankees with a 2-0 count, runners on first and third in the first
inning. Paul Konerko of the White Sox, one out and nobody on in the
second inning. Hitting Shannon Stewart of the Blue Jays in his
first at-bat after he'd led off with a homer wasn't as innocent,
but when all is said and done, only three players plunked by
Martinez would have any chance of making an accusation stick.
</P>
<P>
   Does that sound like a headhunter to you?
</P>
<P>
   And yet, partly because of his reputation, Martinez did not dare
retaliate against Tampa. He didn't want to be thrown out of a game
the Sox needed to win, but neither could he risk a suspension that
could be expected to be worse, because he'd be a multiple offender.
</P>
<P>
   And with a month left in the season, we are reminded of the
words of Tigers manager Phil Garner, who in the wake of Martinez's
suspension in May suggested he might be tempted to order his
pitcher to hit a Red Sox batter early, daring Martinez to
retaliate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we got down to the pennant I tell you what, I'd have to
think about it,'' Garner said at the time. ``I'd have to think
about sending a guy out there and saying, `Hit the first guy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers began the night just five games out of the wild-card
lead. Include the Tigers, and there are nine teams still in
postseason contention.
</P>
<P>
   It could be a long, hot September for Pedro and the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
PEDRO'S INSIDE STUFF
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
