<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 09:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7168 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     08-31 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE W. BUSH: RARELY SMOOTH, NEVER SPEECHLESS 

</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether George W. Bush will make a good president I cannot say,
but he certainly knows how to give a speech.
</P>
<P>
   Not a comprehensible speech, necessarily, but one that is often
rich in insights, nuance and subtle shades of meaning that reveal
themselves to only a select few listeners, specifically those who
have been drinking heavily.
</P>
<P>
   To say that Bush has problems with the English language is like
saying tourists from Michigan have problems with their turn
signals; it just doesn't adequately describe the scope of the
problem. (I have no idea if George W. uses his turn signals
properly, nor do I have any idea how many tourists from Michigan
describe our nuclear arsenal as ``tacular'' weapons. I apologize to
both sides if there was any misunderstanding.)
</P>
<P>
   After a few slow weeks of relatively gaffe-free speaking, the
Republican presidential candidate went to Des Moines last Monday
and in a mere 16 minutes showed the world that he is still the
undisputed king of mangled language.
</P>
<P>
   Bush warmed up the crowd by saying, ``When we carry Iowa in
November, it'll mean the end of four years of Clinton-Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush must be the only person in America for whom the
Clinton-Gore administration seemed to last only four years. For
everyone else, it lasted at least 20.
</P>
<P>
   What the 2,300 Republicans who paid $100 each for the state
party fund-raiser thought of another Bush remark is hard to say,
but it's likely they were terrified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a free-trader,'' Bush said. ``I will work to end terrors _
tariffs and barriers _ everywhere, across the world.''
</P>
<P>
   A Reuters account of the event said that the crowd was generally
enthusiastic and cheered Bush frequently, even if they couldn't
make heads or tails of what he was saying. Bush's comment on
security policy, however, left everyone in the crowd momentarily
stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot let terrorists and rogue nations hold this nation
hostile or hold our allies hostile,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Bush was saying that America and its allies are quite
capable of being hostile without the help of terrorists and rogue
nations. Or something.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, of course, has been putting his own personal spin on the
mother tongue (ouch!) since the first days of his campaign. The
Web, as you might expect, offers a cornucopia of Bushisms, the best
collection being Jacob Weisberg's of Slate magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The scary part is that if you read enough of these things, they
actually start to make sense. Bush's take on the federal budget is
a good example:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly a budget. It's got a lot of numbers in it.''
</P>
<P>
   What else could it possibly be? A grocery list?
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of groceries, Bush was possibly thinking of ways to
liven up the dinner hour when he said to the Greater Nashua, N.H.,
Chamber of Commerce, ``I know how hard it is for you to put food on
your family.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. is from Texas and it's possible his mind was out
riding the open range when this came out of his mouth last February
in Florence, S.C.:
</P>
<P>
   ``The senator has got to understand if he's going to have _ he
can't have it both ways. He can't take the high horse and then
claim the low road.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's professors at Yale might be the ones to speak to this
next quote, also uttered before the poor, suffering people of
Florence:
</P>
<P>
   ``Rarely is the question asked: Is our children learning?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they is and maybe they ain't, Mr. Bush, but you certainly
seem to have plenty of confidence in your own intellectual
abilities, as evidenced by your remark in U.S. News &AMP; World Report:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anybody who doesn't think I'm smart enough to handle
the job is underestimating.''
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
