<HEADLINE>
$ADV02 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For Release: Saturday, Sept. 2, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: Please check local listings for time and channel. All
times listed are EDT unless otherwise specified.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about grumpy old men.
</P>
<P>
   China's President Jiang Zemin answers some tough questions from
Mike Wallace in a rare two-segment interview on CBS' ''60 Minutes''
Sunday at 7, which comes two days before Jiang's scheduled visit to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   We'll expect human rights to be high on the agenda, as well as
the complex issues of trade between the two countries and possibly
even a mention of Tibet. Wallace may be getting up there in years,
but he's still one of the best face-to-face interviewers, and he's
certainly not shy.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the only two-guys-sitting-around-talking show of note
this weekend. Although it may be at the other end of the spectrum
from ''60 Minutes'' in terms of global importance, a lot of folks
will be tuning in curiously to this weekend's debut of the
syndicated ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper &AMP; the Movies'' (various days and times,
check local listings).
</P>
<P>
   Since the death of his longtime partner Gene Siskel, Ebert has
been working with various guest hosts, but he says he's found his
most comfortable match in his fellow Chicago Sun-Times columnist
Richard Roeper. There's been some minor grumbling online because
Roeper is a metro columnist, not a film critic, but we seem to
recall from our days in Chicago that he's a pop-culture sponge and,
well, we're all for columnists getting lucrative TV gigs.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, the guys take an early look at Oscar contenders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
