<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WHOLE TRUTH ABOUT INTERNET HOAXES, ESPECIALLY OHIO  
 BY DR. EMILIO BOMBAY  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: You would do a great service to your readers by
telling us whether this e-mail message is real: ``Free e-mail no
more! Vote NO on Bill 602P!!! Bill 602P will permit the Federal
Government to charge a five-cent charge on every delivered e-mail.
... Our congressional representative, Tony Schnell (R) has even
suggested a `$20-$40 per month surcharge on all Internet service.'
''
</P>
<P>
   _ Can't Afford More Taxes
</P>
<P>
   DEAR CAN'T: I'm really disappointed in the quality of the hoaxes
we're seeing nowadays. In my time, when we wanted to mess with
peoples' heads, we did a much better job. Bet you thought there
really was a guy named Steve Jobs, didn't you? Ha! Pure fiction. I
mean, really, starting an industry in a garage? Get real!
</P>
<P>
   The claptrap you sent me is so full of holes it looks like my
laundry. You didn't really need me to tell you this is completely
bogus, did you? You did? Now I'm really depressed.
</P>
<P>
   Look, just because something is in writing and sounds
quasi-possible doesn't mean you should automatically accept it as
gospel. Hmmm. That's sort of how this column is supposed to work.
Let's try a different approach.
</P>
<P>
   When you get spam like this, please, please, please don't
forward it until you research it. The first thing I did was go to
Yahoo! and search for ``Bill 602P.'' The first hit I got was to the
Urban Legends Archive (www.urbanlegends.com). Does that give you a
clue about your e-mail tax?
</P>
<P>
   The site does a good job of picking the hoax apart, point by
point, but it's nothing you couldn't have found out for yourself.
The biggest giveaway is the name of the bill, 602P. Sure, most of
us slept through high-school civics, but it's pretty common
knowledge that House resolutions begin with ``H.R.'' A more
experienced hoax-meister would have called it H.R. 4602.
</P>
<P>
   Second, there is no Tony Schnell in Congress, as a quick trip to
www.house.gov would have shown. Third, there are other people,
addresses and firms mentioned in the full letter that don't exist
either.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that didn't stop Congress from reacting to the
nonexistent bill. Last May, Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich., actually
drafted legislation to block any such plan. And Rep. Michael G.
Oxley, R-Ohio, vice chairman of the Commerce Committee's
Subcommittee on Telecommunications, Trade and Consumer Protection,
has posted a strongly worded denial on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that denial raises other questions. Is Oxley part
of the hoax? You probably didn't know this, but his ``state'' is
just another urban myth, one of the nation's longest-running
practical jokes. In 1803, fun-loving President Thomas Jefferson
casually mentioned to a few gullible reporters that a 17th state
carved from American Indian territory would be added to the Union.
</P>
<P>
   The nonexistent ``state'' was christened Ohio. It was even given
electoral votes. To this day, anyone who professes to be from
somewhere in Ohio or to have seen the mythical Cincinnati Reds and
Cleveland Browns is in on the joke.
</P>
<P>
   It's true! You read it here! Tell everyone you know!
</P>
<P>
   (What if ``Dr. Emilio Bombay'' is a hoax, too? Wouldn't those
things he said that were untrue be true then? Now we're all
confused. If you can clear this up, write to
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: (817)
390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial
systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-25-00 1213EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
