<HEADLINE>
A MAYOR'S PLUG; REDEEMABLE STAMPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 750 local governments now use the Web site operated by
NetClerk to put the construction-permit process online. But so far,
only the mayor of San Francisco, Willie Brown, has become part of
NetClerk's advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, NetClerk put a picture of Brown and the city's seal
on www.netclerk.com, the company's Web site, along with a letter
the mayor had written praising the company for, among other things,
helping reduce lines at city hall.
</P>
<P>
   So far, NetClerk's PermitCentral service has been used to issue
more than 1,000 building permits in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we enjoy interacting with each and every person who
comes to city hall, waiting in line may not be the best use of a
contractor's time,'' the mayor wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The letter may have been less than a spontaneous testimonial.
Jon Fisher, founder of NetClerk, said the company began discussing
a ``public relations partnership'' with the San Francisco's mayor's
office about a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   So how does a letterhead partnership play out?
</P>
<P>
   ``The city of San Francisco is well known for its forward
thinking, technological savvy,'' the mayor wrote. ``NetClerk offers
a perfect example of how technology can improve a current system to
the satisfaction of all parties involved.''
</P>
<P>
   For Brown, of course, the satisfaction comes from bolstering his
image as a technology supporter and promoter of the Bay Area's
high-technology economy.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, NetClerk, based in South San Francisco, is part
of that economy.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   Redeemable Stamps Online
</P>
<P>
   The Carlson Cos. could be called the grandfather of customer
loyalty programs, dating to 1938, when the company first started
giving out Gold Bond Trading Stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Now Curtis C. Nelson, grandson of the founder and Carlson's
chief operating officer, wants to take it back to its roots _ this
time, online.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson, Minneapolis-based owner of the TGIF restaurant chain,
Radisson Hotels, Thomas Cook Travel and a long list of other
businesses, is beginning to offer redeemable Gold Points to
customers on a new site, 24k.com.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the site will be the online hub of the
company's rewards program, both as a shopping portal and an online
redemption catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Much like S&AMP;H Green Stamps, Gold Bond Trading Stamps were doled
out by the thousands the last half century, typically as a way for
supermarkets, gas stations and shops to differentiate themselves in
competitive markets.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers redeemed their stamps for a range of consumer items
like toasters and hair dryers _ that is, until they began shopping
at discount warehouses and the practice fell by the wayside.
</P>
<P>
   The online customer loyalty business is already fairly crowded,
what with S&AMP;H and others already doling out electronic trading
stamps.
</P>
<P>
   But today's online loyalty programs are an entirely different
beast from their predecessors. Among other things, they take
advantage of Internet data collection that allows merchants to
pitch specific products to customers based on their past shopping
behavior. And these days, customers can redeem their stamps for
much more than toasters.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson says that Carlson has a leg up on other redemption
programs because of the variety of brands it owns. And where it
does not have its own brand, he says, the company will join forces
with other companies to fill the void. Already, 24k.com either owns
or has a partnership with 1,500 sites that offer Gold Points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective,'' Nelson said, ``is to touch the customer 365
days a year, across all facets of their life.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
