<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-FAMILY-COLUMN0829-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Long-distance calls via Web come free, if not so easily
 &HT;    By Anne Meyers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Imagine being so excited about something that you
called yourself to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   I made my mouse tracks across the on-screen dialpad, clicking
along the digits of my phone number. I heard the distant sound of
ringing through my computer's speakers, followed by my recorded
voice. I was alone in my home, and I told my voice mail, ``It
works, it really works.''
</P>
<P>
   My first Internet telephone call was to my own answering
machine. I was amazed and excited when it worked. I suppose that's
why I even left myself a message.
</P>
<P>
   Long-distance phone service was my major vice and a steady
expense ever since I had the money to pay for it. Internet
telephone offers a chance to save money.
</P>
<P>
   I was a reluctant convert to Internet telephone calls. My
neighbor Susan asked me what I knew about the technology, and I was
ashamed to say I had no first-hand experience. I gave her some
articles about it, and she picked a provider.
</P>
<P>
   She invited me to her house to help walk her through the first
call. The process did not go smoothly, but that short exposure made
me curious.
</P>
<P>
   I could understand Susan's motivation to find free or cheap
phone calls. Her daughter met a foreign student who returned to
Germany. Their phone exchanges could get expensive, and Susan
wanted to find a way to reduce the costs.
</P>
<P>
   After fiddling with Susan's setup for a while, I came home and
got to work on my own computer. I downloaded PC-to-Phone software
from Deltathree's Web site (www.deltathree.com).
</P>
<P>
   It took work, but I managed to set it up. Once I was ready to
make a call, I dug out the microphone that came packaged with our
computer.
</P>
<P>
   After the initial call to myself, I was eager to test the
technology on real conversation. Call No. 2 was to my friend Marci.
She was friendly, as always. Then she said, ``I'm sorry, but who is
this?''
</P>
<P>
   Next I called my parents. My mother asked if I was in the car,
and she struggled through a short phone call with me before asking
me to call on a ``real'' phone later.
</P>
<P>
   The microphone is not great for this purpose. My call recipients
also had the distraction of hearing their own voices loud and clear
from my computer speakers while they talked. To optimize your
chances for quality sound, you need a headset that plugs into your
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Electronics stores carry them, and some of the Internet phone
providers sell them from their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   But the exciting news is, even with the bad microphone, the
calls worked. And the price was right; the call was free. Plus,
this technology allowed me to make phone calls while I was online.
</P>
<P>
   I only have one telephone line at home, which I use for my
computer and telephone. When I surf the Web, the phone line is tied
up and calls are sent to my BellSouth voice mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   Using PC-to-Phone, I can use the Internet and make phone calls
through my computer at the same time. I can also check my voice
mail messages by dialing in to the voice mail center. It simply
requires opening another browser window.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Deltathree, there are several companies offering
free calls from personal computers to traditional phones.
Dialpad.com (www.dialpad.com) and PhoneFree.com (www.phonefree.com)
offer free, unlimited calls within the United States. Other
companies like Net2Phone (www.net2phone.com) and MediaRing.com
(www.mediaring.com) offer discounted calls within the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The technology still has imperfections. There are echoes and
voice delays. Some calls are reminiscent of cheap mobile phones or
international calls of 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of those cases where you get something for nothing
and sacrifice a little quality.
</P>
<P>
   One way to improve quality is to buy a headset.
</P>
<P>
   Net2Phone makes a headset that plugs into the back of a
computer. It sells at many local retailers for about $45. Or you
may find headphones that you can order via one of the Internet
phone providers. Deltathree and Dialpad.com offer a selection on
their sites ranging in price from $10 to $75.
</P>
<P>
   To make the calls, you need a computer, an Internet connection,
a sound card, a microphone and speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-28-00 1205EDT &QL;
</P>
