<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-TOOLS0829-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Reader input adds some clarity to discussion about digital
photos
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The recent column on digital photography provoked some
response, both from the unanointed, like me, and the experienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am also an old photographer ready to go digital. But right
now, the more I read, the more confused I become. A number of my
friends have chosen the Sony Mavica line, which uses a floppy disc.
This is appealing to me because it seems so easy. Now Sony is
adding Memory Stick storage. Do you have any suggestions, based on
your own research? Thanks for any info you might have.''
</P>
<P>
   Using 3.5 floppies for image storage provides enormous freedom _
you don't have to carry a laptop or some other expensive storage
device if you intend to make a lot of pictures on a trip. As far as
I can see, the only sure disadvantage is that the Mavica is a lot
larger than most digital cameras. There is also the question of
whether it takes longer to record the image on a floppy than on a
Memory Stick, but I haven't found the answer to that.
</P>
<P>
   Artist Will Christopher passes along some excellent information
for all of us seeking to get into digital images:
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I just this year made that plunge, perhaps my experience
might be of interest to you. Check out this Web site:
www.imaging-resource.com. It will give you all the information you
need and quite a bit more on any digital camera on the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher extols the virtues of the Agfa Ephoto 1680, which
provides 1.9 megapixels, 3X optical zoom and 2X digital zoom. He
paid $429 for it.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site he mentions appears to be just what all of us
beginners need.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Eisele has a related question:
</P>
<P>
   ``Approximately a year ago a piece of software came out which
allows an individual to take data from a VCR or video camera and
make still photos through their computer. Any ideas? It was
advertised on several radio shows about a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   This requires hardware, not just software. The pioneer in this
field is the Snappy Video Snapshot, a little box to be connected
between your VCR/camera and your computer. A similar and perhaps
more sophisticated function is now being included in some video
display cards.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Langan, a reader in Colorado, wonders about the
durability of prints made on an inkjet printer. While the maker of
the Pictorico line of paper I reviewed recently states that its
Photo Gallery High-Gloss White paper is archival, I suspect the
greatest durability lies in the images themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Doubtless over the next 50 years or so there will be advances in
storage formats, and JPG and GIF files will become obsolete. But it
is hard to imagine that there won't be provisions for migrating
images from those formats to new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-28-00 1205EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
