 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Worry not about a bot
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   I've started paying more attention to applications that place
bots on my computer. You should make readers aware that many
programs place bots on their system.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dan Mares, Lawrenceville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: So, what's a bot and what does it do? Bot is short for
robot. It's a software tool that sifts through computer data. It
has been programmed to search and recover information.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Developers send bots on missions with specific
instructions. Web search engines dispatch bots to snag relevant URL
information from other servers. Shopping bots are big. They scan
the Web for prices for online products. Bots can be newshounds,
too, retrieving the latest in news, finance, sports and
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: They help maintain intricate Web sites. They monitor site
links to make sure they're still alive when Web pages are removed
or relocated.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: There is some concern about how they are used. They're
constantly retrieving info and have been called ``spiders'' or
``Web worms.'' This can give the impression that they multiply.
That's not really the case. They use standard Web protocols.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Bots can place demands on a network. There are newer
protocols being designed every day to standardize and limit those
demands. Developers are asked to strike a balance when designing
and deploying a bot.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: So, bots can be good, bots can be bad? In general, bots
are babes.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Readers:
</P>
<P>
   Here's a fun Web site to bookmark. Cruise to www.surprise.com.
Thank you, Dave Garr, for sending it in.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: It's a gift site that doesn't try to sell you anything.
It's big on pointing you to ideas for fun gifts anywhere on the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Click on ``Who's it for'' to pick a present for
grandparents, the baby sitter or your child's coach.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: The ``What Occasion?'' options cover retirement,
housewarmings, graduations, birthdays. Another ``must click'' is
``What are they like?''
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Do they love to throw parties? Perhaps a maid service or
a bubble machine. A gadgeteer? No problem. There are PDAs, a
folding shovel and a wristwatch camera. The list goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Buying for someone with a wacky sense of humor? There's
custom toilet paper or a glow-in-the-dark basketball. For pet pals,
there's a puppy pager.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Ideas are submitted by folks who surf the site.
Surprise.com will pay $100 for ideas that are among the 1,000 most
popular ideas for a three-month period.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Get downright organized about your gift-giving. Set up an
account. Schedule e-mail reminders for anniversaries, weddings,
etc., and keep track of gift ideas you've saved while browsing.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
