<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If Bush loses
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Some Texas Republicans have been contemplating
their slots in a George W. Bush presidential administration. Others
are looking ahead to the political musical chairs that will start
when the Texas governor moves into the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the Texas Senate are jockeying, with varying
degrees of subtlety, to become lieutenant governor when Rick Perry
moves up to replace Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But as Democrat Al Gore's bounce in the polls was a little
stronger than the Bush folks would have hoped and Bush has
struggled to fill in the details of his trillion-dollar tax cut
idea, ponder this:
</P>
<P>
   What if Bush loses?
</P>
<P>
   Personally, it may not be all that devastating. Bush has lost
before _ a Midland-to-Lubbock congressional seat in 1978 to
then-Democrat Kent Hance _ and watched his dad lose in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But a loss might change Bush's oft-stated belief that as
governor, he has the best job in the world. What if his hard-won
1999 tax cut runs into a too-tight state budget in 2001?
</P>
<P>
   And then, take legislative and congressional redistricting _
please. Even with Republicans playing strong roles for the first
time ever, it will have the grace of the Houston Fat Stock Show. It
won't be pretty. And probably not fun.
</P>
<P>
   And a defeated, lame-duck Bush might not be able to keep the lid
on the Republicans pols' ambitions for 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Perry has said he'll run for governor whether Bush wins or
loses, assuming Bush doesn't seek a third term. U.S. Sen. Kay
Bailey Hutchison says she probably wouldn't run against an
incumbent Republican governor. But if Bush loses, she's running.
</P>
<P>
   Expect her to spend a few million bucks of her federal campaign
swag this year to swamp Democrat Gene Kelly, who won the nomination
even though he's never danced in a movie and has no money to spend
on his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose is to keep the Hutchison brand hot, just in case.
Word filters back that she'd much rather be one governor living in
a mansion in Austin than one of a body of 100 in D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Perry continues to fill his coffers using Washington-style,
heavy-handed fund raising so he can stare down other competitors,
including Hutchison. As the most powerful lieutenant governor in
the land, he's in a good position to do that.
</P>
<P>
   But as an incumbent senator who'll still be around if she loses
a governor's race, Hutchison also is in a good fundraising
position. If Bush loses, it'll be interesting to see who blinks.
</P>
<P>
   Some political prognosticators speculate about a Perry-Hutchison
deal: Perry defers to Hutchison for governor and runs for
re-election; she then appoints him to the U.S. Senate. But that
kind of deal could be troublesome for Perry in the special election
that would come soon after the appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Attorney General John Cornyn, who like Perry was
making the speechifying rounds to other state delegations at the
Republican National Convention, continues to look like the guy
central casting would pick for a senator.
</P>
<P>
   Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander reportedly is eyeing the
lieutenant governor's job if Perry leaves for whatever reason.
</P>
<P>
   Land Commissioner David Dewhurst, a millionaire a couple hundred
times over, has seemed pointed at senator or governor _ maybe with
lieutenant governor as a stepping stone. But he is facing a
divorce, which could affect his plans.
</P>
<P>
   Face it: 2001 and 2002 are going to be intriguing political
theater, whether the governor is in Austin or in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   McNeely writes about politics for the American-Statesman. You
may contact him at dmcneely(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
