<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dispatches from Dreamsville: Bitten by the stinging snake
 &HT;    For release Friday, Sept. 1, 2000
 &HT;    (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional column in
which readers share with Cox senior writer Joe Murray their
memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or at
least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
 &HT;    By Clarence Roy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not often that you have a chance to witness a historic
event. Mine came on a spring day in 1952 at Lafargue High School,
located near the banks of the Red River in Avoyelles Parish, La. It
was during an eighth-grade science class I was teaching.
</P>
<P>
   I was lecturing on the characteristics of poisonous snakes when
Elton Lee Lofton, a redhead from lower Vick, raised his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you believe in stinging snakes?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Elton, I don't,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandpa said you wouldn't,'' Elton said.
</P>
<P>
   This last remark annoyed me somewhat, but I ignored it.
Addressing the class, I explained:
</P>
<P>
   ``What Elton is referring to is a superstition, in which a
particular kind of snake, when cornered, defends itself by
injecting its venom through a stinger lodged on the tip of its
tail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no scientific evidence that such a snake
exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Elton's hand was up again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got proof that there are stinging snakes,'' he announced.
</P>
<P>
   He was not going to drop the subject. ``All right,'' I said,
``make your case.''
</P>
<P>
   All eyes turned toward Elton. He folded his arms, leaned forward
and with uncharacteristic gravity began this tale:
</P>
<P>
   ``Last summer Grandpa decided that he needed a new barn. He made
a drawing of it, figured out the lumber and calculated how many
logs it would take. Then he got his good friend Jessie Cole to help
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bright and early the next day, they hitched up the team,
packed the saws and axes, and took off for the woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they didn't know is that a little farther down the trail
was a stinging snake all coiled up waiting for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That snake knew he couldn't get Grandpa or Jessie because they
were too high up in the wagon, but he could sting one of the mules.
</P>
<P>
   ``At just the right time when the team was in range, that snake
pointed his stinger at the closest mule and struck. But his aim was
off, and instead of hitting the mule, he hit the wagon tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stinging snakes have a lot of trouble hitting the target.
That's because the stinger is going one way, and the eyes are
looking the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, sir, those mules reared up something awful, and it took
the longest time to settle them down. In all the confusion, the
snake slithered away.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that snake must have put a bunch of poison in the wagon
tongue because it started swelling and swelling, and kept on
swelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandpa, Jessie and the mules just watched, mouths open, not
believing what they were seeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that tongue finally quit swelling, it was huge. Grandpa
looked at it for a long time before he spoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``'Jessie,' he said, 'I got an idea. We're not going to saw up
logs for that barn, no sir! We're going to saw up this here swole
up wagon tongue!'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, they walked back home, got plenty of help and hauled
that tongue to the sawmill where it was cut up for lumber - enough
lumber to build his barn and then some.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a while, but Grandpa and Jessie built that barn. Man,
it was pretty. There were stables for the mules, a corncrib,
hayloft, even room for his wagon to get it out of the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so proud of it that he decided to paint it bright red.
But he didn't have enough paint. So, in order to make it stretch,
he thinned it with turpentine _ a lot of turpentine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandpa and Jessie finished painting that barn one afternoon,
but the next day when they went to admire it, they were really
shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The barn had shrunk! It was so small it wouldn't accommodate a
family of mice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandpa said he could've just kicked himself real hard. He
should have known that the turpentine would have drawn the poison
out of the lumber.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough was enough. Elton had gone too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that you don't expect us to swallow this preposterous
yarn,'' I told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandpa said you wouldn't believe it,'' Elton said, ``so he
told me to bring the proof.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Elton reached under his desk and pulled out a brown
wrinkled bag. With great care, he removed the contents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thar she is!'' he said proudly as he laid the tiny structure
on his desk. Right before our eyes, sitting on Elton's desk was his
Grandpa's barn, complete in every detail. Elton had single-handedly
taken on the scientific community, and with undeniable proof,
backed it down.
</P>
<P>
   I broke the silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to apologize for being skeptical, Elton, but you must
admit that without that barn, you story would have been hard to
believe.''
</P>
<P>
   I then sent for the principal, Richard Guillory, who when told
the story and shown the evidence, was so impressed that he declared
that day ``Stinging Snake Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Elton graduated from Lafargue High School some years later, and
I lost track of him.
</P>
<P>
   But whenever I recall this incident, I feel of debt of gratitude
for all of the Elton Lee Loftons of this world.
</P>
<P>
   Just as a striking sunset affects an otherwise dull and dreary
sky, they find a way to add a little color to our sometimes very
ordinary days.
</P>
<P>
   So here's to you, Elton Lee Lofton, wherever you are.
</P>
<P>
   Others may have forgotten, but I will always remember the time
you ``proved'' to me and your classmates that stinging snakes are
for real.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Roy lives in Longbridge, La.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a story to share, sent it to Dispatches from
Dreamsville, c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email, jmurray(at)txucom.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
