<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reputable dealers best bet in getting replacement tires
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The tire crisis for Bridgestone/Firestone has become a
crisis for other tire manufacturers as well.
</P>
<P>
   As consumers look for alternatives as replacement tires, other
manufacturers find that this windfall of sales has left them unable
to respond to the unexpected demand. Goodyear expects to ramp up
production of the tires sizes in question by as much as 50 percent.
Other manufacturers are planning similar increases in production.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone has recalled about 6.5 million of its truck and
sport-utility tires after reports of tread separations leading to a
series of accidents mostly involving Ford Explorers.
</P>
<P>
   A dangerous byproduct of the lack of replacement Firestone
tires, coupled with some consumers' unwillingness to use Firestones
on their vehicles, has produced a situation where owners are close
to panic, looking at anything that is black, round and holds air
for their vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   That is a very dangerous scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear's Chuck Sinclair reports, ``Despite the best efforts of
all tire companies to supply the market as quickly as possible with
replacement tires ... any consumers seeking replacements may find
the tires extremely difficult to find . . . or even end up with the
wrong tires on their vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Goodyear, it's a serious mistake to use the wrong
size tires that could put the passengers at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some tips to be an informed vehicle owner and consumer
for buying replacement tires _ or any tires, for that matter:
</P>
<P>
   Refer to your vehicle owner's manual for recommended replacement
tire information and adhere strictly to those standards. If the
manual requires a tire with the designation ``P'' for p-metric
(which means the tire is a passenger car tire, which produces a
less trucklike ride), it should not be replaced with an ``LT'' or
light truck tire.
</P>
<P>
   Shop at a reputable retailer. Go to someone you trust who will
assist you in finding the right tire for your application.
</P>
<P>
   If you are unable to find a suitable replacement tire for your
vehicle, Goodyear engineers offer the following precautionary steps
until your tire of choice arrives at your retailer:
</P>
<P>
   Have your tires visually inspected by a professional. Any
reputable retailer should do this free of charge. Be advised that
the visual inspection can only detect what the eye can see, and
doesn't mean that there are no potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   Check your tire inflation once a week to be certain they meet
with the acceptable vehicle recommendations. There likely is a
difference between the maximum inflation listed on the sidewall of
the tire and what the tire vehicle manufacturer recommends for the
vehicle. Use the vehicle recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Do a walk-around inspection of your vehicle before driving it.
</P>
<P>
   Always fasten your seat belts, and make certain everyone in the
vehicle has their seat belt fastened as well.
</P>
<P>
   Obey all posted speed limits.
</P>
<P>
   Get in touch with your retailer to reserve a set of replacement
tires.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
