<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: This is the first in a five part series on air pollution.
 &HT;    It took human faces to alert Houston on air quality
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON, Texas _ It is said that Texas air pollution got built
into an issue in 1999 because Texas' jogger-in-chief was running
for president. Actually in this city it took some other runners to
make it so.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, the Deer Park High School girls cross country team
went for its daily four-miler. The whole squad shortly was bent
over coughing and wheezing, throats raw. Coach Mike Walker
instantly knew something was wrong. He was right.
</P>
<P>
   They had been flexing their lungs in what Los Angeles would have
classified a Stage 1 Smog Alert, which to the Houston man on the
street was a day without discernible alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle stories about the events at Deer Park brought
it all home.
</P>
<P>
   Though a smog advisory had been issued that day on a city Web
site, Houston had done little to warn anyone. Two days later, a
judge ordered the city to start advising schools on smog alerts.
</P>
<P>
   The respiratory distress signals of these runners were the
sounds of a city and state in denial.
</P>
<P>
   Deer Park is situated near the Houston Ship Channel close to
refineries and a host of petrochemical industries. As a source of
wealth, the refinery hub is a gold mine. As a source of pollution,
it is ground zero.
</P>
<P>
   However, experts say that if every refinery in the ship channel
closed, Houston could still be out of compliance for federal air
standards because of automobiles, utilities and other industrial
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Houston supplanted Los Angeles for the No. 1 ranking
in most air non-attainment days. Houston had 52 days in 1999 in
which it exceeded the federal level for ozone, Los Angeles had 41.
</P>
<P>
   This year, pressured by the Environmental Protection Agency, the
Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission issued a set of
lifestyle-crimping proposals for Houston, including:
</P>
<P>
   A 55 mph speed limit starting in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   An average 90 percent reduction in major industries' emissions
of smog-producing nitrous oxide.
</P>
<P>
   A ban on the use of heavy construction equipment and
gasoline-powered lawn equipment from 6 a.m. to noon.
</P>
<P>
   Such an attention-getter is not Houston's plight alone.
Dallas-Fort Worth, reclassified from ``moderate'' to ``serious'' in
non-attainment of federal air quality standards, also faces similar
restrictions, with Washington threatening to withhold $300 million
in highway funds.
</P>
<P>
   Tough? Merciless? Some will say the federal gods actually have
been merciful. The EPA is enforcing the Clean Air Act of 1990,
after all. That means, Thelma, that our policy makers have been on
the lamb 10 years. Texas is some runner.
</P>
<P>
   The Deer Park coach whose girls had such problems on that
October day now says they train with pollution in mind. If an alert
is issued, work-outs are abbreviated. And the team runs more often
in the evening, when the sun's cooking of nitrous oxide into ozone
is starting to subside. Walker admits that he now knows more about
ozone than he ever wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of a single night's run aren't what bothers Walker,
a lifelong Houston resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major worry is the long-term exposure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, much of Texas is being welcomed to Walker's world.
</P>
<P>
   Hearings start this month on the Dallas and Houston pollution
reduction plans. El Paso continues to struggle with some of the
nation's worst air pollution. Meanwhile, Austin, San Antonio, Tyler
and Longview are on the bubble for potential EPA sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   After soft-pedaling a major public health issue too long, Texas
is hearing foot steps.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
