<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7283 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-HIPHOP-AWARDS-     08-31 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-HIPHOP-AWARDS-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPN CUTS SMASH AND TRASH FROM HIP-HOP AWARDS BASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Thursday, Aug. 31, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When UPN announced it would be airing the Source Magazine
Hip-Hop Music Awards as planned on Aug. 29, I made a note to
program the VCR menu for two hours of rompin', stompin'
entertainment. This would be better than the WWF!
</P>
<P>
   It's not that I cared to have a video record of performances by
the likes of Mos Def, Dead Prez, Cash Money Millionaires or even
Lil' Bow Wow _ although I do prefer the work of Lil' Bow Wow to the
musical musings of Nate Dogg, Snoop Dogg and Underdog, come to
think of it.
</P>
<P>
   I just wanted to see the fights.
</P>
<P>
   The awards program itself took place Aug. 22, at the Pasadena
Civic Auditorium. (As is the case with those cutting-edge MTV
Awards programs, the not-so-cutting-edge execs behind these shows
like a built-in time delay _ the better to delete expletives, edit
some of the more incoherent ramblings, ``tile out'' any inadvertent
nudity and most important, find the best slots for all the
commercials.)
</P>
<P>
   But there was trouble even before the presentations began. For
example, West Coast rapper DJ Quik reportedly was slugged as he
walked down the red carpet, drawing the attention of police
officers who briefly detained the Quik-meister before allowing him
to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's the kind of thing you don't see happen at the Academy
Awards, though it's amazing that some big-gowned starlet hasn't
gone after Joan Rivers or her equally frightening daughter by now.
</P>
<P>
   The Hip-Hop Awards taping was supposed to begin at 5 p.m., but
audience members were still hanging in the lobby and in the aisles
well after 6 p.m. _ and according to one source who was at the
show, the aisles never were fully cleared.
</P>
<P>
   An altercation broke out in the center aisle near the beginning
of the program, but the show continued, and five awards were handed
out before the real trouble started. (Note: Eminem was the winner
in the Best Lyricist category. Then again, Paul Simon wasn't
nominated this year.)
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after a performance by Lil' Kim and Mobb Deep, fights
broke out behind the stage and in the audience, resulting in the
surreal onstage image of awards presenters, uniformed police
officers, bodyguards, muscle-heads in Death Row T-shirts, TV crew
members and assorted other characters all milling about.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, audience members were finding a creative use for
their ``gimme bags,'' which contained such goodies as bottled water
and CDs _ they began hurling the freebies at each other and at the
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Finally the cops decided enough was enough, and they shut down
the show and cleared the auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   No arrests were made that night, but Pasadena police later
announced they were seeking rapper E-40 (real name Earl Stevens) to
question him about allegedly assaulting rival rapper Andre Dow,
whose facial injuries required a brief hospital stay.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, the televised images of the fights on newscasts
across the country did nothing for hip-hop's already badly bruised
image.
</P>
<P>
   So when I heard UPN was proceeding with plans to air the show, I
made rare plans to actually watch UPN. Maybe after showing some
documentary-style footage of the night's events, they'd have an
electronic town hall meeting featuring rappers, eyewitnesses, reps
of the major record labels, police officials and fans. It could be
a combination of ``Cops'' and ``Nightline.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not what happened. Instead, they pretended the fights
never happened and showed a sanitized version of the evening,
augmented by footage taken days after the actual event.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those awards that had not been given out, we'll be taping
those presentations between now and the broadcast,'' a UPN
spokesman before the broadcast. ``So it should be seamless for the
viewer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah yes, seamless _ and completely unrepresentative of what
actually happened on the night in question.
</P>
<P>
   Kinda reminds me of the 2-hour, 30-minute Woodstock '99 video,
which is all about the music and the carefree baring of breasts and
the mud and the friendly moshing, but somehow manages to sidestep
the complaints about price gouging and unsanitary conditions, the
presence of harder drugs, the nearly catastrophic fires, the
vandalism and the numerous reports of sexual assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Rock or rap, no matter. There's no need to let reality get in
the way of a tidy and neatly packaged profit machine.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the co-host of ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper &AMP; the
Movies.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
