<P>
   GUN-CONTROL (Sacramento, Calif.) _ A day before the state
legislature's final deadline, a lawmaker from Pasadena, Calif.,
abandons a bill to require a safety test and a license for handgun
owners after Gov. Gray Davis refused to support the measure this
year. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSING-BRIBES (San Francisco) _ Yolanda Jones was paid $52,000
per year at the city's Housing Authority, but she didn't do any
work. Instead, Jones testified in U.S. District Court, she spent
her workdays taking thousands of dollars in bribes in exchange for
federal rent subsidies for poor people worth as much as $1,000 per
month. By LANCE WILLIAMS and CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-DELAYS (San Francisco) _ Delays in the opening of the
new high-tech international terminal at San Francisco's airport
have bumped up costs another $4.5 million to compensate the
facility's retail tenants. The city Airport Commission approved the
payments Tuesday, two weeks after approving $3.1 million to
reimburse restaurant operators at the terminal for construction
costs and lost earnings caused by the delay. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   DEAD-LAKE (Big Moose Lake, N.Y.) _ For fifty years, Big Moose
Lake has been the poster child for the slow poisoning of Adirondack
waters by acid rain. Big Moose isn't the park's most acidic lake.
But it's size _ 1,266 acres of tea-colored water _ has earned it
the reputation as the largest lake to die from acid rain. By DINA
CAPPIELLO.
</P>
