<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7307 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-EXPO-DESIGN-ART-     08-31 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-EXPO-DESIGN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 NEW DESIGN CENTERS AIM TO BE REMODELING MECCA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Mass. _ Need a bathroom fireplace for cocooning in
the loo? Then maybe a visit to Expo Design Center is in order.
</P>
<P>
   At this huge new showroom store, the claim is that customers can
find just about everything they possibly could want for indoor
remodeling projects, including ``shower towers,'' whirlpool baths,
steam cabinets _ and, yes, even fireplaces _ for transforming a
humble bathroom into a sumptuous sanctuary for private retreats.
</P>
<P>
   There are also opulent kitchens on display that might wow
home-decor guru Martha Stewart, and other sections focus on
flooring, rugs, appliances, windows, lighting, and patios.
</P>
<P>
   Created by Home Depot Inc. to help sustain company growth, Expo
Design Center is opening its first Massachusetts store here.
</P>
<P>
   If Home Depot targets do-it-yourselfers, Expo Design Center aims
to provide one-stop shopping and service to a more upscale crowd
that wants wall-to-wall style and comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Expo Design Center prominently features kitchen and bathroom
showrooms that look like something straight out of Martha Stewart
Living, but Expo president Bryant Scott insists the store is
affordable for nearly all homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   Expo Design Center uses a good-better-best strategy that means
merchandise is available in several price ranges.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have a kitchen redone for $50,000, but you can also
have one redone for $7,000,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   If Home Depot is known as a no-frills paradise for handy men and
women, Expo Design Center targets consumers who may hire private
contractors to help them on big remodeling projects.
</P>
<P>
   Expo Design Center customers are more ``buy-it-yourselfers''
than ``do-it-yourselfers,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   With only about a 10 percent product overlap, Expo Design Center
seeks to complement Home Depot. One merchandise category that
neither store stocks in depth is furniture.
</P>
<P>
   With about 1,000 stores and $38.4 billion in 1999 sales,
Atlanta-based Home Depot is a retail legend of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   But even as it reports solid quarterly earnings, Home Depot has
seen its stock price drop by nearly 20 percent this year. Among
factors cited for the drop are low lumber prices, fears of slowing
consumer spending, high investor expectations, and Wall Street's
general disenchantment with retailers.
</P>
<P>
   For Home Depot, Expo Design Center gets the company into a
business with some pricier product lines. It also gives Home Depot
a second vehicle for domestic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot has been testing Expo Design Centers since 1991, and
nearly 20 stores are now open. The plan is to have about 200 Expo
stores throughout North America by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois-based Sears Roebuck &AMP; Co. is experimenting with a
similar, even larger store concept called the Great Indoors.
</P>
<P>
   Three such stores are currently open _ none on the East Coast.
But there are plans to quickly ramp up to 150 locations over the
next few years, a Sears spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Could the two titans battle it out over the home-decor market
some day? That's a possibility, some Wall Street analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Scott thinks Expo Design Center fulfills an unmet need. ``Expo
provides a unique atmosphere where customers can easily see how
various interior design elements fit together, helping take the
guesswork out of home design.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Burlington store manager Jack Racine: ``This is an idea
store. It tries to get people excited about interior design.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
