<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 12:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7308 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      08-31 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSULATING BASEMENT CEILING WILL SAVE ON FUEL BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My basement ceiling joists sit right on top of the concrete
foundation. Can I insulate the space between the joists where they
meet the outside border joist? There is only a 1 1/2-inch joist at
the border of the basement, between me and the cold outdoors, and I
think I am losing a lot of basement heat in winter.
</P>
<P>
   TRYING TO KEEP WARM
</P>
<P>
   A. It is unusual to have joists directly on the concrete, but,
then again, many weird things are done to houses. There is usually
a wood sill between joists and concrete or stone, but what you have
will do no harm.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you're right about there being very little protection
between you and the great outdoors through those border joists, but
you can insulate between the joists where they meet the border
joists. And, why not insulate the entire ceiling while you're at
it? You will save big bucks in heating bills because heat is lost
through any uninsulated barrier from inside to outside, including
the cold basement.
</P>
<P>
   Buy 6-inch-thick fiberglass with a paper backing. This paper, a
vapor barrier, goes face up, touching the floor above. Hold the
insulation in place with pointed wires, stuffed between each set of
joists, every 24 inches. Do this whether you live in the basement
or not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The fireplace in my condo does not draft enough. The chimneys
were cleaned, but that was not the problem. When I burn Presto or
other compressed-fiber logs, I get an odor throughout the house.
Not smoky, but hazy. When I burn wood, this does not happen. But
wood is hard to store without getting termites on my deck.
</P>
<P>
   I have heard that real wood burns hotter, and causes smoke to
draft better. Could this be what is happening? If so, I'll have to
give up on the Presto and burn real wood. What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   SHARON ALLEN, California
</P>
<P>
   A. I think you answered your own question: Firewood burns hotter
than the Presto and creates a better draft. You can store small
amounts of wood on your deck, say a day's worth, without fear of
termites. Besides, termites do not infest all wood, and if they are
in firewood they will not last very long because they must go to
their nests in the ground twice a day. They are in the wood only to
eat it. Firewood is more likely to be infested by carpenter ants.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to improve the fireplace draft is to open a window
in the same room as the fireplace, to provide it with more air.
This is not practical, but it will work. Or, install a duct from
the outside to your fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I live in a loft downtown, and I would like to strip the
paint off the brick walls. There are 450 square feet of it. How can
I do it? Would sandblasting work?
</P>
<P>
   BRUCE EDWARDS, Boston
</P>
<P>
   A. Don't even think of it. That is the domestic equivalent of
the Big Dig. It will take forever and be plagued by cost overruns.
I don't even think sandblasting is allowed anymore, and if it is,
it would be very expensive. So would any other method of
professional stripping. Maybe you could apply thin brick facing, or
let New England Brickmaster do it; it is real brick, but also
pricey.
</P>
<P>
   Live with the paint; if it is a light color at least you are
getting some light reflection off it.
</P>
<P>
   But you could try a cartoon treatment: paint the brick (brick)
red, then paint the mortar joints white or gray. It will look like
a stage set, but might be fun, even a small area. Or, paint
different sections different colors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How long should I wait after power-washing siding before
painting? I'd guess that some wait would be necessary for siding to
dry out.
</P>
<P>
   JOSEPH DeLAURENSON, Dedham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Wait two to three weeks during dry weather to let painted
wood or fiber cement dry out. Do not power-wash vinyl, aluminum, or
asbestos-cement shingles. Water that gets caught behind the vinyl
or aluminum will take forever to dry out, and power-washing can
release asbestos fibers from asbestos cement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My bathroom exhaust fan is in the ceiling, attached to the
joists. The fan is not excessively loud, but vibrations on the
floor above are annoying. How can I dampen the vibrations? The
house is 175 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ANNOYED, in Bath, Maine
</P>
<P>
   A. For starters, put a heavy pad and rug on the floor above.
Next, dismount the fan housing and try to separate it from the
joists, using connectors like those used to mount an engine in an
automobile. Or, dismount the housing and insert nylon or neoprene
washers between housing legs and the joists.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have an old clothes rack secured to the wall. How can I
refinish it so I can hang clothes on it without staining them?
</P>
<P>
   DAN DANIELS, Harwich, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. For a clothes rack, it is best to keep the wood plain and
unfinished. To do that, wash the rack with straight bleach, rinse
thoroughly, and let dry. It would be a good idea to sand the dowels
to take off any raised grain caused by the water in the bleach. If
you want to paint the rack, apply a latex enamel undercoater,
followed by an eggshell-finish latex wall paint or semigloss latex
enamel.
</P>
<P>
   If all else fails, replace the dowels.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
