<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7309 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-MURALIST-ART-BOS     08-31 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-MURALIST-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 OLD FRIENDSHIP UNITES MURALIST, FRENCH CASTLE OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Mass. _ This is a story of coincidences in life, of
the way that life meanders sometimes before bringing you around
full circle.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five years ago, 9-year-old Joshua Winer moved to a house
on a cul-de-sac in suburban Wayland, next door to a girl named
Sharon Halperin. She was 9, too, and they became best friends. They
went bicycling together, walked to school together, and did art
projects at Winer's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always painting,'' Halperin recalls. ``We'd do
paint-by-number paintings all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But by high school they'd drifted into separate orbits. Winer
studied painting at Yale and architecture at Harvard, and today is
a prominent Boston muralist and public artist known for his trompe
l'oeil decorations on buildings.
</P>
<P>
   After Hampshire College and five years of selling advertisements
for a radio station, Halperin took a trip around the world, during
which met a Frenchman, whom she married. In 1988, they moved to
France.
</P>
<P>
   Winer and Halperin kept in touch sporadically, but their paths
didn't cross again in a significant way _ until Halperin and her
husband bought a 500-year-old castle in the French Alps two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a strange reprise of their childhood, the two, now 44, are at
work on an art project once again. Winer is painting Halperin's
castle, and she is lending a hand.
</P>
<P>
   With 30 rooms to adorn, unlimited opportunities for trompe
l'oeil, faux marbling, and elaborate stenciling, the fixer-upper in
the town of Crots is a muralist's dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mix up the colors for her and tell her what order to put
them in,'' he says. ``It's basically paint by number.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as Winer put it in an interview at his Arlington home, it's
also a tale of how ``everything gets woven together in life.''
</P>
<P>
   As someone who makes his living painting pictures on the sides
of buildings, Winer has followed a career path that could never be
called conventional. His works include the Kennedy family trompe
l'oeil in Brookline; the Harvard Square Theatre facade; the
half-mile-long trompe l'oeil stone wall at the Mall at Chestnut
Hill; and the S &AMP; S Restaurant-Deli mural in Inman Square in
Cambrige, for which he won the 1991 Boston Society of Architects
annual Public Design Award. One of his best-known interior works is
the 100-foot-long cultural mural re-creating historic Jewish
Boston, located in the Hebrew Rehabilitation Center for Aged in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Decorating a castle might seem like a stretch. Still, when he
heard that Halperin and her husband, Jacques Peureux, were planning
to renovate it into a conference center, he knew he wanted to be
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I was the man for the job,'' says Winer. ``I
pushed really hard for this.''
</P>
<P>
   The turreted castle, named Picomtal, is a storybook-like
medieval edifice on a hillside in a small village in the southern
Alps, about 30 miles from the Italian border. It has three floors,
3-foot-thick stone walls, and pointy, slate-covered tower roofs,
called chapeaux or hats. It lacks a moat, but does have ``a little
pond,'' says Halperin, interviewed by telephone from Picomtal,
which sits on 25 acres of land. There is a lake about half a mile
away.
</P>
<P>
   The castle, which was enlarged several times over the centuries,
was originally a military defense fortress, and then home to a
series of families, all of whom were French nobility. Halperin and
Peureux purchased it from a 77-year-old man who had inherited it
from his grandfather. The property had been in his family for 125
years but was in serious disrepair and had not been modernized
beyond the 19th century. It had all of one bathroom. Only a couple
of rooms had electricity, and it lacked a heating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was broken-hearted about selling it,'' says Halperin. ``His
four kids didn't want it. It was just too expensive to keep up.''
</P>
<P>
   But Halperin's husband saw it as a fixer-upper, and he decided
to take a chance on it. He'd operated a successful business in
France importing multimedia software from the United States, and
was ready for a new professional challenge.
</P>
<P>
   For years Peureux had been dreaming about finding a large
building in an attractive place and turning it into a conference
center that could be rented out for meetings. He considered a farm.
He looked at a nunnery. But when he saw the castle on a ski trip
and heard it was for sale, he knew he'd found his dream business.
He bought the castle for the price of a small Tudor in a Boston
suburb _ about $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   And this is where Winer enters the picture. By coincidence, he'd
been spending a fair bit of time in France himself. In 1993, he'd
met and fallen in love with a French woman, Albertine Williams, who
happened to be living in Boston. They had a son, Charles, now 5
1/2. When the relationship didn't work out, Williams took Charles
back to France, to live in Versailles.
</P>
<P>
   But Winer visited him often, and took the opportunity to
reconnect with his childhood buddy from Wayland. Halperin is now an
English teacher and the mother of three girls, aged 10, 8, and 5.
</P>
<P>
   She told him about the castle. ``At the beginning, I thought it
was too crazy an idea to turn a castle into a business center,''
Winer says. ``But the thing that made me believe it would work was
spending more time with them, and seeing how they were handling the
problems that came up with the castle. They are trying to not just
do a good job, but a perfect job. And you sort of get sucked into
the whole thing. It's very inspiring.''
</P>
<P>
   The renovation had to satisfy the French government, which
regulates such restorations, Peureux said in an interview. Every
room _ designed for business clients, not vacationers _ would have
a fax machine and a computer. Many of the 30 rooms were to be
renovated in different historical periods over the 500-year-life of
the castle _ Renaissance rooms, French Empire style rooms, and
Provencal rooms, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized they needed an artist in there,'' Winer says. And
he knew just the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought, `Why not?' '' says Halperin. ``It was a mutual
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Winer acknowledges he would have loved to paint an entrance
mural on the ceiling, with architectural framing _ but Peureux had
his own ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jacques just wants to create an atmosphere in there, and let
the castle be the focus of attention, which is more the French
mentality,'' he says. ``My job is to provide the background.''
</P>
<P>
   So far he has worked on the castle for a total of 15 weeks, over
three different visits, and expects to do at least five or six
months' more work over the next two years. He is restoring the
chapel interior in the north tower, which is decorated with murals
he estimates are a century old. He has done stencil work using
chaux, a pigmented Provencal plaster paint. He has painted faux
tile on fireplaces, and moldings and flourishes at a tower
entryway, and trompe l'oeil door knockers on the flat new doors, to
make them look three-dimensional.
</P>
<P>
   And all these years later, Halperin works with Winer on the art
project, as his new assistant. ``He is teaching me to do trompe
l'oeil, so I can continue working on it,'' she says with a laugh.
``He is a very good teacher, very patient, and a very good
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   They have even drafted their children into the process, setting
up a painting studio in the French Empire room. For Winer, the
symmetry of it all is the assignment's greatest pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met when we were 9, and now our own kids are around that
age, and it all seems pretty repetitive,'' he says. ``Except that
instead of Wayland, it's across the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of amazing. We could not have planned it this way,
to be sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
