<HEADER>
A7310 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TV-MOSCOW-BOS &LR;      08-31 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MOSCOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSCOVITES, BEREFT OF TV, REDISCOVER SURROUNDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ There has been a mini-boom for video-rental outlets,
Internet providers and hourly-rate hotels. Longer walks for dogs. A
palpable dropoff in the numbers of politicians making promises to
the Russian public that they cannot keep.
</P>
<P>
   These are some of the side-effects of life without television in
Moscow after a fire Sunday at the main television tower blacked out
television screens across the Russian capital.
</P>
<P>
   The fire at the 1,772-foot Ostankino Television Tower claimed at
least four lives and added another dark chapter to a
disaster-strewn month that has become known here as ``Black
August.''
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy has overshadowed the fact that one of the world's
largest cities has been undergoing a spontaneous social experiment
unprecedented for peace time in the modern era that suggests
tantalizing answers to the question: What would happen if suddenly
the TV screens went blank?
</P>
<P>
   The shutoff has forced millions of viewers who spend an average
of five hours a day planted in front of the tube to get outside, do
some gardening, spend time with friends and enjoy life, according
to Muscovites interviewed Wednesday. But a TV-less existence has
also left many people cut off from their daily dose of news and
affordable entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Along with television, entire areas of the reality we inhabit
disappeared,'' commented Avtandil Tsuladze, a columnist for the
newspaper Segodnya. ``There are no more politicians with their loud
promises, no streams of compromising materials, no analytical
programs, even the president himself has disappeared.''
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin, who has been a fixture on Moscow
television since coming to power in January, has ordered regular
broadcasting service to be restored within a week.
</P>
<P>
   Using a temporary transmitter jury-rigged to the trunk of the
fire-ravaged Ostankino tower that provided a somewhat grainy
signal, two of Russia's main television channels resumed limited
broadcasting in Moscow late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As their lives slowly returned to normal, many people
interviewed Wednesday said the temporary loss of television was not
all that bad _ after the initial shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day was hard, but then I realized, this will
undoubtedly raise the birth rate,'' said Vadim Byrkin, who works in
Moscow as the spokesman for the governor of Yaroslavl, one of
Russia's 89 regions. ``Someone should do a study in nine months, to
see how many children were conceived in this week. My own activity
has increased drastically.''
</P>
<P>
   Two members of the Russian parliament voiced a similar sentiment
about the potential demographic value of life without television _
Russia's declining birthrate has become a serious political issue
in a country where the population decreased by 425,000 in the first
half of this year alone _ but neither legislator wanted to go on
the record.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did the manager of The Pillow, a Moscow hotel that has
hourly rates. She did, however, say that sales these past three
days were booming.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone has filled their sudden surfeit of free time so
wantonly.
</P>
<P>
   In the rush for information, Muscovites who have computers have
turned to Internet sites. Vladislav Borodulin, editor in chief of
the internet newspaper Gazeta.ru, said visits to his site have
increased by 150 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main news is no news,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another winner was the company Media Most, which had come under
pressure from the Kremlin over differences between its owners and
other leading businessmen. Media Most's flagship station, NTV, is
the only Russian network to have a satellite broadcasting system,
which allowed the station to stay on the air for viewers who could
pick up the signal. Cable operators, who in Moscow usually provide
a single channel to apartment buildings, also made a small killing,
charging residents to hook up signals from national networks.
</P>
<P>
   Unusually long lines at kiosks that sell and rent video
cassettes indicate that some Muscovites were still glued to their
sets. This being Russia, some have peered into the newly dark
screens occupying their living rooms and found an answer to larger
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps, the hurricane tempo of life is good for distracting
us from thoughts about the tragic nature of our existence in this
world,'' wrote Semyon Novoprudsky in the daily Izvestiya.
</P>
<P>
   Still others have taken a break and gone outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many things to do,'' said Yury Novoselsky, a
security guard who lives in Odintsovo, a suburb of Moscow that
normally has 16 channels to choose from; this week, only one UHF
frequency was working. ``The garden, the car, everything needs
work. I'm walking the dog longer than usual. I'm resting.''
</P>
<P>
   But some have warned that the TV blackout could have negative
consequences for thousands of people addicted to daily viewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Russians, in common with people around the world, have
become avid fans of soap operas and psychologists have expressed
concern that, without their daily fix, many problems will emerge,''
the Troika Dialog investment bank said in its daily report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian police precincts had been on the lookout for increased
domestic violence because of the loss of programming, according to
media reports, and some precincts have staffed special counselors
to help people cope with the absence of their favorite soaps.
</P>
<P>
   The limited programming that most Muscovites will be able to
view beginning Thursday includes ``Santa Barbara'' and a Mexican
soap opera along with news programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say that more than anyone pensioners have suffered,''
Tsuladze of the newspaper Segodnya commented. ``Television is for
them about the only pastime they can afford.''
</P>
<P>
   For Antonina Mitkina, a retiree playing in a sandbox with her
granddaughter Katya, the TV could not come back on fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life has changed without television,'' she said. ``First of
all, we don't hear what is happening in the world. And of course we
are upset over the guys who died fighting the blaze. We want to
know what will happen next. And of course, we are sorry for Putin,
who has taken over such a country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty much our whole life is television,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7311 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-BLANCHE-BOS &LR;      08-31 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BLANCHE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMOR LIGHTENS TALE OF RACE, RAPE AND REVENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SANDY COLEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
BLANCHE PASSES GO 
By Barbara Neely 
Viking. 275 pp. $22.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She heard him before she saw him. Then, suddenly, she was
reliving him.
</P>
<P>
   The terror of the night David Palmer raped Blanche White crashed
in on her like a falling concrete wall. While she was at a party
that she was helping her best friend cater, he stood laughing and
drinking, untouched by the destruction he had caused her years ago.
She had to flee the room:
</P>
<P>
   ``A stomach cramp nearly doubled her over. The light grew dingy;
a smell, bitter and fruity, like milk about to turn, stung her
nose; the music went flat; and she was suddenly cold. The pleasant
buzz and of people talking and laughing rumbled ugly, like a mob
forming. She covered her mouth and hurried toward the kitchen,
vomit burning her throat.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Blanche Passes Go,'' the new mystery by Boston writer
Barbara Neely, the smoldering rage over the rape of the
African-American main character by a white wealthy man propels a
tale that deals with murder in a New South that clings to old
racist ways, the settling of old scores, and the healing of wounds
so deep the bleeding won't stop.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fourth novel Neely has written in this enjoyable
series featuring Blanche White, the quick-witted, full-figured,
crime-solving domestic with a nose forever stuck in other people's
business.
</P>
<P>
   As in all her novels, the author again manages to tell a story
full of murder and other serious issues while infusing it with a
pleasant element of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Neely's preceding novel, ``Blanche Cleans Up,'' had the cook and
housekeeper living in Roxbury and working for a Brookline
politician and his wife and, of course, figuring out who done what
to whom.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Blanche Passes Go,'' the main character is taking a trip
home that is as much a symbolic journey as it is a literal one.
Leaving Boston and returning to Farleigh, N.C., where she was born,
she plans to help her childhood friend Ardell get her catering
business off the ground during the town's busy bicentennial
celebration. But also by revisiting the past, Blanche hopes to move
forward with her life.
</P>
<P>
   While home, Blanche has a full plate. She starts dating a
handsome train conductor and has to do that delicate dance of
letting go while holding on tight to independence. She begins the
difficult process of loosening her grip on two children (now
teenagers) whom she has been raising since her sister died. She's
finding new layers to people she thought she knew, including Ardell
and her strong-willed mother, who holds a secret Blanche never
imagined. And, of course, there is the unfinished business of David
Palmer to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   Blanche didn't have the courage to go to the police when she was
raped. In the Southern town, who would believe the black
housekeeper over the wealthy white man, and would they care, given
the disregard for abused black women dating back to slavery? And,
could she survive the shame and the anticipated looks of pity?
Blanche knew the answers too well.
</P>
<P>
   But, she could no longer live with her decision not to do
anything because ``she'd been frozen for the last eight years, as
though her life were a game of Monopoly in which she was stuck at
Go. Certainly she had gone on with her life and she'd done all
right . . . But she could see now that a part of her was still back
there, curled up like a broken child.''
</P>
<P>
   When the perfect opportunity to find some dirt on Palmer
presents itself, she takes on the risky business. And, readers are
taken along on the ride as she sets out to ruin him.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Neely uses her character to explore the issues of
race and class that she has addressed in all her novels. And, it is
never a one-sided attack. She gets in just as many licks against
black folks who discriminate within their own race because of skin
tone as she does against white bigots who do so.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the novel, abused women _ including the murdered
white girl Blanche can't get out of her head _ are a reminder of
how much battering, harassment and deception women can sustain in
this world, often at the hands of someone who ``loves'' them.
</P>
<P>
   Neely has a remarkable way with description. (Blanche's new man
has ``eyes the color of burnt sugar.'') The characters who populate
her stories seem ordinary enough until some weird little quirk
springs up like a loose hair. (Twin sisters who cook for Ardell
finish each other's sentences and are cheating Ardell a couple of
pounds of butter at a time.)
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Neely tells a great story that touches on
many complex themes, from jealousy to redemption. It is not until
the end that the author becomes a bit heavy-handed and gets on the
preachy side as she drives home the point about abused women.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the delicious surprises that mark the end of any good
mystery novel are a little less satisfying because there are one
too many coincidences here. The loose ends are tied up too neatly.
Yet, one important issue doesn't feel resolved. Ultimately, is
Blanche's revenge as sweet as she'd hoped?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7312 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FASHION-COLUMN-ART-BO     08-31 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 PASHMINA PASSE? NOT IN COOL CLIMATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patti Scialfa, Bruce Springsteen's wife and bandmate, dropped
$550 in Bergdorf's last week on a pumpkin pashmina. Apparently, she
didn't get the memo, first circulated via British Vogue last
August, declaring that the soft cashmere wraps are as passe as that
chestnut ``Born in the USA.'' Then the stateside Vogue affirmed the
news last November _ timed as if to save women from being inundated
with packages of pashmina under the Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who want one, or who got one and may be about to
pull it out of the cedar closet in preparation for fall, the
question is: are they in or out?
</P>
<P>
   While some retailers are refusing to carry the cache-less
commodities one year after stocking the shelves with them, others
are piling them up under the heading ``Don't say the pashmina's
dead!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We still feel very strongly about them,'' Debbie Seidenberg,
merchandise manager at Neiman Marcus in Boston, said of the wraps,
priced between $375 and $2,000 in that store. ``It's a necessity at
this point. Being here in the Boston area, it's very practical to
have a wrap and a shawl.''
</P>
<P>
   But because pashminas were copied by mail order vendors, some of
whom used wool or silk to bring down the price tag and because they
became ubiquitous at cocktail parties (paired with little black
dresses), fashionistas panned the popular wrap.
</P>
<P>
   What's different this year is that pashminas are being decorated
with jets (small black beads) or sequins or embroidery and are
showing up in more vibrant colors. The idea has also metamorphosed
into tatty, open-work shawls, as well as ponchos or light capes,
which can be thrown over blazers with the same ease as a pashmina
on a cool fall day.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the pashmina dilemma cries out for another opinion. So we
turned to Kate Betts, editor of Harper's Bazaar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're out,'' Betts said over the phone from
New York, sounding bored by the topic. ``They've just become a
mainstream part of the fashion vocabulary. It's something that
really didn't exist before in our culture. I still see people
wearing them.''
</P>
<P>
   But here's the clincher: ``People in the fashion crowd have
replaced the pashmina with this fall's fur tippet or the fox collar
that Prada and Marc Jacobs did,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The fur tippet?
</P>
<P>
   Barry Alterwitz, another merchandise manager at the Boston
Neiman Marcus, explained Betts's pick. Yes, he said, ``the tippet''
is the hottest thing going. Essentially, it's a free-standing fur
collar with ties on the ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're fabulous,'' Alterwitz said. You can place tippets
around the neckline of a coat, a T-shirt, a blouse, or an evening
dress. And they come in many colors, from purple to brown, and in
faux furs or real ones, ranging from rabbit to mink. Some of the
dyed rabbit furs start at $75.
</P>
<P>
   In case you're thinking a pashmina is less politically
incorrect, consider that the cashmere wrap's popularity spurt has
had broad consequences.
</P>
<P>
   China, which produces two-thirds of the world's cashmere from
goat wool, has been raising the prices for the raw material
produced in other countries. And in neighboring Mongolia, goat
herding has become a trendier job prospect, prompting
environmentalists to worry about overgrazing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many believe China is overpaying for the imported
material in an effort to get a lock on the world's cashmere supply.
(China makes about two-thirds of the 16,500 tons of cashmere
worldwide, compared to Mongolia's 3,000 tons.)
</P>
<P>
   The result: In the past two years, a pound of cashmere has gone
from $4 to $20.
</P>
<P>
   But it could take a while before such costs trickle down to the
consumer. Luxury retailers are bracing for steep increases in
cashmere products next year. In other words, stock up now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Fancy footwear for fall &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What else should ``mainstream'' shoppers be buying?
</P>
<P>
   Betts of Harper's Bazaar said footwear is an important accessory
this year, especially the '40s-style platform heel with an open
toe, which is perfect with a suit at the office.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for women going into shoe shock over the
displays of stilettoes and pointy-toe torture chambers more
effective as pieces of artwork than footwear. Betts sees the
spikier, sexier contraptions as more appropriate for evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``For day, that kind of chunky '40s heel is going to be very
fashionable and it looks great with a tweed suit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In stores, salespeople are reporting that older customers who
have always been accustomed to wearing heels, are loving the return
of more elegant footwear, as are the fashion-conscious young. But
women in the middle demur.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jane Andersen, a member of the American Podiatric Medical
Association, says she has been seeing more young women hobbling
into her office with foot ailments caused or aided by their
unhealthy shoe choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do see young professional women who are beginning to wear
those shoes again,'' said Andersen, whose practice is based in
Durham, N.C. ``I consider anything over 1 1/2 inches to be high.
The pointed toe box is really detrimental. Number one, people get
corns on their toes or blisters. That can cause a lot of problems
that can make your toes curl up. You get hammer toes.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also side effects from wearing high heels, including
the increased risk of a ``traumatic event,'' such as a sprained
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen added that the Achilles tendon and muscles in back of
the leg can also shorten _ permanently _ from wearing high heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, it makes it difficult to wear flats,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And then what are we to do when flats are back in style?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
