<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7315 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-BABY-FASHIONS-HNS &LR;      08-31 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-FASHIONS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     THE ABCs OF DRESSING BABIES  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROSE MARY BUDGE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Babies are so adorable they deserve to goo over
Gucci and wear nothing but the best. But it doesn't necessarily
take big bucks and designer clothing to turn the little darlings
into haute tots. You just need to know the fashion trends from A to
Z and where to find them.
</P>
<P>
   A is for applique
</P>
<P>
   Applique on everything from onesies to overalls is a big fall
trend. Favorite motifs? Animals, flowers, airplanes and cars. You
can find appliqued baby clothes at specialty stores. Or you can
head for mass-market retailers such as Kmart, where appliqued
outfits and separates are $12 and less.
</P>
<P>
   B is for bib
</P>
<P>
   Many designers are including matching bibs with little dresses
and suits. If you prefer to buy bibs separately, brighten burp time
with fun prints, neon colors and stylish logos. Tommy Hilfiger
offers a white terry bib embroidered with his logo (about $12). Or
you can go for the minimal look _ a plain cotton bib from
Walgreen's for $2.
</P>
<P>
   C is for corduroy
</P>
<P>
   A staple that takes spills in stride, corduroy is a top seller
this season. Retailers suggest wash-and-wear pink, purple, teal or
orange for her. Navy, dark green, khaki or bright blue looks good
on little boys.
</P>
<P>
   D is for denim
</P>
<P>
   Babies can wiggle and crawl in denim _ it's tough stuff. She'll
go gaga over denim capris. He will look darling in denim jackets
and jeans.
</P>
<P>
   E is for embroidery
</P>
<P>
   Embroidery can make even the simplest, most inexpensive baby
clothes look like couture. Among the popular embroidered motifs for
fall are lions, tigers and bears. Oh, my!
</P>
<P>
   F is for fun
</P>
<P>
   And fanciful. Think jumpsuits with appliqued bunnies peeking out
of the pockets. Think jumpers embroidered with frolicking felines.
There are plenty of years ahead for grownup, serious styles.
</P>
<P>
   G is for Gucci
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. You really can get Gucci and other big-name labels
for baby. Designers are discovering big bucks in the mini market
where it's oh-so-hard to resist. Department stores such as
Dillard's and Foley's have the Tommy Hilfigers and the Polos by
Ralph Lauren. Pink and tan slippers printed with distinctive Gucci
G's can be ordered for $90 in sizes 2 to 12 months. Or how about
the designer look without the price? Tiny slippers minus the
flourishes are about $5 at J.C. Penney and Sears.
</P>
<P>
   H is for hat
</P>
<P>
   Babies never should leave home without one. A hat can protect
your little darling against the sun, and it can brighten the day
for everyone who sees your child. Choose soft materials and
crushable shapes.
</P>
<P>
   I is for important
</P>
<P>
   Though style counts in baby clothes, practicality is more
important. Is the material fire-retardant? Will the fabric itch or
scratch? Will buttons or trimmings be easy to pull off and even
easier to swallow? If the outfit is questionable, avoid it _ even
if it is a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   J is for jumper
</P>
<P>
   Jumpers are comfy and can be worn with or without blouses _ and
bargains in versatility because the pieces can be worn with baby's
other things.
</P>
<P>
   K is for knits
</P>
<P>
   More and more baby clothes are coming in comfy, easy-care cotton
knit, according to Talbots Kids &AMP; Babies. The material won't
wrinkle and never feels scratchy against tender skin, which adds up
to happy babies and even happier parents.
</P>
<P>
   L is for lightweight
</P>
<P>
   Baby will go from sweetie to sourpuss if the outfit you pick is
hot and heavy. Even in fall and winter, it's better to go with
lightweight materials and layer on a sweater or jacket if the
weather turns cool.
</P>
<P>
   M is for mix and match
</P>
<P>
   Designers are mixing and matching bold colors and patterns for
fall, putting hot pink with lime green and polka dots with plaids.
Pick up some inexpensive separates and give it a try.
</P>
<P>
   N is for navy
</P>
<P>
   If you can only afford one new garment for your little one, pick
versatile and seasonless navy. A navy jumper for her and navy pants
for him can mix and match with almost anything.
</P>
<P>
   O is for orange
</P>
<P>
   Designers have a crush on orange, and it's adding flavor to tiny
tees and cotton-knit pants. A single shot of orange can bring high
fashion to baby's wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   P is for prints
</P>
<P>
   Florals, stripes, plaids and animal prints dominate in the
infants department. Hunt for clothes trimmed with leopard, zebra,
tiger, pony and snake. Or try a bit of fake fur to add luxury to
any garment.
</P>
<P>
   Q is for quilting
</P>
<P>
   Some of the cutest outerwear for fall features quilting. It's
best in airy nylon or featherweight fleece.
</P>
<P>
   R is for ribbing
</P>
<P>
   Ribbed sweaters in every style from turtleneck to cardigan are
showing up in tiny sizes. Fire engine red is the hottest color.
</P>
<P>
   S is for stretch
</P>
<P>
   Many baby fashions include Lycra _ just enough so the garment
moves comfortably and easily with the body. And socks can dress
things up with lace cuffs or embroidered cartoon characters and
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   T is for terrycloth
</P>
<P>
   You can't beat this old favorite for comfort and practicality.
Terry works beautifully in practical onesies and snuggly robes to
wrap up after bath time.
</P>
<P>
   U is for urban edge
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't think baby clothes would have attitude, but it's
the trend. Watch for cool decorated denim, tiny tees, itty-bitty
halters and bootleg jeans for tots 6 to 12 months old.
</P>
<P>
   V is for vests
</P>
<P>
   Little boys will be wearing vests. So will little girls.
</P>
<P>
   W is for waffle knits
</P>
<P>
   Waffle knits add textural interest to fall baby fashions. The
tiny, slightly raised squares in the fabric feel puffy and fun to
little fingers while locking out the cold.
</P>
<P>
   X is for ``xtras''
</P>
<P>
   When designers include packets of replacement buttons or
embroidery threads, it's worth paying a little more for the
garment. These packets, usually found next to price tags, save
frustration when clothes need a quick fix.
</P>
<P>
   Y is for yellow
</P>
<P>
   Some parents like to outfit boys in blue and girls in pink. But
why not yellow, the unisex color? This fall, honey tones are hotter
than pastel.
</P>
<P>
   Z is for zippers
</P>
<P>
   Zippers can be decorative as well as utilitarian. But if you
pick zippered jeans or a zippered jacket for baby, be sure the
zipper is smooth and well set. You don't want to pinch or irritate
sensitive skin and cause the little one to dread getting dressed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Rose Mary Budget by e-mail at
rbudge(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
