<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7316 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-DANTO-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     08-31 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-DANTO-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... bad student.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During World War II, Danto served in the Army Corps of Engineers
in North Africa and Italy. ``I learned a lot about life,'' he says
with a grin. ``I learned a lot about myself. It was like 20 years
of psychoanalysis!''
</P>
<P>
   Danto studied art under the GI Bill at what is now Wayne State
University, in Detroit, and got his BA in two years. This meant he
had two years of benefits left as a veteran. ``When people say to
me, `Why did you go into philosophy?' I say, `To tell you the
truth, to collect GI Bill checks. . . . My idea was, I'm going to
go to New York to be an artist. But I've got these two years I
might well do something with. I didn't want to go to art school. So
I thought, what will I do? I'll study philosophy, because you don't
have to read so much. You're supposed to think, and I do that all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   After getting his PhD, Danto spent a year in Paris on a
Fulbright Scholarship, where he became friendly with the sculptor
Alberto Giacometti. He spent a year teaching at the University of
Colorado, then returned to Columbia. It was a golden age on
Morningside Heights. To name some of Danto's colleagues, with all
of whom he was a friend, suggests what a rich faculty the school
boasted: the Nobel Prize-winning physicist I. I. Rabi, the literary
critic Lionel Trilling, the historian Richard Hofstadter, the art
historian Meyer Schapiro (one of the finest pieces in the new book
is Danto's obituary tribute to Schapiro).
</P>
<P>
   Friendship, in a more general sense, is a key attribute of
Danto's art criticism. For one thing, it got him started: It was
the recommendation of a friend, Ben Sonnenberg, the then-editor of
the literary quarterly Grand Street, that brought him to the
attention of The Nation. More important, in an art world largely
defined by combativeness and what Danto has called the
``denunciatory stance'' of Clement Greenberg, his predecessor as
The Nation art critic, his writing stands out for its consistent
generosity of spirit. ``I try to give people a break,'' Danto says.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say he's a cheerleader. (His opposition to
Richard Serra's controversial sculpture ``Tilted Arc'' put him on
the map as a critic _ and in a minority in the art world). But
precisely because he reviews such a small amount of work, doing
only 10 to 12 pieces a year, he prefers to write about art that
inspires his enthusiasm. ``What am I going to do,'' he shrugs,
``wipe the floor with somebody I'm writing about? Once you're in
there, once you see what someone's trying to achieve with his or
her art, you're already, in a way, on the artist's side.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he has to go a ways to reach the artist's side, but
the philosopher in Danto finds it a journey worth making.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I look within, I encounter a pretty conservative little
soul,'' Danto says of his tastes. ``There are certain things I
really like: usually little, luministic paintings, like Chardin's,
for example, or Morandi's. And I go into a gallery, and I see
something, and I say, `Do I have to deal with this?' Then the
little voice says, `Well, if you want to be an art critic, you have
to deal with it.' So I deal with it and try to put it in place and
try to see what's happening. Often, I wind up liking it a lot. So I
haven't, personally, caught up with myself as a critic, you might
say. I'm still fairly conservative and reluctant. But luckily I've
got this philosophy which kind of keeps me moving and says, `Come
on, don't close up shop; you've got to get in there.' That's the
blessing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
