<HEADLINE>
AS ELECTION NEARS, BOND TRADERS DREAM OF GRIDLOCK'S POTENTIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soon after he was elected president, Bill Clinton made a
discovery that shocked him: The bond market matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you mean to tell me the success of my program and
reelection hinges on the Federal Reserve and a bunch of (expletive)
bond traders?'' he asked his staff, according to an account
provided by Bob Woodward in his book ``The Agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton found out, the bond market has a political agenda,
too. It likes politicians who can deliver low inflation, moderate
growth, and budget surpluses _ the bigger the better. When it gets
what it wants, the bond market responds with lower interest rates.
When it doesn't, rates can head in the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Migliozzi, a managing director at Fleet Investment
Advisors, thinks the bond market is already starting to focus on
the November election. And the bond market has a preferred outcome
too, says Migliozzi: gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   Bond traders would like to see one party control the White House
and the other party control at least one house of the Congress.
That is the way it has been for the past six years, and the bond
market would like to see more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gridlock has been a success,'' says Migliozzi, speaking like a
true bond trader.
</P>
<P>
   In a gridlocked world, nothing much gets done in Washington. The
Democrats block Republican tax cuts, and Republicans block
Democratic spending plans. ``It's a new set of checks and
balances,'' says Nicholas Perna, an economic consultant in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, budget surpluses pile up like drifting snow
during a winter storm. During the Clinton era, the annual federal
budget went from $290 billion in deficit to more than $200 billion
in surplus. The strong economy and several different
deficit-reduction packages contributed to the fiscal shift.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of budget surpluses for the bond market is simple.
When Washington takes in more money than it spends, it uses the
extra money to pay down outstanding debt. That, in turn, reduces
the supply of bonds, which pushes up bond prices and reduces the
yield, or interest rate. With bonds, high prices and low rates is
the ideal combination.
</P>
<P>
   What could threaten this happy picture? A clean sweep in
November by one party. ``Faster policy changes will be possible if
one party wins control of the presidency and the Congress,'' the
economic team at Goldman Sachs wrote recently in a paper called
``Bush versus Gore: A Budget Referendum.''
</P>
<P>
   The Goldman team concluded that the bond market has the most to
fear from a Republican sweep. (Given that they already control
Congress, the Republicans also have a better chance of winning it
all in November than the Democrats.)
</P>
<P>
   According to the Goldman economists, George W. Bush's tax-cut
plan would eat into the surplus and increase the risk that the
already hot economy would overheat. That would boost inflation and
force the Federal Reserve to hike interest rates. The economists
estimate that the Bush plan would add about 50 basis points, or
half a percentage point, to rates over time.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would use up part of the surplus with his plans for higher
spending on education and health care. But the Goldman economists
assume his scheme would have less impact on the surplus and on
interest rates than the Bush proposal.
</P>
<P>
   David Jones has a somewhat different take on the matter. While
he agrees that a sweep in November would probably be a negative for
the bond market, he doesn't see much difference between the two
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush will give part of the surplus back in tax cuts; Gore will
do it with spending. To me they come out about even,'' says Jones,
chief economist at Aubrey G. Lanston &AMP; Co., a New York investment
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Jones makes another point: We are not talking about huge swings
in interest rates here. ``None of this is going to shake the
foundation of our being,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, given their druthers, virtually everyone involved with
bonds would like to see a split decision in November. If a
President Bush faced a Democratic Congress, he would be
hard-pressed to win approval for a big tax cut. If a President Gore
had to contend with a Republican Congress, he would have to
compromise on his spending plans.
</P>
<P>
   Bond traders go to bed at night dreaming of such scenarios.
Their motto might be: ``Four More Years of Gridlock.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you think it would fit on a bumper sticker?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments is spreading out.
</P>
<P>
   The mutual-fund giant is expected to announce soon that it is
adding a fourth building to its campus in Marlborough, Mass. The
new building, which Fidelity will lease, will have 125,000 square
feet, according to those familiar with the project.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity has 3,000 employees in Marlborough, most of them in its
retirement division. When the new building is completed, the
complex will have room for 5,000 workers. Fidelity has more than
13,000 employees in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
