<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7321 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-DANTO-2TAKES-A     08-31 1490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-DANTO-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 NATION CRITIC DANTO LOOKS FOR ART-LIFE CONNECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Arthur C. Danto has a soft, seductive voice that
syncopates in unexpected ways. It's a voice that inflects a lot,
which can make for sentences that sound poised between the
interrogative and declarative. That would be maddening in most
people, but for Danto it's more in the way of a job description. As
one of America's most eminent philosophers, he has spent half a
century working that profound ground where eternal questions sprout
tenative answers.
</P>
<P>
   Philosophers, at least in theory, are seekers after truth.
Truth, the poet says, is beauty. Thus it makes perfect sense that
Danto, who philosophizes by day, should moonlight as one of
America's best-known art critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been such a joy,'' Danto, 76, says of writing about art.
``I never knew there was anything so good as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming art critic of The Nation magazine in 1984, Danto
has published more than half a dozen books of art criticism and
theory, the most recent of which is ``The Madonna of the Future:
Essays in a Pluralistic Art World.'' He has won the National Book
Critics Circle Award, the College Art Association's Frank Jewett
Mather prize for criticism, and in 1995 delivered the prestigious
Mellon Lectures at the National Gallery of Art in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an art critic, Danto moves across eras and cultures of art
in ways that can be breathtaking,'' says Cynthia A. Freeland,
professor of philosophy at the University of Houston and author of
``Art Theory: A Very Short Introduction,'' which Oxford University
Press will publish this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an amazing body of work,'' says David Carrier, himself a
philosophy professor, at Carnegie-Mellon University, and art
critic.
</P>
<P>
   Danto is Johnsonian professor emeritusof philosophy at Columbia
University, where he did his graduate work and has been on the
faculty since 1952. Freeland likens him to another Columbia
philosopher, John Dewey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although their theories of art are quite different, Dewey was
interested in the actual arts of his time, and in some of the
broader social and cultural aspects of how the arts function, as is
Danto. Both of them have what I would call broadly cognitive views
of art _ they think that art plays a meaningful role in human
communication; art embodies ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence that Danto named one of his collections
``Embodied Meanings.'' ``Art appreciation'' interests him less than
``art understanding.'' ``I really try to find a context for the art
I'm writing about,'' he says, ``what's its connection with life,
what's it mean. Art isn't an end in itself for me.''
</P>
<P>
   An eclectic philosophical background has served Danto well in
his criticism. Before he started writing for The Nation, he
published books on subjects as diverse as the philosophy of
history, Jean-Paul Sartre, Asian thought, and Friedrich Nietzsche.
Danto had also long been interested in aesthetics, and Freeland
calls his 1981 book, ``The Transfiguration of the Commonplace,''
``one of the most important works in aesthetics in this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as striking as the intellectual grounding of Danto's
criticism is its relative uninterest in formal properties. ``He's
more interested in the allusions, the philosophical smoke, he can
get out of the art,'' says the painter Joseph Solman. ``He's
thought-provoking, but that's not enough for me (as an artist).''
</P>
<P>
   It's a frequently voiced criticism of Danto's criticism, which
makes it all the more striking that he started out as an artist.
Throughout the '50s, he earned as much doing prints (mostly
woodcuts) as he did teaching philosophy. ``I was considered OK,''
Danto says of his artwork. Though highly gestural and influenced by
Abstract Expressionism, it's very much focused on the human figure.
``De Kooning had a lot of influence on me,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Danto's work is in the permanent collections of the Museum of
Modern Art, the Brooklyn Museum, the Detroit Institute of Arts, the
Walker Art Center, and the Seattle Art Museum. ``Every once in a
while, something of mine comes up at auction, which always makes me
feel funny,'' he laughs. ``I also am not nuts about the work, I
have to tell you, for the most part.''
</P>
<P>
   Danto closed up his workshop in 1962. ``One day I was working on
a print _ I loved cutting _ and I thought to myself (it was like a
real speech), I'd really rather be writing philosophy. So I said to
myself, if that's how you feel, it's time to stop. So I did, cold
turkey. I put everything away, and that was it. I never even
doodled after that. I just became a pure and simple philosopher.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Danto looks the part. With his bald pate and
patriarchal beard, he resembles a flesh-and-blood version of a bust
of Socrates. The effect is underscored by his prominent brow and
deep-set eyes. His left eye is slightly askew, which makes his
expression seem never quite at rest. This is in keeping with a
general impression he conveys of encompassing eagerness: an air of
perpetual curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arthur's one of the youngest people I know in terms of his
attitudes and sensibility,'' says Carnegie-Mellon's Carrier. ``He
has this straightforwardness and lack of pompous dignity. You don't
feel you're with a statesman. You feel you're with this person who
looks and listens, who's always doing new things.'' Pretty much
everything he encounters seems to interest Danto, and (this is
perhaps the crucial thing to know about the way his mind works) to
interest Arthur Danto is to delight him. The intellectual and the
actual come together for him in surprising and energetic ways.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``Beyond the Brillo Box'' (1992), Danto describes an
experience that's emblematic. He was standing at a nondescript city
intersection. There were used-car lots on two corners, a gas
station, and a supermarket on the others. He recalls the motion and
color and excitement of so seemingly mundane a scene as traffic
whizzed past, plastic pennants fluttered, and radios blared.
Suddenly, it hit him: ``Good heavens. This is just remarkable!''
It's an epiphany many people have had, no doubt, but how many of
them went on to serve as president of the American Philosophical
Association and American Society for Aesthetics?
</P>
<P>
   Blending interestedness and delight, Danto communicates a sense
of constant, low-grade merriment. His manner _ open, genial,
unemphatic _ is that of the perfect intellectual host: someone
happy _ no, determined _ to freshen everyone's mental glass. He is
a man with, as he acknowledges, a ``sense of the world as such a
marvelous place, really, so long as you can escape the horrors. I'm
trying to write about (the 18th-century French painter) Chardin
right at this point, and it's that feeling about ordinary objects
(in Chardin's canvases) _ the pots, a basket of plums, something
like that _ it always knocks me out.''
</P>
<P>
   Danto neither looks nor acts his age (``When they took the
census, the guy asked me how old I was, and I said 76. He was
really surprised''). Yet as one who has lived more than
three-quarters of a century, he's aware that he's not going to live
another three-quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about it all the time,'' he says. ``It doesn't do you
any good to be a philosopher. It doesn't give you a leg up. A
friend of mine who has multiple sclerosis and contemplated suicide
said, `What philosophy should I read?' I said it won't help. You
can read the `Crito' of Socrates, but it won't help. Heidegger? It
won't do you any good. But one thinks about it. I really enjoy life
a lot. So the idea of it snapping out like a light, this
deprivation of the world in that way, I sort of hate the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Danto lives near Columbia, on Manhattan's Upper West Side, with
his second wife, the artist Barbara Westman. They've been married
20 years. He has two grown daughters by his first wife, who died in
1978.
</P>
<P>
   Their apartment houses a small, and vigorously varied, art
collection. Artists include Robert Motherwell, Mark Tansey, Sean
Scully, Saul Steinberg, Henri Cartier-Bresson, and Robert Mangold.
Yet the most cherished piece of art may be a collage made out of
the inside of cigar boxes and old rotogravure photos done by
Danto's father as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   He was a dentist, in Detroit, which is where Danto grew up. The
future critic's first experience of art was being taken by his
mother to see Diego Rivera paint the murals at the Detroit
Institute of Arts. ``I had a nice upbringing,'' Danto says, ``but I
was muddled. Later, I realized I had a philosophical mind, but
there was no way of knowing I had a philosophaical mind, so I was a
very bad student.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
