<HEADER>
A7325 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-GREAT-SACANDAGA-HNS &LR;      08-31 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREAT-SACANDAGA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAKE DOMINATED REGION WHERE VILLAGES ONCE STOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN WECHSLER  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To most users, the Great Sacandaga Lake is a place for
recreation: Hundreds of camps line its shore, hundreds of boats ply
its waters, while below the dam, people in rafts, tubes and kayaks
cavort in the warm water released to the lower Sacandaga River.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sacandaga, by far the largest man-made lake in New York,
was not built for fun. It was built to prevent flooding, and its
creation drowned hundreds of farms and villages that had been in
families for generations.
</P>
<P>
   As early as the 1860s, people talked about building a dam on the
Sacandaga. A major tributary to the Hudson, the Sacandaga would
often flood in the spring when the massive Adirondack snows would
melt. Flooding along both rivers was routine.
</P>
<P>
   In summer, a drought could cause the Hudson to become too low
for safe boating. If boats were unable to come up the Hudson,
commerce in upstate New York was crippled.
</P>
<P>
   But the flood that really got the effort going was in March
1913, when parts of Albany, now some 40 miles southeast of the
lake, were inundated. When the waters receded, a typhoid epidemic
broke out.
</P>
<P>
   It took nine more years to do something about it. In 1922 the
Hudson River Regulating Board was created by the New York
Legislature. Made up mostly of private business owners, the
organization was to fund the project using private money.
</P>
<P>
   But they also had public muscle, which was needed when the
locals found out what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   The Sacandaga River valley was home to a dozen villages,
including West Day, Osborne's Bridge, Day, Conklinville, Fish
House, Bennedict, Batchellerville, Edinburgh, Mayfield, Cranberry
Creek and Munsonville. There was also a train track owned by the
FJ&AMP;G Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   And there was an amusement park, Sacandaga Park, which was owned
by the railroad and built on the banks of the river.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the Regulating Board quietly bought up property in the
valley. But once word got out, buying was not so easy, or so cheap.
FJ&AMP;G sued the board over the planned drowning of its park and
railroad, and won $1.7 million. Locals, though, had little money to
sue and could only protest by refusing to leave their homes until
they were forced out by state agents.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of homes, and much of Sacandaga Park, were purposely
burned down to make way for the lake. Four whole hamlets were
drowned, as well as parts of many others.
</P>
<P>
   The earthen dam was completed on March 27, 1930. The
1,100-foot-long bridge contained 790,000 cubic yards of dirt and
rock and another 15,000 cubic yards of concrete. It cost $2
million, with another $500,000 for the half-mile-long
Batchellerville Bridge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7326 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-LAKE-PLACID-HNS &LR;      08-31 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAKE-PLACID-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PERSISTENCE MADE REMOTE LAKE PLACID A RESORT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN WECHSLER  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ One hundred thirty years ago, wealthy
adventurers loved Lake Placid. They just hated getting to it.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, a steamship would take someone as far as the west
shore of Lake Champlain. From there, a stagecoach covered the
40-odd miles to Lake Placid. The dirt tracks were not bad at first.
But as the road made its way up and over several mountain passes,
it became tougher and tougher, and not terribly enjoyable for
someone riding a stagecoach without shock absorbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten miles of rocks and mudholes,'' is how writer A.D. Mayo
described the road leading into the upstate New York village in his
1869 article, ``Adirondacks in August,'' for Old New Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But bad public relations still did nothing to hurt Lake Placid.
Soon after Mayo's less-than-glowing review, the area became the
first real winter resort in the United States. Today, it is one of
the Adirondacks' most popular destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Most of today's visitors don't realize it, but Lake Placid
village is actually located on Mirror Lake, not Lake Placid. The
much bigger Placid, with its huge islands, undeveloped shoreline
and waters that stop at the bottom of Whiteface Mountain, is
accessed at the western end of the village.
</P>
<P>
   Settlements on both lakes predate even the name ``Mirror Lake,''
a moniker that caught on in 1873 after a young girl staying in a
local hotel came up with the name. In 1810, it was called Bennett's
Pond, the name of the first settler to come to the area.
</P>
<P>
   The area around it _ the town of North Elba _ was used before
the Civil War by abolitionist John Brown as a farming community for
freed slaves. But it didn't work out; the weather was fierce, and
most of the former slaves had little experience working their own
farm.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Placid village was founded in 1850, but the area was mostly
known for several large farms. Then, in 1871, a farmer built a
hotel on Bennett's Pond. It was so successful that hotels cropped
up by the dozen during the next several decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``By 1900,'' said Lake Placid historian Mary MacKenzie, ``we
were a very well-known summer resort.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, the area attracted sportsmen and fishermen. Then, when
a train line was established from Saranac Lake in 1893, even more
people seeking mountain fresh air visited the area.
</P>
<P>
   History was also made in 1904 when the Lake Placid Club (started
by Melvil Dewey, inventor of the Dewey Decimal System) left part of
the club open in the wintertime. A group of 10 people came to enjoy
such winter sports as cross-country skiing, skating and
tobogganing. Word spread about how much fun they had that winter,
and the club never closed again for the winter. Lake Placid's
winter playground was born.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the village hosted the Olympics in 1932, it was the
first winter resort in America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7328 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-LATINO-HISTORY-HNS &LR;      08-31 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINO-HISTORY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BOOK DRAWS ON HISPANIC HISTORY SINCE THE ARRIVAL OF COLUMBUS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Ilan Stavans and Lalo Alcaraz are CQ)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RENE A. GUZMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new Hispanic history book written by Ilan Stavans and
illustrated by Lalo Alcaraz carves bold black-and-white strokes in
depicting the nation's varied shades of brown.
</P>
<P>
   An Amherst College professor and self-professed comics fan,
Stavans said the graphic novel made the perfect, powerful medium to
express his ``fiesta of types, archetypes and stereotypes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to tell the standard, predictable history you
find in textbooks,'' Stavans, 39, said in a telephone interview
from his office in Amherst, Mass. ``I wanted to create the idea
that history is not unchangeable. It's not a unity but a
multiplicity. I thought that it would bring in all the essential
elements of what our culture is about. Instead, it should be seen
as a kind of crossroads, many rivers coming together.''
</P>
<P>
   If culling Latin history seems a precarious trek across thin
ice, then Stavans' ``Latino U.S.A.: A Cartoon History'' (Basic
Books, $19.95) is a mad dash across frozen waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latino'' spans more than 400 years along the Latin timeline,
from Columbus hitting the Americas to the North American Free Trade
Agreement bringing them together. Like the ``Culture Clash''
television specials, ``Latino's'' kaleidoscopic perspective bubbles
with an irreverent mix of Latin politics, wit, self-reference and
sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the things that's missing from all Latinos when
presenting ourselves is the incredible humor we have privately,''
says Stavans. ``We share that with each other, but we don't expose
that. I wanted this (book) to be humorous, to laugh at history and
laugh at ourselves in the most democratic sense of the term. I
think you can do that in cartoons. You can be suggestive and
imaginative.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Latino'' might wear culture on its book cover, but don't
expect it to read like ``Maus,'' Art Spielgelman's serious
comic-book allegory about Jews and the Holocaust. The book's
cultural tableau mostly resembles ``The Simpsons,'' making pointed
cultural observations from the safety of its own heady cartoon
trappings.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel ``Meme'' Castillo, executive director of San Anto
Cultural Arts Inc. in San Antonio, co-created the ``Los Necios''
comic strip and the city's El Placazo monthly newspaper. He said
the comics medium makes a great teaching tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it's a more universal way or easier way to
understand history, regardless of your educational or financial
background,'' Castillo, 31, said. ``It definitely makes it more
interesting. `Maus' was an awesome book, easy to understand and not
boring. So people should not be criticized for reading historical
comic books.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Latino,'' the author's fifth-grade teacher (simply called
``Maestra'') narrates the cartoon epic. Along the way, Toucan (a
magical symbol from Mexican fantasy novels) and Calavera (the
grinning skeleton made famous by artist Jose Guadalupe Posada)
acerbically inject their own two centavos worth on every page.
</P>
<P>
   Famous Mexican icons Cantinflas (heralded as the ``Hispanic
Charlie Chaplin'') and El Santo (the wrestler folk hero of the
barrio) throw in some occasional barbs as well.
</P>
<P>
   The history begins with deconstructing the body of water that
simultaneously divides and unifies Mexico and the United States _
the Rio Grande, or Rio Bravo. The setup is a theme prevalent
throughout the text: History's facts and fictions are shared by
several different cultures regardless of borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words,'' Maestra said, ``there isn't a single Latino
history but many.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why a lot of people don't take to the Hispanic label,''
said Castillo, ``because you can't generalize us. Social
backgrounds and educational backgrounds have a lot to do with the
way you view life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to tell your own story,'' he said, ``and not be
complacent about or comfortable with what's being fed to you by
mass communications.''
</P>
<P>
   Stavans, whose books without pictures include ``The Hispanic
Condition'' and ``The Riddle of Cantinflas,'' said ``Latino'' is
really no different than his other works in that they simply strive
to challenge thought and debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should at least be doubt,'' he said. ``Leave the reader
or viewer with a question mark. By this, I don't mean that it's
right or wrong, but if you at least have this inquisitiveness that
would be enough. You may never have `The Truth' in front of you,
but that's life. And that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rene A. Guzman can by reached by e-mail at
raguzman(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
