<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7337 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN3-COX     08-31 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN3-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Probing beyond the pale
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Sept. 3, 2000
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man at the book store ran my credit card through the
machine, then turned and asked my e-mail address. My response was
impulsive: ``I don't have e-mail.'' He then proceeded to finish
ringing up the purchase. At the conclusion, I asked, ``Why did you
want my e-mail address?''
</P>
<P>
   ``So we can e-mail you promotions and offers,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought so. That's why I told you I didn't have one.''
</P>
<P>
   Where does this stuff end? First, retail businesses were
insisting on our zip codes, then addresses, then telephone numbers,
now e-mail addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Here, I have turned over to this person a plastic card with my
name and credit card number on it, but that's not enough. Now, I'm
asked to provide more so he can fill my computer with solicitations
to go along with the dozen or so others that now, without
authorization, arrive on a daily basis _ including some pretty ugly
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Moreso, with the information on my credit card, he already could
have found my life story if he wanted to -- and possibly charged a
flight to Paris on my account.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days earlier, I purchased a TV accessory in a nearby
electronics discount megaplex. I paid cash, under $50. When I got
home, I discovered the clerk had misrepresented my need and I
returned to the store, receipt in hand, for my money back.
</P>
<P>
   ``May I see your driver's license,'' the Returns clerk asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``What for?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't in the mood for an argument, so I acquiesced by
flipping open my wallet to show the license in a credit card
window. ``Take it out, please.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What for?'' I protested again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make a copy of it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a line beyond which I cannot be pushed, and this was
it. ``Listen, I paid cash for this lousy little thing. It says so
on the receipt, and I want cash back without having to go through
this deep an investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The clerk, properly trained to be unyielding, stood her ground
until I demanded to see the manager. I was determined that this
line was not going to be crossed. An affable sort arrived. I
explained my irritation and, being as he was his own authority, he
advised the clerk to return my money without further scrutiny. (I
believe his decision was prompted by the vociferous manner of my
complaint, which was not lost on a dozen or so other customers in
our vicinity.)
</P>
<P>
   Back, in the early '60s, I once balked at identifying my race on
an application for a check cashing card at a discount store. I
thought it unnecessary and discriminatory. As the clerk insisted on
a race, I eventually wrote ``Negro.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not a Negro!'' the clerk exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aha!'' I responded. ``You noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   I was denied the card. It's just as well. The store went out of
business shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when addresses were being demanded for some purchases, I
would perversely put down 77 Wistful Vista, which was the address
of Fibber McGee and Molly of radio show days. To this day, I still
don't put down my telephone number. They can find me anyway,
everyone else seems to have done so.
</P>
<P>
   I have full sympathy for establishments that have been
victimized by thieves with bad checks, phony credit cards and the
like, but the intrusion into my life as a result has grated me to a
raw edge.
</P>
<P>
   Within the past year, at an office supply store, a clerk asked
my zip code. Inasmuch as I was paying cash then as well, I told him
_ amiably, as I recall -- that no information from me was required
for the payment of legal tender. He advised that he could not ring
up the purchase without my zip code, whereupon I went to another
office supply place that could.
</P>
<P>
   We are living in a horrible era, one in which brigands abound
seeking to steal your credit card number, your phone number, your
e-mail address, your Web access. Through the phenomenon of
computers, so much of that is readily available without your direct
participation.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: How many waiters and waitresses or store clerks _
strangers all _ have you given your credit card number to while
simply paying your bill? Who checks them out? What's their phone
number and e-mail address?
</P>
<P>
   Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is not available
today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
