<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7338 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN3-COX     08-31 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN3-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Morality play has played out on the stump
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In case you've forgotten, it's a president we'll be electing
this November, not a national pastor, priest, imam or rabbi. It
would be easy enough to forget, what with the candidates
hosannahing around the country as if they were caught up in a Great
Awakening rather than in what, properly, ought to be a down and
dirty, eye-gougin', ear-bittin' partisan wallow, as God intended.
</P>
<P>
   This holier-than-thou stuff is far more dangerous than partisan
scrapping to national comity and general well-being, which is why
the Anti-Defamation League, a defender of religious freedom, has
asked its co-religionist, the Democratic vice presidential nominee
Joseph Lieberman, to cool it with the God thing.
</P>
<P>
   It is fine for politicians to be religious. Presidential
candidates always have been, or have pretended to be. (Ronald
Reagan, who earlier had never seemed to give a fig about church, at
least put on a good show, as he did in most matters.)
</P>
<P>
   It is quite another thing to open politics up to a bidding war
in piety. That way lies a politics formed around sectarianism, with
all its potential for majoritarian bullying and for disallowing
even the deeply religious candidate who prefers quiet faith to
noisy testimony.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush started all of this by wearing his religion on
his sleeve. As governor, he had proclaimed an official Jesus Day in
Texas. He declared Jesus his favorite political philosopher and
pitched himself to the televangelists and televangites at Bob Jones
University, an academy of Christian exclusivity.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore parried with a gratuitous claim that when stumped, he
often asks himself, in the words of the fad bracelet, ``What would
Jesus do?'' And when Bush kept trying to hang him with President
Clinton's supposed scuzziness, Gore took up the formally religious
Lieberman as a talisman against guilt by association.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, rather than letting his faith be duly noted and
getting on with politics, has been working that line ever since,
equating Medicare with the commandment to honor your mother and
father, declaring ``Our nation was chosen by God'' and Americans
are the ``children of God'' and saying we're ``the most religious
nation in the world,'' which is so, but lamenting that we often
hide that, which isn't so.
</P>
<P>
   And that, in turn, set GOP vice presidential candidate Dick
Cheney off on a Bible Belt tour, with a Christian athletes' group
as his first stop.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is a sinner and Baptist, a muddle most of us recognize
as both deplorable and richly precedented. Republicans, however,
have him as the virtual anti-Christ and, by dint of his misalliance
with an eager intern, figure him for a one-man moral sump who will
drag Gore down. And Democrats are afraid the Republicans are right.
</P>
<P>
   By now, though, the electorate has long since gotten the
message. All four men, in their various ways, believe in and honor
God. Fine. Isn't it time, gentlemen, to get out of the pulpit and
back on the stump?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
