<SLUG> BC-ONE-A-DAY-MED-BRIEF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACTERIUM DOESN'T CAUSE ALL ULCERS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This premium feature from The New York Times Syndicate is
available for a limited time without charge to clients of this news
wire.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 By STAN SIMON  
 c.2000 HealthScout.com  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   The decades-old notion that stomach ulcers were caused by
stress, spicy foods and other stomach irritants was officially
debunked by a National Institutes of Health study six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   By then, a consensus of doctors had been converted to the notion
that most duodenal ulcers were caused by the bacterium Helicobacter
pylori and could be cured with antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out the new notion was another case of overreaction.
Evidence gathered in the last six years shows that less than half
the cases of stomach ulcers are caused by the bacterium, reports
The Washington Post. The other major cause is now thought to be
frequent use of aspirin or nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs
(NSAIDs), though the causes of at least 10 percent of cases can't
be explained, the newspaper reports.
</P>
<P>
   H pylori is naturally dying out, thanks partly to improved
sanitation worldwide, says the newspaper. Up to 60 percent of
Americans born before World War II are infected, while only 20
percent of younger Americans carry the bacterium, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
