<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SEBASTIANI SELLS SOME BRANDS TO WINE GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VICTORIA COLLIVER and JENNY STRASBURG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sebastiani Vineyards Inc. has agreed to sell its
high-volume, lower-end wine division and its marketing unit to the
Wine Group Inc. as part of its effort to concentrate on premium
wines.
</P>
<P>
   The sale includes Sebastiani's Turner Road Vintners along with
its two wineries and a distribution center near Woodbridge, Calif.
Turner makes such brands as Farallon, Heritage, La Terre, Nathanson
Creek, Talus and Vendage.
</P>
<P>
   Also part of the sale is Sebastiani's marketing unit, Humphrey
and Brown International Wine Marketers.
</P>
<P>
   Both Sebastiani and the Wine Group, the San Francisco company
that is known for its wine-in-a-box brand Franzia, are privately
held and declined to reveal the terms of the sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only key difference you'll see, from past to future, is
that the central focus of everything we do will be at the very high
end of the market,'' said Don Sebastiani, chairman and chief
executive of the winery.
</P>
<P>
   Sebastiani said his winery would start producing more estate
wines and other premium offerings. ``You'll see basically the best
of Sonoma in terms of the fruit we have available,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts said Sebastiani's decision makes sense since
high-end labels are the fastest growing sector of the American wine
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real growth in the profitability in the industry has been
in the premium, upper-price categories,'' said Vic Motto, a wine
industry consultant based in St. Helena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The high-profile Sebastiani family, a name synonymous with
winemaking in Sonoma County, split ranks in the 1980s, with Don
Sebastiani sticking to the family label and brother Sam Sebastiani
and his wife, Vicki, starting the Viansa Winery in 1988 at the
southern edge of Sonoma Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Sebastiani has done well with his premium Viansa brands,
Motto said. Meanwhile, ``his brother Don took over the (Sebastiani)
winery and moved it to a more volume operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the family namesake winery is changing directions again,
focusing on its proprietary, estate and other high-end labels.
Motto predicts success in Sebastiani's $10-and-higher price range
during a time when the California wine industry is booming.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do have access to some very good vineyards in Sonoma
County, and certainly are one of the great names in Sonoma
County,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Don Sebastiani played down the 15-year-old split with his
brother, saying Sam Sebastiani is a shareholder in the family
company and a partner in its future: ``This deal was basically
driven by the people who have control over Sebastiani and that's my
sister, my brother and myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Sebastiani sold about 8 million cases of wine in its 2000 fiscal
year ending June 30, of which Turner produced about 7.8 million
cases, according to the company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In selling some of its divisions, Sebastiani said the Wine Group
would essentially trade up for some of Turner Road's higher brands,
such as Farallon.
</P>
<P>
   In a news release, Wine Group chief executive Art Ciocca said:
``The Sebastiani family and their organization have done a
tremendous job of building strong brands, which is very much a
shared value of our company.''
</P>
<P>
   Sebastiani described Ciocca as an old friend. ``I feel more like
I'm gaining a son-in-law than losing a daughter,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
