<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ Think times are good now?
You haven't lived until you've lived in the 1950s. A friend sent me
this bit of e-mail fluff that may or may not be authentic, but it
is interesting to compare just how far we've come in half a
century. (Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ It is not often that you have a chance to
witness a historic event. Mine came on a spring day in 1952 at
Lafargue High School, located near the banks of the Red River in
Avoyelles Parish, La. It was during an eighth-grade science class I
was teaching. I was lecturing on the characteristics of poisonous
snakes when Elton Lee Lofton, a redhead from lower Vick, raised his
hand. ``Do you believe in stinging snakes?'' he asked.''No, Elton,
I don't,'' I said. ``Grandpa said you wouldn't,'' Elton said.
(Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ A friend of mine who moved
here a decade or so from California gave me something undoubtedly
off the Internet, entitled ``If You Are New To Texas.'' As a
transplanted Texan, albeit one who's been here for more than 30
years, I can identify with the feeling that one has entered a
strange if fascinating land with a culture quite different. Here is
a sampling of advice if you have recently crossed the Red or Sabine
rivers.(Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches
Daily Sentinel.) EMBARGOED for Sunday. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Some Texas Republicans have
been contemplating their slots in a George W. Bush presidential
administration. Others are looking ahead to the political musical
chairs that will start when the Texas governor moves into the White
House. Several members of the Texas Senate are jockeying, with
varying degrees of subtlety, to become lieutenant governor when
Rick Perry moves up to replace Bush. But as Democrat Al Gore's
bounce in the polls was a little stronger than the Bush folks would
have hoped and Bush has struggled to fill in the details of his
trillion-dollar tax cut idea, ponder this:
</P>
<P>
   What if Bush loses? (McNeely, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ HOUSTON, Texas _ It is said that Texas air
pollution got built into an issue in 1999 because Texas'
jogger-in-chief was running for president. Actually in this city it
took some other runners to make it so. Last October, the Deer Park
High School girls cross country team went for its daily four-miler.
The whole squad shortly was bent over coughing and wheezing,
throats raw. Coach Mike Walker instantly knew something was wrong.
He was right. They had been flexing their lungs in what Los Angeles
would have classified a Stage 1 Smog Alert, which to the Houston
man on the street was a day without discernible alarm. (John Young
is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED. WITH
GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the first in a five part series on air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   UPSMAIL _ When United Parcel Service Corp. launched its first
experimental retail packaging store this year, Mail Boxes Etc.
franchisees were hurt, angry and worried. How could their preferred
carrier go into business against them? Now, they're hitting back in
an alliance with the U.S. Postal Service. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-MUSIC _ As its executives do battle against Universial
Music Group in a New York courtroom, online music company MP3.com
said Thursday it is teaming up with another record company, Time
Warner's Elektra label, to launch a service that will email new
bands' music to
</P>
<P>
   subscribers as soon as its released. The service is the latest
incarnation of the online music business and - just as
significantly - the first time an independent online music company
has teamed up with a record label. With latest developments from
trial in New York; mention of upcoming hearings in San Francisco in
the Napster copyright case. (Keefe, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Eds. Also moving in the entertainment (e) category.
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-DEALERS _ ATLANTA _Local tire dealers say things seem to be
slowing down but they're having trouble and paying more to get
tires, particularly Michelins. Many customers want their Firestones
off whether recalled or not. At least 5 percent of NHTSA complaints
(and maybe 28 percent) are Firestone tires of other sizes than
recalled ones, and NHTSA hasn't ruled out a wider recall. GA
attorney general is considering joining in on class-action suits
filed by other states. (Grantham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DELTA _ ATLANTA _ Delta is finally getting the ``-air'' out of
its dot com. The airline has long used the unwieldy url
delta-air.com for its web site, apparently because it was too slow
to grab the easier-to-remember delta.com url when the Internet was
in its infancy. Now its bought the delta.com rights (we're checking
how and from whom) and will announce the switch friday. Also, the
airline is setting up a separate e-business unit to coordinate
ecommerce acitivities. (Fonti, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CNN _ Folo on the CNN shakeup, talking to Rick Kaplan about how
he got the boot and seeking comment from Steve Heyer and Phil Kent,
who appear to have more power. (Kloer/Kempner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Eds. Also moving in the entertainment (e) category.
</P>
<P>
   GAPOWER-RACIAL _U.S. District Judge Orinda Evans sets the
groundrules for lawyers in the Georgia Power Co. racial
discrimination case to communicate with employees (Quinn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOHAWK _ ATLANTA _At least three employees of Mohawk Industries
have been arrested for allegedly bilking the company out of tens of
thousands of dollars. The employees were involved in a scheme to
create false invoices and deposit Mohawk checks in their own bank
accounts.The FBI, IRS and local police are investigating Mohawk and
more arrests could follow. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ ATLANTA _ The tire crisis for
Bridgestone/Firestone has become a crisis for other tire
manufacturers as well. As consumers look for alternatives as
replacement tires, other manufacturers find that this windfall of
sales has left them unable to respond to the unexpected demand.
Goodyear expects to ramp up production of the tires sizes in
question by as much as 50 percent. Other manufacturers are planning
similar increases in production.(Sharp, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
