   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL/PROS
</P>
<P>
   FBN-FALCONS-WHITFIELD _ FLOWERY BRANCH, GA. _ To say that
Falcons left tackle Bob Whitfield is a character is a major
understatement. Whitfield didn't get to be on the verge of setting
a franchise record with his 113th consecutive career start without
having resilience -- on and off the field. Whitfield said Wednesday
it's all part of his secret to longevity. ''I'm a spin doctor,'' he
said. ''That's part of the ability to bounce back.'' Whitfield will
get the record for consecutive starts Sunday when the Falcons host
the 49ers in the season opener. (Winkeljohn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-DOLPHINS _ DAVIE, Fla. _ Dan Marino would give a look. Mark
Clayton or Mark Duper would knowingly nod. The cornerback had no
idea what was about to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Ten touchdown passes in that 1984 season were for more than 34
yards. Marino set NFL records for yards passing (5,084) and
touchdowns (48). Clayton and Duper made it to the Pro Bowl. Marino
had 57 completions of 50 yards or more in his career.
</P>
<P>
   The longest pass the Dolphins completed in the exhibition games
went for 39 yards from Jim Druckenmiller to Nate Jacquet.
Druckenmiller is out of football now, and Jacquet was traded to San
Diego. (Archer, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL/COLLEGES
</P>
<P>
   FBC-UGA-DEFENSE _ The re-education of Gary Gibbs. Reader on
Georgia's new defensive coordinator and what he must do to bring
himself up to speed on 21st century SEC football after being out of
the game for several years. (Schlabach, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-MIAMI-DORSEY _ MIAMI _ Ken Dorsey's career at the University
of Miami nearly ended before it began. Sitting in a restaurant just
over the California border into Arizona one year ago, Maggie Dorsey
looked up from her meal and noticed her son's face plunged deep
into his hands. The Dorseys were one day into a five-day,
cross-country trip from their home in Orinda, Calif., to the UM
campus when a wave of doubt and homesickness struck the 18-year-old
quarterback. ``You know mom, I don't know if I've made the right
decision going so far away,'' said Dorsey, his voice quivering.
``I'm going to be a million miles from my friends, my family,
everyone and everything that I know. Did I do the right thing?''
Maggie Dorsey assured her son that he had, but if further
affirmation is needed, just ask UM offensive coordinator Larry
Coker. ``I don't know where we'd be without Kenny Dorsey,'' Coker
said. (Miliam, Palm Beach Post). 20.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-FLA-BULLARD _ GAINESVILLE, Fla _ When Thaddeus Bullard
walked into the Florida Sheriffs Boys Ranch cafeteria for the first
time, he stood about 6-feet-1, weighed about 175 pounds and was
palming a basketball in his right hand. Roger Bouchard, then
residence director of the boys ranch, was expecting a troubled
13-year-old, but this person didn't fit the description of a
typical rising ninth-grader. ``I thought some college kid had come
in,'' said Bouchard, now president of the Florida Sheriffs Youth
Ranches. But this big, strong boy was Bullard, a child who had just
arrived from Boynton Beach. He, his family and local law
enforcement officials all had agreed he needed help growing up. His
mom hated sending him away. (Clarke, Plam Beach Post). 20.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-GASOUTHERN _ Reader on Georgia Southern. A look at this
amazing I-AA program, built out of the imagination of Erk Russell
and molded into one of the best if its kind in the nation. (Reese,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 22.
</P>
