<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7363 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-BETTER-JOBS-HNS &LR;      08-31 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTER-JOBS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DO YOUR HOMEWORK BEFORE SCOUTING FOR A NEW JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As good as the economy is and as wonderful as
the job market is, a lot of people still are struggling. They
really are trying to land a better job, but nothing seems to be
going their way.
</P>
<P>
   If you are one of them and have no idea why the world is passing
you by, consider these possible causes:
</P>
<P>
   _ A weak resume.
</P>
<P>
   Keep it to one page. In the initial screening, your resume will
be glanced at for five or 10 seconds. Long-windedness works against
you. If you get called in for an interview and think the one-page
resume doesn't adequately display your talents, bring a longer
version with you.
</P>
<P>
   Tailor it to the company. What kind of skills does the company
emphasize? How would you fit into a particular job there _ or,
better yet, why should the company create a job that would be
perfect for your skills? If they find the right people, smart
managers are adept at making room for them.
</P>
<P>
   If you are sending an electronic resume, make sure you use the
same job titles and buzzwords the company does. Companies use
software to search for keywords.
</P>
<P>
   List your e-mail address so the company will know you are
familiar with computers. Unless your references are incredibly
influential, don't bother listing them in the early stages. And
make sure that you and a friend proofread the resume; don't rely on
your computer's spell checker.
</P>
<P>
   _ A lack of sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   Applying to dozens of companies at once is almost always a waste
of time. Find a company that you really want to work for and a job
that you really want to have, then go for it. If nothing is
available right now, let people know that you're interested. And
stay in touch.
</P>
<P>
   Do your homework about the company, its needs and its culture.
Write a sincere cover letter explaining why you want to work there
and why you'd be the best person for the job.
</P>
<P>
   _ Poor networking.
</P>
<P>
   Your chances of getting a job at any company are tremendously
greater if you know people there and they think highly of you. Let
friends and associates know you're looking, and go to professional
conferences and workshops to meet people. Don't push acquaintances
for job help right away, but build relationships so you can help
each other in the future.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bad interviews or references.
</P>
<P>
   If you have made it to several job interviews but just can't
seem to get hired, you are either shooting yourself in the foot or
someone is doing it for you.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare for interviews by thinking about anecdotes that show how
you perform under pressure, how you deal with difficult situations
and what skills you have picked up in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Try having a mock interview with a friend or trusted colleague.
If possible, ask an interviewer who rejected you how you could
improve your chances for the future.
</P>
<P>
   If your interviews seem to go well, check your references. Do
you get permission from references before people call them? Do you
alert them about what your prospective job involves so they can
think about which qualities of yours make you particularly suited
for it? Do the interviewers actually call the references? Do you
let your references know that you appreciate their help?
</P>
<P>
   _ Unrealistic expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes workers think they are more mature than they really
are.
</P>
<P>
   By all means, set tough goals for yourself, but realize that
some top employers demand a lot of experience before they'll hire
anyone. Even you. We all want to be millionaires overnight, but
sometimes it can actually take a week or two. Be patient.
</P>
<P>
   _ Exasperation.
</P>
<P>
   If you are in a dying industry or tight market, you might get
turned down many times before landing a job. Make sure your past
failures don't lead to future ones. If you walk in looking like a
loser, that's just how you'll walk out.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
