 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, Sept. 1:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ESTATE-TAX (Washington) _ President Clinton is expected to veto
a Republican bill that repeals the federal estate tax. The White
House describes the bill as ``too expensive'' and says it
``undermines our ability to pay down the debt and strengthen Social
Security.'' By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-REPORT (Washington) _ HHS Secretary Shalala and White House
Drug Control Policy Director Barry McCaffrey release the 1999
National Household Survey on substance use. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TIANANMEN (New York) _ A subpoena was to be served
Thursday on the former Chinese premier Li Peng in connection with a
suit filed Monday in U.S. federal court by Wan Dan and democracy
advocates and relatives of victims of the Tiananmen Square
massacre. By Edward Wong.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-SUHARTO (Jakarta) _ By calling in sick on the first
day of his corruption trial Thursday, Indonesia's former leader,
Suharto, has put up another hurdle to this country's tortuous
effort to come to terms with its past. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-PARLIAMENTS (United Nations) _ U.S. Senator Arlen Specter
met with members of the Iranian parliament on Thursday as part of
an international conference of international parliaments at the
United Nations and said it is time to start breaking down barriers.
By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-RELIGION (United Nations) _ On the final day of the
Millennium World Peace Summit of Religious and Spiritual Leaders.
By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   LIECHTENSTEIN-CRIME (Geneva, Switzerland) _ A special prosecutor
on Thursday issued a report on money laundering and organized crime
in Liechtenstein. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Louisville, Ky.) _ At his most energized rally in weeks,
George W. Bush attacks what he calls the failed leadership of the
Clinton years. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NADER (New York) _ Ralph Nader, the Green candidate, campaigns
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Short items from the world of
politics.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INMATES-FIREFIGHTERS (Draper, Utah) _ A surprising portion of
the armies of men battling wildfires across the West this summer
are convicts from state prisons. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   FORESTFIRES-CAUSE (Dateline to come) _ The bipartisan
Congressional Research Office has reported that longterm forest
management policy, and not environmental decisions by the Clinton
administration, was largely responsible for the devastating
forestfires this year. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DROUGHT (Undated) _ Drought in Texas has caused $5 billion
in damage of the past four years. This year's, the longest ever,
threatens to shut down three power plants if there is no
substantial rain in the next two months. By Ross E. Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   NAMBLA-SUIT (Undated) _ The ACLU of Massachusetts will defend
the North America Man/Boy Love Association, which advocates sex
between men and boys, against a federal lawsuit filed by the
parents of a 10-year-old boy slain by a man who had looked at the
group's website.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-OIL (St John's, Newfoundland) _ Atlantic Canada, from
Nova Scotia to Labrador, is poised to become the next North Sea or
Prudhoe Bay as oil and natural-gas production begins. Newfoundland,
long Canada's poorest province, stands to reap the biggest benefit.
Of the 11 oil fields larger than 100 million barrels discovered
worldwide since 1979, four have been off the coast of Newfoundland,
on the Grand Banks. Although Atlantic Canada's oil industry is now
taking its baby steps, the newest fields can only cement the
position of Canada as the United States' leading energy partner.
Canada already is the top supplier to the United States of natural
gas and the No. 2 supplier of oil, after Saudi Arabia. By James
Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALL (Nashville, Tenn.) _ Rarely has a leading global
company faced such extraordinary problems _ its best-selling
product blamed for scores of deaths, its biggest customer
undermining its every defense, its stock price plunging along with
consumer confidence, its top executive summoned before an angry
Congress. The company, one of America's most familiar brand names,
is now seen as being one a death watch. On Thursday, Washington
regulators raised the number of deaths attributed to failures of
Firestone tires and Venezuela's consumer agency asked the state
prosecutor to bring criminal charges against Firestone and the Ford
Motor Co., saying the design of Ford's Explorer sport utility
contributed to dozens of deaths in accidents there. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-LABOR (Undated) _ Bridgestone/Firestone faces a strike at
nine of its plants by 8,000 members of the steelworkers union if a
contract agreement is not reached by midnight Friday. By Steven
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   FORD-VENEZUELA (Caracas) _ Venezuela's consumer protection
agency is expected to issue a report this week recommending that
criminal charges be brought against both Ford Motor Co. and
Bridgestone/Firestone for fatal accidents.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL-SALES (Undated) _ Retailers are going into the fall
season apprehensive about a slowing economy and a pullback in
consumer spending. As back-to-school sales get into high gear, J.C.
Penney and Target warn that third-quarter results will be weaker
than expected. Other retailers report August sales. By Leslie
Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-RATES (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The European Central Bank
raised interest rates a quarter point Thursday, as expected,
despite the views of many economists that a rate increase was not
needed. The euro, which should have been the chief beneficiary of a
rate rise, instead touched a new low. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   SEAGRAM-BUYERS (London) _ Seagram Co. will open its books to
prospective buyers of its drinks business this week in what will be
the first stage of a process that could run through the middle of
October. By Suzanne Kapner.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-TAX (Paris) _ Taking its cue from Germany, the French
government has announced plans for $16.3 billion in corporate and
individual tax cuts. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-BOURSES (London) _ Developments in the battle for the
London Stock Exchange. By Suzanne Kapner.
