<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7372 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-AIRPORT-DELAYS-HNS &LR;      08-31 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-DELAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AIRPORT COSTS CONTINUE TO CLIMB 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Delays in opening the new international terminal
at the San Francisco airport have bumped up costs another $4.5
million to compensate the retail tenants.
</P>
<P>
   The city Airport Commission approved the payments Tuesday, two
weeks after approving $3.1 million to reimburse restaurants at the
terminal for construction costs and lost earnings caused by the
delay. The most recent action covered construction work that
retailers had to do on their own, including the extension of
utility lines, said airport spokesman Peter Nardoza.
</P>
<P>
   More costs were likely, he said, and the opening date is still
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Some retail tenants of the new terminal have incurred huge costs
in hiring employees in anticipation of an earlier opening, and some
have loan payments that begin before the new facility is open.
</P>
<P>
   The five-story international terminal, the centerpiece of the
San Francisco International Airport's $2.4 billion construction
project, was scheduled to open Sept. 26. Airport officials
announced Aug. 12 that they needed more time to test safety and
communications systems.
</P>
<P>
   A charter company, Sky Service, will begin using part of the
terminal around mid-September, Nardoza said. If all goes well, he
said, other airlines could move in sometime in November.
</P>
<P>
   The budget, originally $850 million, has grown to the $975
million-$1 billion range and could increase by an extra $25 million
to $50 million, Nardoza said. But he said the project is covered
and is not in the red. The increases are due to expansions in
building space available for retail business, approved by the
Airport Commission, and changes in design requested by the
airlines, Nardoza said.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners believe the prime contractor, Tutor-Saliba Corp.,
is taking longer than it should, and will consider going to court
to recover some of the costs if an agreement cannot be negotiated,
Nardoza said. The company has said changes in project
specifications by the commission are responsible for the delay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
