<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7390 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-AFFAIR-SPI &LR;      08-31 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-AFFAIR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTRAIT OF AFFAIR HAS TENDER TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B+  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two middle-aged Parisians meet through an ad in a rather racy
singles magazine for the expressed purpose of impersonal,
no-strings attached sex and remain nameless to one another until
the affair plays out to its nervous, frustrated break.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Affair of Love'' is not a remake of ``Last Tango in
Paris,'' though you might think so based on its original French
title, ``A Pornographic Affair.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathalie Baye (``The Return of Martin Guerre'') and Spanish
leading man Sergi Lopez (``Western'') play the lonely lovers, who
recall their brief love affair for an unseen interviewer. The mock
documentary interview framework, which comes from Ingmar Bergman's
``Hour of the Wolf'' (Woody Allen also used it in ``Husbands and
Wives''), is like a mediated confession to the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Their first meeting is awkward and apprehensive, charged with
both discomfort and excitement as they force small talk over drinks
before leaving for a hotel room. When they enter the room, the
camera discretely backs out of the hallway, staring at the closed
door fading away.
</P>
<P>
   It's an arch beginning to a film that loosens up to an easy
naturalism. Baye's nervous smiles become genuine and joyful as she
grows more confident and assured, and Lopez nicely straddles the
line between nonchalant openness and emotional defensiveness. The
purely physical meetings turn romantic and the discomfort dissolves
into relaxed conversations and passionate looks, until the camera
is invited into their hotel room for a spontaneous, unplanned
coupling.
</P>
<P>
   The original title to the contrary, the discreetly shot portrait
of pillow talk and passionate lovemaking is anything but
pornographic.
</P>
<P>
   Director Frederic Fonteyne briefly discards his naturalism for a
surreal vision of the hotel, a claustrophobic, hellishly crimson
red hall more literary device than dramatic realism, with a cool
blue sanctuary behind the door, a heaven on the other side of
purgatory. It effectively removes their affair so far from the
social world that when it intrudes, first in petty fears and then
in the form of an old couple suffering a loveless marriage, it
shatters their sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   The film is framed in flashback so there are no surprises, but
watching romance unravel is as painful as it is inevitable and
Fonteyne captures it with delicate modesty. Baye and Lopez create
fragile, vulnerable characters whose defensive instincts overcome
their courage as self doubts and second guesses get in the way of
their own honesty, and their performances are rich and nuanced.
</P>
<P>
   It's a modest film but rich with observation and unspoken
regret, and the texture of their performances bring it to life.
</P>
<P>
   AN AFFAIR OF LOVE
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: Frederic Fonteyne
</P>
<P>
   WRITER: Philippe Blasband
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Nathalie Baye, Sergi Lopez
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 80 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: No rating, features brief nudity and sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   LANGUAGE: French, with English subtitles
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1456EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7400 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-WHIPPED-SPI &LR;      08-31 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WHIPPED-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHIPPED' IS A REAL PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: F  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD   
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood seems to be having a competition this year to come up
with the most vulgar, vile and repulsively scatological comedy ever
made _ a reaction, the trade papers say, to the box-office success
of last year's celebration of sex and the bathroom, ``American
Pie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whipped'' is very much in this tradition. But since its studio
_ Destination Films _ is a little guy trying to make a name for
itself, it's gone all out to beat the competition with its volume
of crudity and the sheer gusto with which it rubs its audience's
face in the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   It's the story of three unbelievably odious and moronic
Manhattan bachelor buddies (Brian Van Holt, Jonathan Abrahams and
Zorie Barber) and their married pal (Judah Domke), who get together
every week to brag about their sexual exploits in numbingly graphic
terms.
</P>
<P>
   The plot deals with what happens when they each independently
meet the same perfect woman (Amanda Peet), and suddenly find
themselves in competition for her _ a conflict that's complicated
by the fact that she's quite happy to bed all three.
</P>
<P>
   But this story line _ which rips off the 1962 Kim Novak comedy,
``Boys' Night Out'' _ is only the thinnest imaginable premise for
first-time director-writer-producer Peter M. Cohen to string
together a succession of lame and/or intentionally disgusting sex
and bathroom gags.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, this kind of humor can be a guilty pleasure if it's
done with even a modest comic flair or comes out of an ingratiating
characterization. But this movie was made by a harrowingly
untalented filmmaker, and never comes close to an authentic laugh
or a recognizable human being.
</P>
<P>
   It's like a Woody Allen movie in which the characters endlessly
talk about their bowel movements instead of the incongruity of the
human condition.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps my distaste for this movie is an accumulation of
distaste for all the movies this summer that aim this low. Perhaps
there is a more excruciatingly painful and self-abusive way to
spend 82 minutes. But I honestly can't think of what it would be.
</P>
<P>
   WHIPPED
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR/WRITER: Peter M. Cohen
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Amanda Peet, Brian Van Holt, Jonathan Abrahams, Zorie
Barber, Judah Domke
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 82 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: R, for sex and toilet humor
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: F
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
