<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The top drivers in the Busch Grand National series
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are our picks for the top five drivers on the Busch
circuit:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1. Jeff Green: Green, from Owensboro, Ky., has a realistic
chance to claim the Busch Grand National championship by late
September. He has enjoyed a brief stint in Winston Cup with
less-than-stellar results. Green seems content running up front
each week in the No. 10 Chevrolet. He has two racing on the Busch
circuit, David and Mark.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  2. Jason Keller: Keller, who drives the No. 57 Chevrolet, is a
very solid driver. He's good for at least one victory each season.
Staying in Busch seems to be his best option, because he may not be
as marketable as some of the younger drivers. He is Jeff Green's
teammate.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3. Kevin Harvick: It's unusual for a rookie to be listed among
the top overall drivers. But Harvick has displayed veteran
tendencies in 21 of 22 races he has run. Two victories in a rookie
season is commendable, especially on a circuit where more than 50
cars attempt to qualify each week.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  4. Todd Bodine: Dogged by hard luck, the youngest of the three
racing Bodine brothers seems to have found a comfortable home in
the Busch Series after testing the Winston Cup waters in the early
1990s. Bodine would like to get back to Winston Cup, but realizes
he can be a star in Busch. Live television, large crowds, and
Sundays off is hard to walk away from when you consistently run in
the top five. He won this year in Busch for the first time since
1997 and substituted for Terry Labonte in the Winston Cup Series at
Indianapolis and Watkins Glen.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  5. Ron Hornaday: Busch's ``other rookie'' also has two
victories this year. Hornaday inherited the cars used the last two
years by Dale Earnhardt, Jr., who won back-to-back Busch
championships.
</P>
<P>
   He is a hard-nosed driver who has successfully made the jump
from the Craftsman Truck Series.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR Q&AMP;A: JIM HUNTER, DARLINGTON RACEWAY PRESIDENT
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Darlington Raceway hosts NASCAR's oldest race, the
Southern 500. Jim Hunter, president of Darlington Raceway, spoke
this week with Cox News Service reporter Rick Minter.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How special is it for you to be a South Carolina native and
be president of Darlington Raceway?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's more than a job, it's a lifestyle. When I was growing
up, there were two races on the radio every year _ the Indianapolis
500 and the Southern 500. I listened to both of them faithfully. I
didn't get to come to a race at Darlington until 1961 because I was
always playing football. Little did I know that the first race I
would see here would be as a sportswriter.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which Southern 500 do you consider the best race?
</P>
<P>
   A: Probably two years ago with Jeff Gordon and Jeff Burton.
Gordon was running for a million dollars from Winston. Burton got
about halfway up to him going into the third turn. They banged
fenders and got squirrelly. Jeff Gordon cut him off and went on to
win the million dollars. Jeff Burton said afterwards that if he had
known that was going happen he would have hit him a little harder.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who do you consider to be the best driver that ever ran
Darlington?
</P>
<P>
   A: David Pearson. He could run dirt, short asphalt, big asphalt,
road courses. Darrell Waltrip said you could run 400 miles of a
500-mile race and you'd never know David Pearson was on the same
racetrack. All of a sudden, in the last hundred miles, he'd come
roaring to the front. He was he first driver who raced for the
money. In the last few years, Dale Earnhardt has become a lot like
Pearson.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With NASCAR expanding into new markets, how long can
Darlington continue hosting two races a year?
</P>
<P>
   A: I feel pretty comfortable with our two dates right now.
They're adding two race next year _ at Chicago and Kansas _ and if
you're going to go to another big new market, a new race track is
going to have to be built. That will take at least two years. And
there are three or four tracks that they're going to have to look
taking a race from before they look at Darlington.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who are you picking to win Sunday's race?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think you'll see Rusty Wallace finally win Darlington. But
the Burton boys have won the last three Darlingtons, so it's going
to be pretty interesting.
</P>
<P>
   DID YOU KNOW?
</P>
<P>
   The Darlington Raceway track is shaped like an egg to protect a
minnow pond outside turn four. When the track was built in 1949, a
nearby landowner refused to budge, causing the track to be built
with wide turns one and two and narrow turns three and four. The
pond no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   DISAPPOINTMENT OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   No Rainbows for Gordon: If Jeff Gordon isn't wrecking with Tony
Stewart, then he's burdened with faulty engine parts. It happened
last week at Bristol. ``If we didn't have bad luck, we wouldn't
have any luck at all,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the No. 24 car placed 23rd at Bristol and is
struggling to hold his position in the top 10 in the points
standings.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott laying low
</P>
<P>
   Bill Elliott is a tough man who has spent a career racing with
injuries. Ray Evernham had to talk Elliott, who is recovering from
a broken left kneecap, out of driving at Bristol last week. Elliott
hates to sit on the sidelines, but he needs to lay low until the
knee heals.
</P>
<P>
   Bigger not always better
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Bristol night race did not have one of its
classic finishes, it still was exciting from start to finish. And
alone that was a change from most races this summer. Only three
short tracks remain on NASCAR's schedule. But bigger doesn't always
translate into better.
</P>
<P>
   Wells struggles for respectability
</P>
<P>
   When team owner Cal Wells selected Andy Houston to drive the
McDonald's-sponsored car in Winston Cup next year, he took a big
step toward respectability. Wells was the laughingstock of
stock-car racing earlier this year when he signed two open-wheel
drivers to participate in Busch and Winston Cup. Wells made a key
move by hiring Brad Parrott, the brother of Dale Jarrett's crew
chief, to be the top wrenchman with Pruett. Houston is the son of
Busch legend Tommy Houston and had far more potential than the
other finalist, Chad Little.
</P>
<P>
   Safety concerns muted
</P>
<P>
   The heated safety issue has cooled off in recent weeks. Jeff
Burton was one of only a few of big-name drivers to call for
big-time changes, which included a plea for modifications at New
Hampshire. The drivers return to the sport's ``most dangerous
track'' in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Ince inks deal with MB2
</P>
<P>
   James Ince, the youngest crew chief in the Winston Cup Series,
has signed a two-year contract with MB2 Motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   Ince, 29, is in charge of the No. 10 team of Johnny Benson this
year, and will remain so at least through the 2002 season.
</P>
<P>
   Are drivers really athletes?
</P>
<P>
   Golfers and race drivers have this in common: People always want
to know if they consider themselves to be ``athletes.'' As
expected, the question infuriates golfers and drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I have to say to anyone that thinks it doesn't take good
physical condition to drive one of these cars is that I'll give
them a two-second cushion and all they have to run is 18-second
laps at Bristol and let them run 50 laps straight and let's see
what they look like after 50 laps,'' Wally Dallenbach said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't care if they think we're athletes or not. When
you sit in one of these cars and do it yourself, then you can
answer for yourself whether we're athletes or not. I don't get
wrapped up in that,'' Dallenbach said. ``I think anybody that's
gone through the Richard Petty Driving School or any of those
driving schools has a little bit better appreciation for what a
race driver goes through in four hours in a stock car. When it's
hot, I've lost up to six pounds in a car.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR goes Hollywood
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood stunt man Stanton Barrett will drive the Jimmy
Spencer-owned car in the Busch Series race at Darlington. Barrett
has appeared in such movies as ``The Patriot'' and ``Last of the
Mohicans,'' and in the ``Baywatch'' and ``Beverly Hills 90210''
television series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're testing the grounds to potentially put together a
program for next year,'' Barrett said. ``We have had a few
companies show an interest in sponsoring a car with me driving and
Jimmy as the owner, and we're looking at some other opportunities
too. With my experience as a driver and his experience as an owner,
we think we can do some pretty great things together.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
