<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-TIRES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New tires may tame Darlington
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Darlington Raceway is known as the ``Track Too Tough to Tame.''
But to many Winston Cup drivers, it is the ``Track Too Tough For
Tires.''
</P>
<P>
   Tires get devoured on race days at the aging South Carolina
track. The abrasive surface of the egg-shaped oval ``chews up tires
like a cheese grater munching warm cheddar,'' according to one
NASCAR team member.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear, official tire supplier for the Winston Cup Series, is
doing its best to solve the problem. Today, the company will
introduce a tire with a new compound for Sunday's Southern 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will still see some tire wear and lap time give-up at the
event, but it will be dramatically reduced,'' Goodyear's Tony
Fruend predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Dale Jarrett in the 1999 Southern 500, we will see teams
not have to pit at every caution flag to gain valuable track
position. We believe the tires are on their way to taming
Darlington.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject of tires is always a popular topic in the garage
area, especially before the Darlington and Rockingham races. Ward
Burton, who won the spring race at Darlington last March, isn't
thrilled about the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish Goodyear would leave the tires alone,'' Burton said.
``It doesn't seem like these tires are nearly as consistent as the
brand that we had before, so it creates some problems for us at
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it definitely throws a whole other dimension to not only
using your notes, but also to trying to do your homework properly
before you take a car to the racetrack.''
</P>
<P>
   The new tire supposedly won't have as much grip, but it is
supposed to last longer. Two weeks ago, Tony Stewart's team
practiced with the tire at Darlington under the same hot and humid
conditions forecast for this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't see that it lasted much longer as far as speed was
concerned,'' said Greg Zipadelli, the No. 20 crew chief. ``It had
less grip and the wear wasn't as bad. It seemed like it worked a
little bit, but we gave up a bunch of grip. It was a little
frustrating at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Tire management figures to be the key this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track is so abrasive on tires that you like to pit on your
qualifying lap to get fresh tires,'' John Andretti said with a
chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
