<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BEACH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE POTENTIAL, `PSYCHO BEACH PARTY' STUCK IN THE SAND 
</HEADLINE>
   Our Grade: C+  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Psycho Beach Party'' desperately wants to be the ``Rocky
Horror Picture Show'' of the surf-and-sand movie set.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the campy stage play by Charles Busch (who co-stars as
the butch cop Capt. Monica Stark), it mushes the Frankie and
Annette beach parties with slasher films and psychological
thrillers and stirs it all up with an undercurrent of sexual
repression and homoerotic lust. It's a promising recipe for comedy
that goes flat in the execution.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Ambrose plays Chicklet, a spunky, schizophrenic Gidget
with two alternate personalities: a trash-talking homegirl and a
lusty dominatrix. Chaste cutie Chicklet, clueless to the dating
scene, joins the local surf clan led by Kanaka (Thomas Gibson) and
falls for college psych major dropout Starcat (Nicholas Brendon)
while Kanaka flirts with her dark side.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a blonde, bubble-headed B-movie starlet moves into
the haunted beach house and has a coed slumber party and a
mysterious slasher turns the teenage population into shish-kabobs.
With more hormonal urges and frustrated desire oozing out from the
lacquer of social conformity than a season of ``Dawson's Creek,''
anyone in this community could be the killer, and Chicklet's
tart-tongued alter ego leads the list.
</P>
<P>
   Bright and spirited, with a terrific surf-rock guitar score by
Ben Vaughan, wild go-go dancing credits, and cheesy B&AMP;W mock
drive-in movie clips, the film overflows with quotes from ``Attack
of the 50-Foot Woman'' to ``Marnie'' while ringing every teen movie
cliche this side of the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   So why isn't it funnier? Director Robert Lee King never gets his
young cast beyond their self-consciously gee-whiz spoofing. From a
Scandinavian exchange student with an accent this side of the
Swedish chef from ``The Muppet Show'' to a pair of hunky surfers
whose Greco-Roman gropes and cross-dressing horseplay belies their
heterosexual pose, the one-note parodies wear thin by the time the
film is through with them.
</P>
<P>
   The exception is Busch himself, who channels Eve Arden doing
Dirty Harry to give the best drag gag performance since Divine. He
doesn't overplay the part or wink at the audience, and he's
hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   The overbaked performances and campy melodrama flail in a flat
and functional sitcom style where dialogue comes in sputters and
pauses, as if waiting for the laugh track to kick in. King misses a
prime opportunity to pump up the parody and really shoot this
send-up into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   For all its energy and inspired moments of giddy goofiness,
``Psycho Beach Party'' gets stuck in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   PSYCHO BEACH PARTY
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: Robert Lee King
</P>
<P>
   WRITER: Charles Busch, from his stage play
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Lauren Ambrose, Thomas Gibson, Nichoas Brendon, Charles
Busch
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 95 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: No rating, features horror movie gore and outrageous
sexual innuendo
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
