<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREND-HEALTHYFANS-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BE GOOD FOR YOU 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Healthy FANatics :STUDIES FIND GOING ALL-OUT FOR A SPORTS TEAM CAN (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JAMES A. FUSSELL  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   OK all you know-it-alls, let's see
how you do with this one.
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to several research studies _ including one conducted
at the University of Kansas _ what can you do to foster feelings of
self-worth while insulating yourself from alienation and
depression?
</P>
<P>
   A) Give all your possessions to the poor?
</P>
<P>
   B) Turn off the TV and meditate?
</P>
<P>
   Ha! Some know-it-all you are. The correct answer is of course:
</P>
<P>
   C) Dress up in a weird costume, give yourself a nutty name and
scream your guts out for the sports team of your choice. YEAHHH
BABY! WOOOOOOO!
</P>
<P>
   (Grease paint and silly hat optional.)
</P>
<P>
   OK, we're kidding. But only a little.
</P>
<P>
   A growing body of research suggests that passionate, die-hard
sports fans _ far from being the lonely, alienated get-a-life
losers psychologists once suspected them to be _ are in reality
just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   It all goes back to primitive times when warriors fought to
protect their tribes, psychologists say. Fans at that time might
quite literally have been cheering for their survival. Today sports
teams symbolically fill that same role for a city, and people still
react to them the same way.
</P>
<P>
   And that can be healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Wann, a psychologist at Murray State University in
Kentucky, has done several studies _ including one in 1991 in which
ardent University of Kansas basketball fans were the subjects _
that suggest that ``highly identified'' fans are not only happy and
largely well adjusted, but also suffer fewer bouts of depression
than those who are uninterested in sports _ even when their team
loses.
</P>
<P>
   You realize what this means, of course? It means it's entirely
possible that ``Arrowman'' _ that crazy Chiefs fan who attends
every game with dozens of arrows sticking out of his body _ could
be a better role model for your children than the majority of the
athletes on the field.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, not really crazy after all.
</P>
<P>
   Mom, I wanna grow up to be just like Arrowman.
</P>
<P>
   That's wonderful, Billy. And look! I bought you a new arrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Gosh, for me? (Billy jabs the arrow through his shirt and runs
off doing the chop.) You're the best, Mom.
</P>
<P>
   Recently we caught up with Arrowman, aka Monte Short, to see if
he really did fit the kinder, happier theory about super fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, uhh, tell us, Monte. You're not really some sad, lonely,
alienated loser searching for meaning in your otherwise bleak and
miserable life, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Short is a successful real estate developer with a
beautiful home and an otherwise normal life. He said he's thrilled
that research has shown that ardent fans such as himself are just
regular Joes who just like to have a good time.
</P>
<P>
   He's also glad he no longer has to worry about the rest of his
screwball dress-up friends around the league. He knows them all.
They call him, send him pictures, stay at his house when their team
plays in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   It's just one big happy weird well-adjusted family.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Short was inducted into the Visa Hall of Fans at the
Pro Football Hall of Fame in Canton, Ohio. All the other teams'
super fans were there, too, all happy and bursting with
self-esteem, Short said.
</P>
<P>
   There were Spike and the Violator from the Oakland Raiders, who
paint their heads in silver and black and dress in post-apocalyptic
gear complete with shoulder spikes. There was Barrel Man from
Denver, who spends Sundays substantially naked with an orange
barrel around his waist. There were the Fin Heads from Miami, Larry
the Packalope from Green Bay, Green Man from Philadelphia, Big Dawg
from Cleveland's infamous ``Dawg Pound'' and Mikey T, the Boss
Hogette from the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a comic book that's come alive,'' Monte's wife,
Stacie, said.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago area therapist Aaron Shimmel has studied intense fans
for five years. His conclusion: They're nuts.
</P>
<P>
   But not in a bad way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their devotion and loyalty to teams and players is truly
admirable,'' he said. ``By and large these are happy, healthy
people who've simply found something they really love. Not all of
us can say that.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Michael Torbert, alias ``Boss Hogette,'' who formed a
cheerleading squad for his beloved Washington Redskins. The squad
consists of 11 men who wear long dresses, sunglasses and pig snouts
and cheer as wildly as their attire will allow.
</P>
<P>
   Weird?
</P>
<P>
   Sure.
</P>
<P>
   Sad-pathetic-living-in-the-basement weird?
</P>
<P>
   Actually no. Torbert is a responsible and happy adult. He's also
a nuclear engineer. What's more, he and the Hogettes make more than
100 charity appearances a year. And since 1983, Torbert said, they
have helped raise more than $60 million for children's charities.
</P>
<P>
   While he'll never stop being a crazy fan, Torbert said, he
realizes there are things that are more important.
</P>
<P>
   Like children.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go into sick kids' rooms and they light up like a
Christmas tree,'' he said, ``it's worth all the time in the dress
and the snout.''
</P>
<P>
   So remember. The next time you're tempted to worry about the
dress-for-the-game, live-for-team, odd-looking, rebel-yelling
sports maniac whose whole identity seems to be wrapped up in a
sports team, be careful.
</P>
<P>
   They're as sane, or saner, than you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7417 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-REFORM-PARTY-FUNDING-     08-31 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-FUNDING-$ADV03-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     REFORM PARTY RIVALS FIGHT OVER $12.6 MILLION IN FEDERAL FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Sept. 3.)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly three weeks after their convention in
California ended with chaotic infighting, Pat Buchanan and John
Hagelin, his rival for control of the Reform Party, have shifted
their battle to Washington, D.C., where federal campaign funds
totaling $12.6 million remain up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission (FEC), which will decide who
gets the money, must choose between commentator Buchanan, a former
Republican, and physicist John Hagelin of Iowa, who is also running
on the Natural Law Party ticket. Each was nominated by competing
Reform Party conventions last month in Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC decision will not be easy. The party forged by Texas
billionaire Ross Perot, who garnered 19 percent of the 1992
presidential vote, is in shambles. At its convention, shoving
matches broke out among delegates with differing loyalties after
days of angry negotiations that eventually collapsed and led to the
party's split.
</P>
<P>
   Now the FEC is being forced to sort through the mess and choose
the party's true nominee. But the commission has never faced
anything like it.
</P>
<P>
   Ask what standard the commission will use to decide which
candidate receives the money, FEC spokeswoman Kelly Huff said:
``This is truly a new situation, one that we'll have to deal with
as we go along.''
</P>
<P>
   The party's nominee is entitled to the money because Perot,
running again 1996, received 8 percent of the presidential vote,
exceeding the commission's 5 percent requirement. Since both the
Buchanan and Hagelin campaigns are running low on funds, the
federal money would provide a significant boost.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan joked last month that if he doesn't get the money, his
campaign will ``be on short rations.''Huff said the FEC's first
task will be to certify that both Buchanan and Hagelin are on the
ballot in at least 10 states as the Reform Party candidate.
Buchanan already has submitted documents claiming to have the
Reform Party ballot line in Alaska, Arizona, Delaware, Idaho,
Maryland, New Jersey, New Mexico, South Dakota, Utah and West
Virginia. Hagelin is expected to submit his state list early this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates are scrambling to get their name on more ballots
to bolster their case before the FEC. As a result, some states _
many of which have no procedure to decide who is the party's
nominee _ have resorted to unorthodox methods of choosing.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Iowa officials pulled Buchanan's name out of a
glass bowl, while in Montana, Hagelin's name was drawn from among
20 cards inside a ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC's next step will be to determine whether both men
followed the party's own nominating rules.
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin supporters have accused Buchanan of massive vote fraud.
They claim he sent about 500,000 primary ballots to people on his
Republican donor list, asking them to vote for him in the Reform
Party's mail-in primary. They say the vast majority did not request
the ballots, which party rules require. Hagelin allies claim that a
random check of 14 Buchanan primary voters in Iowa found that 12
had not asked for the ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The Buchanan campaign denies any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's evidence of any illegal actions, we'll look into
it, but as of now, we haven't decided on any investigation into
vote fraud,'' Huff said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the FEC will ``do its best'' to decide within 10 days
after Hagelin submits his state ballot documents. However, Huff
added, the loser may ask for another hearing, which would extend
the final deadline by 15 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the need to get this issue resolved as quickly
as possible and not have it interfere with the election campaign,''
she said. ``But some things are out of our control.''
</P>
<P>
   Huff was referring to threats from both sides to challenge in
court some states' decisions on which candidate represents the
Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   M. Miller Baker, an expert in election law here, said he expects
the FEC to certify Buchanan as the nominee and release the funds to
his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there's some type of wrongdoing, Buchanan won the
majority of primary votes and has the support of the Reform Party
Chairman (Gerry Moan),'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   The final tally of the Reform Party Convention in Long Beach was
49,529 votes for Buchanan and 28,539 for Hagelin. At the rump
convention Hagelin won.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who gets the FEC's blessing, the matter will
almost certainly end up in federal court since each side has
promised to fight any decision that favors the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Verney, founding chairman of the Reform Party and a Hagelin
supporter, said: ``Pat Buchanan will be going out the wrong end of
a nursing home before he sees that money.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In fact, the legal wrangling has already begun. Last month,
Buchanan supporters filed a federal lawsuit in Lynchburg, Va.,
seeking to prevent Hagelin from calling himself the Reform Party
candidate. But last Wednesday, U.S. District Court Judge Norman K.
Moon said he lacks jurisdiction to decide the case because it
raised no constitutional issue.
</P>
<P>
   Some political experts say that even if Buchanan wins FEC
approval, the Reform Party's troubles have effectively destroyed
any chance of his garnering much support this year.
</P>
<P>
   J. David Gillespie, a political science professor at
Presbyterian College in Clinton, S.C., and an expert on minor
parties, said, ``It's hard to imagine him having any substantial
impact on this election.''
</P>
<P>
   A USA Today/CNN/Gallup Poll taken last week put his support
among likely voters at 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
