<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7418 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-POLS-WAVE-NNS &LR;      08-31 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLS-WAVE-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN SEASON GIVES NEW MEANING (OR IS IT NO MEANING?) TO THE
WAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
THURSDAY, Aug. 31, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADVISORY: With two photos, of Gore waving from a plane (NNS1)
and Bush and Cheney waving from a train (NNS2). For information
about purchasing these photos call 202-383-7824.
 By DRU SEFTON 
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's campaign season, so the presidential candidates are waving.
And waving and waving. And waving some more.
</P>
<P>
   As far as photographs go, a candidate needs a baby there to kiss
and a hand there to shake, but doesn't need anyone on the receiving
end of a friendly wave. So candidates for the highest office in
this land can, and do, wave at absolutely no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I've done it,'' admitted Paul Simon, former Illinois
senator and a 1988 Democratic presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Waving at no one while marching in a parade is especially
embarrassing, added Simon, now a professor and director of the
Public Policy Institute at Southern Illinois University-Carbondale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt parades were a little phony,'' he said. ``I'm
not criticizing anybody, I've done them myself. You have to. You
wave, and just hope somebody waves back at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Photojournalists currently trailing all these wave-happy pols
are very familiar with this waving-at-no-one technique.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Williamson, a Pulitzer Prize-winning shooter with The
Washington Post, noticed it while covering Vice President Al Gore
on a 24-hour swing through the flooded Northwest several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was leaving from an airport in Idaho in the middle of the
night,'' Williamson said. ``There was nobody there, nobody. And he
still did the wave.''
</P>
<P>
   Airplanes and airports seem to trigger the reflex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite often when we arrive somewhere the candidate will hop
out of the airplane and instinctively start waving, even if a
crowd's not there to greet him,'' said Rick Wilking, a Reuters
contract photographer and longtime campaign shooter.
</P>
<P>
   As Williamson said of the candidates, ``After awhile they're
kind of like trained seals.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing is this: A wave _ even a wave at no one _ works well
to create a positive impression for the cameras, said Bruce Newman,
a DePaul University professor of marketing and author of ``The Mass
Marketing of Politics: Democracy in an Age of Manufactured
Images.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a portrayal of what the candidate is trying to do with
voters, which is connect emotionally,'' Newman said. ``A wave is
good because they look happy, they look like they're in touch.''
</P>
<P>
   The larger the venue, the greater a wave's impact.
</P>
<P>
   Say the candidate is in front of a rally of thousands of
supporters and campaign workers. He waves to the crowd. Of course,
he's not waving at any one individual.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the workers can go back home and say the candidate waved
at them personally, and they feel like they're getting
recognition,'' Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly the wave is movement. Photographers like movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gestures are a natural way to add video to your audio,'' said
Lillian Brown, image consultant to six presidents (Kennedy,
Johnson, Nixon, Ford, Carter and Clinton) and an adjunct professor
at Georgetown University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Brown counsels candidates on how to look and act on the campaign
trail. One of the basic lessons: Develop a wave of your own.
</P>
<P>
   ``A wave is a totally individual matter,'' Brown added. ``It has
to fit the individual. Queen Elizabeth has hers, and President
Nixon had his.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, a wave gives a candidate something to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not engaged in some form of action you look silly,
and a photographer won't take your picture,'' said Kathleen Hall
Jamieson, dean of the Annenberg School for Communication at the
University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``The photographer wants the candidate to gesture, to talk to
someone, or to wave,'' added Jamieson, author of ``Everything You
Think You Know About Politics ... And Why You're Wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The needs of the politicians and the media work together to
create politics as we now know it.''
</P>
<P>
   This ``waving at no one'' actually is part of a larger
phenomenon, Jamieson said. In campaigns nowadays, an audience's
physical presence is no longer necessary.
</P>
<P>
   This began, she added, in 1984 when Rep. Newt Gingrich of
Georgia started giving impassioned speeches to an empty House
chamber _ empty except for the C-SPAN cable TV cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've transformed the immediate audience, wherever it is, into
essentially a backdrop,'' Jamieson said. ``This is the nature of
contemporary politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
