r e BC-PROFILE-SOULSURVIVOR-     08-31 1745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-SOULSURVIVOR-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUL SURVIVOR:AS AN ORPHAN, FLORENCE B. SMITH BEGAN TELLING STORIES
AND NEVER STOPPED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JAMES A. FUSSELL  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   Sent to an Oklahoma orphanage at age
5, Florence B. Smith cried at nights for her father.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Where are you?'' she wondered. ``Why don't you come get me?''
</P>
<P>
   Now a 71-year-old Overland Park author, Smith can never forget
the paralyzing loneliness of her early life. Neither can she escape
the rejection she felt.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, who was divorced, sent Florence and her younger
sister Martha to the red-brick orphanage in Helena, Okla. Their
mother also got a court order to prevent the father from finding
his children.
</P>
<P>
   A family took Martha almost immediately. But Florence stayed in
the orphanage for seven years, longing to be reunited with her
father.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to escape into his arms, she escaped into her mind. She
made up stories to entertain herself. Fun stories, adventure
stories, stories of girls getting adopted by wonderful families, of
loving fathers finding long-lost daughters.
</P>
<P>
   When there was little else to do, she'd turn to her fellow
orphans and said, ``Want to hear a story?''
</P>
<P>
   They always would.
</P>
<P>
   The children came to love Florence's fanciful tales. They loved
them so much that when she would be sent to the discipline room,
they would get themselves into trouble, too, just so they wouldn't
miss one.
</P>
<P>
   Today Florence B. Smith is still telling stories. Only this time
she's writing them down.
</P>
<P>
   A 35-year member of the Kansas City Writer's Group, Smith
specializes in adventure novels of the Old West, with most set in
the late 1800s. Her books, many spotlighting Kansas counties and
towns, are rich, regional melodramas spiced with romance and
rescues, with a sprinkle of history thrown in for authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   She has submitted her work to publishers but has had scarcely
more than a nibble. So several years ago she began self-publishing
her books. Edited by her husband and proofread by friends, they
sell for an average of $7.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three years she has sold more than 1,500 of her
books at regional festivals, fairs and through her Web site,
www.readwest.com//florencebsmith.htm. A selection of her books also
is offered on Amazon.com. She's not getting rich but has cultivated
a growing number of fans who read her religiously.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has no intention of giving up. This year she finished her
38th book. The resolution
</P>
<P>
   It certainly hasn't been easy.
</P>
<P>
   At the orphanage, Florence had settled into a routine. She had
friends there. She went to school there. She had a life there.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed at age 12 when her mother suddenly reappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Remarried by then, her mother needed Florence not so much as a
daughter, but as a servant, Smith said. She wanted her to cook and
clean, wash and baby-sit her new son.
</P>
<P>
   To the outside world her mother was an upstanding woman. But at
home, she was too often a monster. One time, after Florence stole a
dime at school, her mother beat her until she was nearly
unconscious. Florence couldn't return to school for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Florence tried to run away several times with no success. It was
only through marriage at age 16 that she finally got away.
</P>
<P>
   If making up stories helped Smith survive the loneliness of the
orphanage, surely committing them to paper would help her deal with
years of abuse at the hands of her mother.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that Smith resolved to write. At 36, then living in
Kansas City, she joined a writer's group.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one problem. She was awful. While smart and
determined to learn, she knew virtually nothing about such writing
basics as punctuation, grammar and sentence structure, not to
mention the more subtle techniques involved in plotting, dialogue
and characterization.
</P>
<P>
   She refused to give up. She took advice, read books, pored over
critiques.
</P>
<P>
   And she got better. A lot better.
</P>
<P>
   To fellow local writer Sophia Myers, Smith is a study in
perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anyone who is more inspirational insofar as
starting with no education, no opportunities, no one to encourage
her and out of sheer determination becoming a really successful
writer.''
</P>
<P>
   How's this for successful: Smith sat at a small table at a
festival in Troy, Kan., two years ago with stacks of her
self-published novels piled around her. Just then an exhibitor from
a nearby booth walked up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got any books about Indians?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' she said, handing him her book Guardian Falls. The man
bought the book, then sat down to read it.
</P>
<P>
   The next day he came back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I doubt you can do better than this,'' he said, ``but
have you got anything else like it?''
</P>
<P>
   Smith nodded, then sold him four more books. When the festival
ended, Smith figured she'd never see him again. But four months
later he knocked at her front door. He had driven nearly two hours
to Overland Park to get even more of her books. Smith obliged,
selling the man 29 more on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Although not nationally distributed, her work does get around.
</P>
<P>
   A woman named Nancy D'Alessandro from Los Altos, Calif., sent
Smith a hand-written note thanking her for her book Separated By
Hate, the story of a mixed-race woman with a terrible secret that
threatens to ruin her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the best stories I have ever read,''
D'Alessandro wrote. ``I enjoyed Devil From Franklin County, too.
But Separated I couldn't put down. On hot summer nights I was
reading outside _ by flashlight!'' Growing through words
</P>
<P>
   Over the years writing has been more than an avocation for
Smith; it's been a way to heal the wounds of her past.
</P>
<P>
   Like any good writer she uses her experiences to her advantage.
Therefore her books are teeming with villains, conflicts, hard
times, girls who need rescuing, heroes and romance.
</P>
<P>
   It's an old-fashioned style that fans say makes for a
rip-roaring good read.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can put down a great novel like (one by) John Irving and not
worry,'' said Virginia DeCoursey, a longtime friend, proofreader
and fan. ``But I get into one of her things, and I can't put the
darn thing down. I gotta get the girl out of the well or off the
railroad tracks. You get all caught up in the spirit of it. They're
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Publishers, DeCoursey said, don't know what they're missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gets in romance, sex, history, oh, she just twists your
heart. They're just great old melodramas. You want to hiss the
villain.''
</P>
<P>
   But as impressed as friends are with Smith's growth as a writer,
they are even more impressed with her growth as a person.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years she reunited with her father and her sister,
forgave her mother and lived a life of faith, service and love.
</P>
<P>
   Her teen-age marriage to her husband, Ike, has lasted for 55
years.
</P>
<P>
   Although she could not have children of her own, she and her
husband did adopt three children. Their first child, David, a deaf
and mentally challenged 53-year-old, still lives with them. In
addition she and her husband have taken in 25 foster children. And,
yes, she told them stories.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them still call her Mom.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, friends said, some of her most moving writing has
been about her children.
</P>
<P>
   DeCoursey remembers being moved by an article Smith wrote for
Field &AMP; Stream magazine about a fishing trip she and her husband
took with David.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just broke your heart,'' she said. ``David had a real
expensive fishing rod. And he caught a catfish, and when he saw the
catfish he started signing ``Jaws! Jaws!'' It frightened him, and
he let go of the pole, and it washed away. She wrote that she was
never so proud of her husband as when he took David into his arms
and held him. You know, the heck with the rod.''
</P>
<P>
   Her friend Teresa Peck thinks people could profit from Smith's
example in many ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who is that good a person, who is that dedicated and
who has overcome so much, is an inspiration,'' she said. Whirlwind
writer
</P>
<P>
   Today you can't get Smith to stop writing, even when her
daughters drop by for a visit. Her friends call her ``The
Whirlwind.''
</P>
<P>
   One time she was in the middle of writing a love scene when she
called out to her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me a kiss,'' she said, still typing.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right,'' he said. ``Am I a 21-year-old buck or a
50-year-old toothless man?''
</P>
<P>
   She hadn't realized she had said the line she was typing out
loud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take your pick,'' she said quickly, turning around to give him
a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Others may sell more books, those who know her say. But no one
has more fun writing them.
</P>
<P>
   When researching her historical novels, she typically takes
friends on fact-finding missions. It could be to LeCompton,
Atchison, Council Grove or Cherryvale. She never knows where she's
headed next.
</P>
<P>
   Millie Alport of Lenexa has gone with her as much as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to go anytime,'' she said. ``I've learned a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith typically visits the towns and counties where she sets her
stories so she can give her tales a tinge of historical
authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   She is dogged, Alport said, hitting newspaper archives,
historical societies, libraries and buying as many books about the
area as she can carry. Then she buttonholes locals along the street
or in the corner cafe and learns even more.
</P>
<P>
   Her favorite history includes anything involving underdogs and
minorities. Her grandfather was half Cherokee. The locals in Enid,
Okla., used to call him names.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hurtful,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She's also sensitive to what she calls the ``bum start''
received in the Old West by blacks, Hispanics and women.
Consequently many of the characters in her book, including some
high-profile heroes and heroines, are minorities. In Black Knights
and Starshine, a strong black character named Molec Ross leads a
group of 120 former slaves from Tennessee on foot to a new life in
Oklahoma, while helping them learn more about life and themselves
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Her historical novels are liable to be about anything, ranging
from true love to serial killers.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how much she writes, the man who once drove two
hours to find her still can't get enough.
</P>
<P>
   He caught up with her again when she returned to the festival in
Troy earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got any more books?'' he wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just one,'' Smith said, handing him her latest, Confederate
Gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
