<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7434 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-`CELL'-LIEBERMAN-RESE     08-31 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`CELL'-LIEBERMAN-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD'S LOVE AFFAIR WITH GORE (AND WE DON'T MEAN AL)  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...RESENDING from Aug. 24)   (This 850-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In his speech accepting the Democratic
vice-presidential nomination recently, Joseph Lieberman made one of
his customary swipes at the gratuitous sex and violence coming out
of Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many Americans,'' he told delegates at the party convention
in Los Angeles, ``there is a swelling sense that our standards of
decency and civility have eroded.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Senator Lieberman's worst nightmare has just come to life.
</P>
<P>
   In one of those fortuitous coincidences that are simply too good
to have been manufactured, the film currently topping the U.S. box
office is a veritable orgy of grotesque imagery, stomach-churning
violence, scenes of torture for torture's sake, rape, child abuse
and serial murder.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``The Cell,'' it purports to be a phantasmagorical
exploration of the mind of a vicious killer, a bit like ``The
Silence of the Lambs.'' Instead of the suave, urbane,
psychologically terrifying Hannibal Lecter, however, we have Carl
Stargher, played by Vincent D'Onofrio, who appears to have no
redeeming social skills at all.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite pastime is to kidnap women and imprison them in a
plexiglass cell in the middle of the Mojave desert, where their
slow death by drowning is captured on videotape in gruesome detail.
</P>
<P>
   Stargher then douses the corpses in bleach, lays them on a
coroner's slab, plays back the death video and masturbates over
them while suspending himself from the ceiling with chains attached
to 14 steel rings embedded in his back.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the start of it. Most of the film actually takes
place inside Stargher's head, where FBI agents played by Vince
Vaughn and Jennifer Lopez are transported by the wonders of modern
technology _ I kid you not _ only to watch a horse being sliced and
diced into Damien Hirst-like tranverse sections, observe a woman
drowning in a bath of her own blood and, in one particularly
unpleasant sequence, have their own guts ripped out with a pair of
scissors and twisted on a barbecue spit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cell'' is the debut feature of an Indian commercials
director called Tarsem Singh, previously best known for making the
music video for the REM song ``Losing My Religion.'' (In the spirit
of Hollywood sequels, this venture might have been called ``Losing
My Lunch'').
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, he doesn't think there is anything particularly
violent about his movie. ``It's graphic,'' he told one interviewer
last week, ``but not violent.''
</P>
<P>
   To anyone unimpressed by claims of ``arty'' production design or
modish preoccupation with the bleakness of the human spirit, this
film actually looks like the best argument for censorship the
anti-Hollywood faction in Washington ever had.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is it nasty, it is shamelessly directed at teenagers.
Rated R rather than NC17 (which means children can, to all intents
and purposes, get in with little trouble), it made most of last
weekend's $17.2 million take from adolescent boys in search of the
latest celluloid thrill _ exactly the market, and the material,
that got Hollywood into such trouble after the Columbine High
School shootings last year.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if this were the only film Joe Lieberman or his
Republican counterpart in the morality crusades, Bill Bennett, got
to see this decade, there's a fair bet the film industry would go
the way of Big Tobacco and be hit with billion-dollar lawsuits for
threatening the health and sanity of the nation's children.
</P>
<P>
   And yet _ the cultural warriors have been remarkably silent
about ``The Cell.'' Film critics have certainly vented their
disgust: the Los Angeles Times called it ``nauseating'' and the
sort of film you are sorry you ever saw. But from the politicians,
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   There are just two words to explain their reticence:
presidential election. The Republicans have never gained any
mileage from Hollywood-bashing on the campaign trail, and know
better now than to shoot their mouths off and risk losing votes.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Democrats, both Lieberman and Al Gore may have
expressed concern in the past about sex, violence and profanity in
the entertainment industry, but they have their own constituencies
to think about.
</P>
<P>
   Gore raised a record-breaking $5 million in direct campaign
contributions from Hollywood during the convention week, and can
hardly afford now to bite the hand that fed him.
</P>
<P>
   As for Lieberman, he agreed as part of the price of admission to
the presidential ticket to drop his more confrontational rhetoric.
For example, the Silver Sewer awards, which he and Bennett doled
out each year to products just like ``The Cell,'' have been put on
hold on the grounds they are not ``vice presidential.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Hollywood is home free, and looking remarkably cocky
given that a special Federal Trade Commission report on the
marketing of violence to children is about to be released to
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The self-flagellating promises the industry made to police its
own exploitative excesses in the wake of Columbine now appear to be
forgotten. Instead, gore is in vogue once again _ and not the Gore
the Democrats might have hoped for. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 850-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
