<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-CONTROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAWMAKER SHELVES GUN-LICENSING BILL FOR YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Conceding that Gov. Gray Davis would not
support his gun-control measure this year, a Pasadena lawmaker has
abandoned a bill to require a safety test and a license for handgun
owners.
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate had already approved the bill, one of the most
sweeping gun-licensing proposals in the nation, but Davis signaled
that he would do nothing to advance the bill in the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline for legislative action was Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on conversations with the governor's office, I
reluctantly have become convinced that my best chance for seeing
this bill become law is to pursue it next year,'' said Democratic
Assemblyman Jack Scott, whose 27-year-old son died in a gun
accident.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to get gun-control legislation passed in the
Assembly, where some moderate Democrats from the Central Valley are
skittish about offending conservative voters, especially in an
election year.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a Democrat, helped persuade some of these same lawmakers
to pass four tough gun-control measures last year, but declined to
do the same thing during the 1999-2000 session. Davis said he
thought the Legislature should wait to see the effect of the new
laws before writing more gun control legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation Davis signed last year ban the manufacture and
sale of certain high-powered weapons, prohibit the purchase of more
than one gun a month, require trigger locks be sold with every new
gun, and set new safety standards for the manufacturing of
handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, the author of last year's trigger-lock bill, said he
understood Davis' concerns about passing new measures, but had
``hoped that I would be able to convince the governor my licensing
bill should be an exception.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott's bill would have required every Californian who buys a
handgun to pass a four- to eight-hour safety class before applying
for a license.
</P>
<P>
   New handgun owners also would have been required to prove their
aptitude at a firing range and on a written exam covering legal use
of deadly force, gun storage and gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would have been the most comprehensive gun-licensing
bill in the nation. Scott said he would take the issue up again
next year ``or however long it takes for it to become law.''
</P>
<P>
   About 780 Californians were accidentally killed by firearms
between 1991 and 1997, according to the most recent state
statistics. Of those killings, 226 were children. During the same
period, 1,924 children and 6,333 adults were injured after
unintentional shootings.
</P>
</TEXT>
