<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the Republican presidential nominee, George W.
Bush, named Richard Cheney to be his running mate four weeks ago,
there were quips from Bush critics that the ticket was the wrong
way around. Was Not Cheney, a former White House chief of staff and
defense secretary during the Gulf War, better equipped to be
president than the one-and-a-half-term governor of Texas? Now,
though, with opinion polls showing Bush and his Democratic rival,
Vice President Al Gore, running neck and neck into the crucial
Labor Day weekend, that same Cheney is looking increasingly like a
liability for the Bush ticket....By Mary Dejevsky, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
