   (675 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TV-JUNKIE MUSCOVITES FACE LIFE WITHOUT THEIR `NARCOTIC' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TV-LESS-MOSCOW-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Muscovites were thrown back to the pre-electronic age
this week after the devastating fire at the Ostankino television
tower, which knocked most of their TV channels off the air. The
body of a third victim, trapped in an elevator which plummeted
furing the blaze, has been identified, yet all but close relatives
of the dead were more concerned about how they would cope with the
loss of news and entertainment programs to which they had become
addicted....By Helen Womack, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAFETY FEARS OVER `UNSAFE' CZECH NUCLEAR POWER PLANT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CZECH-CHERNOBYL?-INDEPENDENT-600&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEMELIN, CZECH REPUBLIC _ The people who live near Temelin, in
the rolling hills of south Bohemia, have been issued two small
tablets each. They have been told to keep them in a safe place _
and to take them if anything goes wrong at the Soviet-designed
nuclear power plant that is to be activated _ on or around Sept. 10
_ a few miles from their homes _ a plant neighboring Germany said
this week it was not convinced is safe....By Justin Huggler, The
Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (EDITORS: Note Sept. 5 and 10 _ grafs 2 and 4) &QL;
</P>
