   &UR; ON THE SECTION FRONT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL-ELECTRIC (Undated) _ In a few months, John Welch will
step down as chief executive of the General Electric Co., ending a
remarkable 20-year run of earnings growth and near cultlike
devotion. The three front-runners to succeed this 20th-century
business icon fit a pattern: All are gung-ho results-getters for
the company _ and all are white men. Where are the women? The
blacks? The Latinos? The Asians? Together, these groups make up
about 40 percent of GE's domestic workforce, but they are not easy
to find in the executive corps of GE, which is regarded as
America's most admired corporation. By Mary Williams Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   JOHNNIE-COCHRAN (Undated) _ Talking money with celebrity Johnnie
Cochran. Success is not new to Cochran, now 62. Long before his
mustache and sharp ties became a daily staple of the grisly O.J.
Simpson murder trial, he was a big-time lawyer with a heavy
criminal practice. His disciplined, relentless cross-examination at
the trial, however, made Cochran one of the most famous _ and
controversial _ lawyers in America. But it didn't leave him as rich
as it left him famous. Now, he is determined to close that gap. By
Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-WATCH (Undated) _ Weekly Wall Street commentary. By
Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE THE SECTION: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOWARD-BUFFETT-PROFILE (Decatur, Ill.) _ As the eldest son of
the so-called ``Oracle of Omaha,'' a man many consider the greatest
stock picker of all time, Howard Buffett is now positioned to
become the next chairman of Berkshire Hathaway, the holding company
his father turned into an investor's gold mine. A profile of the
younger Buffett, an investor in his own right. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BUSINESS (Undated) _ Despite scandal and huge expense,
Olympic sponsorships remain hugely popular, with revenues from them
setting new records this year. No matter what happens on the track,
in the pool or over the field, there may be no more dramatic an
Olympic comeback in 2000 than the one the IOC has pulled on the
sponsorship front. By Randall Lane.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   DEBITCARDS-STUDENTS (Undated) _ Parents who hope to keep their
college-age kids from getting over their heads in debt often
arrange for them to have debit cards rather than credit cards for
emergencies. Card issuers are sabotaging that strategy by giving
debit-card kids ``overdraft protection'' that amounts to an
expensive revolving line of credit _ in other words, a credit card.
By Nancy Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
<P>
   DEBITCARD-DRAWBACKS (Undated) _ Little-known reasons debit cards
are a rotten deal for all consumers, and especially for financial
novices like college kids. By Nancy Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   FIVE-QUESTIONS-BANKRUPTCY (Undated) _ A decade ago, a trio of
scholars, in an award-winning analysis of bankruptcy filings,
destroyed the myth that most of those seeking refuge from creditors
were blue collar workers. People in every occupation go bankrupt in
rough proportion to their numbers, Elizabeth Warren, Teresa
Sullivan and Jay Lawrence Westbrook found in a widely praised study
of Bankruptcy Court records. Now they have refined their research
and shown that misfortune, not profligate living, is behind most
bankruptcy filings. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INVESTING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-BROKERAGE (Undated) _ Brokers, according to Wall Street
truism, prosper when the market goes up and when it goes down. But
this year the market has gone nowhere _ no major average has moved
as much as 4 percent from its Dec. 31 level _ and the brokers have
done better than ever. And many in Wall Street think that brokerage
shares, despite rich prices and a history of sharp cyclical swings,
have still more room to fly. A major reason, analysts say, is how
they are taking business from banks in a new regulatory landscape
for which the banks themselves lobbied vigorously for decades. By
Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Market Insight Q&AMP;A . Subject to
come. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-WHITE-QW&AMP;K (Undated) _ Investing With Edward B. White of
the GW&AMP;K Equity Fund. By Carole Gould.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-BONDS (Undated) _ With the bond market outperforming the
stock market for the first time in a decade, a bullish forecast for
Treasuries should offer investors a glimmer of hope, and Dr. Edward
Yardeni, chief global economist and investment strategist at
Deutsche Bank Securities is making just such a forecast. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL COMMENTARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STRATEGIES-COLUMN (Undated) _ Even a new study that credits
mutual fund managers with market-beating stockpicking skill _ a
rare positive finding _ says that their advantage is more than
counteracted by the expensive inefficiency of the fund industry,
leaving investors lagging behind the market anyway. By Mark
Hulbert.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CONTRARY-COLUMN-LABOR (Undated) _ In some very important ways,
the National Writers Union is the union of the future, and the
apparatchiks who run more old-fashioned unions had better take
notice. The United Auto Workers did just that eight years ago, when
it took in the writers' union as one of its locals. By Daniel Akst.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Topic tk. By Steven Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SENIORS-COLUMN-ROLLATORS (Undated) _ As athletes say, the wheels
go first: seniors often find that mobility is their most vexing
problem, even if otherwise healthy and able to be active and
self-sufficient. Enter the little-known rollator, which looks like
a sawed-off grocery cart with fat rubber wheels, bicycle handle
bars and hand brakes. It helps people walk easily under their own
power, over floors, sidewalks and grass. It even has a seat if the
user needs to take a rest, and folds up so it can be taken along in
a car or on a plane. By Fred Brock.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY&AMP;MEDICINE-COLUMN (Undated) _ So, what ever happened to
medical savings accounts? These accounts _ which permit people or
their employers to put away a certain amount of tax-free money
every year to pay for health care costs _ was presented an a
panacea to the Big Health Insurance problem by supporters only a
few years ago. And how it failed to ignite says much. By Jennifer
Stenhauer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUTOS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ABOUTCARS-TOYOTA-AVALON (Undated) _ The Avalon is Toyota's Buick
and that's not such a bad thing. By Leonard M. Apcar.
</P>
<P>
   CARSMART-TOYOTA-SOLARA (Undated) _ The Toyota Solara convertible
captures the sense of effortless, tamely glamorous fun in the sun
that so many middle-aged, middle-class adults yearns for. By Peter
Passell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
