<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7449 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     08-31 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR DETAILS RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN ENTREPRENEURS AND INVESTORS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CLAUDE CROWLEY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Angel Investing: Matching Start-Up Funds with Start-Up
Companies'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Van Osnabrugge and Robert J. Robinson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   422 pages, Jossey-Bass, San Francisco, $32 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Americans are an enterprising bunch.
</P>
<P>
   If you could read the minds of people on their lunch breaks,
you'd probably find many of them intently thinking about an
entrepreneurial project: a new software product or toy, an online
retail outlet, a unique restaurant, an automobile component or a
print shop. Varied as their ideas are, all of these enterprising
people are challenged by one thing: finding the money to make their
entrepreneurial dreams come true.
</P>
<P>
   Brushing elbows with these imaginative and ingenious people are
other people who, through wise investing or good luck, possess
discretionary funds that they would be willing to place with an
entrepreneur _ provided that the potential for returns is
attractive enough.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of Mark Van Osnabrugge and Robert J. Robinson's ``Angel
Investing'' is to establish a sort of mutual admiration society
between the two groups. It educates readers in each category to the
opportunities the other category offers and guides them through the
process of joining forces for mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angels'' _ private financial supporters, rather than banks or
other professional underwriting entities _ provide more funds to
business entrepreneurs than any other source, the authors say, but
their role is little understood.
</P>
<P>
   Osnabrugge and Robinson say that no well-researched study of the
subject has been printed before, and they promise to correct that.
Their book delivers the goods, and not just in a theoretical way.
It presents readers with a comprehensive body of knowledge about
angel investors: who they are, how they operate and how they can be
contacted. Up-to-date documentation of angel-financed businesses,
such as Amazon.com, give the book readability and credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Some fascinating details plowed from the book's rich soil
include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Many of our largest corporations were initially angel-funded,
including Ford, Apple and Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Angels fund 30 to 40 times as many entrepreneurial firms as
the formal venture capital industry, involving three to five times
as much money. About 60 percent of all new technology firms are
angel-financed.
</P>
<P>
   _ The authors estimate that the number of business investment
angels (now estimated at 3 million, investing more than $50 billion
in entrepreneurial firms each year) will double within a decade.
</P>
<P>
   _ Many high-earning, successful firms, especially in the
technology and Internet fields, have become angel investors.
</P>
<P>
   The book is arranged into four logical areas.
</P>
<P>
   The first, consisting of six chapters, introduces the subject,
examines funding options and concludes with a chapter on steps for
tapping into funds available from private sources.
</P>
<P>
   The next five chapters cover what the authors call first-time
insights into how business angels and venture capitalists decide to
make investments, stages in the process and important tips for
entrepreneurs courting investors.
</P>
<P>
   The third area covers the nuts and bolts of securing and
investing funds. This material is written for entrepreneurs and
potential angels. It includes negotiation and valuation methods and
suggestions for taking advantage of the changing angel marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   If networking or personal contacts aren't successful in finding
angel funding, the entrepreneur can turn to a matching service,
which leads to the fourth and last area of the book. That section
is made up of three appendices, the first of which lists more than
70 matching services in the United States. Interestingly enough, 58
percent are non-profit and 42 percent are private.
</P>
<P>
   Appendix Two lists further helpful resources, such as
associations (worldwide, by country) and organizations, directories
and trade journals.
</P>
<P>
   Appendix Three gives Dutch-uncle advice on writing a winning
business plan, which the authors say can be the most important and
time-consuming part of the process.
</P>
<P>
   The appendices may be the most useful part of the book to many
readers. But I couldn't help but wonder why the appendices weren't
issued as a separate, updatable workbook. Any long list, such as
the 70 matching organizations, starts to go out of date the day it
is written. Within a year or two, a great many of the addresses,
Web sites, phone and fax numbers and other pertinent information
will change. Why not issue the entire book as an annually updated
and improved directory or at least place the information on a Web
site that can be conveniently accessed and updated periodically?
</P>
<P>
   But that is just being picky. Van Osnabrugge and Robinson worked
for years to make this book the bible of angel investing; any
serious entrepreneur or investor who conscientiously studies it
can't fail to profit from the experience.
</P>
<P>
   Van Osnabrugge is a management consultant at Marakon Associates,
an international consulting firm, and has experience as a
matchmaker helping entrepreneurs find investment funds. Robinson is
an associate professor at Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   (Claude Crowley reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
