<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7454 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-AFFAIR-TEX     08-31 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-AFFAIR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AFFAIR WITHOUT PASSION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``An Affair of Love's'' original title was ``Une Liaison
Pornographique,'' and you don't have to be fluent in French to know
the literal translation of that. It's a good thing the title was
changed, because _ despite some tastefully filmed sex scenes that
wouldn't raise an eyebrow from anyone who's ever seen ``Sex and the
City'' _ the movie is nowhere as salacious as ``A Pornographic
Affair'' would indicate. The bad news is that it is as generic as
the new English-language title would indicate.
</P>
<P>
   The movie begins with an offscreen interviewer asking a woman
and a man (Nathalie Baye and Sergi Lopez, whose characters are
identified only as ``Her'' and ``Him'') about their fling. It's
never clear whom the interviewer works for, but it's hard to
conceive of a news outlet or documentarian who would be interested
in their story. The man and woman agree that the affair was purely
sexual at first _ they met through a magazine ad, and their trysts
fulfilled a fantasy so outrageous that the filmmakers leave it to
the audience's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with anonymous, no-strings-attached relationships,
however, is that human nature makes people want to attach strings _
and sure enough, the woman and the man begin to have feelings for
each other. That's pretty clear from the new title, leaving the
movie with only one mystery: Will these two stay together?
</P>
<P>
   If it's true that the left brain controls rational thought and
the right brain controls emotions, then ``An Affair of Love'' is a
left-brained movie about right-brained subjects. It's so
dispassionately intellectual about passion that when the man and
woman talk during sex, it's more like coffee-table discussion than
bedroom talk _ which is strange, since they're talking about sex.
It's so detached that when the man cries, although both people say
they're touched, you're likely to wonder why his face is leaking.
</P>
<P>
   Director Frederic Fonteyne and writer Philippe Blasband must
have had something in mind when they came up with this; the movie
is well-filmed, and Baye and Lopez are appealing. But ``Affair''
doesn't seem to be about anything. It's too coy too be about the
dangers of sexual obsession, too arid to be about the risks of
romantic love, and too silly, with its often elliptical dialogue,
to be about communication. The closest that it comes to dealing
with real sexual issues is that it will make some people want to
roll over and go to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   In French with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``An Affair of Love''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Frederic Fonteyne
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Nathalie Baye, Sergi Lopez
</P>
<P>
   Length: 80 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ nudity and sexual content
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
