<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7455 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-CHILD-STARS0901-COX     08-31 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-STARS0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life behind the scenes for child actors
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I've always wondered why any parent would let
their child go into show business. Sure, the potential for huge
paydays is tempting. But is the price that must be paid for that
possible fortune worth it? On Monday, A&AMP;E will air ``Child Stars:
Their Story'': 9-11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Child Stars: Their Story `` attempts to reveal what it's
really like being a young star. The two-hour documentary, narrated
by Hayley Mills, assembled an impressive array of talent (over 30
in all) from five generations. Patty Duke (''The Patty Duke Show'')
talks about being forced to go to her dad's funeral in her
character's costume and makeup. David Faustino (''Married...with
Children'') remembers what it was like drinking at Hollywood's
hottest nightclubs at 14. Melissa Gilbert (''Little House on the
Prairie''), one of ``Child Stars''' executive producers, recalls
crying, sweating and breaking out in a rash after forgetting her
lines. Diana Serra Cary (''Baby Peggy'') recalls feeling like a
``senior citizen'' at age 15.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to several interviews, ``Child Stars'' also features
a roundtable during which eight former stars, including Kim Fields
(''The Facts of Life''), Jerry Mathers (''Leave it to Beaver'') and
Sara Gilbert (''Roseanne'') talk openly about drugs, rejection and
the pros and cons of having a sexy image.
</P>
<P>
   Child stars are often robbed of a normal childhood. Growing up
is hard enough. Imagine having to do it in front of millions of
people watching your every move or snickering about every
goofy-looking pimple you get. The pressure to perform is also
insanely intense. Many adult actors can't even take the heat and
often resort to drugs and alcohol to cope. Just think what it's
like for a kid to overhear a producer angrily talking about low
ratings and possible cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   And in a business where rejection is the norm, just what kind of
toll does that take on a child's psyche?
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, child stars seem to have it all. They make great
money. Get invited to glamorous parties and have adoring fans
screaming their names. But when the cameras stop rolling and the
director yells, ``Cut!'' the bottom line is, many are just sad,
lonely and scared little kids.
</P>
<P>
   When you hear the term ``former child star,'' most people, I'm
sure, immediately think of such troubled actors as Todd Bridges
(''Diff'rent Strokes''). Bridges' brushes with drugs and the law
are now legendary. In the special, he says he always felt more at
home on the ``Diff'rent Strokes'' set because his real dad was a
raging alcoholic who acted like a ``pit bull'' at home.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the stories are tales of woe. Some are downright
hilarious. Bill Mumy (''Lost in Space''), for example, remembers
shooting an ``Alfred Hitchcock Presents ``episode when he was 7.
Mumy kept fidgeting during his scene, which drove the intimidating
director nuts. So, Hitchcock finally told a terrified Mumy that if
he didn't stop moving, he'd nail his feet to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the blood,'' Hitchcock intoned, ``will come pouring out
like milk.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's the always delightful Danny Bonaduce (''The
Partridge Family'') who loved his time as a child star. ``I was
short, fat with red hair and freckles,'' he says, ``and I took two
cheerleaders to the prom...life was wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1600EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ATTHEMOVIES-NYT &LR;      08-31 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
 THE MOVIES-NYT   By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE GRINCH GETS A SOARING SCORE
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Ron Howard, the director, and James Horner, the
composer, were huddled behind an enormous control panel overlooking
the scoring stage where, minutes earlier, Horner had conducted a
full orchestra in a climactic sequence from ``How the Grinch Stole
Christmas.'' As the scene played back on a movie screen on the far
wall, the two men listened intently to the way the lush music
worked with the dialogue and the on-screen gymnastics of Jim
Carrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a funny tone in there,'' Howard said. ``What do
you think?'' Horner listened and nodded. At issue was whether the
soaring music was undercutting the comic aspects of Carrey's
performance. It was a tricky question.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is based on the classic Dr. Seuss children's book
about a fuzzy green creature who is so bitter that he conspires to
ruin everybody's Christmas in Whoville, the town beneath his
mountaintop lair. Carrey plays the Grinch in full green regalia,
including long furry fingers and latex snout, but with yellow
contact lenses. In the scene, he bounces around the snow-capped
cliff like a pinball, clutching at his heart.
</P>
<P>
   If the music is too emphatic and emotional, it might drown the
comedy. But if the music is toned down too much, the scene might
not give the audience the emotional catharsis it wants from the
climax. ``It's like being a tightrope walker with one foot in the
air at all times,'' Horner said. ``My feeling is that the funniness
is going to come through whatever, so I tend to err on the side of
making things emotive.''
</P>
<P>
   The scoring stage is about the size of a basketball court,
strewn with instruments awaiting the afternoon session. A gaily
decorated Christmas tree stands in one corner, and brightly wrapped
packages are scattered around the room. Horner's crew members often
decorate the stage to match the film on which they are working. For
``The Perfect Storm,'' the same stage had been festooned with ships
and plastic frogmen.
</P>
<P>
   The score, the computer effects and the final sound mix are
always the last pieces to be put into place in the weeks before a
movie's release. In this case, Horner and his musicians are working
with a little time to spare; ``Grinch'' is not due in theaters
until Nov. 17, vying with films like ``102 Dalmatians,'' ``Rugrats
in Paris'' and the new Adam Sandler comedy, ``Little Nicky,'' for
the lucrative Thanksgiving market.
</P>
<P>
   During the lunch break, Horner walked through the crowded
scoring stage, picking his way through the tangle of cellos and
electronic synthesizers to a line of oddly twisted plastic hoses
resting on the floor. Each of the peculiar objects was a musical
instrument, created by Horner's team to make the kind of odd sounds
that might come from the Baroque-meets-Dali instruments drawn by
Dr. Seuss for his Whoville town band. He picked one up and
energetically blew into it, producing a vibrating honk that sounded
at once plaintive and hostile. ``We had one that had a slide on it,
like a trombone, but it took two people to work it,'' Horner said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most prolific movie composers of the last
quarter-century, Horner has worked on more than 100 film and
television scores, though he is perhaps best known for his
Oscar-winning work on ``Titanic.'' (He won for best score and best
song, ``My Heart Will Go On.'')
</P>
<P>
   Horner said he usually took about six weeks to write the initial
score. ``I do it at a desk with pen and paper,'' he said. ``I don't
use a computer in writing at all. I'm sort of old-fashioned about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the public aspect of his job _ when he must stand up
before a room filled with seasoned musicians, explain what he wants
and then conduct them through it _ is the most uncomfortable. ``I
tend to be a shy person,'' he said. He does not, for instance, go
to the premieres of his films, when he must walk a red-carpet
gantlet of television cameras, unless he is forced to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Horner wandered into a side office to work on that afternoon's
pieces of the score. He is feeling pretty confident about the way
things are going on the ``Grinch'' score.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it makes me cry, then I know I've nailed it,'' he said.
``I can't do any better.''
</P>
<P>
   JOYS OF SUMMER
</P>
<P>
   Michael Tollin was excited. He was preparing to direct the final
scene for ``Summer Catch,'' a romance between a poor boy (Freddie
Prinze Jr.) and a rich girl (Jessica Biel) set in the world of the
Cape Cod summer baseball league, and Ken Griffey Jr., center
fielder for the Cincinnati Reds, was going to be playing a key
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pivotal scene,'' Tollin said. ``We needed a guy who
really transcended the sport, who was more recognizable than the
average baseball player, and Junior said he was up for it. The
scene is a confrontation between him and Freddie's character, and
there is some scripted dialogue and some chances for him to do some
ad-libbing. I think he's really got the chops.''
</P>
<P>
   Tollin, a producer for live-action programs on the Nickelodeon
network, directed his first film, ``Hank Aaron: Chasing the
Dream,'' in 1995. Indeed, he has shown a decided inclination toward
the national pastime. In addition to directing ``Summer Catch,''
tentatively scheduled for release next spring, he is producing
``Hardball,'' another movie for release next year that is about a
young man in the Chicago projects who becomes a Little League
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always enjoyed working with professional athletes,'' he
said. ``Stunt casting _ call it whatever you want. For `Summer
Catch' I got Hank Aaron to come down and do a cameo, Carlton Fisk
plays himself, Richie Allen plays a scout and Curt Gowdy is the
Cape Cod league announcer.''
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET AT SUNDANCE
</P>
<P>
   The Sundance Film Festival, which runs for 10 days every January
in Park City, Utah, has decided to institute an Internet component
next year. Film festival organizers all over the world have been
struggling with how to embrace the work being done on the Web, and
Sundance decided this was the way.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on Jan. 18, the opening day of the next Sundance
gathering, the Sundance Online Film Festival _ StreamSearch.com,
the company that staged the Internet Film and Music Festival in
February, is to produce it _ will present work created specifically
for the Web. Festival organizers said they would consider all types
of work, including animation, live-action, documentary, interactive
and experimental.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dynamic material currently being generated for the Web is
something we are excited to present,'' said Geoffrey Gilmore, a
co-director of the festival.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1603EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7461 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIE-HANK01-COX     08-31 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HANK01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hank Greenberg: Pioneer, hero, star
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a rare film that begins with ``Take Me Out to the Ball
Game'' sung in Yiddish.
</P>
<P>
   And ``The Life and Times of Hank Greenberg'' is a rare film
indeed _ a documentary that mixes peanuts and Cracker Jack and
prejudice. It's a film with a decided point of view, yet one that's
drenched in a fan's affection.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Greenberg _ or Hammerin' Hank as he was known when he was
knocking 'em out of the park for the Detroit Tigers in the 1930s
and '40s _ wasn't the first Jewish guy to play professional
baseball. But he was the first not to change his name and the first
to become a superstar. Greenberg batted in 183 runs in one season,
almost broke the Babe's single-season home-run record and was voted
most valuable player as a first baseman and an outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   He also led his team to four pennants and two World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even as he was amassing these astonishing on-field feats,
he was subjected to anti-Semitic taunts. ``Throw him a pork chop,''
someone would yell. ``He won't hit that.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Greenberg remained graceful, self-effacing and
focused on the game. In an interview given before his death in
1986, he's more interested in talking about his RBI than
Jew-baiting. Perhaps the most telling statement is made by his son.
Greenberg left baseball the same season that a certain rookie named
Jackie Robinson started. In fact, the two once collided at first
base. ``My dad said he never knew about having it rough until he
saw Jackie Robinson on the ball field.''
</P>
<P>
   Much like her subject, Aviva Kempner is a straightforward,
no-frills filmmaker. There's nothing fancy, just the usual
assortment of documentary footage, period artifacts and talking
heads. Which, in this movie's case, includes such illustrious
Greenberg fans as actor Walter Matthau and attorney Alan
Dershowitz.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the late Matthau's familiar mug adds another layer of
poignancy. He could be speaking for an entire generation when he
admits that simply knowing a guy like Greenberg was out there gave
him hope. ``It meant I didn't have to end up in the Garment
District.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Dershowitz's comments are more combative and
political. He even says he thought Greenberg could have been the
first Jewish president _ an oddly resonant and timely tribute with
Joe Lieberman on the Democratic presidential ticket. Notes
Dershowitz, ``Baseball was a way of saying we were as American as
anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg himself was not particularly religious. But he
accepted the mantle of Symbol with the same gracious ease he
brought to his game. The film makes quietly clear that this was no
small thing in a time when anti-Semitism was virulent and more
socially acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Kempner's documentary celebrates a hero, both on the diamond and
off. Robinson sums it up simply: ``He gave me encouragement. Mr.
Greenberg is class.''
</P>
<P>
   So is his movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Life and Times
</P>
<P>
   of Hank Greenberg''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   A documentary about baseball player Hank Greenberg. Directed by
Aviva Kempner. Not rated.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1604EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7462 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIE-STEVE01-COX     08-31 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-STEVE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Tao of Steve' borders on the offensive
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to Dex (Donal Logue), the genially chubby star of
``The Tao of Steve,'' the way to be cool and get all the girls is
to be Steve McQueen. Of course, you don't have to really be
McQueen; you just have to learn how to groove into his unflappable
Steve-ness.
</P>
<P>
   Explains Dex, ``James Bond is a Steve. Michael Jordan is a
Steve.''
</P>
<P>
   Dex, too, is a Steve. He's got the sexual conquests to prove it.
``The Tao of Steve,'' which charmed a lot of folks at last winter's
Sundance Film Festival, is basically about a fat boy who's a babe
magnet. Why this would be inexplicable to anyone _ his pals make
much of a fuss over how he gets as much as he does _ seems
inexplicable to me. Do the names John Belushi, John Goodman or John
Candy ring a bell? Hardly Adonises, but certainly attractive in
their own roly-poly way.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the twist in the movie is that Dex runs into a brick
wall _ or, given the McQueen metaphor, a barbed-wire fence _ when
he runs into a former classmate named Syd at their college reunion.
She's staying on in Santa Fe to design sets for the city's famed
opera company. Dex tries his usual tricks and convoluted come-ons,
but she's impervious. Initially challenged, then obsessed, Dex
finds that not only has he fallen for her but he's violating his
own rule of cool: ``We pursue that which retreats from us.''
</P>
<P>
   The picture was co-written by two sisters, Jenniphr Goodman, who
also directs, and Greer, who also stars as Syd. Their gender seems
to have given them carte blanche for conjuring a slight,
occasionally charming, but often borderline offensive story. More
is made over Dex's looks than seems necessary.
</P>
<P>
   If Dex were a Dexette practicing The Tao of Gwyneth, the
character would probably be seen as desperate and pitiful (and, of
course, a bit sluttish). Further, the bits of wisdom with which he
entices so many women are embarrassingly stupid and obvious _ the
sort of thing horny college professors have been saying to students
for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Logue, who's appeared in such mainstream movies as ``The
Patriot,'' is the best thing in the film, with a shaggy-dog appeal
that transcends his Steve pose. But the movie as a whole is the
sort of thing that no one should take to heart. And that's pretty
much a fatal flaw in a romantic comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tao of Steve''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Donal Logue and Greer Goodman. Directed by Jenniphr
Goodman. Rated R for profanity and drug use. 1 hour, 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The Tao of John _ as in Belushi, Candy and Goodman
_ is more like it.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
