<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7463 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS01-     08-31 3237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of current movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray and Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grades range from A to F.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Momma's House'' PG-13 (crude and sexual humor, profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Martin Lawrence and Nia Long.
</P>
<P>
   Review: It's one super-sized Martin Lawrence. As an FBI agent on
a neighborhood stakeout to capture a vicious bank robber, Lawrence
dons layer upon layer of prosthetics to impersonate a 325-pound,
small-town granny in Cartersville (the movie, however, was filmed
in Los Angeles). The results may be predictable, but with
Lawrence's manic comedic timing they are also occasionally quite
funny. (BL) 1 hour, 39 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Bless the Child'' R (violence, drug content and brief
profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kim Basinger and Jimmy Smits.
</P>
<P>
   Review: A junky would-be religious thriller about a little girl
with special powers. The latest cinematic struggle of good vs.
evil, the film swipes everything it can from ``The Omen,'' ``The
Exorcist,'' ``End of Days,'' ``Stigmata'' and other
Catholic/satanic epics, all while managing to bore the pants off
you. (SM) 1 hour, 50 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``Blood Simple'' R (violence, sex, nudity , language)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Dan Hedaya, Frances McDormand and M. Emmet Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   Review: The Coen brothers' first film is back in all its
devilishly degenerate glory. Re-released in a spruced-up but
still-smirking so-called director's cut, the movie is pretty much
exactly as it was when it hit theaters in 1984. That is, a
good-old-boy gothic full of flashy camera angles and trashy people.
What's astonishing is how much of the Coens' unique talent was
evident from the start. (ERG) 1 hour, 37 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Bring It On''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kirsten Dunst.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 (sex-related material and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Review: Kirsten Dunst stars in a comedy that pits two rival high
schools' cheerleading squads in a we-hate-you showdown at the
national cheerleading championships. Pretty much all the jokes fall
flat. Actually, the funniest bit involves projectile vomiting. And
what does that say about this movie? (BL) 1 hour, 33 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm a Cheerleader'' R (profanity and sexual themes)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Natasha Lyonne and Clea DuVall.
</P>
<P>
   Review: Call it ``Girl, Intercepted.'' Megan (Natasha Lyonne) is
a cheerleader shipped off to a homosexual rehab center called True
Directions because of certain ``telling'' signs. There's potential
here for some funny, nasty satire, but filmmaker Jamie Babbit soon
backs off the risky stuff. The funniest thing in the movie is
RuPaul as a rehab counselor who proudly disowns his gay past and
wears a ``Straight is Great'' T-shirt. (ERG) 1 hour, 25 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Cecil B. Demented'' R (profanity, sex, violence, substance
abuse)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Melanie Griffith and Stephen Dorff.
</P>
<P>
   Review: Not quite demented enough. There are some amusing bits
and some savvy cinema in-jokes in John Waters' movie about a
Hollywood star (Melanie Griffith) kidnapped by underground
filmmakers and forced to star in their no-budget flick. Like Patty
Hearst (who appears in the film), Griffith becomes a convert to
their cause and their wild-eyed leader (Stephen Dorff). Too much of
the film is slapdash and just plain silly. (ERG) C-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cell'' R (violence, language and nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jennifer Lopez, Vince Vaughn and Vincent D'Onofrio.
</P>
<P>
   Review: Don't get trapped in this one. Jennifer Lopez plays an
intrepid child therapist who, through an experimental sci-fi
technique, can enter the minds of others. A detective (Vince
Vaughn) asks her to stroll through the brain of a serial killer
(Vincent D'Onofrio) so he can find where he's stashed his latest
victim. Visually provocative, narratively impaired, it's like ``The
Silence of the Lambs'' without the compelling characters. (ERG) 1
hour, 52 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicken Run''
</P>
<P>
   Featuring the voices of Mel Gibson and Miranda Richardson. G
</P>
<P>
   Review: Set on a chicken farm in 1950s Britain, the movie is
about some hens' repeated attempts to fly the coop after their
villainous owner decides there's more money in chicken pies than in
chickens. If you're in the mood for something offbeat and wackily
deadpan, this may be just your kind of amiably bird-brained
entertainment. (ERG) 1 hour, 22 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Coyote Ugly'' PG-13 (sensuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Piper Perabo, Adam Garcia, Maria Bello and John
Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   Review: Dog-face hideous. The come-on is five hot chicks serving
liquor in a rowdy fun-time saloon (they splash whiskey across the
bar and set it afire; they douse each others' T-shirts with big
pitchers of water). But it's really the slapdash story of a young
waif, a struggling songwriter aching for stardom in New York City.
``Coyote'' is profoundly stupid and earnestly inept at conveying a
story. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 34 minutes. D
</P>
<P>
   ``The Crew''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Richard Dreyfuss and Burt Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 (sexual content, violence and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Review: It stereotypes Jews and Hispanics and belittles the
group it's supposed to be celebrating, retirement-age Americans.
Even worse, the movie's not even funny. The stars are old mafia
wiseguys trying to fight a rent increase in their Miami hotel. Lame
plot twists ensue. (SM) 1 hour, 28 minutes. F
</P>
<P>
   ``Croupier''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Clive Owen and Alex Kingston.
</P>
<P>
   Unrated
</P>
<P>
   Review: This 1998 film involves a struggling author who takes a
job at a casino running a roulette wheel to look for writing
inspiration. Soon he's convinced to join a robbery scheme.
``Croupier'' has more on its mind than danger and plot twists. It's
a fascinating, hard-edged portrait of a man who swears he doesn't
gamble. (SM) 1 hour, 31 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinosaur'' PG-13 (sexual content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring the voices of D.B. Sweeney, Della Reese and Julianna
Margulies.
</P>
<P>
   Review: Leapin' lizards! The prehistoric critters in Disney's
years-in-the-making, $200 million-plus computer animation do more
than leap. Alas, the plot is worth about two cents _ something
about an Iguanodon raised by lemurs who helps a herd of dinosaurs
find a fabled nesting ground after a disastrous meteor shower.
Parents be aware: while most of the movie is Barney-tame, the scary
parts can be quite scary. (ERG) 1 hour, 24 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``The End'' Unrated (includes alcohol use, sexual situations and
violence)
</P>
<P>
   Skateboarding flick featuring Tony Hawk and Bucky Lasek.
</P>
<P>
   Review: An action/adventure skateboarding flick full of wild
stunts, slo-mo balletic moves and total 'tude. There is no plot per
se, just skateboard legends like Tony Hawk, Bucky Lasek and a half
dozen or so other dudes exhibiting their stuff. When the movie's
not showing staggering stunts, it's stoking the young male,
overadrenalized, grunge-rules lifestyle. (BL) About 41 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Eyes of Tammy Faye'' PG-13 (some sexual content)
</P>
<P>
   A documentary about Tammy Faye Bakker Messner, narrated by
RuPaul Charles.
</P>
<P>
   Review: The rise and fall of evangelical diva Tammy Faye Bakker
Messner, the PTL Club and her marriage to Jim Bakker makes a
fascinating story. But somewhere along the way, directors Fenton
Bailey and Randy Barbato turned the subject of their documentary
into its mascot. Often captivating and informative, but full of
gaps and lacking key interviews. (SM) 1 hour, 19 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl on the Bridge'' R (sexual themes) subtitles
</P>
<P>
   Starring Daniel Auteuil and Vanessa Paradis.
</P>
<P>
   Review: Starts great but loses steam. The fine French director
Patrice Leconte (``Monsieur Hire'') has cooked up a romantic fairy
tale about a suicidal gamin (Vanessa Paradis) and a professional
knife-thrower who persuades her to become his new target. After an
impressive first hour in which the film creates an aura of
unresolved romantic tension and intensity, it goes adrift. (ERG) 1
hour, 31 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Godzilla 2000'' PG (monster violence and mild profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Takehiro Murata, and Tsutomu Kitagawa (as Godzilla).
</P>
<P>
   Review: ``Godzilla 2000'' is everything hard-core fans want it
to be. So corny and campy. And, God bless it, so badly dubbed in
English it soars. Sure it's bad filmmaking. Sure it's a guy _ actor
Tsutomu Kitagawa _ clad in a nearly vintage latex Godzilla get-up
and stomping through Tokyo, knocking down cardboard mini-buildings
and upending toy-sized cars with his gnarly feet. But that's the
point. (BL) 1 hour, 37 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone in 60 Seconds'' PG-13 (sexuality, profanity and violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Nicolas Cage and Angelina Jolie.
</P>
<P>
   Review: Nicolas Cage plays Memphis Raines, a reformed car thief
called back behind the wheel when his little brother bungles a deal
for a British crime lord. ``Gone'' delivers a long, harrowing car
chase that easily outdoes the motorcycle finale in ``M: I-2.'' A
few IQ points may be lost while watching the flick. But you'll be
having too much fun to care. (SM) At metro theaters. 1 hour, 59
minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollow Man'' R (graphic violence, nudity, profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kevin Bacon and Elisabeth Shue.
</P>
<P>
   Review: A high-tech fusion of ``The Invisible Man'' and ``Dr.
Jekyll and Mr. Hyde,'' it lets director Paul Verhoeven (``Starship
Troopers,'' ``Total Recall'') show off some gruesome,
state-of-the-art computer effects and exercise his gleeful brand of
brutal action. But his filmmaking energy is wasted on a weak script
and characters so two-dimensional, they're virtually all
transparent. (SM) 1 hour, 54 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``The Life and Times of Hank Greenberg''
</P>
<P>
   A documentary about baseball player Hank Greenberg. Not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Review: Aviva Kempner's documentary is a rare film indeed _ a
celebration of Hank Greenberg, a pro baseball player in the 1930s
and '40s who became the first Jewish sports superstar. Greenberg
broke records, was voted most valuable player twice and led his
team, the Detroit Tigers, to two World Series _ even as he was
being subjected to anti-Semitic baiting by fans, rivals and,
sometimes, his own teammates. Jackie Robinson puts it best: ``Mr.
Greenberg was class.'' So is his movie. (ERG) 1 hour, 35 minutes.
A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Jordan to the Max'' Unrated
</P>
<P>
   Imax documentary
</P>
<P>
   about Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Review: It shoots; it scores. Like Mount Everest, Michael Jordan
has his own 2-D Imax film. It's the biggest format for the biggest
sports story ever told. Part bio, part well-deserved pat on the
back, it's a loving look at the Chicago Bulls superstar and hones
in on the 1998 NBA playoffs when a determined Jordan led his team
to a sixth championship before retirement. (BL) 45 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Nutty Professor II: The Klumps'' PG-13 (crude humor and sexual
content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Eddie Murphy and Janet Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Review: The big problem in ``Nutty Professor II: The Klumps'' is
the nutty professor. This sequel to the 1996 hit seems designed for
video: You want to fast-forward through all the parts focused on
tubby scientist Sherman (Eddie Murphy) so you can get back to the
rest of his family (played by Murphy, Murphy, Murphy and Murphy,
plus a fat kid). Murphy is jaw-droppingly funny. But the script is
simply not nutty enough. (SM) 1 hour, 45 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Old Man and the Sea'' Unrated
</P>
<P>
   A live-action animated short.
</P>
<P>
   Review: This 'toon, based on an Ernest Hemingway novel, is, like
the author's word choice, deceptively simple and strikingly
beautiful. It's everything a moviegoer would expect, but didn't
get, from ``Fantasia/2000.'' (BL) 22 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Original Kings of Comedy'' R (language and sex-related
humor)
</P>
<P>
   Featuring Steve Harvey, Cedric the Entertainer, D.L. Hughley and
Bernie Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Review: There's nothing that original. It's just a lot of funny
stuff knocked out by four sharp stand-up comics. And under Spike
Lee's direction, it's one of the liveliest concert films in years.
The routines get raucous and rude but hold off on the blistering
verbal assaults of other comedians. Lee looses several cameras
through the venue, capturing audience reactions and giving the
movie the dynamic spark of the live event. (SM)1 hour, 57 minutes.
A-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriot'' R (strong war violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Mel Gibson, Heath Ledger and Jason Isaacs.
</P>
<P>
   Review: Mel Gibson single-handedly wins the American Revolution,
among other historical revisions. The latest from Roland Emmerich
takes the jingoistic spirit of his ``Independence Day'' and amps it
to a feverish, flag-waving pitch. The movie is beautiful on the eye
and crafted with great care. It relies on oversimplification, cheap
sentiment and a villain so two-dimensionally nasty even Satan
wouldn't claim him. (SM) 2 hours, 44 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Perfect Storm'' PG-13 (profanity , scenes of peril)
</P>
<P>
   Starring George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg and Diane Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Review: The fishermen of the Andrea Gail take a pounding, and so
does the audience in the latest movie directed by Wolfgang
Petersen. Based on Sebastian Junger's best seller, it re-creates
the collision of three weather systems in the fall of 1991 _ and
the battle of men (George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg) and women (Mary
Elizabeth Mastrantonio) trying to survive the monstrous sea. (SM) 2
hours, 15 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Pokemon the Movie 2000''
</P>
<P>
   Animated film featuring the voices of Ikue Ootani and Unsho
Ishizuka. G
</P>
<P>
   Review: The new Pokemon movie is a lot better than last year's
first flick. And slightly better than a poke in the eye. ``Pokemon
the Movie 2000'' has more accomplished animation, more drama and a
decent-enough sprinkling of jokes, all adding up to something
barely watchable. Still, it's mostly cheaply made, barely
interesting and focused on niche marketing. (Bob Longino) 1 hour,
24 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Replacements'' PG-13 (crude sexual humor and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Keanu Reeves and Gene Hackman.
</P>
<P>
   Review: It's got it all. Bone-crunching football plays.
Boneheaded comedy (the team kicker, a wire-thin Welsh soccer
player, puffs cigs while booting field goals). And a dumb-as-dirt
pep squad whose sideline lap-dance cheers cause the opposition to
fumble a lot. Keanu Reeves and Gene Hackman star in this dumb romp
about adult scabs taking over for striking pro players. (BL)1 hour,
58 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Grace'' R (drug content and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Brenda Blethyn and Craig Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
   Review: A guiltless, feel-good flick in the ``Waking Ned
Devine'' mold. The film has everything it takes to be hopelessly
twee: steaming teacups and scenic seascapes, eccentric villagers, a
rowdy pub and some naughty business involving marijuana. But to the
credit of everyone involved, especially Brenda Blethyn in the title
role, the comedy mainly skirts the pitfalls of preciousness. (SM) 1
hour, 33 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Scary Movie''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Anna Faris, Shawn Wayans and Marlon Wayans. R (crude
sexual humor, profanity, drug use,violence)
</P>
<P>
   Review: Propped up by the Wayans brothers _ Keenen
(writer/director), Shawn (writer/actor) and Marlon (writer/actor) _
``Scary Movie'' is a parody of teen horror flicks. The ``Scream''
trilogy, ``I Know What You Did Last Summer,'' ``The Blair Witch
Project'' and, just because it was popular, ``The Matrix,'' all get
skewered in a thousand jokes that are either hilarious, funny, not
funny or simply crude. (BL) 1 hour, 28 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaft'' R (violence and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Samuel L. Jackson, Christian Bale and Jeffrey Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Review: You can dig it. Sporting the original Oscar-winning
theme song, the ``Shaft'' 2000, starring Samuel L. Jackson, is one
bad I'm-messin'-with-your-head movie. While the plot is a
trumped-up trifle involving both a suspected racist killer
(Christian Bale) and whacked-out drug lord (Jeffrey Wright), the
movie clicks because of the performances. Wright steals the
picture, directed by John Singleton. (BL) 1 hour, 37 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Space Cowboys'' PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Starring Clint Eastwood, Tommy Lee Jones, James Garner and
Donald Sutherland.
</P>
<P>
   Review: The right stuff. Geezer chic gets a grand showcase in
Clint Eastwood's shamelessly crowd-pleasing comedy-thriller. When a
decrepit Russian satellite threatens to crash to Earth, four aging
astronauts who were axed from the program in the '50s are summoned
into service to repair the thing. The best part of the film is
watching these veterans play off each other like seasoned pros on
the Senior Tour. (ERG) 2 hours, 15 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tao of Steve'' R (profanity /drug use)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Donal Logue ,Greer Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   Review: A slight and slightly obnoxious romantic comedy about a
chunky non-hunk (Donal Logue) who's a babe magnet because he
practices the so-called tao of Steve, i.e., the way to get girls is
to emulate the sheer coolness of Steve McQueen. The twist comes
when this lumpen Lothario falls for a set designer (Greer Goodman)
impervious to his method. Logue can be charming, but the whole
premise seems contrived and a bit false. (ERG) At Tara. 1 hour, 30
minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Time Regained'' Unrated (sexual situations)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Catherine Deneuve, John Malkovich and Emmanuelle Beart.
</P>
<P>
   Review: Ultimately it's designed for Marcel Proust readers, who
are likely to love and loathe it in equal parts for its attempts to
give concrete form to his work. It's like a gorgeous silk tapestry
shrouding a statue meant to memorialize decay and regret and
ineffability _ a statue that can't really be seen in its entirety
with the naked eye (or the camera lens). (SM) 2 hours, 45 minutes.
B-
</P>
<P>
   ``What Lies Beneath''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Michelle Pfeiffer and Harrison Ford.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 (terror, violence, sensuality, profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Review: What lies beneath ``What Lies Beneath'' is a script that
could have come from a 1970s TV movie. Narratively old-fashioned,
but boosted by star performances from Michelle Pfeiffer and
Harrison Ford and suspenseful direction, it's a lovingly crafted
throwback to haunted-house movies that relied more on suggestion
and slowly building creepiness than over-the-top effects. (SM) 2
hours, 10 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderland'' R (profanity, sexuality.)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Gina McKee and Shirley Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   Review: In Alice's Wonderland, things got curiouser and
curiouser. In Michael Winterbottom's ``Wonderland,'' things get
grimmer and grimmer. The movie is a series of interconnected
vignettes (a la ``Magnolia'') showing the unfulfilled lives of
three sisters (Gina McKee, Shirley Henderson, Molly Parker) in
South London. Besides the film's bleakness and hyper-realism of
Mike Leigh or Ken Loach, the acting is fine and the observations
acute. It's one of those hurts-so-good films. (ERG)1 hour, 49
minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``X-Men'' PG-13 (sci-fi action violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Halle Berry, Hugh Jackman, Anna Paquin, Patrick Stewart
and Ian McKellen.
</P>
<P>
   Review: ``X-Men'' never comes close to classic status. The best
movie to work this superhero turf lately was the shamelessly
entertaining ``The Matrix.'' But director Bryan Singer and his
collaborators treat the comic's mythology with seriousness and
respect (unlike other recent, slapdash comic adaptations ``Spawn''
and ``Blade''). It's an engaging popcorn movie in a summer that's
littered with duds. (SM) 1 hour, 44 minutes.B-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
