<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7464 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIE-WONDERLAND01-CO     08-31 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WONDERLAND01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Wonderland' a gritty, lyrical place
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Alice's Wonderland, things kept getting curiouser and
curiouser. In Michael Winterbottom's ``Wonderland,'' things keep
getting grimmer and grimmer.
</P>
<P>
   Set in a listless corner of South London, the movie is a series
of interconnected vignettes (a la ``Short Cuts'' or ``Magnolia'')
focusing on a few days in the lives of three sisters. It's not a
pretty picture. These young women mostly inhabit a world of singles
bars and single parenthood. The one attached sister, Molly (Molly
Parker), is very pregnant, but her partner, Eddie (John Simm),
finds himself less and less ready for fatherhood as the due date
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Middle sister Debbie (Shirley Henderson) already has a child _ a
watchful, neglected 11-year-old she farms out as often as possible
to her irresponsible ex (Ian Hart) so she can do some partying. The
youngest sibling, Nadia (Gina McKee), is so unaware of her pluses
and so desperate to connect with someone _ anyone _ that she does
the singles scene, places personal ads and sleeps with guys who
clearly don't intend to call her again.
</P>
<P>
   How'd these women get in this fix? Well, take a look at their
parents' loveless marriage. Dad's (Jack Shepherd) a henpecked sad
sack, Mom (Kika Markham) an edgy harridan deeply mired in her own
misery.
</P>
<P>
   The only happy character in the lot is the girls' brother (Enzio
Cilenti). He's cut himself off from the family, but a last-minute
phone call leaves the lingering suggestion that blood ties can't
always be severed so easily.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this is not what anyone would call a feel-good film,
and, for a while, its utter bleakness wears you down. Yet the
ensemble cast is so good, the script's observations so acute that,
after a point, it becomes one of those movies that hurt so good.
</P>
<P>
   Winterbottom isn't just saying that life is empty and
meaningless. He's showing us people with the potential to feel that
emptiness more than most. People who are isolated and without hope.
And then he shows us tiny, tiny rays of light in all the gloom _ an
unexpected smile, the miracle of a new life. He takes us to the
edge of the abyss and asks us to look, but he doesn't give us the
final shove.
</P>
<P>
   The picture's hand-held style echoes the up-close hyper-realism
of Mike Leigh or Ken Loach. But there's an unexpected lyricism,
too. Say, in a shot of the usually stoic Nadia wiping away a tear
as she rides the bus back home. Alone. Again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderland'' can feel thin, but it also feels real. There's a
grittiness here that's hard to shake. You leave the theater
thinking no one's been let off the hook _ not the characters, not
the filmmaker, not even the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderland'' Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Gina McKee and Shirley Henderson. Directed by Michael
Winterbottom. Rated R for profanity and sexuality. 1 hour, 49
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A bittersweet look at some drab London lives.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
