<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7467 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GREENBERG0901-C     08-31 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GREENBERG0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hank Greenberg film is compelling but one-sided
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Since she has been toiling for the past 12
years on ``The Life and Times of Hank Greenberg,'' an affectionate
documentary tribute to the first Jewish baseball star,
writer-director Aviva Kempner could not have intended it as a
metaphor for the current barrier-shattering campaign bid of
Orthodox Jewish Sen. Joseph Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with the film's commercial arrival now, it is hard not to
see parallels to the Democratic vice presidential candidate in the
saga of the New York-born Detroit Tigers slugger who encountered
overt anti-Semitism on his way to baseball's Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is a film that needs no such topical analogy to make
it compelling, as well as entertaining. It is worth being reminded,
or to learn for the first time, how much Jewish baseball fans lived
vicariously through Greenberg's presence on the field, taking
ethnic pride in his fence-busting heroics.
</P>
<P>
   Such prominent Jews as Sen. Carl Levin, attorney Alan Dershowitz
and the late actor Walter Matthau _ friends of Greenberg or merely
fans of the game _ are recorded speaking adoringly of the hulking
athlete's inspiring exploits amid overt hatred.
</P>
<P>
   It is a stirring tale of triumph but one that Kempner is canny
enough to tell with leavening humor. It begins with a rousing
``Take Me Out to the Ball Game'' sung in Yiddish, includes
context-setting film clips from ``Gentleman's Agreement,'' ``Woman
of the Year'' and the television series ``Brooklyn Bridge,''
concluding with a few moments of baseball chaos from the Marx
Brothers. Even with such a fascinating corner of sports _ and
cultural _ history, the challenge is to tell it in a visually
interesting way. Kempner does so with vintage newsreels, Greenberg
family home movies, some stock footage, still photos and talking
head interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Because baseball was such a prime American sports pastime,
particularly in Greenberg's heyday of the '30s and '40s, his
inclusion was all the more symbolic and significant. Factor in his
acceptance in predominantly blue-collar Detroit, the home of such
prominent anti-Semitic figures as Henry Ford and Father Charles
Coughlin, and the story takes on even greater resonance.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg was a two-time Most Valuable Player award recipient, a
runner-up to Babe Ruth's former single-season home run mark (58)
and at one time the highest paid player in baseball ($100,000). As
World War II loomed, Greenberg became a symbol of American Jewish
resistance to Hitler. He served in the army for four years, largely
in a propaganda role, so his career statistics obviously suffered
from his sense of nationalistic duty. And his final ballplaying
days overlapped with color barrier breaker Jackie Robinson. In a
telling anecdote, Greenberg offered the black athlete encouragement
as his teammates continued to hurl abuse.
</P>
<P>
   It is not hard to become involved in Greenberg's story, even if
your interest in baseball is minimal. At times, however, Kempner
focuses too narrowly on the specifics of the game, recounting the
details of World Series wins and losses that threaten to bog the
film down into the ordinary. She occasionally overplays her hand
trying to pump up the drama, making too much of Greenberg's shift
from first base to the outfield, for instance. And hyperbole like
Dershowitz calling Greenberg ``the most famous Jew in America'' _
What about radio and movie star Eddie Cantor? Supreme Court Justice
Louis Brandeis? _ goes unchallenged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Life and Times of Hank Greenberg'' is hardly an objective
portrait. It would have helped to hear another side of his story,
or some hint of an imperfection. But for those who like their
sports stars glorified _ and perhaps Greenberg comes close to
deserving it _ this film is a four-bagger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Life and Times of Hank Greenberg''
</P>
<P>
   3 - 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   Not rated
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 1 hour, 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A well-researched, affectionate tribute to
baseball's first Jewish slugging star, illuminating sports and
cultural history.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
