<HEADER>
A7470 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-POSTAL-0901-COX     08-31 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSTAL-0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    'GOING POSTAL' A BAD RAP FOR POSTAL SERVICE, STUDY FINDS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Postal Service employees are no more likely to ``go
postal'' than are other American workers, according to a national
workplace study released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going postal is a myth, a bad rap,'' said Joseph Califano,
chairman of the U.S. Postal Service Commission on a Safe and Secure
Workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Postal workers are no more likely to physically assault,
sexually harass or verbally abuse their co-workers than (are)
employees in the national workforce,'' said Califano. ``Postal
employees are only a third as likely as workers in the national
workforce to be victims of homicide at work.''
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference, Califano said these findings are the
result of ``the most comprehensive survey ever'' of job site
violence. The two-year, $4 million, independent study was
commissioned by the Postal Service after several highly publicized
shootings by disturbed postal workers. The incidents _ such as a
1986 massacre in the Edmond, Okla., post office when letter carrier
Patrick Henry Sherrill killed 14 co-workers before shooting himself
_ made ``going postal'' a slang term for getting irrationally angry
or violent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If 'going postal' is meant to suggest that postal employees
are more violent than the national workforce, it is simply
untrue,'' the report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   However, if the study debunked the notion of postal workers as
teetering on the brink of insane violence, it lent some credence to
the TV stereotypes of malcontent letter carriers Newman on
``Seinfeld'' and Cliff on ``Cheers.'' Postal workers have more
negative attitudes about work than those in the overall job force,
the report found.
</P>
<P>
   Postal employees were twice as likely as other workers to say
they would change jobs for the same pay and benefits. They were
more likely to file grievances and less confident in management's
fairness and honesty.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, many postal workers seem to have bought into the
``going postal'' perception. Postal workers are almost six times
likelier than those in the national workforce to believe that they
are at risk from workplace violence from co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a post office ``is one of the safest places in
America'' to work or visit, said Califano, a former Secretary of
Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   Postmaster General William Henderson said he was glad the study
had disproved the perceptions that postal workers were more prone
to violence. But he conceded that the findings were not of ``a
clean bill of health'' for the service.
</P>
<P>
   He said a recommendation to ``overhaul the dispute resolution
system'' will be considered in negotiations with postal service
unions.
</P>
<P>
   As of last April, when the report's researchers completed their
task, Postal Service employees had 126,000 grievances awaiting
arbitration. ``This level of grievance activity appears unmatched
in the public or private sectors,'' the report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, in the entire auto industry, only 11 grievances
reached arbitration in 1998. However, with 900,000 employees, the
Postal Service has more than twice as many workers as the auto
industry's 400,000. The Postal Service is the nation's second
largest civilian employer, behind only Wal-Mart, said Califano, who
is president of the National Center on Addiction and Substance
Abuse at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   The commission examined 29 incidents of workplace homicide
involving postal workers as either victims or killers from 1986 to
1999. They found 15 postal employees killed 34 postal employees and
19 outsiders killed 14 postal workers.
</P>
<P>
   Such violence had prompted Henderson to analyze the problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go to one more postal facility and explain
why some father or mother was murdered,'' the he said.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that the homicide rates at postal
facilities were considerably lower than in other workplaces. In
major industries, the highest rate of 2.1 homicides per 100,000
workers was in retail trade _ which includes convenience stores,
which are often targets for armed robbers. The next highest rate of
l.66 was in public administration, which includes police officers.
The homicide rate for postal workers was .26 per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The most dangerous occupation was taxi drivers and chauffeurs,
with a homicide rate of 31.54 per 100,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   The 249-page report is based on an analysis of data from the
Bureau of Labor Statistics, surveys of 12,000 postal employees and
3,000 employees in the national workforce, and more than 300
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that postal workers ``resent the phrase
and the image'' of ``going postal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some employees say they are embarrassed to tell people where
they work because of the violent stereotype,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ One in 20 American workers was physically assaulted on the job
in the past year _ about the same rate for postal workers as
others.
</P>
<P>
   _ About one in six workers were sexually harassed on the job _
14 percent for postal workers compared to 16 percent overall.
</P>
<P>
   _ About one in three workers said they were verbally abused on
the job _ 36 percent of postal workers, 33 percent overall.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that 14 of the 15 postal workers who committed
homicides had histories of violence, mental illness, substance
abuse or criminal convictions. It recommended that the agency
screen job applicants more carefully for potential violence.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the American workplace, the level of violence is
``unacceptably high,'' said Califano.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For online information: www.usps.com
</P>
