<HEADER>
A7475 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-MIAMI-DORSEY0901-     08-31 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MIAMI-DORSEY0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UM's high expectations energize mellow Dorsey
 &HT;    By Jorge Milian
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Ken Dorsey's career at the University of Miami nearly
ended before it began.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a restaurant just over the California border into
Arizona one year ago, Maggie Dorsey looked up from her meal and
noticed her son's face plunged deep into his hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Dorseys were one day into a five-day, cross-country trip
from their home in Orinda, Calif., to the UM campus when a wave of
doubt and homesickness struck the 18-year-old quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know mom, I don't know if I've made the right decision
going so far away,'' said Dorsey, his voice quivering. ``I'm going
to be a million miles from my friends, my family, everyone and
everything that I know. Did I do the right thing?''
</P>
<P>
   Maggie Dorsey assured her son that he had, but if further
affirmation is needed, just ask UM offensive coordinator Larry
Coker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where we'd be without Kenny Dorsey,'' Coker said.
</P>
<P>
   Probably not ranked No. 5, which is where the Hurricanes begin
the season tonight against Division I-AA McNeese State in the
Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   When Kenny Kelly unexpectedly left UM in January to sign a pro
baseball contract, the Hurricanes were in a lurch. Dorsey was the
only other scholarship quarterback on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   But Dorsey had played so well in three starts last season as a
freshman that voters in the AP poll gave the Hurricanes their
highest pre-season ranking in Butch Davis' six seasons as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Subbing for an injured Kelly in November, Dorsey completed
64-of-91 passes for 718 yards (.703 percent), nine touchdowns and
one interception while leading the Hurricanes to three consecutive
victories and their highest three-game point total (155) in school
history.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly returned in mid-December and took over the starting job
for the Gator Bowl, where he struggled before being replaced by
Dorsey in the second half of Miami's 28-13 victory against Georgia
Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Still, skeptics claimed Dorsey did most of his damage against a
collection of powder puffs. While Kelly made starts against four
teams ranked in the top 10, Dorsey confronted Big East
cellar-dwellers Temple (55-0) and Rutgers (55-0) as well as
struggling Syracuse (45-13).
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are people that have no idea what college football is
all about,'' Dorsey said. ``They weren't the elite teams that Kenny
played against, but they were good teams. I choose not to listen
(to the skeptics).''
</P>
<P>
   It's about the only subject that will get a rise out of Dorsey,
who is mellower than a James Taylor album.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsey spends most of his free time watching cartoons and
describes himself as ``boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Few of those who know him best disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's real laid-back,'' said UM offensive tackle Bryant
McKinnie, one of Dorsey's closest friends on the team. ``Kenny
doesn't come out that often. We have to drag him out. He doesn't
like to cause conflict so he comes out to please us.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dorsey: ``I love being lazy. I'm probably going to be 300
pounds when I get older.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't get the wrong impression. Dorsey is no slacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fiercely competitive,'' said Maggie Dorsey, a retired
phone company employee. ``When he was little, he would get very
upset if he didn't play well. He wouldn't say anything, but he
would get this look that told you he was angry.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't often that Dorsey didn't play well at Miramonte High
School. In two seasons, he passed for 4,968 yards and 52 touchdowns
while leading Miramonte to a pair of area championships. He lost
only twice at Miramonte, with both defeats coming on missed extra
points after Dorsey-led comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the field, I'm a lot more intense,'' said Dorsey, who
picked UM over Tennessee and Southern California. ``Sometimes you
can't see it because of my demeanor. That's something that people
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Blades, UM's hard-hitting free safety, is one of those
people. Upon first meeting Dorsey, Blades didn't know what to make
of the rail-thin and peach-fuzzed 6-foot-5, 170-pound freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at him . . . he's thin, no muscles and he's quiet,''
Blades said. ``You might think he's scared, that if you hit him one
time, he might curl up and not want to play anymore. But he's a
fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to talk trash to him. He won't talk it back, but he
takes the ball and shows you. It's like he's telling you, 'You can
talk, but I'm going to do my job.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dorsey's job this season is simple: Stay healthy. The Hurricanes
are deep with talent, but Dorsey's backups include Ethenic Sands, a
converted wideout with no college quarterback experience, walk-on
Troy Prasek and first-year players Derrick Crudup and T.J. Prunty.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsey's intense off-season workout program boosted his weight
to 193 pounds, but, as Davis said, ``He's still not going to win
any He-Man poster awards.''
</P>
<P>
   A bigger concern than size may be Dorsey's ability to handle the
pressure that comes with renewed expectations at UM. He is the
youngest starting quarterback among teams ranked in the Top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take a lot of pride in being a true sophomore and being able
to play at this level,'' Dorsey said. ``I feel like there's no
reason I shouldn't produce and help this team win. A lot of teams
are going to look at that and say, 'Yeah, he's inexperienced so
we'll throw a million different things at him and do as much as we
can to confuse him.' I welcome those challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
