<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7479 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-FLA-BULLARD0901-C     08-31 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLA-BULLARD0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Safe haven' changes Bullard's life
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ When Thaddeus Bullard walked into the
Florida Sheriffs Boys Ranch cafeteria for the first time, he stood
about 6-feet-1, weighed about 175 pounds and was palming a
basketball in his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Bouchard, then residence director of the boys ranch, was
expecting a troubled 13-year-old, but this person didn't fit the
description of a typical rising ninth-grader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought some college kid had come in,'' said Bouchard, now
president of the Florida Sheriffs Youth Ranches.
</P>
<P>
   But this big, strong boy was Bullard, a child who had just
arrived from Boynton Beach. He, his family and local law
enforcement officials all had agreed he needed help growing up. His
mom hated sending him away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the hardest things I ever had to do,'' said
Daria Bullard, a customer service representative. ``He was getting
in trouble at school and being hard-headed at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Her son agreed, although he still can't explain why he had such
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a bad kid with a really bad temper. I got into fights
and had an attitude,'' he said. ``We just needed to find an
alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   They found one about 350 miles north at the 3,300-acre boys
ranch near Live Oak. It was a place that changed Bullard's life. It
became his home and his second family.
</P>
<P>
   Without it, he doubts he would be a University of Florida
graduate. He would not be the school's student body vice president.
He would not be a starting defensive end for the Gators. He isn't
sure what he would be without that ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day and probably to the day I die, I will argue with
anyone about that being one of the best programs in the country,''
Bullard said. ``It's a safe haven. People get the impression it's
like a prison. It's not true. There are no bars, no fences.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is structure at the voluntary intervention center.
Administrators fill nearly every minute of every day for the 70-80
boys living at the ranch at any one time. They rotate chores in
their cottages and must get jobs for spending money. They must go
to school, do homework and keep their grades up if they want to
play sports.
</P>
<P>
   That was Bullard's biggest motivation, Bouchard said. His study
habits were poor and staff members had to make sure he completed
his work. They also worked hard to teach Bullard how to handle his
temper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awful. He about wore us all out,'' Bouchard said. ``He
was 13 years old, but physically he was larger than most of the
adults there. He had learned to get his way through bullying other
people because his physical presence was so intimidating.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullard eventually improved his demeanor enough that he could
have gone home, but he never did. He attended Suwannee High in Live
Oak for four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more than 10 percent of the kids we work with stay all the
way through high school,'' Bouchard said. ``With Thaddeus, he had a
lot of things he had to work through and even after he was doing
well in the program, he was so involved in athletics and the school
he just really didn't want to move.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, as a high school senior, Bullard left the ranch at
administrators' urging so he could be more independent. He moved in
with then-Suwannee County school superintendent Charles Blalock and
his family, who had become friends.
</P>
<P>
   That year, Bullard also racked up athletic awards and
recognition. He was named a Parade All-America and second-team USA
Today All-America and was wooed by FSU, Ohio State and Tennessee
before choosing Florida. He looked forward to playing close to his
family and his Live Oak home.
</P>
<P>
   But as a freshman, he faced more difficulties. The NCAA
clearinghouse questioned his test scores and he was forced to
withdraw from school as a freshman. It was 1996, the year of UF's
first and only national title. He sat in the stands each week with
a different batch of recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to just sit there and watch every game,'' Bullard
said. ``But as time went on, I thought this might have even been
the best thing that happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard agrees that it was just part of the maturation process
for Bullard. In high school he had learned about handling his
temper. As a college freshman, he discovered football accolades and
physical prowess don't solve life's problems, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw how life might be after football,'' Bullard said. ``I
learned, don't take advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Since first playing in 1997, however, he's had to remember that.
He's had lots of playing time (750 plays) but hasn't become a star.
He made 39 career tackles and 27 so-called big plays but has
started just twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't done as much on the field as I've wanted, but I hope
to change that this fall,'' said Bullard, who now is 6-4 and 263
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bullard earned a sociology degree in the spring and now is
taking graduate classes in higher education. He was elected student
body vice president and spends time juggling school, political
responsibilities and football, along with some charitable works.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been real proud of him. He's developed a real sense to
give back to kids,'' Bouchard said.
</P>
<P>
   That's a long way from the big kid Bouchard met a decade ago and
remembers sitting with so ma
</P>
<P>
   ny late nights, telling him people would say things he didn't
like for the rest of his life but ``it's up to you how you handle
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
