<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dolphins have to go back a long way for evidence of a big play
 &HT;    By Todd Archer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ Dan Marino would give a look. Mark Clayton or Mark
Duper would knowingly nod. The cornerback had no idea what was
about to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Ten touchdown passes in that 1984 season were for more than 34
yards. Marino set NFL records for yards passing (5,084) and
touchdowns (48). Clayton and Duper made it to the Pro Bowl. Marino
had 57 completions of 50 yards or more in his career.
</P>
<P>
   The longest pass the Dolphins completed in the exhibition games
went for 39 yards from Jim Druckenmiller to Nate Jacquet.
Druckenmiller is out of football now, and Jacquet was traded to San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Fiedler will be making the second start of his career Sunday
against Seattle. The longest pass he has completed in a
regular-season game is for 25 yards, although he and Jimmy Smith
connected for a 70-yard pass in Jacksonviille's 62-7 playoff
victory against the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't simulate game situations as much in practice, but
we're working at it,'' Fiedler said. ``We've thrown the deep ball
for conditioning after practices the last few days. It helps us
work on the timing with the wide receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty passes last season went for 25 yards or more. Damon
Huard's 69-yard pass for a touchdown to Tony Martin was the
Dolphins' longest play from scrimmage. The three deep threats _
Martin, Bert Emanuel and Leslie Shepherd _ have been on the
receiving end of touchdowns of 99, 85 and 73 yards, respectively,
in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has his own style,'' Emanuel said. ``The most
important thing is that it's there. That he drops it in a bucket.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice in practice Sunday, Emanuel said Fiedler threw perfect
deep passes down the sideline to Shepherd and Martin where the
defensive back didn't have a chance to make a play on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to keep throwing it and keep throwing it and keep
throwing it,'' Shepherd said.
</P>
<P>
   Fiedler's hip injury kept him out of practice for three weeks,
denying him the chance to develop a chemistry with his wide
receivers. In the exhibition season finale against New Orleans,
Fiedler's first pass traveled 24 yards to Martin. Emanuel caught a
17-yard pass. Oronde Gadsden caught an 18-yard pass.
</P>
<P>
   The running game, which looked good in the exhibition season,
will help the deep ball. If the Dolphins can move the ball on the
ground, then teams will have to bring a safety up to the line of
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best scenario,'' Gadsden said. ``Teams are going to
have to come after an inexperienced quarterback. If they bring a
lot of people up, then we're going to hit them. That's what you
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Chan Gailey's offense calls for a lot of short, crossing passes
and intermediate routes that sometimes result in long passes. Troy
Aikman threw touchdown passes for 90 and 76 yards last year in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, St. Louis' Kurt Warner came to closest to a
Marino-type season, earning NFL Most Valuable Player honors with 41
touchdown passes. He threw the ball all over the field to wideouts
Isaac Bruce, Torry Holt and Az Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is trust,'' Emanuel said. ``Jay is the type of guy
if he sees one-on-one coverage, he's going to take advantage of it.
He will allow us as a wide receivers to make plays. He's
aggressive, which I like. Sometimes it takes a gutsy throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiedler will have to make the throw at some point. In the past,
that would have led to the Marino look, the Marks Brothers' nod and
a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   This year?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a whole lot of film to refer back to in the
pre-season,'' coach Dave Wannstedt said. ``We're going to have to
work on it in practice, like we do, and make them count when we get
the opportunities in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
