<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MED-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   Here is THURSDAY'S package of Medical News Today health-news
stories and features prepared by HealthScout.com and distributed by
The New York Times Syndicate. For information about subscribing to
this daily service, call 888-269-8796.
</P>
<P>
   OLD BARBIE DOLLS MAY CONTAIN TOXIC CHEMICALS, by Suzanne Leigh
</P>
<P>
   Next time you feel like letting your daughter play with your old
Barbie dolls _ don't.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say that old vinyl toys made with certain
plasticizers can disrupt the body's delicate endocrine system,
causing damage to the ovaries and testes and interference with
sperm production.
</P>
<P>
   Plasticizers known as phthalates are added to vinyl toys like
dolls, pacifiers and rattles to make them flexible. The phthalates
used in toys made in the 1950s, such as early Barbie dolls, have
been known to ooze out as they decay, according to Yvonne Shashoua,
a conservation scientist speaking at the recent national meeting of
the American Chemical Society in Washington, D.C. (450 words)
</P>
<P>
   WESTERN WILDFIRES CAUSING WIDESPREAD LUNG DAMAGE, by Neil
Sherman
</P>
<P>
   The 84 fires burning across 6.2 million acres in 11 western
states are also taking their toll on people's lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Those with asthma, heart disease or chronic lung disease are at
increased risk from the 500-mile, ash-filled smoke plume that's
spread across Montana, the Dakotas and Iowa, health officials say.
And while the smoke is no serious long-term threat to healthy
Westerners, scratchy throats, runny noses, difficulty in breathing,
headaches and irritated sinuses seem as much a part of the
landscape as Montana's burning, and now famous Bitterroot Valley.
(420 words)
</P>
<P>
   `GENETIC' DECAF MAY TASTE THE SAME AS REGULAR COFFEE, by Nicolle
Charbonneau
</P>
<P>
   Sick of decaf coffee or tea that's got no jitters but tastes
like dishwater? Take heart _ in the future, you may be able to grab
a brew with all the taste but without a trace of caffeine.
</P>
<P>
   British and Japanese researchers report that it may be possible
to grow coffee and tea plants that miss two tiny genetic steps in
the biosynthesis of caffeine, potentially producing full-flavored
decaffeinated brews without using the toxic solvent or fluid
extraction techniques that remove caffeine. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   NEW HOPE FOR RELIEF FROM PAIN SYNDROME, by Edward Edelson
</P>
<P>
   It's a condition that can be painful enough to drive some
patients to suicide, so hard to define that even its name is in
question and so hard to treat that even studies involving a handful
of patients warrant publication in a major medical journal.
</P>
<P>
   It is reflex sympathetic dystrophy, RSD, classified as a rare
disease because officially fewer than 200,000 Americans are
believed to suffer from it. Two new studies in the New England
Journal of Medicine describe promising studies on treatment of the
pain and dystonia of RSD. Both studies were done in the
Netherlands, but the treatments are available in the United States.
(700 words)
</P>
<P>
   OSTEO DRUG HELPS BUILD MEN'S BONES, TOO, by Adam marcus
</P>
<P>
   Men with osteoporosis can boost their bone density and cut their
risk of fractures with a drug approved to treat the crippling
condition in women.
</P>
<P>
   A two-year study by international researchers showed that men
who used the drug alendronate had stronger skeletons and suffered
fewer broken bones than those who didn't get the therapy, according
to the study, which appears in the New England Journal of Medicine.
(750 words)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
