<HEADER>
A7489 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-HOUSING-BRIBES-HNS &LR;      08-31 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-BRIBES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOUSING OFFICIAL DESCRIBES BRIBERY SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LANCE WILLIAMS and CHUCK FINNIE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A former San Francisco Housing Authority
official testified in federal court that she earned a salary of
$52,000 while taking thousands of dollars in bribes to provide
clients with government rent subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Section 8 subsidies for poor people, Yolanda
Jones told a U.S. District Court jury on Wednesday that on a
typical workday, ``I went out and sold Section 8s.''
</P>
<P>
   The subsidies amount to as much as $1,000 per month.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 39, spent three years as city relocation specialist,
which ended when she left on a workers' compensation claim in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who also is known as Yolanda Bradley, is the daughter of
Hunters Point trucker Charlie Walker, a friend and former law
client of Mayor Willie Brown. She is the self-described goddaughter
of the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   She has emerged as a star government witness in the corruption
trial of her boss, longtime Housing Authority official Patricia
Williams, a $72,000-per-year executive accused of masterminding a
lucrative bribery scheme that, Jones testified, occupied most of
Jones' time as a city employee.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has pleaded guilty to 10 counts of conspiracy and bribery
in connection with the alleged scheme, in which she and Williams
allegedly charged tenants as much as $2,500 to create a bogus paper
trail entitling them to rent subsidies that are supposed to go only
to eligible poor people.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, testifying Wednesday, was matter-of-fact about her own
activities. ``I had to take responsibility for my wrong,'' she told
the jury.
</P>
<P>
   But she said none of it could have happened without Williams,
57, whom she described as a greedy and corrupt boss who happily
accepted bribe money ``at home, at the store, McDonald's,
wherever.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who faces as many as 12 years in federal prison, has
pleaded not guilty. Wednesday, she listened intently and took notes
as Jones was questioned by prosecutor John Hemann.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jones' story, she and her boss cooked up the
bribery scheme in 1996 at a time when the city was demolishing or
remodeling five big public housing projects, forcing thousands of
poor people to move at one time.
</P>
<P>
   Tenants dislocated by the upheaval were offered either places in
other public housing projects, or Section 8 subsidies to help them
rent apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Jones described the relocation process as chaos. Because of lax
procedures and the city's rush to move the tenants, it was obvious
that many people who didn't even live in the projects were
receiving aid, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a man who had been sleeping in a tent in the
parking lot of the Hayes Valley project was approved for aid as a
displaced tenant, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the relocations, Jones said that an old
acquaintance, Tracy Baker, who is a niece of the football legend
O.J. Simpson, had approached her and offered a bribe in exchange
for a Section 8 certificate.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said she had taken the idea to Williams, who as relocation
manager had the power to make such a thing happen.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said Williams liked the idea. They charged Baker $1,500 to
qualify her for Section 8 certificates, splitting the bribe money
between them, she testified. After that, they took $1,500 from
Baker's sister to get her Section 8 vouchers, as well.
</P>
<P>
   And after that, Jones said, they were off, taking bribes from as
many as two dozen other people.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said she had recruited tenants, and Williams had provided
phony addresses in the projects awaiting demolition.
</P>
<P>
   The tenants were then instructed to swear out false affidavits
saying that they had lived at the fake address, and also were told
to supply birth certificates and other identification. Jones said
she would deliver the package _ and half the bribe money _ to
Williams, who would walk the paperwork through.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said Williams had set the prices, charging $1,000 for a
public housing unit and as much as $2,500 for Section 8 vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of her plea agreement, Jones won't be sentenced
until after Williams' trial concludes. Testimony continues Thursday
before Judge Charles Legge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
