<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7492 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-0903-COX     08-31 1573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ONCE TRAILING, GORE EXUDES A NEW CONFIDENCE AS RACE ENTERS
STRETCH
 &HT;    Eds: Can be twinned with story slugged BUSH.
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Sept. 3
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Vice President Al Gore is right where he wants to
be in his race for the White House with Texas Gov. George W. Bush _
ahead or dead even in most polls, with voters increasingly
demanding substance over style, issues over personality.
</P>
<P>
   And with the traditional Labor Day start of the general election
campaign, Gore is following a strategy that not only has erased the
double digit lead Bush held in the polls less than a month ago, but
also has dramatically altered the rules of engagement between the
two presidential hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than try to match the Bush charm offensive, Gore has
drawn the governor into the more treacherous terrain of comparison
politics, offering a long list of specific policy proposals and
challenging his opponent to ``put up or shut up'' with his own set
of proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has taken the bait, at least on the potentially potent
issue of providing prescription drug benefits under the
federally-funded Medicare health care plan for seniors. In response
to Gore's challenge, Bush plans to put forth a detailed
prescription plan this week.
</P>
<P>
   Gore used an issues-laden club to dispatch former Sen. Bill
Bradley of New Jersey, his sole opponent, in the Democratic
presidential primaries. But there is no guarantee it will work on
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to let Al Gore do to Governor Bush what he did
to Bill Bradley,'' said Bush campaign spokesman Don Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there is always the prospect that Gore could slip
back into the attack dog style that he finds so comfortable in the
clutch. It's a style he recently admitted ``probably did'' turn off
voters earlier this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the whole nature'' of the presidential campaign has
changed in the month since both candidates formally accepted their
party nominations, said Thomas Mann, an analyst at the Brookings
Institution, a Washington research organization.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``can no longer just give the back of his hand to a
discussion of the issues,'' Mann added.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's travels, speeches and advertising in the weeks since
accepting the Democratic Party's presidential nomination suggest
why.
</P>
<P>
   They also reveal the broad contours of the game plan Gore
intends to follow in the weeks ahead. It is a general election
strategy that:
</P>
<P>
   - Targets the swing states of the industrial Midwest in order to
reach the 270 electoral votes needed to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   - Ties Bush down in several Southern states, notably Florida and
Georgia, and perhaps splits what has been a solidly Republican area
of the country in presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   - Woos working family voters, especially younger married women
who don't have college degrees and disillusioned younger voters,
with populist rhetoric .
</P>
<P>
   - Emphasizes domestic issues, such as targeted tax cuts, health
care, education, Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   - Involves TV ads that retell Gore's life story, contrasting his
Vietnam military service, family life and pre-politics career in
journalism with Bush's less directed youth.
</P>
<P>
   - Attacks Bush's record in Texas, especially on the environment,
education and health care for children .
</P>
<P>
   - Anticipates a powerful performance by Gore in the October
debates.
</P>
<P>
   - Relies on grassroots get-out-the-vote efforts by labor and
activist groups that promote abortion rights, civil rights and
environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   - Limits President Clinton's role to fund-raising, appearances
before core Democratic constituencies and helping his wife Hillary
in her Senate campaign in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race is right where we want it to be,'' said Mark Fabiani,
a senior Gore official at the campaign headquarters in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along that we were right on the issues and that
once the voters started focusing on the issues, that they would see
that Al Gore stands with the people and not the powerful,'' said
Chris Lehane, Gore's traveling press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout much of the year, Gore has trailed Bush in national
polls, largely as a result of Bush persuading voters that he would
do a better job in handling government functions that typically
have favored Democrats _ most notably education, Social Security
and health care.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest Gallup Poll results, which were released last
Thursday, show that Gore now leads Bush by 10 points or more on all
three issues.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Gallup Poll shows that Gore has wiped out the
19 point lead Bush once held on cutting taxes, the cornerstone
issue of the Bush campaign. Forty-seven percent said Gore would do
a better job on taxes, 43 percent favored Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unprecedented economic growth of the last eight
years, Gore is trying to tap into the discontent of ``working
families'' _ those who are not necessarily better off than they
were when the Clinton-Gore administration took office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   He is appealing especially to younger, white married women with
families who did not attend college. Gore pollster Stan Greenberg
describes this group as ``financially squeezed, even in the strong
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   These women are also ``fairly traditional in terms of values,''
according to Greenberg, and are likely to find Gore's family ties
and running mate Joe Lieberman's religious faith appealing.
</P>
<P>
   To further appeal to these women and their families, Gore is
offering not only federal income tax cuts targeted to the middle
class, but also expanded government services, such as quality
preschool.
</P>
<P>
   He also has proposed tax credits for college tuition for middle
class families and new opportunities for health care coverage for
working families unable to afford insurance.
</P>
<P>
   But even the issues aimed at older voters are presented by Gore
in terms of how they benefit the entire family.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida last week, for instance, the vice president cast his
enhanced Medicare prescription drug coverage as a ``family value''
and one that relieves middle class families of some of the expense
of elderly relative's health problems.
</P>
<P>
   It was no accident that Gore pitched his prescription plan so
hard in Florida, a state with a heavy elderly population and 25
electoral votes. And it is not surprising that Gore is kicking off
his Labor Day week of campaigning in Pennsylvania, another state
with a large elderly population and 23 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   What is surprising is that Gore is competitive in Florida and
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's brother Jeb is governor of Florida and, consequently, the
state was once viewed as out of reach for Gore. But the state's
senior population and hotly contested race to replace retiring GOP
Sen. Connie Mack has given Gore a strategic opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida is a real Achilles' heal for the Republicans,'' said
Tad Devine, a senior Gore strategist.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Pennsylvania once was widely regarded as a sure thing
for Bush if he chose the state's governor, Tom Ridge, as his
running mate. But Bush passed over Ridge, a supporter of abortion
rights, and instead chose former Wyoming congressman Dick Cheney, a
staunch opponent of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   To a large degree, Gore is following the same strategy as
Clinton in finding the right combination of states to reach the 270
electoral votes needed to win the White House: carry California and
the Northeast, pick off a few key Southern states and battle it out
in the pivotal industrial Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Gore has solidified his lead in California and
New York, which represent 87 electoral votes. He believes he is
competitive in Florida, Georgia, North Carolina and Louisiana,
although his home state of Tennessee is closer than he would like.
And he has wiped out Bush leads in such important Midwestern states
as Ohio, Michigan, Wisconsin and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton carried most of the Midwestern states in 1992 and 1996,
but Gore has had trouble breaking through in the region, largely
due to the free trade policies of the administration and the
president's impeachment-related troubles.
</P>
<P>
   But union leaders in the Midwest are warming to Gore. The United
Auto Workers finally endorsed him just before the Democratic
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   And since declaring himself his ``own man'' and stepping out
from Clinton's shadow, the vice president has surged ahead in the
polls in Michigan, one of the most important states in the Gore
electoral strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's finally cut the umbilical cord with Bill Clinton,'' said
Lansing-based pollster Ed Sarpolus.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Gore campaign views the election as close, one in
which most voters will not make up their minds until the final two
weeks of the campaign. Consequently, Gore strategists view the
debates scheduled in October as crucial to the vice president, a
fierce debater.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is still unclear whether the debates, as set by the
Presidential Commission on Debates, will take place.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign last week formally endorsed the commission's
plan for three 90-minute, prime time TV debates. But Bush's
campaign has yet to accept the commission's invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's email address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
