<HEADER>
A7494 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SOUL-POSSESSED01-COX     08-31 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUL-POSSESSED01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Soul' possesses a muddy, multiple personality
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few things can be said with certainty about ``Soul Possessed,''
the Debbie Allen dance drama opening the Alliance Theatre's
2000-2001 season. It apparently wants to be deeply mystical, but
the results are deeply mystifying. It can be safely stated,
however, that the show:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Is about a woman in love with two men, and heartbroken about
it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Is set in a timeless version of Louisiana bayou country.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Contains terrific dancers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Features one of them as ``Death,'' who with his bare torso,
skintight leather pants and endless writhing resembles a
Chippendale stripper with the world's worst crick in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond these observations, we enter heavy fog. The bayou country
is indeed fascinating by virtue of its many cultures and religions,
its mix of the graceful and the raw, but Allen _ as writer,
director and choreographer _ overloads it with dissonant dance
styles and religious references.
</P>
<P>
   There's no cohesive vision or tone. Instead of flavorful,
indigenous music we get the urban-contemporary, FM-radio sound of
co-composers Allen and James Ingram, which has about as much
cultural authenticity as an L.A. sound stage.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: There's more to cooking gumbo than throwing everything
in the kitchen at the pot.
</P>
<P>
   The evening does benefit from striking, elegant leads. Tai
Jimenez is Ysabel, the willowy, high-spirited bride-to-be. Destan
Owens is Luke, her distinguished but somewhat aloof betrothed.
Carmen de Lavallade is the icy mother-in-law-to-be who dismisses
Ysabel with a haughty toss of her regal head. Miguel Angel _
although he sounds uncomfortable with his few lines of dialogue _
is the soulful, handsome drifter who tempts Ysabel away from her
wedding preparations.
</P>
<P>
   Allen strives for originality, then trips up by trying to give
the tale a spiritual dimension, always tricky in popular musical
theater. Beyond the art form's built-in challenge, it's hard to
decipher what Allen is really trying to say, spiritually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soul Possessed''
</P>
<P>
   Through Sept. 24. 8 p.m. Tuesdays-Saturdays; 2:30 and 7:30 p.m.
Sundays. $16-$45. Alliance Theatre, 1280 Peachtree St. N.E.
404-733-5000 or www.alliancetheatre.org
</P>
<P>
   /alliance2.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An overgrown multicultural mishmash.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
