<P>
   CHINA-TIANANMAN (New York) _ Five survivors of the Tiananman
Square massacre are suing Li Peng, the second highest-ranking
official in China, in a federal court in New York for human rights
abuses, the first time that such a legal action has been taken
against a Chinese official. The lawsuit was filed on Monday. Among
the five plaintiffs are Wang Dan, a prominent student dissident who
organized talks at Beijing University, and Zhang Liming, whose
sister was killed by a single bullet in the chaotic early morning
hours of June 4, 1989. Li, the head of China's parliament, was
attending a conference of world leaders at the United Nations this
week and was served with a court summons early Thursday morning at
the condominium tower where he was staying in Manhattan. Li was
prime minister during the Tiananmen Square incident. By Edward
Wong.
