<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Bush fires up `failed leadership' theme
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush, fired up and on the attack, berated the Clinton
administration today for seven years of ``flowery speeches,'' big
talk and failed leadership. Turning combative, a re-energized Bush
lashed out at Al Gore as a member of an administration that failed
to lead for seven years and could not ``make the case'' for four
more. Bush, who has been hammered by Gore over his lack of
specifics on big-ticket issues, told reporters in Toledo, Ohio,
''The reason they're pounding me is because this administration, of
which Al Gore is a part, has been unable to lead.''
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVE AD AT THE READY
</P>
<P>
   Making an issue of Al Gore's credibility, Republicans are
planning to air an ad reminding voters of his fund-raising visit to
a Buddhist temple and his suggestion that he invented the Internet.
``There's Al Gore reinventing himself,'' a woman says in the
Republican National Committee ad. The 30-second spot _ which
Republicans described as tongue-in-cheek _ would be the party's
most direct attack yet, and Gore spokesman Mark Fabiani reacted
strongly: ``When (George Bush's ) back is against the wall, he will
do anything to get elected. He visited Bob Jones University, he
saluted the Confederate flag and now he's going to break his own
promise . . . that he would not engage in personal negative
attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH VISITS 100TH SCHOOL
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush visited the 100th school of his presidential
campaign today to highlight his $47 billion education plan. He
marked the occasion in the gymnasium of Springfield (Ohio) High
School, an event intended to symbolize his commitment to giving
school systems more control and holding them accountable for poor
student performance. He also highlighted what he said were
opportunities for education reform missed by the Clinton-Gore
administration, saying, ``We must not allow children to be trapped
in schools that will not teach and will not change.'' Al Gore's
campaign said the visits are more like ``100 photo ops'' about
misguided proposals.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH HITS BACK ON JUDGE'S ORDER
</P>
<P>
   En route to Ohio today, George W. Bush dismissed criticism of
the way Texas provides health treatment for poor children, saying
that a court order demanding action came from ``an activist,
liberal judge'' and that Democrats were only trying to change the
subject from their own poor record. U.S. District Judge William
Wayne Justice said in his order that Texas was not adequately
providing health services to children despite the state's promise
four years ago to make changes. Bush defended his record: ``We are
doing everything in our power to take care of the disadvantaged
children of the state of Texas.'' He criticized the federal
government for refusing to grant waivers that he said would have
made the process easier.
</P>
<P>
   PUSH FOR `PATIENTS' BILL OF RIGHTS'
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore and Joe Lieberman say all Americans are entitled to a
``patients' bill of rights'' that sets minimum standards of care,
and they challenged George W. Bush to offer the same. Gore and
Lieberman pushed their idea at a rally today in Seattle, the
culmination of a weeklong focus on health care issues. Before that,
they were up early to greet commuters arriving from Baybridge
Island across Puget Sound by ferry. They then boarded the ferry to
ride to the island and back. Gore used the occasion to urge
additional funding for alternate forms of mass transit, saying of
the ferry, ``This is mass transit in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   CANDIDATE AS MOUNTAIN TOUR GUIDE
</P>
<P>
   For almost 15 minutes, while his plane was en route from
Portland, Ore., to Seattle, Al Gore fondly recalled three days he
spent with his son, Albert III, last year climbing Mount Rainier, a
peak of 14,4le to lift this country up to its national
possibilities.'' Nader said he expects to be on the ballot in 45
states ``and the overwhelming population will have a chance to vote
for the Green Party candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   NATURAL LAW-REFORM PARTY ALLIANCE
</P>
<P>
   It's ``a marriage made in heaven,'' John Hagelin said today,
announcing an alliance between his Natural Law Party and a faction
of the Reform Party that favors him over Pat Buchanan. Hagelin, an
Iowa physicist, made the announcement at the Natural Law Party's
convention in Alexandria, Va., where he accepted the presidential
nomination. The convention was attended by about 400 people, about
half of them delegates. Hagelin and his running mate, Silicon
Valley entrepreneur Nat Goldhaber, assured the crowd that a general
election victory was possible.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY WOULD REDUCE TROOPS OVERSEAS
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney said today that if he and George W. Bush are elected
they'll look at scaling back U.S. troops in the Balkans and letting
European allies take on more responsibility for peacekeeping. ``I
haven't seen yet any proposal from the administration to get out of
Kosovo or Bosnia,'' Cheney said at a school in Fort Lauderdale,
Fla. ``One approach would be to have our European friends and
allies pick up a bigger share of the burden there.'' Cheney has
accused the Clinton-Gore administration of running down the
military, but he said today he's not ready to say where he would
recommend increases until a new Bush administration does a complete
military review.
</P>
<P>
   BATTLE LINES FORM OVER MILITARY
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's claim that the next president will inherit a
military ``in decline'' is producing a political tug of war among
present and former Pentagon commanders. Al Gore's campaign has put
forth Defense Secretary William Cohen, the only Republican in the
Cabinet, and former Clinton Defense Secretary William Perry to
dispute the assertions. Colin Powell, the retired chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff during the presidency of Bush's father,
joined the fray. ``Readiness has declined, investment has declined,
maintenance has declined, training has declined,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   STRAW VOTE FOR VETERANS
</P>
<P>
   Jumping into the debate over defense readiness, the American
Legion invited the nation's 27 million veterans and active-duty
military today to vote in a presidential ``straw vote'' on the
Internet. A new Web site (www.mylegion.com) will tabulate the votes
and provide information on the military positions of candidates
George W. Bush and Al Gore, said Al Lance, national commander of
the 2.8 million-member veterans' organization. Lance said there
also would be a process by which respondents could voice their
views on related issues such as health care, education and the
problem of unemployment among veterans.
</P>
<P>
   GERALDO RIVERA AS MAYOR?
</P>
<P>
   Geraldo Rivera wants to run for mayor of New York City, and he
doesn't mind if that makes people laugh. ``I expect the first
reaction to be, `Geraldo as mayor, ha ha,' `` Rivera told The New
York Times. But the television journalist, who anchors a talk show
on CNBC, says he is serious about an independent campaign for
mayor, after a ``totally self-financed'' petition drive to get his
name on the ballot. ``I think the city needs someone from the
outside,'' Rivera, 57, said today on NBC's ``Today.'' The election
is in November 2001. Mayor Rudy Giuliani is barred by law from
seeking a third term.
</P>
<P>
   ETHNIC NERVE IN BLACK COMMUNITY
</P>
<P>
   The bitterness of a feud between two black Democrats in the 11th
Congressional District in Brooklyn, N.Y., has torn apart a
longstanding friendship and has spread the anguish. The political
contest has brought to the surface simmering _ and often unspoken _
tension between African-American New Yorkers and those with
Caribbean heritage. In her campaign for Congress, Una Clarke, a
Jamaican-born city councilwoman, has not only heralded her
Caribbean roots but has accused her old friend and mentor, Rep.
Major Owens, of being anti-immigrant. Owens, born in Memphis, has
accused Clarke of trying to turn black Brooklynites against one
another by using ethnic chauvinism to get votes.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN: ADL OVERREACTED
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman said the Anti-Defamation League misunderstood him
earlier this week when he advocated a greater role for faith and
religion in American public life. He said the response to his
remarks at a black church in Detroit on Sunday and an interfaith
breakfast in Chicago on Monday was ``a bit of an overreaction.''
After those speeches, the ADL urged Lieberman, the first Orthodox
Jew on a national party ticket, to tone down his references to
religion. ``I respect the ADL, but I respectfully disagree,'' he
said. ``I think they misunderstood part of it, part of what I was
trying to say. And the whole point of it is that I think faith has
a constructive role that it can play in American life.''
</P>
<P>
   NADER WINS UNION BACKING
</P>
<P>
   The United Electrical, Radio and Machine Workers of America
voted to endorse Green Party presidential candidate Ralph Nader,
its first departure from backing Democrats. Nader had addressed the
union's 200 delegates at its 65th national convention in Erie, Pa.,
offering himself as an alternative to the two major party
candidates, even though the Democratic Party has traditionally been
labor's partner in politics. Before Nader, the union had endorsed
only four presidential candidates, all Democrats: Franklin
Roosevelt, Lyndon Johnson, George McGovern and Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   GORE GOING TO LETTERMAN
</P>
<P>
   Get ready for questions about The Kiss. Al Gore has accepted an
invitation to appear on David Letterman's ``Late Show'' on Sept.
14. Gore undoubtedly will be asked about his convention lip-lock
with his wife, Tipper. Letterman has repeatedly run taped footage
of the lengthy kiss. It'll be Gore's first appearance with
Letterman since they both donned eye goggles in 1993 to watch Gore
smash ashtrays with a hammer. George W. Bush appeared via satellite
on Letterman's show March 1.
</P>
<P>
   REMEMBER THOSE HEALTH CARE REFORM ADS?
</P>
<P>
   A Republican group plans to air a new TV ad criticizing Al
Gore's proposal to add a prescription drug benefit to Medicare. The
Republican Leadership Coalition spot warns that Gore would dip into
seniors' Social Security checks to pay for the program. But an
elderly woman seated at a table has a message for Gore: ``Get your
hands off my Social Security check!'' Viewers could easily be
misled, however. The government currently deducts Medicare premiums
from Social Security checks before issuing them. And Gore's program
would be optional; seniors would be charged only if they sign up.
The ad doesn't make either of these points.
</P>
<P>
   POSITIVE CAMPAIGNS GET HIT, TOO
</P>
<P>
   With three weeks to go before the Democratic primary in
Washington state, Insurance Commissioner Deborah Senn unveiled her
TV ad campaign for the Senate nomination. Senn accuses her
better-financed opponent, ex-Rep. Maria Cantwell, of dodging
debates and ``hiding in a TV'' via her own ads. Cantwell, who
became a millionaire several times over as an Internet exec after
being turned out of office in the 1994 Republican takeover of
Congress, has been showing ads pointing out her business experience
and other credentials and all but ignoring Senn. The winner of the
Sept. 19 primary will face Republican Sen. Slade Gorton.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-LIEBERMAN, HEBREW-STYLE
</P>
<P>
   It was bound to happen. At a late night rally in downtown
Portland, Ore., Al Gore and Joe Lieberman were greeted by
supporters waving placards that spelled out Gore-Lieberman in
Hebrew letters. The New York Times said it should be noted,
however, that the signs said ``Gore-Lieberman 2000,'' not
``Gore-Lieberman 5761,'' the year of the coming election in the
Hebrew calendar.
</P>
<P>
   PACKER FANS PUT TO THE TEST
</P>
<P>
   The love affair between the Green Bay Packers and their fans
faces the ultimate pocketbook test the week after next. The
question is whether to enact a half-percent sales tax to help
finance a $295 million facelift and expansion of Lambeau Field,
home of the Packers. The answer is not a sure thing heading into a
Sept. 12 referendum in which about 170,000 Brown County, Wis.,
residents will decide the tax's fate. Emotions are strong on both
sides, and a recent poll had the election a virtual tossup. The
stadium was built in the late 1950s for $960,000.
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNORSHIP BALANCE SEEMS ON HOLD
</P>
<P>
   Only 11 states are holding elections for governor in November.
By all accounts most of the races are too close to call, but the
biggest swing that either party realistically envisions is two or
three seats. The real test of the parties' struggle for the
nation's statehouses is not likely to come until the off-year
elections of 2002, with governors' races in 36 states. In 1994, two
years into President Clinton's first term, voters reversed the
Democrats' 30-18 advantage in governorships. The Republican Party
now has 30-18 advantage in governorships. (Maine has an
independent, Angus King, and Minnesota has Jesse Ventura, now with
the Minnesota Independence Party.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
