A7529 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-WEEKEND01-COX     08-31 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The week on TV
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no official low point of the television season, but the
de facto bottom traditionally comes over Labor Day weekend. Many
people are on vacation or doing something other than watching TV,
and so television just sort of shrugs and gives up.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Labor Day weekend is the calm before the onslaught of
new fall network programs, but this year the networks' big
premieres are being pushed back to the first week in October so
they don't have to go up against NBC's Summer Olympics the last two
weeks of September.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, here's what's out there.
</P>
<P>
   Today
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``This Week in History'' (8 p.m. on the History Channel) _ The
date was Sept. 3, 1977. The song was ``It's a Long Way to
Tipperary.'' And Mary Tyler Moore turned out the lights for the
last time at TV station WJM.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Television Show With John Henson'' (10 p.m. on ABC) _
How 'bout that title? This new special, hosted by ``Talk Soup''
smarty-pants Henson, takes a look at everything TV, mainly the
offbeat. It's a pilot that ABC didn't pick up.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Outer Limits'' (8 p.m. on Showtime) _ The anthology
series has its final episode and has lined up a big-name cast. In
``Final Appeal,'' the year is 2076 and a scientist (Amanda Plummer)
is being tried for bringing her time machine to an era that has
outlawed technology. The judges' panel includes Charlton Heston,
Hal Holbook, Cicely Tyson, Swoosie Kurtz and Robert Loggia.
</P>
<P>
   To set up the show (although all episodes stand alone), Showtime
will run eight previous episodes from 2 to 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Best Bet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Jerry Lewis Muscular Dystrophy Association Telethon'' (9
p.m. Sunday on WUPA, continuing for 21 1/2 hours).
</P>
<P>
   OK, scoff all you want, but while you're sitting back in your
recliner looking down your nose at Lewis' ruffled-shirt shtick,
he's actually raising money for a good cause. That's more than you
can say for most of television.
</P>
<P>
   Over its 35 years, Lewis' annual telethon has become a camp
classic, a kind of bizarre hybrid of an old ``Ed Sullivan Show''
marathon and a PBS pledge break, the whole thing just going onnnn
and onnnnn.
</P>
<P>
   What's really happened is that the telethon hasn't changed, but
the audience has. Despite a few bells and whistles here and there,
Lewis and his guests are doing basically the same show they did in
the '60s _ hour after hour of earnest, straight-into-the-camera
stuff and Vegasy schmooze. The audience, meanwhile, has been
Letterman-ized, and we expect irony and arch self-awareness. Lewis
is still old-school, and we've become new-school.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, among those helping Lewis raise money for
research this year are Christina Aguilera, Wayne Brady, Dennis
Franz, Billy Gilman, Casey Kasem, Jack Lemmon, Frank Sinatra Jr.,
Martha Stewart, Regis Philbin and the casts of ``Fosse'' and ``Lord
of the Dance.'' And of course, Ed McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
