<HEADLINE>
$ADV04 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   EDITORS: Subs to fix time element to 1998 in second graf. 
 (For release Monday, Sept. 4, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard.  
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Monday Night Football'' kicks off its 31st regular season
tonight at 9 on ABC, as the Denver Broncos visit the St. Louis
Rams. The real test tonight, though, is for new ABC color man
Dennis Miller, who was the network's out-of-left-field choice to
take the third seat in the booth alongside Al Michaels and Dan
Fouts.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody expects Miller to return the festivities back to the days
of Howard Cosell and Dandy Don Meredith. But it would be nice for
ABC if he could at least make things entertaining. By itself, an
improved game schedule probably won't be enough to help ``Monday
Night Football'' stem the ratings decline that resulted in an
all-time low in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Miller has had a couple of preseason games to warm up, and the
results have been mixed. He knows a lot about the game, as ABC
promised, and he's had moments of inspired wit. But he's obviously
been trying hard, and the great ones make it look effortless. If
he's going to truly find the groove, it'll start tonight.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: An earthquake, that's what we need. A
big fault opening right under the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mysterious Ways,'' NBC at 8: Bad medicine. The voices haunting
a woman may be real, not schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moesha,'' UPN at 8: The sixth season premiere of the sitcom
starring Brandy finds her on tour with Q. Back home, Hakeem and
Niecy wonder how their kiss has changed all of their relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal,'' Fox at 8: Two back-to-back episodes feature
more of the usual grim real-life predicaments, such as a
10-year-old practicing lawyer and an insanity plea based on a foot
fetish. Repeats.
</P>
<P>
   ``King of Queens,'' CBS at 8:30: Doug's big-screen TV is stolen.
At least he won't have to watch ``Big Brother.'' Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' CBS at 9: An old sitcom chestnut _
Whom shall we name as guardians of our children in case something
happens to us? _ becomes a high-stakes matter when members of Ray's
family are among the candidates. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order,'' NBC at 9: A dead stripper leads to an insider
trading case. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Becker,'' CBS at 9:30: The titular curmudgeon quits smoking,
and it doesn't improve his disposition. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family Law,'' CBS at 10: Bo Derek guests as the estranged wife
of Christopher McDonald's Rex _ that's believable _ who shows up
demanding an adjustment in her support payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antiques Roadshow,'' PBS at 8: Toronto and a silver tea set
are on tonight's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Rodgers and Hammerstein's Cinderella,'' Disney at 8:35:
All-star cast includes Whitney Houston, Brandy, Whoopi Goldberg,
Jason Alexander and Bernadette Peters. From 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Married With Children'' marathon, FX from 2-11 p.m.: If you
have absolutely nothing else to do _ Your shower need grouting? _
FX is running the ``Married to Sports Labor Day Marathon,'' with a
bunch of sports-related episodes of this over-the-top sitcom about
Al Bundy, his wife, Peg, and their awful kids, Bud and Kelly. Sure
your gutters don't need cleaning?
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Open Tennis, USA at 7:30: Live from Flushing, N.Y. CBS airs
a wrap-up show at 12:35 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Becoming Dick,'' E! at 9: Harland Williams stars as an
aspiring actor whose friend (Bob Saget, who also directed) says
he's just too nice to make it in Hollywood. Four years later he's a
big star and wonders how he got there _ his People's Choice Award
fell on his head giving him amnesia. Robert Wagner co-stars as his
butler. Premiered last week.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: Dwight Yoakam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: George Clooney and
music by Dogstar, Keanu Reeves' band. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 12:35 a.m.:
Graham Nash. Rerun. (Note time after tennis update.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: William H.
Macy.
</P>
