<HEADER>
A7541 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ESTATE-VETO-0901-COX     08-31 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTATE-VETO-0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON VETOES ESTATE TAX BILL
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton vetoed a bill Thursday that would
have repealed the federal estate tax, saying the measure was too
costly and that it would benefit only the wealthiest 2 percent of
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other 98 percent of the American people literally get
nothing out of this,'' said Clinton. ``It is wrong on grounds of
fairness. It is wrong on grounds of fiscal responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., criticized Clinton's
action. But he stopped short of threatening to try to override the
veto.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton has just given the back of his hand to
working families who want to leave their hard-earned family farm,
small business or Internet start-up to their children after they
die,'' Lott said in a statement. ``Apparently, even death can't
protect you from the Clinton-Gore administration's insatiable
desire for higher taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   By phasing out the estate tax, the bill, passed earlier this
summer by the Republican-led House and Senate, would have provided
wealthy families with a projected total of $105 billion in tax cuts
over the coming decade. White House analysts said only 54,000
American families, farms and small businesses would benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, said Clinton, half the benefits would go to just 3,000
wealthy families, each of which stood to gain a tax-cut windfall
that he said would be worth, on average, $7 million per family.
</P>
<P>
   Further down the road, said Clinton, repealing the estate tax
would cut $750 billion from federal revenues between 2011 and 2021.
That's when the cuts, which would have been phased out gradually
under the Republican plan, would take full effect, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes referred to as the death tax, the estate tax is levied
against the assets of someone when they die and pass along their
estate to others.
</P>
<P>
   Few Americans actually pay such a tax, because the first
$675,000 of a personal estate is exempt from the tax, under current
law. Farms and small businesses get even larger exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton supports Democratic efforts to hike the personal estate
exemption further to $4 million, over time, and he held out the
prospect of compromise with congressional Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our party is not against reasonable estate tax relief,''
Clinton told reporters gathered in the White House East Room
minutes after he vetoed the legislation. ``But we have to proceed
on grounds of fiscal responsibility
</P>
<P>
   and fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislation to repeal the estate tax over 10 years passed in the
Senate in a July vote by 59-39. It passed in the House in June by a
margin of 279-136.
</P>
<P>
   Neither vote carried the two-thirds margin required to override
a presidential veto, and White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said he
was confident the presidential veto would stand.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used his veto to highlight election-year differences
between Democrats and Republicans on competing approaches to tax
and budget issues.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cast the estate tax repeal bill as part of a larger
package of Republican efforts to extend hundreds of billions of
dollars in tax breaks to wealthy families and large corporations
over the coming decade, a move he said would put the government
budget at risk.
</P>
<P>
   The government is projected to take in roughly $2 trillion more
than it spends over the coming decade, not counting Social Security
surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   That is roughly the amount of the tax cuts proposed or approved
by the GOP-led Congress, according to White House tax and budget
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The estate tax repeal is part of a larger Republican strategy
to have now over $2 trillion of tax cuts over the next 10 years,''
said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you add it all up, (it) would take us back to the bad old
days of deficits, high interest rates and having no money to invest
in our common future.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans can be reached by e-mail at: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
