<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYUNDAI TIBURON: ONE OF THE HIP ENTRY-LEVEL CARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the Ford Focus _ wagon, four-door, hatchback _ that has
become the latest exemplar of hip and affordable.
</P>
<P>
   In these times of renewed interest in entry-level cars that are
more than basic econoboxes, Consumer Reports magazine just named
the Focus its top-reated small sedan.
</P>
<P>
   The Chrysler PT Cruiser falls into this category, though with
dealer-primed prices it's a bit expensive compared to others, and
so do the Volkswagen New Beetle and Toyota's Echo, although the
Echo does not seem to have caught on the way Toyota had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   So how about a surprising addition to the list? Can you say
Hyundai?
</P>
<P>
   The Hyundai Tiburon, two doors and seating for four, is a smooth
blend of sports car and sedan. Aimed at younger drivers, both in
price and appearance, its outside says verve, from its bulging
front fenders to the arc of spoiler that graces the plump rear
deck.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, it's young and high-tech all the way: the center console
and its controls are angled toward the driver; techno-metal-looking
trim surrounds gauges, knobs, vents, and the shift housing (though
real metal would look a lot better than this aluminum-painted
plastic). There is one odd grouping of controls on a single pod on
the dash _ windshield wipers, cruise control, and rear window
defogger. But overall, the layout, with big knobs and easy access,
is quite functional.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that when you look at the Tiburon from the outside
you see sports car, it is surprising that it is as roomy inside as
it proves to be. The front-seat passengers have plenty of legroom,
and side-to-side space is made pretty good because of the way the
doors curve, giving concave space to the outer body.
</P>
<P>
   The back seat, also, can hold two adults in reasonable comfort,
a pair of children in plenty of space.
</P>
<P>
   For about $3,000 over base price, the tested Tiburon came with
an upgrade package that included leather power seats, better sound
system, the rear spoiler, and a power sun roof.
</P>
<P>
   The front bucket seats were wonderful, with firm ridges on the
outsides of the thighs and the back. Thigh support at the front of
the seat was firm and the backs were broad enough to support even
big-shouldered folks. I've seen far worse seats in far more
expensive cars.
</P>
<P>
   Since it's aimed at a younger crowd looking for performance, the
Tiburon needs at least a modicum of quickness and it has it _ in
places.
</P>
<P>
   When it was introduced in 1997, it came with a standard
1.8-liter 4-cylinder engine that bopped out 130 horsepower. Now, at
2.0 liters and 140 horses, it's reasonably peppy. It's not so much
that it's real quick from a standing start, but once it gets
cranking it loves to romp in the high RPM band.
</P>
<P>
   Even with its engine pushed regularly over two weeks of driving,
it managed just under 24 miles per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   I found the five-speed manual shifter a bit sloppy and too long
in the throw. But for those tuners who like to tinker with their
inexpensive performance cars, I'm sure there's a conversion kit out
there that would tighten up the shift sequence and cut the throw by
40-60 percent _ at not a particularly high cost.
</P>
<P>
   The Tiburon, with gas-charged struts, stabilizer bars, and a
rigid body is a stiff little car. You feel the rigidity in corners
and it can be a bit jarring on bumps. But that's the case with lots
of sports cars and sports sedans and a price many enthusiasts are
willing to pay.
</P>
<P>
   The trade-off is a smooth, solid straight-ahead ride on the
highway, easy lane-to-lane transitions when passing, and virtually
no body roll when cornering.
</P>
<P>
   On my favorite rising and twisting hill, it made the transition
from corner to corner to corner with a sure-footed stickiness that
surprised me. Just as it comes off the assembly line, this car
could handle even more power from its engine.
</P>
<P>
   In testing cars, it is useful to ask how each might be used by
its buyer. The Tiburon _ it will be bought by adventurous types in
their first jobs, college-bound students (or their parents), or
enthusiasts looking for an inexpensive base from which to tune up
to a performance car _ can fill lots of needs.
</P>
<P>
   It seats four comfortably. It has a fairly large trunk that
becomes absolutely huge if you accept it as a two-seater and fold
the rear seats down. And on different days and on different
missions, it can be different cars for you. And in these times of
adventurous lifestyles, that is a good selling point.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that Hyundai's remarkable warranty _ 10 years, 100,000
miles for the power train, five years, 60,000 miles bumper-to
bumper, and five years, unlimited mileage roadside assistance
(including towing) _ and you've got an inexpensive, fun car well
worth looking at.
</P>
<P>
   Nice Touch:
</P>
<P>
   --The air vents built into the front of the doors. Great
position from which to direct air flow right back at passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance:
</P>
<P>
   --The wasted space between the front seats. You get a small,
covered bin toward the rear and the console slopes down _ slashed
by two tiny slots for paraphernalia _ toward the shifter. A bigger
box would have provided more storage and arm support as well.
</P>
<P>
   --A bit of humor:
</P>
<P>
   Open the ashtray (it's where I toss coins) and you see that the
Korean manufacturers have made sure to label this item for those
who might be confused. ``ASSY-TRAY,'' it says right there in raised
letters. So, that's where you put your butts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE NUMBERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Base price: $13,999 &QL; 
Price as tested: $17,207 &QL; 
Horsepower/Torque: 140/133 lb.-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 97.4 inches/170.9 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 68.1 inches/51.7 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 2,566 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 4 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
</TEXT>
