<HEADLINE>
WHEN SHOPPING PRESENTS A CARLOAD OF CHALLENGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's go shopping for a car, but let's impose some rules.
</P>
<P>
   Here's $23,000 to spend, but as you shop, you can't use your
legs. You can only look at two-doors because you have to be able to
squeeze a wheelchair in behind the driver's seat, and the center
pillar of a four-door makes that impossible. You have to buy an
automatic. You must be able to reach and close your car's open
trunk lid from a seated position.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, did I mention you can't take any cars for test drives? You
don't find cars fitted with handicap controls sitting on dealer
lots. You might find yourself shopping not for what you want, but
for what works.
</P>
<P>
   It's a challenge that has put Betsy Pillsbury, 47, into the
driver's seats of an eclectic lineup of autos in the 30 years she
has spent using a wheelchair. First car? A Gremlin. Chair went onto
the front seat beside her and had a tendency to slide off and hit
the accelerator in sudden stops. Then an AMC Pacer _ before Wayne
and Garth from ``Wayne's World'' made that car cool. Then a Nissan
Pulsar. Awful car, says Pillsbury, who is the assistant director
for special projects in the Massachusetts Office on Disability.
Today, she owns a 1991 Volkswagen Jetta, a car she likes, but also
a car that she must enter from the passenger's side and that she
has had to alter radically inside.
</P>
<P>
   The shopping goal on this Saturday? Find a car Pillsbury can
enter from the driver's side and simplify the complicated
entry-exit routine she goes through each time she drives.
</P>
<P>
   To get into the Jetta, for instance, she wheels up to the
passenger side door. Using her arms, she hoists herself into the
seat. Then she slides the seat forward. Reaches out and folds her
chair and lifts it onto the floor behind her. Slides the seat back.
Uses her hands to lift her legs into the car. Shuts the door. Uses
her upper body to pull herself across to the driver's seat _ an act
made possible only because she has had the center console ripped
from the car, and only then after she shifts from park to first so
her legs can clear the shift lever. Each time she exits the car,
she does all this in reverse, each time knowing that a slip puts
her on the ground, where she'll need help getting up or that _ and
this has happened _ her chair might roll away on a hill before she
can get into it.
</P>
<P>
   A string of simple acts to most folks can be a long chain of
challenges in Pillsbury's world. Her solution: simplify by
shortening the skein. Getting in on the driver's side would be a
big step in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   She likes her Jetta and has long had her eye on a Cabrio, so the
first stop is the Volkswagen Gallery in Norwood, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Levy, a sales and lease manager, steps forward to help.
Pillsbury tries a Beetle and finds the distance between her chair
and the outer edge of the driver's seat to be a bit wide. But she
says she could get used to it. Then she tries, after sliding the
driver's seat as far forward as she can, to fit her chair in behind
her. It won't go. And even if it did, the space between the back of
her seat and the front of the rear seat is too small to allow her
to slide the driver's seat back once she is ready to drive.
</P>
<P>
   As we shop, it is surprising to realize just how small that
space is. How small? Let's say you have average-size hands. Spread
your fingers and thumb as far apart as they will go. Look at the
distance from the tip of the thumb to the tip of the little finger.
All she needs is two inches more than that. She doesn't get it in
the Beetle and, alas, the Cabrio is virtually the same size.
</P>
<P>
   But not all is fruitless at Volkswagen. Levy sincerely engages
Pillsbury in her challenge. He goes out to the lot to see if a Golf
might work. No. Neither will a Passat. So then he does something
Pillsbury says she has seen only once before. He starts
recommending cars made by other manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   So it's back out into the Jetta _ where years of putting in the
chair and taking it out have worn away the fabric on the back of
the front seat _ and off to the Saturn dealership. Saturn sells a
three-door, with the third door on the driver's side. The rear door
opens toward the rear of the car, there is no center pillar, and
that leaves ample space through which to put a chair. The problem
is, there is little space behind the front seat and the chair would
only fit if placed on the back seat. That could be an arduous lift
and, in an accident, it could be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   But Pillsbury's biggest problem with the Saturn is that once the
third door is open and she is in the driver's seat, she can't reach
back to close that door. The salesman suggests tying a string to
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strings break, and then where would I be?'' Pillsbury asks
later.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Focus, with a big front door and a trunk whose base is
at lap level, offers promise. But Reidar Davies at Jack Madden Ford
says that automatics are in short supply and the power seat
Pillsbury longs for is not an option. To fit her chair behind the
driver's seat, she'll have to remove one wheel, another task, but
one she is beginning to realize she might have to take on.
</P>
<P>
   At Boch Toyota, Steve Wight goes out to the back lot to bring in
a Solara, a relatively luxurious two-door that comes with Toyota's
reputation for longevity and power seats. At about $23,000, it's at
the top of her price range, though Wight says the manufacturer will
help out with the costs of installing special gas and brake
controls for Pillsbury.
</P>
<P>
   She goes back and tries the trunk _ can't reach it from the
rear, but because it is counterbalanced, she can easily close it
with a gentle touch from the side. She gets into the power seat,
slides it forward, and tries the chair. Still too wide, it misses
by about an inch. But she likes the car, and that causes her to
re-examine her possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the wheel off the chair is not a complicated task. Push a
button and pull off the wheel. Just don't drop it and let it roll
away. And it clicks right back on. And with the Solara, she'd only
have to remove one wheel, the floor space is plentiful and, Wight
shows her, the floor-anchor for the seatbelt folds out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a tradeoff, taking the wheel off _ or ripping out
the console'' and continuing to enter from the passenger's side,
Pillsbury says. By Monday morning, she sounds as though she's made
a choice. No more climbing between seats. She'll learn to deal with
the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toyota looks like a winner,'' says Pillsbury, who played by
the rules.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
