<HEADLINE>
REPORT CRITICIZES LIECHTENSTEIN'S RESPONSE TO MONEY LAUNDERING 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ A government-sponsored inquiry into whether
Liechtenstein is a center for money laundering found shortcomings
in the way the country handles the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Liechtenstein's justice system has been at a ``partial
deadlock,'' with some cases sitting idle for years, and its
assistance to prosecutors in other countries has almost ground to a
standstill, the special prosecutor, Kurt Spitzer of Austria,
concluded Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal proceedings remained unprocessed for years, hampered by
such things as inaction by judges and failures to respond to
requests for legal investigations and residential searches, he
reported. In some cases, any possibility of prosecution was
eliminated because of the time elapsed.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The principality, which sits between Switzerland and Austria,
asked Spitzer, a prosecutor at home, to examine allegations that
Colombia drug cartels, a Sicilian Mafia group and Russian criminal
gangs were cleaning up sums by passing them through Liechtenstein's
asset managers and 300 banks. With a population of just 32,000,
Liechtenstein has some 300 banks.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Liechtenstein was listed as one of 15 countries
failing to cooperate in fighting money laundering, and last month
millions of dollars linked to the late Nigerian dictator Sani
Abacha were traced to the country's banks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer shook up the country's clubby atmosphere when he had
documents seized from the bank owned by the realm's royal family.
The brother of the deputy prime minister and a member of Parliament
were detained for questioning during the inquiry.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But, in his report, Spitzer concluded that white-collar crime in
Liechtenstein is ``no different'' than elsewhere in Europe. ``Most
assets that wound up in the principality to be laundered have
already undergone a pre-wash in other countries. This ought to
serve as a reminder to those countries which are now pointing the
finger at the principality,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mario Frick, the country's prime minister, acknowledged
``blunders'' in pursuing illegal assets but said the report showed
that ``Liechtenstein is not and never has been a criminal state.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Liechtenstein has become a wealthy enclave by exploiting its
status as an offshore banking center. But pressures from the United
States and European countries to stamp out havens for criminals and
tax cheats forced the country in July to abandon its system of
anonymous accounts. Banks and fiduciaries are now required to
identify their clients and the source of their deposits.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's report singled out ``unjustifiable delays'' by the
judiciary and other legal officers in aiding other countries'
efforts to ferret out concealed funds. The principality has made a
pledge to give legal assistance to other nations, which has quashed
much of the vocal criticism of it from Switzerland. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
