<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7565 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-HOWARD-BUFFETT-PROFIL     08-31 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOWARD-BUFFETT-PROFILE-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOWARD BUFFETT INVESTS, TOO, BUT CORNFIELDS COME FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 3)  
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DECATUR, Ill. _ Howard Buffett, the 45-year-old son of the
investing legend, does not spend his days surveying stock charts or
analyzing corporate growth prospects. He surveys cornfields from
the cab of his John Deere tractor.
</P>
<P>
   He also drives a Ford pickup, wears battered blue jeans and
flashes an aw-shucks grin. If people still don't understand, he
puts it more pointedly: he may have a dad who is worth roughly $29
billion, but his grain bins here are not Fort Knox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have that much money,'' he said with a grin
burnished by frequent use. ``I'm not the guy listed on the Forbes
400 list.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the eldest son of Warren E. Buffett, the Oracle of Omaha,
Howard Buffett stands to become the next chairman of Berkshire
Hathaway, his father's holding company-turned-gold mine.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors circulating on the Internet last winter about his
father's supposedly failing health made the succession a delicate
subject. In fact, though the senior Buffett did have surgery in
July to remove a section of colon containing noncancerous polyps,
he celebrated his 70th birthday last week in good health at home in
Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't feel better,'' he said in a telephone interview
last week. But if he were hit by a car tomorrow, he said, his
chairmanship would pass to Howard.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Buffett has arranged matters so that, although his son
will not run the company himself, he will provide crucial
oversight. ``I want Berkshire and the culture to continue, and he
would be there to ensure that happens,'' Warren Buffett said. ``And
he has my ideas about who I think should be running it.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Buffett, meanwhile, is content to farm a 700-acre spread
near here where he lives with his wife, Devon, a 16-year-old son,
Howard, and one of his four step-daughters. He serves as chairman
of the GSI Group, a maker of agricultural equipment. He also does
charitable work on conservation and health issues and travels
regularly to countries like Uganda and Zimbabwe to photograph
exotic wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love wildlife,'' he said. ``I used to sleep out in the
back yard with my dog when I was growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, Howard Buffett and his two siblings, Susan, 47, and
Peter, 42, have staked out their own lives, quite apart from the
world of value investing that Warren Buffett has come to dominate.
</P>
<P>
   Peter found music, and made a name for himself in Hollywood by
writing the score for a scene in ``Dances With Wolves.'' Susan
worked at The New Republic and at U.S. News &AMP; World Report, then
switched to philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   And Howard? Well, Howard chose tractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always loved the outdoors,'' he said. ``I'm very
mechanical. When I got out of college, I just wanted to run a
bulldozer.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on his farm, though, he cannot avoid intrusive questions
about his father's publicly stated intention to leave the bulk of
his fortune to charity rather than to his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he leaves me 1 percent, I'll be OK,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Even scraps of the Buffett empire would be a colossal
inheritance. As things stand now, a mere 10 percent bequest divided
among the children would still give them each nearly $1 billion, to
add to the ``small gifts'' of stock that Howard Buffett said that
he and his siblings have received from their father at
Christmastime.
</P>
<P>
   What the Buffet children do not inherit, they may yet control.
Susan and Peter already serve on the board of the Buffett
Foundation, which is expected to become one of the world's largest;
Howard has a seat on Berkshire's board. All three have charitable
foundations of their own, financed by their parents.
</P>
<P>
   If Warren Buffett planted a seed of succession early on, it may
have been in naming his first son, Howard Graham Buffett, after two
men he greatly admired: his own father and Benjamin Graham, his
mentor and former professor.
</P>
<P>
   He also passed along to his son a love of sports. Saying that
Howard worships the Nebraska Cornhuskers football team doesn't
really tell it: His office at GSI is festooned with Cornhuskers
autographed footballs, sweatshirts and photographs.
</P>
<P>
   After attending three different colleges himself _ and working
as a bulldozer operator, farmer and real estate salesman _ he
served as a county commissioner in Omaha. Then he moved to Decatur
to work for Archer Daniels Midland, the giant grain handler.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, after the company became mired in a price-fixing
scandal in which he was not involved, he resigned, sold his stock
and bought the farm _ a proposition that did not pass his father's
value-investing test but won paternal approval anyway. ``It's not a
good business,'' Warren Buffett said of farming last week. ``But
it's a satisfying business.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Buffett also bought a stake in GSI, one of the largest
makers of grain storage bins, betting _ as his father might _ that
the growth of genetically engineered crops would oblige farmers to
erect separate storage facilities for conventional and biotech
grain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is he a chip off the old block? He answers the question with an
avuncular, plain-spoken tour of his office, a joke about his weight
and a confession that he has been known to accept chocolate milk
shakes during interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in my dad's philosophy, buying for the long term and
holding,'' he said at last.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his father, Howard Buffett has bought a few technology
stocks. But both men have a weakness for well-known brands and
neither is above a bit of boosterism. Howard speaks effusively of
his love for John Deere tractors; his father is often seen at
Berkshire's annual meeting swigging Cherry Coke and snacking on
Dairy Queen ice cream, both made by companies in the Berkshire
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, when Howard Buffett met a guest at local
restaurant for a meal of pork chops and mashed potatoes, he
jokingly snarled at a waiter who was showing off a Pepsi logo
tattooed on his arm.
</P>
<P>
   When his guest ordered a Coke, Buffett feigned a trot to the
men's room. In fact, he left the restaurant and made a beeline for
a Coke machine in a nearby parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's your Coke,'' he said when he returned. ``The Buffetts
don't drink Pepsi.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
