<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7566 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ONLINEMUSIC-0901-COX     08-31 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINEMUSIC-0901-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW SERVICE E-MAILS MUSIC TO SUBSCRIBERS
</P>
<P>
   By BOB KEEFE
</P>
<P>
   c 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ As its executives battle Universal Music Group over
copyright issues in a New York courthouse, online music company
MP3.com Inc. teamed up with another record label on Thursday to
launch a service
</P>
<P>
   that e-mails new music to some subscribers as soon as songs are
released.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com said the Internet service it's rolling out with Time
Warner Inc.'s Elektra Entertainment label was the first of its
kind. It's also the first time an independent online music company
has done a major joint venture with a traditional record label.
</P>
<P>
   As the entire online music industry struggles to find ways to
stay alive after being hammered by several negative court rulings
nationwide, San Diego-based MP3.com has been the most aggressive in
trying to forge
</P>
<P>
   better relationships with major recording companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to,'' explained Nitsan Hargil, senior Internet
analyst with the Kaufman Brothers investment banking firm. ``They
were not only humbled in court, but they had their heads taken off.
They know that
</P>
<P>
   becoming more legitimate is the only way they can go.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, a federal judge found MP3.com guilty of infringing on
five recording companies' copyrights. Since then, MP3.com has
reached settlements with four of them, including Time Warner, under
which it will pay for the use of their songs.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth company, Universal, opted not to settle. A judge in
New York heard testimony in the case this week and is expected to
make a decision on penalties against MP3.com by Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com isn't the only company whose courtroom woes are changing
the fledgling online music industry, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Napster Inc. in July lost a separate but similar copyright
infringement lawsuit filed by the Recording Industry Association of
America. A three-judge panel in San Francisco is scheduled to hear
that case on
</P>
<P>
   appeal during the first week of October.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com and Elektra hope to make money with their new service by
pairing the e-mail music with advertising. Internet links also will
take listeners to the artists' or Elektra's Web sites, where they
can
</P>
<P>
   purchase complete CDs immediately.
</P>
<P>
   For Elektra, the service _ dubbed ``singleserving'' _ also gives
it a new advertising medium without a major expense. And with
MP3.com's extensive database, where users have described their
tastes, ages and other
</P>
<P>
   information, Elektra can target particular markets or listeners
with particular tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The singleserving e-mail service is groundbreaking in that it
gives major labels the opportunity to achieve full media saturation
immediately upon the release of new music,'' Michael Robertson,
chairman
</P>
<P>
   and chief executive of MP3.com said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, MP3.com took another step toward the
mainstream, striking a deal with a company planning a chain of
stores and entertainment complexes. Under that agreement, patrons
of Outernet
</P>
<P>
   Inc. could use computer kiosks to digitally download different
songs from different artists using MP3's site and ``burn''
custom-made compact discs for $1 a title.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Hargil said he expects MP3.com and other online music
companies to continue seeking new ways to become more legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking for a business model that can work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Keefe can be e-mailed at: bkeefe(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
