<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7569 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EUROPE-RATES-NYT &LR;      08-31 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-RATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHER INTEREST RATES FAIL TO STEM EURO'S SLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ It was supposed to be a show of steely
toughness, an antidote to the chronic weakness that has plagued
Europe's single currency, the euro, ever since its debut in January
1999.
</P>
<P>
   But when the European Central Bank raised interest rates
Thursday for the sixth time in less than a year, the euro continued
to founder near its all-time low amid widespread fears that it will
sink even lower. Indeed, more than at any time in the short history
of the euro, many analysts view the central bank as not only weak
but off balance in response to changes in the economic climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are behind the curve,'' said Thomas Mayer, a senior
economist with Goldman Sachs in Frankfurt, who argues that the bank
is getting tougher just as the European economic growth shows signs
of getting weaker. ``In April 1999, they reduced interest rates
even though the economy already seemed to be taking off. We could
very well be in a similar situation right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed in large part by what it called the ``protracted
depreciation'' of the euro, the European Central Bank raised its
baseline interest rate by a quarter point Thursday, to 4.5 percent.
In a brief statement, the bank said the euro's weakness threatened
to push up the cost of imported goods at a time when high oil
prices _ compounded by the fact that oil is priced in dollars _
were threatening to ripple through the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But if the move was supposed to build confidence in the euro, it
did not. Within minutes of the announcement, the euro slipped
slightly to roughly 89 cents against the dollar. It fell further
later in the day, settling at 88.78 cents _ the lowest it has been
quoted in New York trading.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, the European Central Bank faces a devilish
problem. The euro has lost nearly one-quarter of its value against
the dollar since its introduction, and the biggest cause of that
decline has been the United States' magnetic draw on investment
money from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   If the weak euro does indeed fuel inflation, its credibility and
value in world markets will slip further. But if central bankers
slow down economic growth in an attempt to avoid inflation, the
euro could lose value as investors and corporations tilt even more
heavily away from Europe and toward the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``European corporations are voting with their pocketbooks,''
said Paul Mortimer-Lee, markets economist with BNP Paribas in
London. ``If you raise interest rates too far there is a danger you
will squeeze growth.'' And that, in turn, would hurt the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Though European inflation remains low, at an annual rate of 2.4
percent a year, it is now above the central bank's self-imposed
limit of 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts argue that the central bank and its president, Wim
Duisenberg, are clamping down on the money supply at a time when
European economic growth already appears to be peaking. Though most
economists predict that the overall growth of countries in the euro
zone will expand by more than 3 percent this year and next, recent
surveys show that business confidence has declined in Germany,
France and Belgium in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   The inflationary signals have been ambiguous as well. Stripping
out the impact of oil prices and other one-time increases, the
underlying rate of inflation is still very modest at 1.3 percent.
And although higher oil prices can ripple through the rest of the
economy, especially in wage demands from labor unions, the European
Central Bank's most recent assessment is that those effects have
not shown up in non-energy goods.
</P>
<P>
   Partly as a result, the move to raise interest rates has thus
far had the opposite effect on the euro that central bankers
wanted. In the two weeks since central bankers began sending out
clear hints of their intentions, the euro has weakened
significantly. Indeed, after staging a modest rebound in June, the
euro is now just a smidgeon above its all-time intraday low of
88.25 cents against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The ECB has trapped itself, Mortimer-Lee of BNP Paribas said, by
setting an inflation target that is too rigid. The Bank of England
and the Swedish national bank, neither of which is part of the
euro-zone, have set targets of about 2 percent but allowed for
greater flexibility by letting the rate vary 1 percentage point
above or below the target. The European Central Bank, by contrast,
has set 2 percent as the upper limit and never really set a lower
limit.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, economists generally agree that the euro's woes
reflect the persistently faster growth of the United States in
comparison with Europe. ``There is a massive flow of money into the
United States, and that has become a major new influence in the
past two years,'' said Ian Gunner, a currency analyst in London at
the Dutch bank ABN Amro.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States' investment allure ties back to its higher
growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do companies want to take over other companies?'' Gunner
asked. ``It has to do with the general well-being of the economy.
The Euro-zone is one year into its recovery and the ECB is already
worried about inflation. That is just not very impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the euro was introduced, Europe has experienced a combined
net outflow of both direct investment in companies and properties
and portfolio investments in stocks and bonds that total about 200
billion euros. Much of that reflects a sharp increase in
trans-Atlantic mergers, from Daimler and Chrysler to Credit Suisse
Group's $13 billion deal this week to acquire the investment
banking firm Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of analysts complain that the European Central Bank
has been inherently slow to recognize changing economic conditions.
Most economists believe the bank erred when it sharply reduced its
core interest rate from 3 to 2.5 percent in April 1999. At the
time, central bankers were afraid the Asian financial crisis and
the collapse of Russia would lead to a severe slowdown in western
Europe. The fears were correct, but by the time the rate was
decreased Europe was already exhibiting many signs of renewed
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The current problems are complicated by the widening divergence
of growth rates within the euro-zone. Germany, Europe's biggest
economy, lagged far behind the pack and grew by less than 2 percent
in 1999. But Ireland has been growing at well above 5 percent.
Irish consumer prices are surging at an annual rate of 6.2 percent,
while housing prices are climbing at about 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the ECB, the president is more of a moderator and
consensus builder than a strong leader,'' said Mayer of Goldman
Sachs. The process of building a consensus is more time-consuming
and difficult than at the U.S. Federal Reserve, he said, and that
may have made the European Central Bank slower in its response.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
