<P>
   POSTAL _ WASHINGTON _ Are U. S. Postal Service employees going
postal? Postmaster General William Henderson holds a news
conference to release a report that compares violence in the U.S.
Postal System with other workplaces. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   ESTATE-VETO _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton vetoed a bill
Thursday that would have repealed the federal estate tax, claiming
that the Republican legislation favored only wealthy
</P>
<P>
   Americans and would have reduced federal revenues by $105
billion over the coming decade. The move, which was expected,
highlighted election-year tax differences between Democrats and
Republicans. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Atlanta, National, Other
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ George W. Bush, still reeling from the Texas court
decision and seeming on the defensive, lashes out at Clinton and
Gore during a visit to Toledo for failed leadership. He also
highlights a Toledo family that would benefit from his programs.
(Hershey, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY _ LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ Dick Cheney, the GOP vice
presidential candidate, on Thursday visited Highland Elementary
school in Lake Worth. Earlier in the day, a bit of a political row
erupted in Broward County, a Democratic bastion just south of Palm
Beach County, when Democratic school board members attempted to
force a cancellation of a Cheney visit to a school there. His visit
had been arranged by the sole Republican on the 9-member school
board. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   BEAR-VS-ALPACA _ A bear is the apparent suspect in the Wednesday
night death of an alpaca - a llama-type critter - on 29.5 Road. DOW
is being called in, but a neighbor says scratch marks and dung
mixed with apples suggest a bear was the culprit. Neighbor says
this is proof that people are stupid when they feed bears. (Grand
Junction) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   RAMSEY _ A deep look at the last 10 days of ``Ramsey in the
news'' and why we as a society care so much. We'll toss a lot into
the stew, including the individual news tidbits, none of which
probably are too important on their own, and get another round of
analytical perspective on the story that, if goes to trial, might
be bigger than O.J. (Schneider, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RAMSEY-WEB _ The world of the Ramsey case online. Keys to
several sites. (Tamman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-MUSIC _ As its executives do battle against Universial
Music Group in a New York courtroom, online music company MP3.com
said Thursday it is teaming up with another record company, Time
Warner's Elektra label, to launch a service that will e-mail new
bands' music to subscribers as soon as its released. The service is
the latest incarnation of the online music business and - just as
significantly - the first time an independent online music company
has teamed up with a record label. With latest developments from
trial in New York; mention of upcoming hearings in San Francisco in
the Napster copyright case. (Keefe, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Eds. Also moving in the financial (f) and entertainment (e)
categories.
