<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-WEEK1-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITANS-BILLS REMATCH HIGHLIGHTS OPENING WEEK OF THE NFL SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; GAME OF THE WEEK (SUNDAY, 8 P.M.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee at Buffalo
</P>
<P>
   This of course is a rematch of the ``Music City Miracle'' which
was Tennessee's last second kickoff runback in the playoffs last
year that won the wildcard playoff game against the Bills. Though
Buffalo plays well at home, the Titans won't stumble, mainly
because the Bills don't have the run defense to stop Eddie George,
who had 1,304 yards rushing last season. In the preseason it has
sometimes taken four defenders to bring him down.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction; Titans, 28-21
</P>
<P>
   Arizona at Giants
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals' quarterback Jake Plummer has 11 fourth-quarter
comebacks in 36 career starts. It is his sometimes-electrifying
play that has made him one of the best young throwing talents in
the game. Last year, however, Plummer, because of a bad thumb and
even worse decisions, tossed 24 interceptions. He's looking to
rebound immediately and should pick apart a weak Giants secondary.
The Giants hold on in a high scoring game behind the defensive play
of Michael Strahan and quarterback Kerry Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Giants, 35-28
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore at Pittsburgh
</P>
<P>
   This game could not be more perfect for Baltimore's top defense.
Quarterback Kent Graham is a solid passer but his wide receivers
are young, which means the offense's chemistry might be off, making
them susceptible to the blitz, and the Ravens love to blitz. Middle
linebacker Ray Lewis, a murder trial fresh in his memory, wants to
take out the pain of what he feels was an unfair prosecution on
opponents. Quarterback Tony Banks will have a better game, and
better season, than many think.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens, 28-14
</P>
<P>
   Carolina at Washington
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins have more big-time players than an NBA all-star
game. The problem with possessing all that talent-and it is a
problem a lot of coaches would love to have-is getting it all to
mesh. There will be rough spots early in this game and early in the
season. The Panthers might actually jump out to a halftime lead.
But eventually all that talent will kick in, and what made the
Redskins so good last year, quarterback Brad Johnson, running back
Stephen Davis and wide receiver Michael Westbrook, will dominate a
weak Panthers' defense.
</P>
<P>
   Redskins, 25-13
</P>
<P>
   Chicago at Minnesota
</P>
<P>
   Please, everyone, relax about the Vikings' quarterback
situation. Daunte Culpepper will be just fine. He does have the
Hall-of-Famer Cris Carter and brilliant Randy Moss to throw to.
There will be bumps for Culpepper, but few quarterbacks have failed
in Dennis Green's offensive system. Besides, to slow down
Minnesota, a team has to have a great running game, and Chicago's
Curtis Enis does not qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Vikings, 28-17
</P>
<P>
   Detroit at New Orleans
</P>
<P>
   Running back James Stewart is the key. For Jacksonville last
season, before he signed with the Lions as a free agent, Stewart
had 13 rushing touchdowns. In preseason he has displayed the kind
of quickness and power Detroit had hoped for. He will stabilize
what has been a chaotic situation with quarterback Charlie Batch,
who is still recovering from a broken leg. Batch's status as
starter will be determined late in the week, and that delay always
throws off game plans. Still, the Lions survive.
</P>
<P>
   Lions, 24-10
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis at Kansas City
</P>
<P>
   This game will let the Colts know early the challenge that lies
ahead. Knowing Indianapolis is a strong Super Bowl favorite, every
team will play its best against the Colts. The Chiefs finished the
preseason 0-4 but has won eight of their last 10 regular-season
games at home. Quarterback Peyton Manning wins this one in the
final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Colts, 20-17
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville at Cleveland
</P>
<P>
   Biggest mismatch of the weekend. The Browns have no chance,
especially because quarterback Tim Couch, the savior, is playing
poorly. Quarterback Mark Brunell should have a healthy set of
statistics after this one, even though Courtney Brown, the No. 1
overall pick, might get to him a time or two.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars, 28-6
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco at Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers are fighting to avoid finishing last in the division,
while the Falcons are fighting to get back to the playoffs. San
Francisco is young and not very talented. Jeff Garcia is the first
49ers quarterback other than Joe Montana or Steve Young to start
Week 1 since 1980. If preseason is any indication, and it likely
is, Garcia will be good for throwing about two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons, 17-10
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay at New England
</P>
<P>
   There should not be much suspense in which team will win: The
Buccaneers will, of course. What will be interesting to watch is
how well the offense blends with wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson in
the fold. During one preseason game, the Buccaneers ran the same
play seven consecutive times _ a running play. Bland. But the team
will open things up against New England, and Johnson will be the
focal point. Will the team implode once Johnson begins demanding
the ball? That is Tampa Bay's biggest question as the team makes a
Super Bowl run.
</P>
<P>
   Buccaneers, 19-7
</P>
<P>
   Jets at Green Bay
</P>
<P>
   Favre did the right thing this week. He rested his tired
throwing elbow, though there is still a question of when the elbow
will fire up again. Most likely that won't happen against the Jets.
Actually, both the Packers and the Jets have problems at
quarterback. Vinny Testaverde seen little action in preseason,
which will surely affect his timing with the offense as well as his
endurance. Since Favre is at home, he wins the battle.
</P>
<P>
   Packers, 20-13
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 4 P.M. GAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia at Dallas
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Donovan McNabb finished the preseason with an 89.7
passer rating. The rest of the NFC East should be getting a little
nervous. The second-year quarterback is starting to get a good feel
for the game. Throw in talented runner Duce Staley, who accounted
for 41 percent of the team's offense last season, and Philadelphia
could end up steamrolling an aging Dallas team.
</P>
<P>
   Eagles, 21-6
</P>
<P>
   Seattle at Miami
</P>
<P>
   Probably the toughest game of the week to call because the teams
are so evenly matched. The edge probably goes to Miami since they
are at home and play well in season openers. Also, Seattle
quarterback Jon Kitna was disappointing in preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins, 21-14
</P>
<P>
   San Diego at Oakland
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Ryan Leaf gets the start for the Chargers and his
rebirth begins. Known more for being a crybaby than a professional
thrower, maybe Leaf can turn his career around. If that does
happen, it won't start against the Raiders, whose secondary is
pretty solid. Oakland sticks to its excellent ground game and wears
down the Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   Raiders, 15-7
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONDAY NIGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Denver at St. Louis Rams
</P>
<P>
   There will be times this season when the Rams feel the crush of
being the defending Super Bowl champions. But not this game. On the
surface, this seems a close matchup but the Broncos don't have the
speed to keep up with St. Louis on that slick artificial surface.
Terrell Davis has bravely made the comeback from torn knee
ligaments but few players come back from those injuries quickly.
Denver will be forced to rely on quarterback Brian Griese, who is
extremely inconsistent. This might be a blowout.
</P>
<P>
   Rams, 30-21.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
