<HEADER>
A7573 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-VOTER-TURNOUT-HNS &LR;      08-31 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTER-TURNOUT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GROUP PREDICTS LOW VOTER TURNOUT IN NOVEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite a spirited race between Vice President Al
Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, voter turnout in the 2000
presidential election could be the lowest in modern American
history, according to a study released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Gans, director of the nonpartisan Committee for the Study
of the American Electorate, said low turnout in the primaries,
scant political coverage by the major television networks and an
increasingly disinterested public were to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The critical problem with which the leaders and parties must
deal is mobilizing an electorate which is showing that the old-time
religion of civic duty and responsibility no longer hold sufficient
sway to propel many to the ballot box,'' said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 presidential race, voter turnout dropped to 49
percent of the voting-age population, equaling the total in 1924 _
the lowest percentage for a presidential election in the modern
era.
</P>
<P>
   The study by Gans' organization predicts turnout will be lower
on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Gans said despite the interest sparked by Arizona Sen. John
McCain's renegade bid for the Republican presidential nomination,
voter turnout in the primaries was about one-third lower than the
average turnout two decades ago, falling to 17.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gans attributed this decline to the primary process in which
both parties' candidates are effectively chosen early by a handful
of large states, making most voter participation unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the Democratic nominee, and Bush, the Republican Party
candidate, had won enough support by early March to ensure their
nominations _ months before the party conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Gans advised the candidates to find a way to energize alienated
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fall-off in voting after the crucial decisions have been
made is unfortunate but understandable, but the long dormant time
between the end of the contested primaries and the fall campaign
may pose problems in re-mobilizing the electorate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gans said the major television networks should increase their
political coverage to help voters learn about the candidates and
their stances on issues. He noted that the two major conventions
this received the smallest amount of coverage ever from the
networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The networks can say that with everything decided, there is
nothing to cover but what is to cover and critique is the image and
issues the parties are presenting by their judgement of what is
their best case,'' Gans said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1815EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
