<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7575 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-31 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GO,PAT,GO _ AWAY! 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _The Reform Party, torn apart by the dubious
posturing of both Pat Buchanan and John Hagelin as its presidential
nominee and heir to its founder Ross Perot, is but a ghost of its
former self.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is not clear just what those Reform folks should be
called these days. The party is too chaotic to be described even as
an organization any more, a designation that implies some internal
order.
</P>
<P>
   It has imploded, demolished by the Buchanan battering ram like
some empty, decaying building of no use to anyone any more.
</P>
<P>
   The fight for the empty title of presidential nominee between
Buchanan, the conservative commentator, and Hagelin, the obscure
physicist from Iowa, is, unsurprisingly, less about political
influence than about money.
</P>
<P>
   Both contenders are demanding that the Federal Election
Commission turn over to them the $12.6 million in taxpayer funds
the old party earned by winning more than 5 percent of the vote
four years ago. But this is not same political group playing by
confusing but comprehensible rules that it once was. It is not even
one group, but two. These people do not meet any logical standard
to warrant recognition as a legitimate political party.
</P>
<P>
   Common sense says the FEC should refuse to pick between the two
men and tell their non-existent party to take a hike. The law need
not sanction the pretense that this farce deserves public financial
support.
</P>
<P>
   Surely creative FEC lawyers can find some way to throw the
matter into the courts, where it will languish until the election
is over. A federal judge in Virginia, in fact, may have suggested
the complications of just such a development this week by refusing
to intervene in the presidential power struggle. Buchanan allies
had sought an order barring the Hagelin faction from using the
Reform Party name.
</P>
<P>
   The judge hid behind the familiar excuse of a lack of federal
jurisdiction, which prompted Buchanan's lawyer to declare he would
shift to a state court.
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin, like Buchanan, has threatened to take to court any FEC
ruling refusing him the money. And both candidates are waging legal
and political battles to get on state ballots for which they do not
automatically qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Neither can claim much public support or interest. Hagelin does
not even get a tiny bump in the polls, and Buchanan, who previously
twice sought the presidency, got only 1 percent in a recent USA
TODAY-CNN-Gallup Poll.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's celebrity has dominated the Reform Party tragicomedy,
but it has not worked to his advantage. A lot of people know who he
is but don't like his hard-edged, intolerant right-wing views.
</P>
<P>
   He attempted to take over the Reform label by inventing new
rules and stacking the convention with buddies of no previous
Reform Party identification or sympathy with its causes.
</P>
<P>
   The original, outraged Reformers regrouped around Hagelin,
tossed a rival convention and declared themselves the real core of
the party, which they seem to be.
</P>
<P>
   At bottom, this debacle is a product of Buchanan's irrational,
raw ambition and political unpopularity. He left the Republican
Party only after his flopping presidential candidacy reflected a
fatal GOP weariness with his fiery oratory. He treated the Reform
campaign as his personal vehicle to power and money, counting on
his celebrity to make voters forget that he had no vision and no
message.
</P>
<P>
   He recently had gall-bladder surgery, but that is not generally
considered a permanently dangerous condition that could stop his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's worst move may have been his desperate effort to
match the inclusive approach of the Democrats and Republicans by
picking a Los Angeles woman named Ezola Foster, who happens to be
African American, as his running mate. It was a shockingly
frivolous selection of a person with not a single qualification to
be president, let alone vice president. Based on that sample of his
political judgment, he doesn't deserve even the 1 percent support.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan chose Foster, a conservative activist and typing
teacher who is a former member of the far-right John Birch Society.
According to the Los Angeles Times, she collected workers'
compensation payments for nearly a year for a mental disorder she
now says she never had. She has never held an elected public
office.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Buchanan has never held an elected office either. His
basic qualification for the presidency is having a combative,
conservative, motor mouth. And taxpayers are supposed to reward
that with $12.6 million earned by a party that no longer exists in
any responsible form?
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin, of course, is no better. He's never held public office
either. We just don't know him as well.
</P>
<P>
   A political plague on both their heads, and on their party, and
on the FEC if it doesn't keep that $12.6 million out of their
greedy, undeserving hands.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
