</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7577 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ARTHOUSE-FILMS-2NDTAK     08-31 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTHOUSE-FILMS-2NDTAKE(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
 
Undated: sexual games.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood would probably never make a movie like ``Chuck and
Buck,'' because it would be considered too threatening to a young
male audience. But if by any chance it did, the story would surely
end in a murder. ``Chuck and Buck,'' while not literally
believable, is more tender-hearted. Reminiscent in some ways of
Todd Solondz's subversive family satire ``Happiness,'' it is really
a fable of how we all carry our childhood within us, whether or not
we admit it. Mike White's portrayal of the creepy, pathetic,
lollipop-addicted Buck is the stunt performance of the year,
comparable in virtuosity to that of Hilary Swank as a transgender
murder victim in ``Boys Don't Cry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tao of Steve'' is a witty, lighthearted portrait of an
extremely overweight, improbably successful womanizer (Donal Logue)
whose technique of seduction involves putting a distorted Buddhism
into action. A Hollywood version of the same idea would probably
star a Chris Farley type and be an extended, offensive fat joke.
</P>
<P>
   One alternative niche that American independent cinema is doing
a good job filling is the market for camp. ``Psycho Beach Party''
translates to the screen Charles Busch's uproarious drag theatrical
spoof of the ``Gidget'' and ``Beach Party'' films (and the seething
subtexts under their squeaky-clean surfaces). Margaret Cho's
concert film, ``I'm the One That I Want,'' is a hilarious,
autobiographical cri de coeur from this Korean-American comedian
that deals pungently with her devastating experience of being
racially stereotyped on network television.
</P>
<P>
   Finally there is John Waters' witty but not howlingly funny
comedy, ``Cecil B. DeMented,'' in which a cult of cinematic
terrorists kidnap a Hollywood star (Melanie Griffith) and force her
to appear in their cinema verite guerrilla attacks on movie
theaters. Waters' movie inadvertently exemplifies the plight of the
art films that it pretends to champion so ardently. But its
terrorists' movie aesthetics are so stringent that, as the critic
Anthony Lane astutely pointed out, the enemy isn't only Hollywood
and philistinism but the movie audience itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cecil B. DeMented'' unwittingly points toward the basic shift
in popular culture at the turn of the millennium, as the vision of
humanity evoked by movies, music and television evolves from one
rooted in psychology to one more anchored in biotechnology.  &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   On fronts ranging from sports medicine to psychotherapy to
fashion, popular art increasingly views people as perfectible
machines who can be improved through drugs, diet, exercise and
surgery. Most of the soul's ailments, this view presupposes, are
physical imbalances that can be corrected.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As millions avail themselves of everything from Prozac to
plastic surgery, this mechanized notion of the human body has begun
to take hold. It seems bound to accelerate. Cloning, genetic
engineering and the unraveling of the human genome tantalize us
with the prospect of extended life and beyond that, perhaps even
immortality, through some hybrid of human and computer.  &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Already digital technology can infinitely replicate sounds and
images without any degradation of quality, and the Internet has
made us figuratively omniscient. With all these humanly engineered
intimations of infinity, who needs God when you can imagine being
God? Until immortality arrives, there's always the gratification of
turning yourself into a pumped-up action figure with 5 percent body
fat or a curvaceous pin-up with fake 42-inch breasts.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For all its promise, the biotech version of human life, in which
all pleasure, even spiritual rapture, is quantifiable, is also
profoundly animalistic. Beneath its progressive agenda, it is pure
Darwinism. From reality television to professional wrestling to the
beat-driven boasts and retorts of hip-hop, to gross-out blockbuster
films, the messages of popular culture are becoming more brutally
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Many have already commented on the sexual crudeness embedded in
many of this summer's Hollywood blockbusters, in which one movie
after another paraded gross-out anal gags that left little to the
imagination. Conventional wisdom says that the appetite for crude
humor is merely a sign of the movie audience's youth, that
dirty-minded adolescents have always been dirty-minded adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   But the popularity of gross-out humor may be more than just a
result of a conjunction between adolescence and the lifting of
taboos. It's arguably another powerful sign of _ and perhaps an
anxious response to _ the mass cultural shift away from spiritual
and psychological ground to the purely physical. Goodbye, Freud,
Marx and Einstein! Hello, lab technician!  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   We don't need those old philosophers. We've been there and done
that. This is the brave new world.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But here, where life is an endless contest and the pressure to
compete nonstop, the climate is a bit chilly. Yet this is what the
majority seems to want. The most popular television shows
(``Survivor,'' ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'') have become
contests, and more and more Hollywood movies are obsessed with
winning, whether the reward is being crowned prom queen or victory
in an ancient Roman arena.  &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   In such a pressurized climate, it's reassuring to be reminded
that for all our polish and technological know-how we are still
messy animals who leave behind a stench. We're all fools stumbling
in our own body waste. The more intense the pressure, the more
explosive the laughter.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the great things about Kieslowski is that he sensed what
was coming. In its opening episode, inspired by the commandment
``Thou shalt have no other God before me,'' a professor's
brilliant, computer-wise young son is torn between the values of
his rationalist father, who doesn't believe in an afterlife, and
those of his devoutly Catholic aunt. When the boy decides he wants
to go skating, his father helps him calculate the thickness of the
ice on the lake to make sure it's safe. But these careful
calculations don't ensure the boy's safety, and he falls through
the ice and drowns.
</P>
<P>
   The story is embellished with surreal touches that suggest the
professor's hubris shattered by the hand of fate. In one touch,
both the father's and son's computers appear to have minds of their
own. After the boy dies, the father arrives home to find his
computer mysteriously turned on. It flashes an enigmatic message in
English: ``I am ready.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1817EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7579 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-BIGBUSRIDE-HNS &LR;      08-31 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGBUSRIDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITY TRIP: INTERNATIONAL CREW TAKES BUS JOURNEY THROUGH THE
AMERICAS 
WITH PHOTO
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DANIEL J. VARGAS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
It's a bit ``Road Rules'' and a smidgen ``Real World.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   And probably a pinch of ``Survivor'' mixed in, too.
</P>
<P>
   No cash is up for grabs, but there will be _ without a doubt _
some drama. That's expected when you cram six twentysomethings into
a double-decker bus for nine months as they travel from northern
Canada to the southern-most tip of South America _ Tierra del
Fuego.
</P>
<P>
   There'll be no running water or lights. No restrooms. No phone.
</P>
<P>
   Dengue and cholera might be on the menu. And there will be
camera crews recording their every move and lane change for a
13-part documentary series to air on television around the world.
</P>
<P>
   One of the adventurous young guns behind the wheel will be
Houstonian Paul Strobl, a 26-year-old world traveler who has the
whole retirement thing backward _ travel now and worry about
finding a desk job later in life.
</P>
<P>
   There is a big difference, though, separating this endeavor,
which is dubbed the ``Big Bus Ride'' and kicks off Sept. 16 in
Winnipeg, Canada, from those ``reality'' TV shows: It's a serious
effort to raise awareness and $300,000 for the international,
nonprofit group War Child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike those shows, we're chosen to work as a team,'' says
Strobl, the lone American on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   War Child is a 7-year-old organization that provides emergency
relief and rehabilitation programs for children both during and
after wars and military conflicts such as in Kosovo and East
Africa. It's still seeking another sponsor for the bus trip that
will hit 18 countries and come through Houston in late October or
early November.
</P>
<P>
   Strobl, who has a degree in anthropology with a minor in Spanish
from Southwest Texas State University, has traveled the globe the
last two years since trading his job at Motorola in Austin for a
life of backpacking and temporary jobs in New Zealand, Australia,
Japan, Hawaii, Canada and England.
</P>
<P>
   While strolling through London, he saw a newspaper ad for the
Big Bus Ride project. Strobl checked out War Child on the Internet
to make sure it was a legitimate group. Like most Americans, he
didn't know about the international organization.
</P>
<P>
   Strobl applied for a spot on the bus on the group's Web site
(www.warchild.org) by writing a short essay. He didn't think
anything would come of it.
</P>
<P>
   Then, War Child contacted him, asked for a resume and more
in-depth answers to the questions on the original application. He
made the first cut to 120 applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Next was a screen test. He made the cut again _ this time Strobl
was among an elite group of 24.
</P>
<P>
   Those finalists were taken to the countryside for a weekend of
team-building exercises. It was rainy and muddy. Some couldn't take
it and left. Strobl hunkered down and made the final six.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love traveling. I'm kind of addicted to it,'' he says.
``It's for a good cause, and I get to go to all these countries _
granted they're not the most posh places. But it seems like it
could be fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think I can make a difference,'' he continues. ``To
have a hands-on experience is something I look forward to. It's not
like sitting behind a desk at work, and you just give some money to
charity.''
</P>
<P>
   Strobl's father, Karl, wasn't surprised when his son called to
say he would be driving a bus along with five other people across
two continents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since he was 8, his lifelong ambition was to travel around the
world,'' he says. ``Here's a kid who gets the best of both worlds:
He gets to travel, and it helps a charity.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl Strobl, a certified public accountant, says his son is
getting a ``world-class education'' as he travels because he
studies the cultures and languages of each country or region he
visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``His problem is that he can't sit still,'' he says. ``He learns
something and says `What's the next challenge?' If he has the
opportunity to travel, more power to him.''
</P>
<P>
   And Dad isn't worried about his youngest son traversing the
Americas either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul does very well on his own,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But how about with five other foreigners packed like sardines on
a nine-month bus trip? Time will tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there will be conflicts,'' Strobl says. ``Nobody _
whether they're married, in a relationship, best friends, or even
siblings _ has to live together 24 hours a day, seven days a week.
That will wear on us. There will be difficult times that we will
have to endure. We may hate each other for a couple days, but
that's all part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Strobl's bus mates will be Catalina Benavides, a 21-year-old
Peruvian student; Sarah Coombes, a 23-year-old British model;
Catherine Aird, a 28-year-old British journalist; Ashley Goldstraw,
a 28-year-old Australian forester; and Stefan Pavlik, a 23-year-old
Austrian computer software representative.
</P>
<P>
   The six will engage in a little friendly competition to raise
the most money, hoping to total at least $300,000. They're still
working on fund-raising ideas, but Strobl is thinking of raffling
off a weeklong ride on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the money raised will go to War Child emergency
projects. The rest will be spent on South and Central American
projects such as land-mine clearance and help for street children
and training in El Salvador and Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   During the trip, each of the six will get a $15-a-day allowance
in Canada and the United States to buy food and toiletries, do
laundry and cover any entertainment. South of the border, they'll
get $12. They cannot dip into their personal funds.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Ellis, events coordinator with War Child in London, says
the organization chose Strobl from a pool of 2,000 applicants
because he speaks Spanish fluently and is a seasoned traveler. The
group wanted individuals who had a sense of humor and valuable
mechanical, first-aid and language skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``During our team-building weekend, he impressed the producers
by working hard at all group activities, and mixed in well with all
the other nationalities,'' she says. ``He is confident in front of
the camera, quite analytical and quite an extrovert in the right
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   The American representative is learning how to drive a 1958
double-decker bus with no power steering and a double-clutch.
</P>
<P>
   ``A double-clutch means you hit it once to go into neutral and
then again for the next gear,'' Strobl explains. ``It hasn't been
too bad, but my biceps are getting a workout.''
</P>
<P>
   The pack of six will sleep upstairs on the bus _ only a few feet
from each other. Their clothes will be housed in a cabinet directly
beneath their beds, but there isn't much room there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be cozy,'' Strobl says.
</P>
<P>
   They will share a small gas stove with two burners and a
personal-size refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   There may be times when they go days without bathing, but that
doesn't bother Strobl. They'll bathe whenever and wherever they can
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so bad if you all smell,'' Strobl jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Although they will see such spectacular sights as the Grand
Canyon and the Andes mountains, they also must travel through
unstable areas such as El Salvador and Guatemala, where land mines
are a danger, and Colombia, where drug trafficking creates its own
peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be some hairy moments there,'' Strobl says.
</P>
<P>
   Enough of the bad thoughts. He's focusing on being a good War
Child ambassador and polishing his fund-raising skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to grab the moment and enjoy it,'' the traveler
says.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true free spirit.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
