<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, Sept. 1 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   ESTATE-TAX (Washington) _ Saying the nation's prosperity should
not be squandered, President Clinton on Thursday vetoed a bill to
repeal the federal estate tax, all but assuring a classic
election-year showdown over tax cuts and how best to spend the
surplus. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT16.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Washington) _ Stepped up debate over the timing
of decisions concerning the national missile defense system. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Louisville, Ky.) _ After watching its presidential nominee
struggle in recent days against the surging campaign of Vice
President Al Gore, the Republican Party plans to broadcast
television commercials on Friday raising sharp questions about
Gore's credibility and mocking his appearance at a Buddhist Temple
fundraiser four years ago. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT6,7.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-RELIGION (Undated) _ When Sen. Joseph Lieberman urged a
greater role for religion in public life in campaign speeches this
week, he touched off a new round in the sharp but unsettled debate
over the role that personal beliefs should play in American
politics. Some critics of Lieberman's remarks, including the
Anti-Defamation League, cast the issue in terms of separation of
church and state, suggesting that the senator had infringed that
principle. But another way to look at what Lieberman said is to ask
whether American culture has changed enough of late so that his
remarks are more acceptable, socially and politically, than before.
A news analysis by Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALL (Nashville, Tenn.) _ Rarely has a leading global
company faced such extraordinary problems _ its best-selling
product blamed for scores of deaths, its biggest customer
undermining its every defense, its stock price plunging along with
consumer confidence, its top executive summoned before an angry
Congress. The company, one of America's most familiar brand names,
is now seen as being one a death watch. On Thursday, Washington
regulators raised the number of deaths attributed to failures of
Firestone tires and Venezuela's consumer agency asked the state
prosecutor to bring criminal charges against Firestone and the Ford
Motor Co., saying the design of Ford's Explorer sport utility
contributed to dozens of deaths in accidents there. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   NY-FOSTER-CARE (New York) _ When a child is troubled, the range
of options available to the privileged _ military-style private
schools, private psychiatric treatment _ are not readily available
to poor parents. So instead, every day, dozens of them stream into
a courtroom in Manhattan designated for so-called voluntary
placements into the foster-care system. These children represent
about 10 percent of the children who enter foster care every year.
Many are teen-agers, either delinquents or emotionally troubled
children in need of mental health services. A look at such
voluntary placements and how they affect parents, the already
flooded city agency and especially the teen-agers themselves. By
Somini Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   EMULEX-ARREST (New York) _ Federal prosecutors on Thursday
charged Mark S. Jakob, a 23-year-old California man, with
securities fraud in last week's hoax on the high-technology company
Emulex, which temporarily cost Emulex shareholders more than $2
billion. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
