<HEADER>
A7587 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      08-31 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINGING FROM MUSIC VIDEOS TO ROCK DOCUMENTARIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Broadcast notes appear at end of review. Time, channel
are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
 BY JULIE SALAMON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   ``I think music videos have really
ruined the art of music,'' says the filmmaker and provocateur
Michael Moore in a special four-part series on the Sundance
Channel's ``Shorts Stop: An Hour of Short Films.'' He is talking
about the crossover between video directors and movie directors.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Before you would hear the song and then you would invent your
own image,'' Moore continues. ``The music video tells you this is
the only way to look at this song. When you hear this song you are
to think of men without shirts jumping in a field of daisies.''
</P>
<P>
   That pretty much describes my own feelings about music videos.
Yes, I know they're important, have altered a generation's visual
imagination and transformed the marketing of music _ and everything
else _ since they have influenced advertising, too. But important
and omnipresent doesn't mean good. McDonald's is everywhere, too.
With rare exceptions video imagery always seems too literal-minded
or tritely symbolic or simply vulgar. The prevailing artistic
wisdom seems to be: Marginal ideas take on weight if shot in slow
motion. If that doesn't work, go superfast.
</P>
<P>
   But I was willing to be convinced otherwise and the Sundance
Channel promised illumination. This month the cable channel is
presenting ``Sonic Cinema,'' films and programs intended to
highlight the way movies and rock 'n' roll overlap. The seven
feature documentaries about rock performers include ``Gimme
Shelter,'' the Maysles Brothers' brilliant concert film about the
Rolling Stones' free _ and ultimately tragic _ concert at Altamont
Speedway in December 1969 (it's also currently playing at the Film
Forum).
</P>
<P>
   The ``Shorts Stop'' segments, which begin this Sunday, aim to
show that music videos are related to the rock documentary, at
least in spirit. So these programs feature the work of independent
filmmakers _ including Moore, despite his antivideo stance _ who
have crossed over in both directions.
</P>
<P>
   The series host, Mark Anthony Thompson, talks loftily about
``the cross-pollination of music and cinema'' _ at least as lofty
as a man can be slouching on a couch and wearing sunglasses
(indoors) and orange flip-flops. But the series proves mainly that
interesting imagery distracts from good music and can't elevate
lousy music, and that annoying pictures can actually prove
deafening. You simply tune out.
</P>
<P>
   The best work in the series comes, not surprisingly, from Spike
Jonze, who sprang exuberantly from the video world into film, with
the inventive ``Being John Malkovich'' (and more recently into the
world of politics, with his biographical documentary of Al Gore for
the Democratic convention). His ``Oh So Quiet'' music video for the
Icelandic pop star Bjork, set in a Goodyear tire store, is an
extravagantly produced homage to Hollywood musicals of the 1930s.
Bjork gleefully high-kicks and prances in an orange dress, looking
happy to be in this bright, amusing little spectacle, where the
music and pictures actually seem to have something to do with one
another (even if they don't).
</P>
<P>
   Another film director, Hal Hartley, has created an amusing mock
concert for the English folk singer Beth Orton's ``Stolen Car.''
While singing, Orton slyly assumes ``meaningful'' poses in various
corners of a room, flops on a couch and pretends not to notice the
expressionless assistants sticking microphones in front of her
mouth. She pricks her finger with the thorn of a rose and a drop of
her blood lazily drifts through a glass of water. Hartley has
artfully staged the video in grays and reds, but I'd still rather
listen to Orton's lovely voice with my eyes closed.
</P>
<P>
   As for the pugnacious Moore, director (of ``Roger and Me'') and
television crusader (on ``The Awful Truth'' and ``TV Nation''), he
paired up with a band that could have been named just for him, Rage
Against the Machine. Moore has styled his video as just another of
his impromptu assaults _ this one on the New York Stock Exchange.
As Rage wails outside the exchange, the police arrive. Moore
confronts. The action is intercut with a parody of ``Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire'' No daisy fields, that's for sure.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the opening night program is video as usual. Harmony
Korine, directing ``Sunday'' by Sonic Youth, meets the expectations
set in 1997 by ``Gummo,'' his feature film debut, which Janet
Maslin in The New York Times pronounced ``the worst film of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Later episodes in the ``Sonic Cinema'' series contain some
arresting imagery of Patti Smith's edges, in a video filmed by
Melodie McDaniel, a talented fashion photographer. There is sweet
candor from Mike Mills, a graphic artist and entrepreneur who began
shooting videos only after he had designed record jackets. ``I can
treat it all like an integrated package,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The series also offers Richard Kern, described (accurately) by
the host, Thompson, ``as a downtown, fetishist photographer
filmmaker who deals with a lot of images of bondage and violence.''
By the end, I'd learned this: three minutes can be a very long
time.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES: &QL; 
`SONIC CINEMA'  &QL; 
At 8 p.m. ET Sunday on Sundance Channel &QL; 
Adam Pincus, executive producer; John Bedolis, director and
supervising producer; Marge Doherty, segment producer; Frank Floyd,
editor; Doron Schlair, director of photography. Marc Anthony
Thompson, host. WITH: Bjork, Michael Moore and Beth Orton.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7588 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-SENIORS-COLUMN-$ADV03     08-31 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIORS-COLUMN-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENIORS ROLLING ALONG WITHOUT THE STIGMA OF A WALKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 3)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRED BROCK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In conversations with experts about mobility problems,
especially among the elderly, two themes almost always crop up. One
is that the choices are scant when it comes to devices that help
you get around: you can clomp along with a cane or a walker, or
take to a wheelchair, which limits exercise. Second, many people
who have trouble walking say they are most comfortable pushing a
grocery cart, because it lets them move along with balance and
stability.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there is the social unease that many elderly
people experience when they use assisted-walking devices,
especially ones that make the user feel or look awkward and clumsy.
America, at least the one presented by a youth-obsessed Madison
Avenue, is the land of joggers and rock climbers with little time
or patience for anyone who is older and slower. That is in sharp
contrast to other parts of the world, including Europe, where aging
and its problems are not viewed as something to be hidden or
ashamed of.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Kahn, a co-author of ``Successful Aging'' (Delacorte
Press) and professor emeritus of public health and psychology at
the University of Michigan, says this nation's approach to mobility
problems is characteristically American.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go from walking to motorized devices like electric
wheelchairs and carts, skipping intervening possibilities,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the little-known rollator _ developed in Europe _ and its
proponents, like Nick Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   A rollator looks like a sawed-off grocery cart with fat rubber
wheels, bicycle handle bars and hand brakes. It helps people walk
easily under their own power, over floors, sidewalks and grass. It
even has a seat, in case the user needs to take a rest, and it
folds up for storage in a car or on a plane. Though rarely seen in
the United States, rollators are common in Canada and Scandinavia.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, 39, a former lawyer, saw a picture of a rollator in
1989 and decided to start importing a line of models made by a
Swedish manufacturer, Ahlberg A.B. His Pittsburgh company,
NobleMotion, is the exclusive importer of the Ahlberg rollators,
which sell for $364 to $450; an extra $35 buys an odometer to keep
track of the miles walked. Medicare, he said, usually pays about
$100 toward the cost of a rollator for those who are eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hilary Siebens, associate director of physical medicine and
rehabilitation at Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston, saw one
of Thompson's rollators seven years ago at a conference on strokes
and ordered one on the spot for her patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really allows for functional walking,'' Siebens said.
``Walkers are stop-and-start. With a rollator, patients can get an
immediate sense of freedom.'' Some people can use rollators to get
themselves moving again, and avoid spending up to $20,000 for two
to three weeks of rehabilitative therapy, she said. ``Also, people
are less resistant to a rollator,'' she said, ``because it is
easier to use than a cane or a walker.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite virtually universal positive comments about the
rollator, the last decade has been slow going for Thompson, who
only last year increased his salary to $26,500 from $24,000. An
investor backed out, and Thompson has had trouble spreading the
word about his product, which is among several rollators being sold
in what has been a very small market. But he has aggressively
pressed on, handing out leaflets and giving demonstrations at
grocery stores, malls and conferences. He has reached a point, he
said, where his business is secure, if not booming; he hopes to pay
himself $30,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Although he wants to make money, Thompson also views his efforts
as a ``battle against sedentary habits.'' His company has a Web
site and a toll-free telephone number (www.wheels4walking.com, 800
234-9255).
</P>
<P>
   ``My customers are looking for products to help them,'' he said.
``If you enjoy walking with a grocery cart, here's a grocery cart
that goes on the sidewalk, with hand brakes and a seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who say they have been helped is Maxine Marx, 82, a
self-described ``adorable old lady'' and retired casting director
who is Chico Marx's daughter. She ordered one of Thompson's
rollators several years ago and now uses it to get around her
Manhattan apartment and to take occasional walks in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a godsend,'' she said. ``It saved my life. Otherwise I
would have to use one of those awful walkers. Whenever I see
someone hobbling in the park, I always show them my rollator.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the users are elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Welch, 55, is a project manager for a dot-com start-up in
Houston. Three years ago, he developed severe arthritis and was
unable to work. A year and a half later, he discovered the
rollator.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal when I was disabled for 18 months was to get vertical
and get engaged in work again,'' he said. ``The rollator has helped
me do this.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this country, people have a cultural hang-up about using
assisted-walking devices. So many just sit, or walk very, very
poorly. They would be in much better shape with a rollator.''
</P>
<P>
   Kahn says many studies have shown that that walking and exercise
are crucial to the health and longevity of older people.
</P>
<P>
   The rollator, he said, ``keeps people on the move.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for those with strokes or Parkinson's disease,
because it helps with balance,'' he added. ``A motorized wheelchair
or cart can be a blessing if you have no other choice. But it's too
bad if you go to motorized transportation when you still have the
capacity to walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Kahn, who is 82, doesn't need any assistance for his daily walks
to and from his office or for his trips to a gym three times a
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regular exercise is like religion,'' he said. ```You need it
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
