<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7589 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN01-COX     08-31 1421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In dead heat, Bush campaign appears to be behind
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For George W. Bush _ whose chances of becoming
president vacillate between inevitable and inconceivable _ it's
campaign-trail deja vu, a political summer rerun.
</P>
<P>
   You may have caught this story line during it's earlier run
after surprising losses in the primaries: Bush is a malaprop-prone
guy who hasn't offered enough specifics, ducks debates and perhaps
should jettison the political team that took him this far.
</P>
<P>
   As in the primary season, months of front-running are being
interrupted by weeks of doubt. As Labor Day approaches, the
double-digit leads of polls from primary season until the
Democratic National Convention have evaporated into a statistical
dead heat with Democratic nominee Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Going into tomorrow's traditional _ and artificial _ start of
the fall campaign, the Bush campaign looks something like it did
after Arizona Sen. John McCain stomped him in New Hampshire and
beat him in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new reality is that Bush is on the defensive and Gore has
put him there,'' said University of Texas government professor
Bruce Buchanan, a presidential scholar and longtime Bush observer.
``I didn't think Gore could do it, but somehow he managed to stop
shooting himself in the foot and shake Bush up for the first time
since McCain did it in the New Hampshire and Michigan primaries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The aura of inevitability is gone,'' Buchanan said of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Not if the Bush team can help it. Doubt may reign among
academia, the Sunday morning talkers and conventional wisdom, but
it has no place in the public pronouncements of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are slightly better off than we thought we'd be on Labor
Day. This is going to be a close election. We've said that all
along, `` said Karl Rove, Bush's top strategist. ``The neat thing
is we are fighting on (Gore's) territory rather than him fighting
on ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Fueling the confidence _ real or otherwise _ is the prospect of
victory in states that have not gone Republican in a presidential
election in a long time. For example, Herbert Hoover, in 1928, was
the last Republican to carry West Virginia. Polls indicate Bush has
a shot. Ditto for states like Missouri, Wisconsin, Minnesota, Iowa
and others that haven't gone GOP in awhile.
</P>
<P>
   Rove does the math and has the answer: Bush needs to find about
44 more electoral votes to get over the 270 needed to get the White
House keys. There are lots of places to get those votes, Rove
believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be more than 270, close to 300,'' said Rove.
</P>
<P>
   When they gather to strategize on the second floor in the
downtown office building that houses the headquarters, Bush
advisers work toward reaching out to the two groups of undecided
voters they see making the difference on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   In house, the first group is called ``radical centrists'' or
``radical moderates.'' They are issue-driven, but the issues are
all over the board, some fiscal, some social, some international.
They are weakly aligned with parties.
</P>
<P>
   The other group of undecideds is less issue-driven, more
interested in the nature of the candidate. They want leadership,
credibility and trust.
</P>
<P>
   As issues are fleshed out, the first group of undecideds
diminishes and the second group becomes more important, according
to the Bush campaign theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Gore has a fundamental credibility problem with these
people,'' said Rove, reflecting an attitude highlighted in a
Republican National Committee ad airing in key states.
</P>
<P>
   The ad shows footage of Gore at the now-famous 1996 Buddhist
temple fund-raising event. A woman's voice, complaining about Gore
``reinventing himself'' says ``Who's he going to be today? The Al
Gore who raises campaign money at a Buddhist temple or the one who
now promises campaign finance reform?''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, who has promised an optimistic, uplifting campaign,
going after Gore is a necessary part of the equation. Asked last
week if he could win without negative ads, he said, ``It all
depends on the definition of negative ads.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan believes the Bush campaign's best, perhaps only, hope
is something approaching a personality contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Bush can win a policy argument. He can't
outpromise Gore on anything but tax cuts. His competitive
advantages are bipartisan leadership, likability and the prospect
of change,'' the professor said. ``The goal is to get public
attention focused on these things again, with policy more in the
background.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, Bush adviser Tom Rath believes that's where
Bush wants the campaign to wind up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they come out of the debates it's going to turn from an
issue-driven race to a character race, an ability-to-lead kind of
race. And that's the race they feel the most comfortable about,''
said Rath. ``They eventually believe this will turn into a national
job interview.''
</P>
<P>
   Wherever the campaign is headed, Bush aides want everyone to
believe it is on a course charted long ago and resistant to wild
swings in poll numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, we have a plan,'' said Rove. ``We are executing the
plan. We know we've got a lot of work to do and there are going to
be ups and downs. But I have confidence in the ultimate outcome
because our base is energized. They are going to be standing in
line when the polls open and the other side seems relatively
lukewarm.''
</P>
<P>
   From the outside, some see Rove's confidence as poker-faced
bluster from a man holding a lesser hand after the most recent
shuffle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the Bush camp says they always expected it,'' said
Buchanan. ``But I don't think anybody expected what we see now. For
Bush, a dead heat must feel like 10 points behind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign seems off balance,'' he added. ``Bush seems less
confident on the stump. The malapropism rate has gone back up. The
Gore campaign is driving the policy debate. And they're letting the
argument about debate formats seem like Bush is afraid to debate
Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   An out-of-state Bush adviser in close contact with the campaign
said he believes Rove's confidence is far more sincere than spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the one thing that disquieted them in the last week is the
slippage in Florida,'' the adviser said. ``They think they will get
Florida, but they will have to work harder to hold it than they
thought they would.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida, with 25 electorate votes and Jeb Bush, the candidate's
brother, as governor, is considered a key part of the Bush victory
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is does Bush have a positive and optimistic
agenda that will grab people's attention,'' said a top Bush aide.
``It's a work in progress and we are doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   That confidence is bolstered by internal polls showing that Bush
is selling well in key, swing states. In one of those states,
Bush's lead in the internal poll is in the low single digits among
registered voters. But the lead goes up to low double digits when
the poll is refined to reflect self-identified likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also a pattern in other states we are looking at,'' said
a Bush aide familiar with the numbers. ``We have a nice lead
developing among likely voters. Every bit of evidence is we do
better among likely voters than we do among registered voters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign also takes Labor Day solace in the fact that
he also does better among Electoral College voters than among
popular voters. While the national polls show a tight race
nationwide, the state-by-state polls show Bush ahead in states with
248 of the 270 electoral votes needed for victory. Gore leads in
states with 168 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Bush faithful, it adds up to make-your-reservations
kind of confidence, tempered by the fact that no deposit is
required.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that with all your hard work...George W. Bush will win
in November!'' Marian Miller, president of the National Federation
of Republican Women said in a missive to members last week. ``That
means this January we will witness the inauguration of the first
Republican president in eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller touted inaugural packages offered by Washington hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would be asked to reserve the room prior to the election
with the understanding that, if Governor Bush is not elected, you
can cancel your reservation with no penalty,'' Miller added.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
