<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTAMINATED-DENTAL-WATER-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTAMINATED DENTAL WATER UNDER SCRUTINY  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MONDAY, SEPT. 4, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By DIANE MARTINDALE   
 Copyright 2000 New Scientist/RBI Magazines Ltd.   
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oral water sprays used by dentists contain levels of some
bacteria that could kill vulnerable patients, government
researchers have discovered.
</P>
<P>
   They found that levels of opportunistic pathogens exceeded
English drinking water safety limits in 52 out of 55 water samples
taken from 21 dental surgeries in the southwest of England.
</P>
<P>
   This means people with weakened immune systems, such as cancer
patients and those with HIV infection, are at risk, the researchers
warn. James Walker of the Center for Applied Microbiology and
Research at Porton Down and his team found several types of
opportunistic pathogens in many of the dental unit waterlines
tested, including species of Mycobacterium and Legionella _ both of
which can cause life-threatening pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   David Turner of the British Dental Association admitted:
``People with compromised immune systems should worry.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also isolated oral streptoccoci in 10 percent of
the samples. Since the bacteria is only found in the mouth, it is
most likely that it was sucked back into the tools and into the
waterlines during dental procedures. Robert Staat of the University
of Louisville's school of dentistry has also found oral
streptococci in dental unit waterlines. ``This is like sharing
spit,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, most of the bacteria breeding in these waterlines
occur naturally in the environment and pose little threat to most
people. Even so, healthy patients shouldn't be exposed to these
levels of bacteria when they are at a healthcare facility, argues
Hugh Pennington, a microbiologist at the University of Aberdeen.
``I wouldn't want to have these in my mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker's team found levels of bacteria between five and 1200
times higher than the permitted 2500 microbes per teaspoon of
water. Some of the highest bacterial counts came from dental unit
waterlines that were either supplied with bottled water or were
recently sanitized. This casts doubt on the effectiveness of
recommendations by the British Dental Association and its U.S.
counterpart, the American Dental Association, that surgeries should
use bottled water and disinfectants to reduce the risk of bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   The ADA said that similar studies carried out in several U.S.
cities revealed bacterial counts that surpass its own safety
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Dentists in both the United States and Britain are advised to
use sterile water for immune-compromised patients and those
receiving surgery where the gumline is cut. But both the American
and British Dental Associations admit it's not clear how strictly
this advice is followed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the millions of people who visit a dentist each year,
contaminated dental water was blamed for only a handful of
infections. Although some patients died, the link to dental water
was never proved.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science and
technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
