r a BC-EFFECTIVE-ANTIVENOM-D     08-31 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EFFECTIVE-ANTIVENOM-DEVELOPMENT-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNA TECHNOLOGY PROVIDES EFFECTIVE ANTIVENOM  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MONDAY, SEPT. 4, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By ANIL ANANTHASWAMY  
 Copyright 2000 New Scientist/RBI Magazines Ltd.  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Safer, cheaper and more effective snake antivenom may soon be
made using DNA technology. The development could help overcome an
imminent shortage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a crisis in antivenom production worldwide,
particularly in Africa. The traditional manufacturers are closing
down for economic reasons,'' says David Warrell of Oxford
University.
</P>
<P>
   Antivenom is still made by a century-old method. Animals, mainly
horses, are injected with increasing levels of venom. The
antibodies they produce are then extracted and purified. But such
antiserum has serious shortcomings. Many of the antibodies it
contains are useless because they target harmless components of the
venom, and it can also cause nasty side effects such as
anaphylactic shock or serum sickness.
</P>
<P>
   These problems can be overcome by injecting animals with DNA
rather than the venom itself, say Rob Harrison and his colleagues
at the Liverpool School of Tropical Medicine in England. ``Our
effort is focused on generating antibodies specific to the toxic
venom components,'' Harrison says.
</P>
<P>
   To show this approach works, Harrison's team took the gene for
jararhagin, a deadly enzyme in the venom of the Brazilian pit viper
(Bothrops jararaca) that causes hemorrhaging. They shot microscopic
gold beads coated with this gene into the skin of mice. The mice
responded by generating antibodies to the enzyme that their cells
made from the gene. Although these antibodies targeted only a
single venom component, they neutralized over 70 percent of the
hemorrhagic activity of the whole venom, says Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   The group is now starting to develop antivenom for the Echis
genus of snakes, or carpet vipers. ``This snake is responsible for
more deaths than any other snake in the world,'' says Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to inject venom genes into genetically modified mice
whose immune systems produce human-type antibodies. The
antibody-producing B cells will then be extracted and fused with
immortal cells, providing a potentially unlimited supply of
antivenom without any further use of animals. Since the antivenom
will consist of human antibodies, says Harrison, it shouldn't have
the harmful side effects of conventional antiserum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a rational way to make antivenom,'' says David
Weiner, of the University of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia. ``It's
very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science and
technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
