<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7595 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-GASOUTHERN0901-CO     08-31 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GASOUTHERN0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Erks dream fuels growth at Georgia Southern
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATESBORO, Ga. _ Two practice fields sit adjacent to each other
near a creek that has become a part of Georgia Southern's football
lore.
</P>
<P>
   About 4 o'clock most late-summer afternoons, Statesboro's
best-known and most-celebrated resident parks near the field where
the Eagles' defensive team practices and sits on the tailgate of
his white jeep.
</P>
<P>
   After a second hip-replacement surgery about a month ago, Erk
Russell has had to take a break from the four or five rounds of
golf he used to play each week. Russell is 74 now and needs a
walking cane to get around, but, in these parts, Russell remains
the most powerful force around.
</P>
<P>
   With Russell's winning football program as the catalyst, the
university and its surrounding community has gone through
eye-popping growth. ``I came here in January of '81, and Erk came
in July of that year,'' said Bucky Wagner, the former Georgia
Southern athletics director. Wagner had pursued Russell
relentlessly until he finally agreed to take the job as football
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were only about 6,000 students here then,'' Wagner said.
``But after we won the first (1-AA) national title in '85, we
started to add about 1,000 students a year until we hit 14,000 and
tapered off.''
</P>
<P>
   When Russell put his first team on the field at the local high
school in 1982, Statesboro's population was 12,423, and Bulloch
County's was 35,783. As Erk sat watching his son Rusty coordinate
the Eagles defense in preparation for Saturday's game against
Georgia, Statesboro was up to 21,958 and the county 51,562.
</P>
<P>
   The increase and Russell's presence are not coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it kind of goes to show you that the university is the
center of things, and, when it grows, it affects the community and
industry the same way,'' said Russell, who retired as a coach after
leading the Eagles to their third I-AA national title in 1989.
``Football gave us marketing. Ain't no way we could've had money to
buy what it brought in publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Wagner, now an associate professor of sports
management at the university, an estimated $125 million has been
spent on capital improvement at the state-supported school since
the football team won consecutive national titles in 1985 and 1986.
That number does not include the cost of 18,000-seat Paulson
Stadium, which was built in 1984 with private funds. Financing is
in place for a $24 million nursing-physics facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like we've added another campus,'' Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, an assistant on Vince Dooley's staff for 17 years at
Georgia, left Athens seven months after the Bulldogs won the 1980
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like, as far I was concerned, I had one of the best
coaching jobs in the country,'' he said. ``But there was something
different and exciting (about starting a football program at
Georgia Southern), especially about coming to a place where you're
starting over. Both of my boys were out of school, so it was just
my bride and I, and I really felt like I didn't have that much to
lose. So why not give it a shot?''
</P>
<P>
   That shot made an impact unequaled in the annals of 1-AA sports.
It ignited a winning tradition that now includes five national
championships. The Eagles won their latest one last season under
Paul Johnson, a member of Russell's staff in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive-line coach John Pate also was a member of Russell's
staff. Pate recalled what made it special then.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a great learning experience,'' said Pate, who left the
school in 1989 but returned as a member of Johnson's staff in 1997.
``Not only did we get a chance to learn X's and O's from the
master, but he mentored us and put us in a position to go out and
coach them. . . . With the old man here back then, it was like
being in Camelot.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner still lists luring Russell to Statesboro as his greatest
accomplishment. On Saturday, Russell will be among the horde of
spectators in Sanford Stadium. He missed the first game played
between Georgia and Georgia Southern in 1992 because of his first
hip-replacement surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Based largely on what he has observed from his tailgating spot
near Beautiful Eagle Creek, Russell is not too optimistic about
Georgia Southern's chances Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``First you look out there and you say, 'How many of these
people did the University of Georgia offer a scholarship' ''
Russell said. ``You probably don't come up with a large number
there. Secondly, how many of these guys could make Georgia's first
or second team on offense or defense? You don't come with a very
large number.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they've got 85 scholarships and we've got 63. When you
play four quarters, depth is sometimes a determining factor. You
keep talking realistically, it shapes up as no contest. But we
ain't gonna play on paper. We're going play out there on turf.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
