<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7602 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-DEBIT-CARD-DRAWBACKS-     08-31 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBIT-CARD-DRAWBACKS-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADDING UP THE DRAWBACKS OF A CREDIT CARD THAT ISN'T 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also DEBIT-CARDS-STUDENTS) 
(For release Sunday, Sept. 3) 
 By NANCY LLOYD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   They look like credit cards, are accepted in almost as many
places, and are now carried by tens of millions of consumers. But
debit cards can turn out to be much more expensive to use for any
consumer, not just a financial novice like a student. Here are some
of debit cards' little-known drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   _Higher prices for merchandise. When you pay with a debit card,
some merchants add a fee similar to an ATM surcharge _ a fact that
may not be posted in the store. Such surcharges are almost never
imposed on credit card purchases.
</P>
<P>
   _Holds on your checking account. &UR;  &LR; When you present a debit card
to initiate a purchase whose amount is not known at the outset _
like checking in at a hotel, renting a car or even filling the gas
tank _ the merchant typically places a hold on your account for an
amount much greater than you are likely to wind up spending. Such
holds may take days to be cleared, and checks may bounce as a
result, even though the money to cover them is in the account _ and
you may be assessed returned-check charges that can be difficult to
reverse.
</P>
<P>
   _No proof of creditworthiness. Car rental companies may let you
make a reservation and pay the bill with a debit card but still
insist that you produce a credit card with adequate available
credit as security before they release a car to you.
</P>
<P>
   _Less leverage in disputes with merchants. If you use a credit
card to order merchandise that never arrives or is defective,
federal law offers strong protections, letting you refuse to pay
until the dispute is settled. Not so with debit cards, which
transfer your money to the merchant almost immediately, as if you
had paid in cash.
</P>
<P>
   _Less protection against theft. Federal law limits a consumer's
maximum liability for others' fraudulent use of a credit card or
card number to $50, provided that the bank is notified of the
card's loss or theft within 60 days. But for a debit card, under
federal law, consumers must report the theft or loss within two
business days to limit the loss to $50. After that, the potential
loss rises to $500, and after 60 days there is no cap _ every penny
in the account and any linked credit line are at risk. Some banks
promise to extend to 60 days the reporting period for the $50 cap,
but the promise has no force of law and can be withdrawn without
notice.
</P>
<P>
   _Salt-in-the-wound fees and problems. &UR;  &LR; Even if you report a
debit-card theft in time to be eligible, the $50 loss limit applies
only to money removed from your account by the thief's actions. You
can still be assessed with fees if the theft drives your balance
below your account's no-fee minimum or causes checks that you have
written to bounce, and those bounced checks can damage your credit
standing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
