<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-CARDIO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIUM REPORTS ADVANCE IN CARDIO TREATMENT DEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NAOMI AOKI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Millennium Pharmaceuticals Inc. has discovered a potential new
target for treating cardiovascular disease, advancing its effort
with partner Eli Lilly &AMP; Co. to develop drugs for the treatment of
congestive heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   Although research is at an early stage, the Cambridge, Mass.
biotechnology company described the discovery Thursday as
significant because the potential target is the first known to be
related to angiotensin-converting enzyme, or ACE, a catalyst in
hypertension and congestive heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   The newly identified gene, angiotensin-converting enzyme-related
carboxypeptidase, or ACE2, is similar in structure to ACE.
Millennium scientists believe they likely evolved from the same
parent gene and serve similar functions in the body.
</P>
<P>
   ACE, found throughout the body, produces a substance known as
angiotensin II that narrows blood vessels, forcing the heart to
work harder to pump blood through the smaller channels. The class
of drugs known as ACE inhibitors blocks the production of
angiotensin II, lowering blood pressure and reducing the risk of
heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ACE, however, ACE2 is found only in the heart, kidneys,
and testes. It produces an angiotensin peptide whose function is
not yet known. And Millennium scientists said it does not respond
to the ACE inhibitor drugs currently on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it is only found in the heart and kidneys, it provides
an opportunity to develop more specific therapies with potentially
fewer side effects,'' said Dr. Roger Breitbart, senior director of
cardiovascular biology at Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street embraced the news. After the findings were reported
in Circulation Research, a publication of the American Heart
Association, the company's stock shot up $13.13 to close at $143.13
in heavy trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market. More than 2.8 million
shares traded hands, a million more than the daily average.
</P>
<P>
   Even as investment analysts warned that the discovery might
never lead to a drug, they hailed it as more evidence of
Millennium's strong position in the genomics area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only one example of many that Millennium can point to
where they're succeeding at finding new drug targets,'' said
Carolyn Pratt, biotechnology analyst in Needham &AMP; Co.'s Boston
office. ``They just keep doing this over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Millennium scientists found ACE2 while sifting through 19,000
gene sequences found in biopsies of human hearts suffering from
heart failure. The gene caught the scientists' attention, Breitbart
said, because of its similarities to ACE. After more study, they
realized it was a good potential target for new drugs because of
its differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it responded to the ACE inhibitors, we wouldn't pursue this
project,'' Breitbart said. ``It's exciting because it gives us
another potential way to treat cardiovascular disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardiovascular disease is one of the largest drug markets in the
United States. Almost 60 million Americans suffer from one or more
types of cardiovascular disease according to the American Heart
Association. Of those, about 4.6 million suffer from congestive
heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium and Eli Lilly partnered in 1995 to isolate genes that
cause artherosclerosis, a type of heart disease in which the
arteries are blocked by fatty deposits, but later changed the focus
to congestive heart failure. Now that Millennium has identified
ACE2 as a potential target, Eli Lilly will play a bigger role in
the research efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have to figure out exactly what role ACE2 plays in
congestive heart failure and then turn that knowledge into an
effective drug. Even if all goes well, it would be years before a
product is available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an exciting new target,'' said Robert W. Grupp, a
spokesman for Eli Lilly. ``Now, the collaborative research to
develop a drug begins in earnest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
