<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTRARY-COLUMN-LABOR-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE CONTRARY: WRITING FOR A DIFFERENT KIND OF UNION LABEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 3) 
 By DANIEL AKST    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last month, just in time for Labor Day, I did something I
haven't done since working my way through college as a doorman. I
joined a union.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, it's a union of writers _ even though, in my
experience, every writers' organization is either an oxymoron or a
shambles. But whether writers have a union, or whether that union
includes me, isn't the point. What matters far more is the unusual
nature of the group I joined, the National Writers Union; it could
offer an interesting model for other unions hoping for redemption
from the long twilight of irrelevance to which they have helped to
consign themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In some very important ways, the National Writers Union is the
union of the future, and the apparatchiks who run more
old-fashioned unions had better take notice. The United Auto
Workers did just that eight years ago, when it took in the writers'
union as one of its locals. The UAW, though usually identified with
the traditional assembly line, has been in the forefront of
organizing nontraditional workers, many of them more familiar with
Socrates than socket wrenches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a growing field,'' said Phil Wheeler, director of the
UAW's northeast region. Of the writers' union, he said, ``We felt
we could learn from them, and we could be very helpful to them.''
</P>
<P>
   (I must say I feel pretty macho belonging to what is now Local
1981 of the UAW, and I look forward to a nice jacket or at least a
logo-bedecked baseball cap.)
</P>
<P>
   Since affiliating with the UAW, the writers' union has grown to
6,300 members from roughly 2,500, according to its president,
Jonathan Tasini. Admittedly, those are still small numbers in a big
country.
</P>
<P>
   But the union may be on to something. It represents
private-sector knowledge workers, precisely the kind of people whom
traditional unions have had little success in trying to organize.
And the writer-members are largely self-employed, which means that
the union does its work without benefit of the National Labor
Relations Board. Just about all these workers use computers, and
many have electronic-rights issues. They usually have to buy their
own health insurance. And a big proportion of them are women.
</P>
<P>
   In short, they're the work force of tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   That is what makes the union so interesting. The first Labor Day
of the 21st century, after all, finds American unions in general
representing fewer than 10 percent of all private-sector workers
and struggling to keep up with the changing nature of work and the
work force. Against so gloomy a backdrop, the writers' union, at
least, understands the problem _ and is growing.
</P>
<P>
   The organization has also foresworn the basic tactic of many
other unions, which try to force higher pay and benefits for their
members by turning the work force into a cartel, the way unions of
screen writers and other workers (industrial and otherwise) have
done. Tasini acknowledged that his union lacked the power to do
that, and anyhow, he'd prefer to have a union that people actually
want to join, instead of one seen merely as an overbearing gobbler
of dues.
</P>
<P>
   The union's battle to gain electronic reprint rights for its
members has attracted the most attention. Personally, I doubt that
most writers will see big money from electronic rights anytime
soon. But someday we might, and meanwhile even nickels and dimes
from the millions of Internet users out there can start adding up
to worthwhile amounts.
</P>
<P>
   To make it easier for publishers to comply, the union has set up
a Publication Rights Clearinghouse, which will administer a
licensing and royalty program akin to the ones run by Ascap and BMI
in the music industry. One online publisher, Steven Brill's new
Contentville.com, has already signed a license agreement giving
writers (through the clearinghouse) 30 percent of the fee it
receives when an article is downloaded, or about 90 cents of a
typical charge of $3 an article.
</P>
<P>
   The union also maintains a database of job openings, offers
group rates on medical insurance and is the only place I can think
of where individual writers can find affordable, comprehensive
libel insurance.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that the National Writers Union is some kind
of latter-day workers' paradise. The jobs in its database do not
look very appealing, and there is an odor of political correctness
about the organization's Web site _ a report from the inevitable
diversity committee is signed ``In Solidarity.'' Moreover, it makes
me uncomfortable professionally to belong to an organization that
lobbies members of Congress for help, as it has in its e-rights
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, publishers try to influence policy in their favor,
so why should an organization of writers disarm unilaterally? And I
belong to other groups with which I don't always agree, from the
Democratic Party to the American Automobile Association. Heck, I'm
a member of Sam's Club.
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. I wonder if they give any kind of union discount.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1846EDT &QL; 
