<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cheney talks up Bush schools policy
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ Maybe Dick Cheney didn't see the ``Dandy
Diners'' bulletin board with 18 names and construction paper
fishes.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe he didn't notice the book ``Life of a Sun Flower.''
</P>
<P>
   In the tiny cafeteria of Highlands Elementary School, the
Republican candidate for vice president looked out at his fourth
and fifth grade audience, congratulated them on going from a ``D''
school to an ``A'' school and then talked about school construction
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   After noting that America needs to ``create enough facilities to
be able to assimilate and accommodate all the people in school
these days,'' the former defense secretary explained the idea that
he and Texas Gov. George Bush are promoting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under current law, states are allowed to issue a certain
number of tax exempt bonds for private contractors to build public
facilities such as airports and low income housing. However public
school construction is not today allowed to use these special
bonds. We want to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   If the kids wanted to change speakers, they didn't let on. The
students and faculty were thrilled to have all the attention that
comes with having a national candidate drop by. Secret Service,
television cameras and time off from school.
</P>
<P>
   Three Highland students got special recognition. Fourth-grader
Jackie Soto and fifth-graders Jasmine Alexander and Jordan Fisher
got rewarded for being good students by getting a chance to meet
Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   He congratulated them on their good work, and they each shyly
smiled as news cameras took their pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``America has the best kids in the world so why shouldn't we
have the very best schools in the world?'' Cheney said
</P>
<P>
   Education is considered a key issue this year. Both Bush and
Cheney were spending the day visiting schools. Cheney began his day
at a Fort Lauderdale school after a day of controversy there about
his visit.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the Broward County School Board objected to
allowing Cheney to use Croissant Park Elementary School for a
campaign stop. School Superintendent Frank Till refused to stop the
visit saying to do so at the last minute would be an embarrassment
to Broward schools.
</P>
<P>
   While Cheney was in Florida. Gov. Jeb Bush was in California
campaigning for his older brother. The topic there _ education.
</P>
<P>
   briancrowley(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
