<HEADLINE>
U.S. BUSINESS BRIEFS FOR AUG. 31 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c. 2000 Bridge News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cisco to buy PixStream for $369 mln in stock
</P>
<P>
   By BridgeNews
</P>
<P>
   San Jose, Calif.--Aug. 31--Cisco Systems Inc., the world's
largest network equipment maker, said Thursday that it agreed to
pay about $369 million in stock for PixStream Inc., a maker of
products that enable digital video over networks.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco said the acquisition, seen closing in the first quarter of
2001, will accelerate broadband deployments and build networks that
enable service providers to offer data, voice and video services.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems makes products that link networks and enhance the
Internet, including products like routers and switches. It also
makes dial-up access servers and network management software.
</P>
<P>
   Privately held PixStream develops, manufactures and markets
products that enable network service providers and enterprises to
distribute and manage digital video.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the San Jose, Calif.-based Cisco Systems rose $1.75,
or 2.63 percent, to $68.3125 on the Nasdaq stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Onyx to buy Waste Management's Hong Kong, Mexico assets
</P>
<P>
   By BridgeNews
</P>
<P>
   Houston, Texas--Aug. 31--Waste Management Inc. said Thursday
that it agreed agreed to sell its Hong Kong waste services
operations, its hazardous waste facility in Mexico and its 49
percent interest in Advanced Environmental Services LLC to Onyx for
about $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   Onyx is the waste services subsidiary of Vivendi Environnement
S.A.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the divestitures are a part of Waste
Management's strategy to re-focus on its North American waste
operations. The company plans the sale of other international
businesses, as well as non-core and non-integrated solid waste
assets in North America.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that it intends to use the proceeds to reduce
debt and to make acquisitions of solid waste businesses in North
America.
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management, a provider of waste management services, has a
network of landfills and collection operations, as well as waste
transfer, disposal and recycling services.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Houston, Texas-based Waste Management rose 18.75 cents
to $19.25 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   GE Medical forms $1 bln infotech firm for hospitals
</P>
<P>
   By BridgeNews
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee, Wis--Aug. 31--GE Medical Systems said Thursday it has
formed a $1 billion global information technology company that will
provide data systems to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The new unit, GE Medical Systems Information Technologies, will
sell information systems that will allow hospitals and healthcare
providers to better manage medical data and images.
</P>
<P>
   GE Medical has named Greg Lucier, former vice president and
general manager of GE Medical Systems' global services, as
president and chief executive of the new company.
</P>
<P>
   GE Medical Systems, a subsidiary of General Electric Co., offers
healthcare information systems, patient monitoring systems and
conventional and digital X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Canada to sell KG Telecom stake for C$790 mln
</P>
<P>
   By BridgeNews
</P>
<P>
   Montreal, Quebec--Aug. 31--Telecommunications service provider
Bell Canada International Inc. said Thursday it has agreed to sell
its 20 percent stake in Taiwan's personal communication services
provider KG Telecom to Taiwan Cement Corp. for around C$790
million.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Canada said it would receive NT$53, or C$2.526510, for each
KG Telecom share. Bell Canada, which expects to receive an initial
payment of about C$120 million in September and the rest by Feb.
28, 2001, said the divestiture is in line with its strategy of
focusing on Latin American markets.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Canada, owned 74 percent by Canada's largest
telecommunications firm BCE Inc., offers telecommunications
services in Latin America and the Asia-Pacific region and has more
than 6.3 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   KG Telecom provides mobile voice and data services to more than
1.7 million subscribers in Taiwan. Taiwan Cement Corp. is KG
Telecom's largest shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the Montreal, Quebec-based Bell Canada jumped C$2.15,
or 5.64 percent, to $40.25 on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Penton Media to buy Duke Communications
</P>
<P>
   By BridgeNews
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland, Ohio--Aug. 31--Diversified business media firm Penton
Media Inc. said Thursday that it has agreed to acquire privately
held publishing firm Duke Communications International. Financial
terms of the deal were not mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Penton Media said that it plans to use Duke's Brands to offer a
larger in-person media product. Penton Media, which expects to
close the deal by the end of September, said Duke would become part
of Penton's Advanced Technology Media division and would continue
to operate from Loveland, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Penton Media publishes 50 trade magazines covering industries
from construction to the Internet, produces more than 100 trade
shows and conferences, and maintains around 90 Web sites. Loveland,
Colo.-based Duke Communications publishes five magazines in the
U.S. and one title in the U.K.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the Cleveland, Ohio-based Penton Media rose 6 cents to
$31.66 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Electronics for Imaging to buy Splash for $146 mln
</P>
<P>
   By BridgeNews
</P>
<P>
   Foster City, Calif.--Aug. 31--Electronics For Imaging Inc. said
Thursday that it has agreed to acquire color server marketer Splash
Technology holdings Inc. for $146 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the Sunnyvale, Calif.-based Splash jumped $2.3125, or
32 percent, to $9.3593, while shares of Electronics For Imaging
dropped $1.6250, or 5.59 percent, to $27.4375 on the Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Imaging, which makes printer connectivity software,
said that it would pay $10 for each Splash share, which is a 20
percent premium over Splash's Wednesday close of $7.0625. This buy
is part of its plan to expand presence in all segments of the color
market, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Splash said that it expects 2000 revenue growth to
be flat due to increased focus on inventory levels at one of its
key channel partners, as well as a delay in the launch of a new
product line.
</P>
<P>
   Foster City, Calif.-based Electronics For Imaging offers
hardware and software that link computer networks to color copiers
and desktop laser printers. Splash sells color servers and software
that connect desktop computers to digital color laser copiers.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer to buy Sybron Chemicals for $202 mln in cash
</P>
<P>
   By BridgeNews
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh, Pa.--Aug. 31--Bayer Corporation, the U.S. subsidiary
of Germany's pharmaceutical giant Bayer AG, announced late
Wednesday that it agreed buy U.S. polymer and specialty chemical
producer Sybron Chemicals Inc. for around $202 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the Birmingham, N.J.-based Sybron Chemicals rose
$3.75, or 12.20 percent to $34.50 on the New York Stock Exchange
Thursday. Bayer's $35 per share offer price is a 14 percent premium
to the Sybron's Wednesday closing price of $30.75 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The Sybron acquisition gives Bayer's Coatings and Colorants
Business Group and its Specialty Products Business Group access to
new technologies and products, the company said. The acquisition is
expected to provide Bayer an entry into the powder coating raw
materials market.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer makes pharmaceuticals, polyurethanes, engineering
plastics, agricultural chemicals, medical diagnostic equipment,
fibers, additives, rubber, industrial chemicals, and coatings and
colorants.
</P>
<P>
   Sybron Chemicals makes products in textile chemicals,
environmental intermediates, and polymer intermediates. Sybron saw
sales of $147.13 million during the first half year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ViaLink jumps 19 percent on PepsiCo contract
</P>
<P>
   By BridgeNews
</P>
<P>
   Edmond, Okla.--Aug. 31--Shares of e-commerce firm viaLink Co.
rose 19 percent Thursday after soft-drink maker PepsiCo Inc. said
it will use viaLink's services.
</P>
<P>
   Frito-Lay will be the first enterprise to utilize viaLink's
syncLink service to synchronize item, price and promotion
information with its trading partners. The company said that
Frito-Lay also agreed to market viaLink's services to its major
retail accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ViaLink will also provide its services to Pepsi-Cola Co. and
Tropicana Products Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ViaLink's subscription-based, business-to-business e-commerce
services enable consumer packaged goods and grocery industry
participants to manage their supply chain information.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the Edmond, Okla.-based viaLink rose $1.656250 to
$9.968750 on the Nasdaq Stock Market while shares of the Purchase,
N.Y.-based PepsiCo rose 68 cents, or 1.64 percent to $42.6250 on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Service Corp sells part of loan portfolio for $95 mln
</P>
<P>
   By BridgeNews
</P>
<P>
   Houston, Texas--Aug. 31--Service Corporation International, the
world's largest funeral and cemetery firm, said Thursday it agreed
to sell part of its Provident Services loan portfolio to Dallas,
Texas-based Bellwether Investment Corp. for $95 million.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the Houston, Texas-based Service Corporation rose
18.75 cents, or 8.82 percent, to $2.3125 on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Services Corporation said that it would use the funds from the
sale of its lending subsidiary to reduce debt. The firm would
continue to hold and collect interest and principal payments on the
remaining portion of the Provident portfolio estimated to have a
face value of about $57 million.
</P>
<P>
   Services Corporation, which has around 4,500 funeral homes,
cemeteries, and crematoria, offers services that include
embalmment, burial, cremation and prearranged funeral services.
</P>
<P>
   FBI charges Michael Pitelis in Parametric extortion case
</P>
<P>
   By BridgeNews
</P>
<P>
   Boston--Aug. 31--The Federal Bureau of Investigation said
Thursday that computer consultant Michael Pitelis has been indicted
for attempting to extort more than $1.5 million from computer
software company, Parametric Technology Corp.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Pitelis faces a maximum sentence of 20 years in
prison and a $250,000 fine for each count.
</P>
<P>
   Pitelis, who was arrested last week, allegedly obtained
Parametric Technology Corp.'s secret proprietary information and
threatened to publish it on the Internet if the company did not pay
him. On Aug. 11, Pitelis demanded $400,000 plus $40,000 per month,
before raising it to $1 million and extending to $1.5 million on
Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Parametric Technology received an email Aug. 3, requesting
payment in exchange for not publishing confidential master ``keys''
to its Pro/Engineer software package on the Internet. The keys
allow for the illegal use of Pro/Engineer without paying for it.
</P>
<P>
   While Pitelis was making these threats via e-mail, Special
Agents of the FBI traced the e-mails and arrested Pitelis from
Florida. Waltham, Mass.-based Parametric Technology is a
manufacturer of mechanical computer-aided design and engineering
software.
</P>
<P>
   End
</P>
