<HEADER>
A7615 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-PROSTATE-BENEFIT-BOS &LR;      08-31 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSTATE-BENEFIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS CRITICIZE PROSTATE SCREENING TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE BARNARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Dole, Arnold Palmer and Harry Belafonte have all gone on
television to urge all men over 50 to get tested for prostate
cancer. But the widespread screening advocated by the American
Urologic Association and the American Cancer Society may lead to
more harm than good, two British researchers argue in a paper in
the current Lancet Oncology.
</P>
<P>
   Until a study proves that screening leads to a drop in prostate
cancer deaths, ``the ethics of subjecting symptom-free men to
screening tests is questionable,'' wrote David Neal, a professor at
the School of Surgical Sciences at the University of Newcastle upon
Tyne, and Jenny Donovan, a researcher at the University of
Bristol's Department of Social Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs is the latest salvo in a debate that pits urologists and
radiation oncologists against some family physicians and
preventive-medicine experts, who say the screening catches too many
dormant cancers that would never have become lethal, leading to
unnecessary treatment with side effects that damage quality of
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making an awful lot of men impotent and incontinent,''
said Dennis Fryback, a member of the U.S. Preventive Services
Council, which in 1997 came out against widespread screening.
</P>
<P>
   How Bob Dole fared is a private matter, he added, but what was
his next ad campaign? Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates on the other side are equally passionate. Dr. Robert
Smith, an epidemiologist at the American Cancer Society, said
physicans could ``wait forever for the perfect gold-standard
data.'' But he called that a conservative approach that ignores
signs that screening may be saving lives. For example, he said,
there has been an 11 percent drop in mortality among black men
since 1993 and a 16 percent drop among white men since 1991. And in
one Austrian county where screening was introduced, mortality rates
fell 42 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ideological passion abounds: Advertising campaigns have argued
that embarrassment and secrecy were killing men, and celebrities
from New York Yankees coach Joe Torre and New York mayor Rudy
Giuliani to Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf have been praised for putting a
public face on the disease.
</P>
<P>
   And critics like Fryback, a professor of preventive medicine at
the University of Wisconsin, see prostate screening as another sign
that doctors and drug companies push treatments without regard for
the extra worry and side effects they bring.
</P>
<P>
   But what the debate really reflects is a philosophical dilemma
about how to manage risk, on both an individual and societal level,
said Dr. Michael Barry, who researches prostate disease at
Massachusetts General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In the United Kingdom, which is debating coverage of the
screening under the national health plan, physicians tend to be
more conservative, Barry said, waiting for a study like the one
that showed mammography for women over 50 reduces their chance of
dying of breast cancer by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, he said, the consensus leans toward
screening. The American Cancer Society and the American Urologic
Association both advocate offering screening to men over 50, and to
men over 40 who are African-American or have a close relative
diagnosed with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Men have a 15 percent chance of being diagnosed with prostate
cancer in their lifetime, but only a 3 percent chance of being
killed by it, meaning that many cancers, if left undetected, would
not be lethal, Barry said. At the same time, the most common
treatments _ radiation and surgery _ leave more than 50 percent of
patients suffering from sexual dysfunction and 3 percent to 15
percent with incontinence.
</P>
<P>
   The prostate is a walnut-sized gland that produces seminal
fluid, which transports sperm. It is surrounded by nerves that
control urinary and sexual function. Screening consists of a rectal
exam and an inexpensive blood test that detects prostate specific
antigen, a protein produced in greater quantities by an enlarged or
cancerous prostate. If PSA levels are elevated, a biopsy follows.
</P>
<P>
   Once a cancer is found, said experts on both sides, it is
psychologically difficult for a patient to choose not to have
radiation treatment or surgery -- especially since it is currently
hard to predict which cancers will progress and which will not.
</P>
<P>
   The American Cancer Society estimates that 32,000 men will die
of prostate cancer this year, and that 180,000 new cases will be
diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   The incidence of prostate cancer spiked after screening was
introduced around 1989, and has now fallen below its 1992 peak. In
their paper, Neal and Donovan argue that while drops in mortality
could have been caused by screening that caught cancers at a
treatable stage, they also could simply reflect that more
non-aggressive cancers were caught.
</P>
<P>
   Smith of the American Cancer Society said he is confident that a
cancer-screening trial now being run by the National Cancer
Institute will validate screening. But in the meantime, he said, it
is important that men receive complete information about the risks
of treatment so they can make informed decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a work in progress,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1853EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
