   ``And then I wasn't paying attention much to what they were
saying.''
</P>
<P>
   The shuffle that pushed Kaplan out also dilutes the role of CNN
News Group Chief Executive Tom Johnson and gives more power to
executives from TBS, of which the news group is a unit. Namely, TBS
President Steve Heyer gets more business oversight while TBS
veteran Phil Kent moves to CNN News Group as president. Neither has
been available for interviews. The changes come as parent Time
Warner prepares for a merger with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan said he accepts the decision to restructure, which many
CNN staffers think also is tied to the network's ratings drop this
year of about 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not angry. If I don't fit in, I don't fit in. I'm a big
boy, and I've been in the business a long time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan wrote a statement for the press Tuesday afternoon and
called Jon Scanlon, an old public relations friend in New York. ``I
told him I've got a statement; I don't know how to send it out. I
don't know how to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Every Wednesday, Kaplan has a regular 12:15 p.m. meeting with
his staff, with U.S. bureaus hooked in on speakerphone. Even though
the story of Kaplan's firing had whipped through the newsroom
Tuesday night and been in the next morning's Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, he made the formal announcement. He told them
that ``you don't have to have been at CNN for 20 years to love
it,'' praised the new management team, and ended by saying, ``CNN
is a great network and it's going to stay a great network.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People looked at me like 'Why aren't you angry?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I love CNN. I love these people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The firing came during a tumultuous season for Kaplan. He was
planning convention coverage and getting regular reminders of CNN's
ratings woes when he was told his daughter Robin, 25, was badly
injured in an auto accident this summer in California. Kaplan took
some time off to be with her; now she's with him in Alpharetta.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a very rough eight months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, Kaplan said, he plans to relax, play golf on
his home course and visit friends in Chicago (his hometown), Los
Angeles and London.
</P>
<P>
   His business plans are uncertain. He has 1 1/2 years to go on
his contract and would not say what settlement CNN would make, only
that he doesn't anticipate financial problems. He did not have a
``no-compete'' clause, so he's free to work wherever he wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to stay in television news. Maybe I'll do consulting,
maybe teaching, maybe I'll write.'' He isn't likely to return to a
TV executive position soon, because those would be in New York or
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sell my house,'' he said. ``I love Atlanta and
I expect to stay in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
