<HEADER>
A7636 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELTA0901-COX     08-31 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta carves out e-unit, buys delta.com address
 &HT;    By Nancy Fonti
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines is finally getting the ``-air'' out of
its dot-com.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based carrier has bought the domain name delta.com
from Delta Financial Corp., a Woodbury, N.Y., speciality consumer
finance company. The airline wouldn't say how much it paid, but the
name was purchased July 20, according to Network Solutions, the
national registry of Internet domain names.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has long used the unwieldy delta-air.com address for its
Web site because delta.com was taken when the Internet was in its
infancy.
</P>
<P>
   The airline has already advertised its new address during at
least one Atlanta Braves game and will officially announce it
today. Online customers with delta-air.com bookmarks will be
automatically redirected to delta.com, the airline said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of an effort to promote the Delta brand, the airline
began pursuing delta.com a few months ago because it is easier to
remember and quicker to type, said Vince Caminiti, senior vice
president of e-business. Online bookings at all Web sites accounts
for about 10 percent of Delta's sales.
</P>
<P>
   Cyber-squatting and competition among companies with similar
names has prevented some airlines and other businesses from getting
their first-choice addresses. United Airlines, for instance, only
secured united.com and unitedairlines.com in mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   Delta also on Thursday said it formed a new unit to handle its
electronic-commerce businesses, which include, among other things,
partnerships with and equity investments in Internet companies,
Internet marketing strategies and new products offered through the
airline's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti will head the unit, dubbed e-Delta, which Delta hopes
will generate $150 million in ``annual benefits'' by 2002 through
cost savings and partnerships. Delta reported profit of $1 billion
for the fiscal year ending June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our single point of focus and accountability for our
e-initiatives,'' Caminiti said. ``This will define our overall
e-business strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Delta isn't the first airline to dedicate a unit to its
e-commerce dealings. United created an e-commerce unit in January.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
