<HEADLINE>
STOCK TRADE CLEARING HOUSES FORMULATE PLAN TO SUPPORT
LONDON-FRANKFURT MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE KAPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In a move intended to shore up support for the planned
merger of the London and Frankfurt stock exchanges, the clearing
houses for the two markets introduced a plan Thursday that would
cut settlement costs by 90 percent for certain trades.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers have expressed concern about the potential for
escalating costs should the London and Frankfurt exchanges combine
to form a pan-European bourse, which would be called iX. Winning
the support of brokers for the merger with Deutsche Boerse is
crucial for the London Stock Exchange in its attempts to ward off a
hostile bid from OM Gruppen AB, the Swedish company that runs the
Stockholm stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good workable blueprint,'' Brain Mairs, spokesman for
the Association of Private Client Investment Managers and
Stockbrokers, said of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   While Thursday's proposal went a long way toward addressing
shareholder concerns, questions about how the savings will be
achieved and who will benefit the most underscores the difficulty
that European stock exchanges are facing as they try folding
different technologies and regulations into one entity.
</P>
<P>
   A certain amount of overlap in terms of how trades are settled
have led some shareholders of the London Stock Exchange to call the
proposal a political Band-Aid, rather than the most economically
viable solution.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, since the plan laid out by the London settlement
firm, CrestCo, and its Frankfurt counterpart, Clearstream, is not
contingent upon the formation of iX, it remains unclear how
effective the measures will be in warding off the Swedish bid.
CrestCo has said that it will work with whichever partner London
Stock Exchange shareholders choose.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can go ahead without iX,'' Don Cruickshank, the chairman
of the London Stock Exchange, acknowledged Thursday at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, which could be introduced by next summer, the
cost of domestic trades will remain constant, while the price of
cross-border trades could fall by as much as 90 percent.
Transaction costs for trading pan-European stocks are more than 10
times those for trading stocks in the United States, according to
an estimate by Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Only trades made through a central counterparty, a kind of
clearinghouse system intended to allow large institutional
investors to remain anonymous in trades, will be subject to the
savings. Since most retail brokers do not use such a system, it is
unclear how much they will benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Institutional investors accounted for the majority of
international trades last year on the London Stock Exchange, which
amounted to 2.4 trillion pounds, or $3.48 trillion, compared with
1.4 trillion pounds ($2.03 trillion) for domestic trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence this is good news,'' said Michael Clark, a director
of the British brokerage house Charles &AMP; Stanley &AMP; Co., which owns
100,000 shares of the London Stock Exchange. ``What bearing it has
on a decision regarding iX, I'm not sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
