<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECT-ARREST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREGNANT SECT MEMBER ORDERED TO JAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTLEBORO, Mass. _ Refusing to ``bow down to a false god,'' a
pregnant member of a fundamentalist sect _ who this week spurned a
court-ordered medical exam and is suspected of neglect in the death
of her last baby _ was ordered Thursday to a prison hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The decision may be the first time a healthy pregnant woman has
been forced into custody to protect an unborn child. Rebecca
Corneau is likely to remain in custody until giving birth,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   State troopers escorted Corneau through a phalanx of
photographers to an unmarked Ford Taurus after a closed hearing in
which prosecutors and a court-appointed lawyer for the fetus
demanded a judge reverse his earlier decision allowing her to
remain free.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Juvenile Court Judge Kenneth P. Nasif ruled Corneau
could remain at her home here if she agreed to daily visits by a
court-appointed nurse. Corneau, however, vowed not to allow the
examinations.
</P>
<P>
   The next day the 32-year-old mother kept her courtroom promise
and refused to talk about her medical condition when the nurse
visited, calling medicine a false god.
</P>
<P>
   Miffed after Corneau violated the judge's order, Bristol County
District Attorney Paul F. Walsh returned to court to force her
hand. Speaking after the closed hearing, Walsh said he was relieved
the judge changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was a good day in court,'' he said. ``I think we finally
have some assurances that medical professionals will be able to
assist a healthy baby boy or girl be born within the next two or
three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's order requires Corneau to submit to a physical exam.
Prosecutors believe she's at least 8 months pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   If she has several more months before giving birth, Walsh said,
it's possible Corneau could be released from the Neil J. Houston
House in Roxbury, in Boston, a 12-year-old medical facility that
caters to pregnant women in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry we had to go this length, but I don't think there's
any choice,'' said Bethany Collins, the court-appointed nurse of
the Attleboro Public Health Department who was rebuffed after
visiting the home Corneau shares with several members of the sect.
</P>
<P>
   Corneau _ who has chosen not to hire an attorney, also on
religious grounds _ has consistently refused to allow health
officials enter her home. The small fundamentalist Christian sect,
which authorities say consists of only 13 members, shuns science
and medicine as a form of blasphemy.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday neither she nor other members of the sect would answer
repeated questions from the press after the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Eight adult members have been jailed for contempt after refusing
to cooperate in an investigation into the deaths of two infants,
including Corneau's infant son, Jeremiah.
</P>
<P>
   The children may have died from neglect _ including one from
starvation _ and were buried in a state park in Maine, authorities
said. Three searches have so far come up empty.
</P>
<P>
   Though sect members insist Jeremiah was stillborn, prosecutors
say their diaries suggest the baby died after his lungs were not
properly aspirated, a routine procedure in hospital births. Samuel
Robidoux, a 10-month-old boy who died, apparently starved to death
after he stopped nursing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two dead babies,'' Walsh said earlier this week,
outlining why he took action against Corneau. ``I don't want
another dead baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Judge Nasif declared Corneau an unfit mother,
taking away her three children and removing eight other children
from the sect, the youngest of whom is only 2 months old. Officials
from the state Department of Social Services are expected to take
custody of Corneau's baby just after its birth.
</P>
<P>
   Corneau's case appears to be resolved, but the stage is set for
another showdown in several months: The mother of the 2-month-old,
Trinette Daneau, appears to be midway through another pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, however, would not speculate about the next case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll cross that bridge when we come to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Corneau, Jeremiah's 32-year-old father, and Jacques
Robidoux are among eight sect members behind bars for refusing to
talk before a grand jury investing the infants' deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The eight could face charges ranging from improper disposal of a
body to murder. No charges have been filed.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining what prosecutors said was an unprecedented court
order, Walsh repeated he has no political agenda: ``This as a case
not a cause.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A life was at stake,'' he said, ``and maybe in some small way,
we helped to save a life this morning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
