<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    3 accused of defrauding Mohawk
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Police in North Georgia have arrested three employees
of Mohawk Industries on charges of defrauding the carpet maker, and
more arrests are coming.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have uncovered fraud at Mohawk's offices in
Calhoun and Dalton involving at least $80,000 in embezzled funds,
and employees may have stolen equipment and goods as well, Calhoun
police said. The arrested Mohawk employees were involved in a
scheme to create false invoices and steal checks that were issued
by the company, police said. The FBI and the Internal Revenue
Service have joined the case, said Capt. Randy Gallman of the
Calhoun Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be more arrests and charges coming. The individuals
arrested are lower-level supervisors (and a secretary), but this
will go higher in the company as we progress,'' Gallman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we're waiting on the FBI and the IRS before we
make more arrests,'' he said. ``We've subpoenaed bank records and
other documents. We may uncover other areas of fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Regina Roberson, 42, of Dalton was arrested Friday by the
Whitfield County sheriff's office and charged with one count of
forgery on a check for $7,725. Investigators said Roberson, who was
a secretary at Mohawk's Calhoun office, forged 11 other checks,
ranging in value from $4,000 to $7,000, since June 1999. Evidence
on those charges will be presented to a grand jury, said Whitfield
Sheriff Scott Chitwood.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun police arrested David W. Biggs Sr., 46, of Calhoun, and
Terry R. Wheeler, 33, of Silver Creek. Police said the men were
supervisors of equipment maintenance and were charged with theft by
deception. Biggs was also charged with being a party to a crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all operated together on a certain level, but there were
separate and independent incidents, too,'' Gallman said.
</P>
<P>
   Police began investigating the employees in July after an
internal auditor discovered the fake invoices, Gallman said.
</P>
<P>
   A Mohawk spokesman declined to comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
