<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BAY MEADOWS TRACK GETTING OFF TO A FAST START 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MATEO, Calif. _ The Bay Meadows racetrack won't wait long
for a marquee attraction.
</P>
<P>
   The track will open a 57-day meeting on Friday night, and on
Monday will check in with the $125,000-guaranteed California Turf
Championship, which will head the Labor Day card.
</P>
<P>
   That is expected to attract a number of top handicap horses,
including Southern California heavyweights Native Desert and Full
Moon Madness.
</P>
<P>
   Native Desert has the top handicap weight of the contenders _
120 pounds _ while Full Moon Madness is at 118.
</P>
<P>
   The Bob Marshall-trained Full Moon Madness has won three
straight races, the last of those the Robert K. Kerlan Memorial
Handicap at Hollywood Park July 16.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a good thing for Marshall and his thoroughbred that
the California Turf Championship, a mile grass race for
3-year-olds-and-up bred in California, is being run at night. The
night of Full Moon Madness' victory in the Kerlan Handicap, there
was a full moon, just as there had been after his win in the Answer
Do Stakes on June 17.
</P>
<P>
   And the horse's win in the Bay Meadows Express Handicap in
January came on the afternoon following a total eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   Whether lunar matters really figure into all this is open to
debate, but Full Moon Madness has become an extremely reliable
runner, with six wins in nine races this year following his return
from a couple of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's unusually sound for a sprinter,'' Marshall said. ``They
are very hard to maintain. They tend to overrun their legs. I've
tried to pick and choose races carefully for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the moon, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The California Turf Championship will be the first of six graded
stakes at this Bay Meadows meet, including two $200,000 races, the
Grade III Breeders' Cup Sprint Sept. 16 and the Grade III Bay
Meadows Handicap Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first meet at the Peninsula oval under the
stewardship of Magna Entertainment Corporation and its chairman,
Frank Stronach, who already own Santa Anita and Golden Gate Fields.
Magna's purchase of Bay Meadows was just approved by the California
Horse Racing Board.
</P>
<P>
   The $20 million deal gives Magna control of the Bay Meadows
Operating Company, but not the racetrack itself, from Paine Webber
Inc. Magna will continue to lease the track from Paine Webber for
racing through Dec. 31, 2002. Paine Webber plans to develop the
property after that, with racing operations moving elsewhere _
perhaps at a new track in Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   Opening night of the current meet, which will run through Nov.
12, will feature free grandstand admission.
</P>
<P>
   Post times (except Friday nights) will be 1:45 p.m. from
Saturday through Sept. 13; 1:15 p.m. from Sept. 14-Oct. 1 and 12:45
p.m. from Oct. 4-Nov. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Day's first post will be at 12:45.
</P>
</TEXT>
