<HEADLINE>
AGASSI DUMPED BY CLEMENT AT U.S. OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT10, 26-28 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andre Agassi saved four match points against Arnaud
Clement Thursday night, then on the fifth match point, he stabbed
at Clement's serve with a forehand, sending the ball right into the
net. It was over faster than anyone could have imagined. A 6-3,
6-2, 6-4 upset. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my best victory,'' Clement said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was a staggering victory. The U.S. Open is now without its
top two men's seeds this early in the tournament for the first
time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clement had made three tournament semifinals this summer, but
few could have foreseen the Frenchman's aggressive dismissal of
Agassi, the defending Open champion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to figure out how to get to him but I couldn't do
it,'' Agassi said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Agassi looked flat-footed at times as Clement cranked out 12
aces and whacked a total of 36 winners in the humidity-soaked
Arthur Ashe Stadium in Flushing Meadows-Corona Park. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He was beating me in a number of departments,'' Agassi said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Second-seeded Lindsay Davenport and fourth-seeded Mary Pierce
showed glimpses of vulnerability Thursday, but both delivered
powerful third sets to win their second-round matches.
Twelfth-seeded Anna Kournikova and seventh-seeded Conchita Martinez
won in straight sets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And Jelena Dokic, whose father-coach was evicted from the
tournament after an outburst in the cafeteria on Wednesday, said
the incident was not a distraction in her 6-1, 6-4 victory Thursday
over Miriam Oremans.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something you have to deal with, and deal with it I
did,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ninth-seeded Lleyton Hewitt, 11th-seeded Tim Henman and
fifth-seeded Yevgeny Kafelnikov advanced on the men's side. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And Hyung-Taik Lee beat 13th-ranked Franco Squillari, 7-6 (3),
7-5, 6-2. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In her afternoon match against Kim Clijsters, Davenport never
felt in danger of losing but said she did feel tight after dropping
the first set. The 17-year-old Clijsters refused to be intimidated
by Davenport's deep groundstrokes and surprised her with an early
fusillade of winners. Clijsters parlayed her only service break of
the match to capture the first set, 6-4. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Davenport pounced on Clijsters' second serve to break her
four times in the next two sets to win, 4-6, 6-2, 6-2. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I got up a break in the second set, I was able to attack
with a lot more confidence,'' Davenport said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Pierce's mistakes mounted Thursday, she tightened. She
slapped easy forehands into the net. She labored chasing after
balls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But faced with a third and deciding set a lot earlier in the
tournament than she expected, something clicked. Pierce relaxed,
and her shots began to hit their target. Pierce played a nearly
flawless final set to beat Magdalena Maleeva, 7-5, 2-6, 6-1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pierce lost to Maleeva three times in the mid-90s but that was
before Pierce's rise into the elite. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maleeva, once ranked fourth, can still be a dangerous player.
Pierce did not help matters any by fretting after mis-hits in a
clunky second set. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pierce, the French Open champion, racked up 23 unforced errors
in the first two sets but limited her miscues to three in the
deciding set. Pierce capitalized on Maleeva's puffy second serve
throughout the match, winning 21 of 32 points. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an afternoon men's match, Hewitt accused Julien Boutter of
gamesmanship after beating him, 7-6, 6-4, 6-4. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Hewitt serving for the first set at 5-4, Boutter called an
injury time-out for his aching back. Boutter broke Hewitt's serve
after the timeout, but Hewitt eventually took the set in a
tiebreaker and had little trouble afterward. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the match Boutter complained about his back despite
serving three straight aces at one point, Hewitt said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy has been a little bit known to do something like
that,'' Hewitt said. ``I wasn't surprised. I've spoken to a few
people before. They said he's pretty wild out there; he's going to
distract you as much as he can.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Henman, Great Britain's highest-ranked player, was the
beneficiary of 40 unforced errors by Fernando Gonzalez in their
encounter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to try and make out that I played a great
match,'' Henman said after winning, 6-3, 6-4, 6-2. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Popp committed 73 unforced errors to hand Kafelnikov a
7-6 (3), 6-4, 6-4, 6-4 victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
