<SLUG> BC-MONEY&AMP;MEDICINE-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENDING ACCOUNTS NEED A CURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, September 3)  
 By   JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   Whatever happened to medical
savings accounts?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Please pick your eyelids off the floor. This is actually an
important question. These accounts, which allow some income to be
put aside each year, untaxed, to pay for health care, were
presented just a few years ago as a panacea for the Big Health
Insurance Crisis. They have not exactly caught fire, and the
reasons say much.
</P>
<P>
   Congress created the accounts in 1997, specifically to help
workers at small businesses with 50 or fewer employees _ companies
that often cannot afford other kinds of health benefits. The
accounts are paired with bare-bones catastrophic health insurance
with a high deductible, $1,500 to $2,250 for individuals or $3,000
to $4,500 for families.
</P>
<P>
   The savings account can be used to pay medical costs not covered
by the insurance, including those needed to satisfy the deductible.
The worker or the employer can put aside in the account each year,
exempt from income tax, up to 65 percent of the deductible amount
(for an individual worker) or 75 percent (for family coverage). If
the employer pays, the contribution is also exempt from employment
tax.
</P>
<P>
   Don't confuse these accounts with the somewhat similar flexible
spending accounts that many big companies offer. Though both types
of accounts work by setting aside untaxed income to cover
unreimbursed health costs, the money in a flexible spending account
is lost if not used by the end of the year, and the accounts are
usually offered to workers with regular health benefits. With
medical savings accounts, money can accumulate from year to year,
but workers who have other kinds of health coverage are ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of medical savings accounts even extolled them as a
way to sidestep the problems of managed care, because people who
use them can go to doctors of their choosing whenever they want,
and still save money by paying part of the cost with untaxed
income.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot project approved by Congress is limited to the first
750,000 workers to sign up, but that ceiling has never been
approached. So far, only about 100,000 accounts have been
established. Many employers know little or nothing about the
program, and dozens of insurance companies, including Empire Blue
Cross and Blue Shield of New York, have stopped offering the
accounts because of lack of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Congress renews it, the law will expire on Dec. 31.
That's a shame, because with a bit of tweaking, the accounts could
be much more successful.
</P>
<P>
   The dismal performance of the medical savings account program
points up what can happen when the political system lays its hands
on health care. Medical savings accounts were first introduced as
part of broad health care legislation in 1996, with wide support
from Republican leaders. Many Democrats opposed the plan, and what
was left after negotiations was a program so restricted and
confusing that few people understood it and fewer could be bothered
to take part.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, eligibility was limited to the companies and
people least likely to experiment with them. ``Confining MSAs to
the small employment market was a terrible idea,'' said Greg
Scandlen, a senior fellow at the National Center for Policy
Analysis. When it comes to benefits, these employers are ``not
innovators,'' he said, ``because they don't have time to think
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, laws in some states keep small business owners from
offering MSAs.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the law's inflexible requirements for
deductibles. Workers who already had basic insurance plans with
different deductibles, either higher or lower, could not take
advantage of the accounts. Scrapping an existing plan only to pay
more for one with a higher deductible was hardly an attractive
option.
</P>
<P>
   The law also permits contributions by employers or employees,
but not both _ a bizarre requirement when most benefit plans
involve sharing the cost between employers and workers. It takes no
account of regional differences in health care costs. Figuring out
how to make contributions is no cinch. ``It is confusing,
particularly for families,'' Scandlen said. ``If you can't explain
the concept in 15 seconds, then you are basically lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Because so many insurers have dropped these plans, almost no
effort is being made to evangelize small employers on the subject.
``To tell you the truth, I never reviewed with my accountant
whether they would be cheaper,'' said Brian Zimmet, who runs a
small law firm in Manhattan. ``No one ever tried to market it to
me. I offer an HMO _ it is not cheap, maybe $400 a month for each
employee, but in order to attract qualified employees I need to
have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Who the plans are best suited for remains in debate. Critics
thought that only highly paid people would use the accounts, but
some studies show that this has not been the case. The rollover
feature would seem to be advantageous for the young and healthy,
who can salt away years of tax-free savings for use later in life.
But if a big, expensive illness strikes, 75 percent of $3,000
doesn't go far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, you are really unable to put enough money away to
cover a really serious health issue like cancer,'' said Maria
Berthoud, vice president for federal government affairs at the
Independent Insurance Agents of America.
</P>
<P>
   Berthoud and others say they believe that Congress will expand
medical savings accounts to cover a wider swath of workers, and
perhaps make other adjustments. ``I think that the prospects for
renewal are very good,'' said Berthoud, adding that if Congress
relaxes some of the restrictions, as she expects, participation
will rise sharply.
</P>
<P>
   For that to happen, support will have to come from both
political parties. But Berthoud is optimistic that this time,
Congress will get it right. ``Medical savings accounts were a
classic example of good policy getting jettisoned by politics,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1943EDT &QL; 
