<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7667 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH0901-COX     08-31 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bprescription drugsBy William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOLEDO, Ohio _ George W. Bush used his 100th campaign visit to a
school Thursday to give Democrat Al Gore a long-distance lecture on
prescription drugs for seniors and tax cuts for the middle class _
two issues that have come to dominate an increasingly heated
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also outlined his plans to increase federal spending for
public schools by $47 billion over the next 10 years. His stop at
Springfield High School just outside Toledo was part of the Texas
governor's effort to put a Republican imprint on education, an
issue that resonates with voters but that Democrats Gore and
President Clinton used to their advantage in the last two
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, campaigning in Ohio for a second straight day, seemed
lifted by the raucous applause and shouts in the packed school gym,
but his upbeat mood couldn't erase the cloud that followed him from
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   On the early-morning flight to Toledo from Cincinnati, where
Bush spent Wednesday night, he attempted to put the best face on a
federal judge's ruling this week that Texas has failed to live up
to a 1996 agreement requiring the state to make major changes in
how it provides health care to poor children through the Medicaid
health insurance program. The state is appealing the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have worked as hard as we can to to sign up little children
to the Children's Health Insurance Program as well as to Medicaid.
I asked the federal government for waivers that would make it
easier to sign up people,'' Bush said. ``Those waivers were denied.
. . . We are doing everything within our power to take care of
disadvantaged children in the state of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the timing of the ruling in the midst of the
presidential campaign, Bush said the judge, William Wayne Justice,
is a ``well-known activist liberal judge.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip was Bush's first to Ohio since Gore rebounded in the
polls and the Texas governor appeared to be trying to regain the
initiative by defining leadership and the issues on his own terms.
</P>
<P>
   There was no mention of the court case in the school gym where
Bush tackled head-on two issues Gore has tried to use against him _
Bush's proposed $1.3 billion across the board tax cut and the
governor's lack of a plan to provide prescription drugs for
seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has said that his tax-cut plan, when would provide targeted
tax credits in areas such as child care, college tuition and health
care, would help working families more, while the wealthy would
benefit the most from Bush's approach.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, said Clinton and Gore promised both prescription
drugs under Medicare and middle class tax cuts in their 1992
campaign _ and delivered on neither.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had their chance. They have not led and I will,'' he
said. ``It's time to put somebody in office who's going to do what
he says he's going to do on the campaign trail.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is scheduled to unveil his prescription drug proposal next
week. He has voiced support for a bipartisan congressional proposal
that would provide seniors with a subsidy to purchase prescription
drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has called for adding prescription drugs as a benefit under
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   In Toledo Thursday, Bush also showcased a local family _ Tim and
Tami Shelton and their two sons, Jonathan and Brian _ who he said
would benefit from his tax-cut plan. The couple, with a combined
income of $65,000, paid $5,990 in taxes last year. Their tax bill
would be reduced by $2,160 under his plan, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday in Cincinnati, Bush had showcased a Cincinnati-area
couple who would benefit from his tax plan. Also in Cincinnati,
Bush attended three fund-raisers with a combined take that could
reach $4 million for the Republican Party, party sources said.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's school appearance, Bush was accompanied by Ohio
Gov. Bob Taft and drew applause for his education plans from the
more than 3,000 students and adults in attendance. The plans
include everything from providing more money to teach reading to
promoting school safety and character education. Bush emphasized
that he favors local control of schools but also would hold states
accountable for improving student achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Normajean Rerucha, 62, who just retired as head of the business
computer department at the high school, liked what she heard. ``I
thought it was terrific. . . . Very impressive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Toledo police officer Edward Liwo, 59, also gave a
glowing review.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good speech,'' Liwo said. ``I like his moral
character.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's efforts to cast himself as the leader that he said Gore
hasn't been rang hollow to David Leland, Ohio Democratic chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk about a lack of leadership,'' Leland said. ``. . . A
federal judge (in Texas) said that George W. Bush violated the law
and denied health care to 1 million poor children in the state of
Texas. You can talk about compassionate conservatism. You can't
warm a cold house with warm thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
