<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7670 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-BROKERAGE-$ADV     08-31 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-BROKERAGE-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK WHO'S   SMILING IN   A SIDEWAYS   MARKET YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, September 3)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   Brokers, according to a Wall
Street truism, prosper when the market goes up and when it goes
down. But this year, the market has gone nowhere _ no major average
has moved as much as 4 percent from its Dec. 31 level _ and the
brokers have done better than ever.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Certainly the firms' stocks have _ many of the big ones are up
30 to 85 percent this year _ and they rose further on Tuesday when
Credit Suisse First Boston agreed to pay $90 a share for Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, which was changing hands less than a year ago
for $36.50 a share. That followed a blockbuster deal, announced in
mid-July, under which PaineWebber, the fourth-biggest American
brokerage firm, will be acquired by the banking group UBS.
</P>
<P>
   Many people on Wall Street say brokerage-firm shares, despite
rich prices and a history of sharp cyclical swings, have more room
to fly. A big reason, analysts say, is that they are taking
business from banks in a freer regulatory landscape for which the
banks themselves lobbied vigorously for decades. ``What you're
seeing is a paradigm shift from banks to brokers,'' said Meredith
Whitney, senior financial services analyst at First Union
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Henry McVey of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter put it, the
brokers are ``winning the land grab.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only are brokerage firms making more inroads into
traditional banking territory than the banks are making into the
securities business, but they are also seen by analysts as
``cleaner'' financial plays. There are no bad loans to write off,
for example.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks of brokerage firms are also benefiting from favorable
demographics. Only about half the baby-boom generation has reached
the prime stock-owning years.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is greatly expanded opportunity in Europe, where a
unified market and the euro are spurring mergers. According to Guy
Moszkowski of Salomon Smith Barney, a looming crisis in European
governmental pension systems means that employers are investing
more in securities. Individual Europeans, moreover, are only now
migrating in large numbers to equities from bonds and bank
deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is the seasonal lift that brokerage firms' stocks
often receive in anticipation of their strongest periods of the
year, the fourth and first calendar quarters. The list of stock
underwritings this fall, initial and secondary alike, is building
rapidly, although seasonal and cyclical swings have become hard to
disentangle, Moszkowski cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   But Steven Eisman, financial services analyst at CIBC World
Markets, said the fundamentals ``are still really good; much better
than for the banks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're recommending them all,'' Eisman added, despite
historically high price-to-earnings multiples that include at least
some premium for the possibility that a suitor will make a buyout
bid.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts express little concern that decimalization, trading in
cents instead of fractions of a dollar, will do much damage to the
firms. The gap between bid and asked prices will no doubt narrow,
shrinking trading profits, but they say this will probably be
offset by expanded volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over all, it's neutral to positive'' for the industry, said
Lauren A. Smith, who analyzes brokerage firms for Keefe, Bruyette &AMP;
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Still, prices are steep. J.P. Morgan, Lehman Brothers and Chase
Manhattan were reported to have expressed interest in Donaldson,
Lufkin before it went to Credit Suisse for three times book value.
Traditionally, Smith said, ``you buy brokers at book and sell them
at two times book,'' a rule of thumb that may soon be forgotten
given where some industry kingpins are trading. Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter is at 6.8 times book value, and Charles Schwab at 13.6
times.
</P>
<P>
   With Donaldson, Lufkin spoken for, in effect swapping one
European parent _ AXA _ for another, the spotlight has been aimed
more intensely at Lehman Brothers, up 67 percent this year, and
Bear Stearns, up 54 percent; both have relatively modest
price-to-earnings ratios of about 12.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Lehman, which is now expected to earn $12 a share
in 2000, compared with $7.70 when the year began, is enjoying
strong business and is equipped to compete on its own with Goldman
Sachs and the other giants if it chooses. Eisman rates it a
``strong buy,'' and Moszkowski said it could rise an additional 20
percent, along with Goldman and Merrill Lynch, over the next 6 to
12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns, very strong in securities processing and trading
but weak in asset management and stock underwriting, has said it
will consider selling at $120 a share, or four times book value, a
rich price indeed. Some suggest that its fiercely competitive,
independent culture would pose severe integration challenges for an
acquirer.
</P>
<P>
   Mosckowski considers the fast-growing Charles Schwab, trading at
a lofty 56 times earnings, ``pretty fully valued,'' and Morgan
Stanley, at 21 times earnings, ``fairly valued.'' As for leading
regional firms, he said valuations for Legg Mason of Baltimore and
A.G. Edwards of St. Louis ``are not particularly outrageous,''
despite sharp run-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're clearly dealing with outsize returns, but right now
there's little to rock the boat,'' said McVey, noting that the
Federal Reserve has now had two policy meetings without further
raising interest rates. But he warned of a potential double jolt if
the investment climate changed and if profits, which face
tough-to-beat comparisons with the first half of 2000, came up
short next year. ``There's always the risk'' with this group, he
said, ``of earnings and multiple compression at the same time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7671 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FIDELITY-INFLOW-BOS &LR;      08-31 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-INFLOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MONEY SLOW TO FIND ITS WAY TO FIDELITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes net inflows text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fidelity Investments may be having a banner earnings
year, but it's no thanks to its mutual fund business.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston investment giant is being outrun by a host of smaller
rivals this year in attracting new money from fund customers, a new
report shows. Fidelity has fallen to 10th place in the industry,
well outside of its usual top-three slot, and far below the likes
of Janus, Putnam Investments, and Vanguard Group.
</P>
<P>
   Janus, with its popular, aggressive stock funds, had reeled in
$36.50 billion of assets from investors through July _ 78 percent
more than last year at this point. Meanwhile, Fidelity had
attracted just $4.02 billion, according to a report by Financial
Research Corp. of Boston. That's a 77 percent plunge from the $17.7
billion of new money customers sent to Fidelity a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're even below Invesco _ that's embarrassing,'' observed
Jim Lowell, editor of Fidelity Investor, an independent newsletter
in Needham.
</P>
<P>
   He sees the asset bleed as a result of poor marketing, not poor
investment results. ``The irony is, they're having poor sales, but
they're having great performance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity said its vast menu of funds skews its ranking in the
asset-gathering lineup. Spokeswoman Anne Crowley said investors
poured nearly $32 billion into the firm's growth funds and sector
funds through July 31. But they pulled billions out of bond funds
and other categories that Janus and some rivals don't offer,
offsetting the gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see both sides of the ledger all the time,'' Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact remains that the people who pulled money out of
Fidelity bond funds didn't move their money into Fidelity stock
funds. They took their money elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   That's baffling to Lowell. He believes investors chasing Janus's
white-hot record of last year could become disappointed. Of 49
Fidelity funds in the growth or growth-and-income categories, he
said, 38 are beating the benchmark Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index in
2000. ``Some by a whisker,'' he said. ``Some by leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   The FRC numbers show Fidelity having a dismal July, with more
than $2.9 billion leaving the firm, half of that from asset
allocation funds, which hold a mixture of stocks, bonds, and cash.
Fidelity disputes that figure, saying it shed only $200 million in
the month.
</P>
<P>
   FRC's numbers are generally considered reliable in the industry.
Steve Cummings, an analyst with the research firm, said FRC
traditionally has maintained a margin of error smaller than 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   July was a slow month for much of the industry. As investors
worried about a rocky stock market, they slowed the pace of their
stock-fund investments by 21 percent from June, to $17.58 billion.
They invested slightly more in safer money markets and municipal
bond funds.
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps telling that Fidelity's best-selling fund in July
was not a household name, but one of its broker-sold offerings,
Advisor Equity Growth. This year, Fidelity's top selling funds are
its Growth Co. fund _ the second biggest seller in the industry _
with $7.56 billion of net flows. The only fund that's taken in more
money is Janus Worldwide, with $8.05 billion of new assets this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity will have to post a phenomenal second half of the year
to get back to the top of the pack in attracting assets and to
maintain its market share. According to FRC, Fidelity commands a
dominant 30 percent share of the direct-sold (that is, brokerless)
fund business. Its share of the total fund market was 12.75 percent
at the end of June, down from 12.77 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Growing mutual fund assets is getting harder as the business
matures, analysts say. In 1999, Fidelity's retail mutual fund
assets grew 20 percent to $351.1 billion, according to the
company's annual report. Other business lines, from 401(k)
retirment plans and brokerage to venture capital, are growing
faster.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity manages more than $400 billion in corporate and public
retirement plans, vs. about $355 billion in mutual funds. The
retirement business grew at a 31 percent rate in 1999. Brokerage
assets for individuals and institutions grew at a 49 percent rate,
to $614.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, that diversity is precisely what Fidelity wants.
Several years ago, it set out to grow its other lines of business,
so the overall company's success wouldn't hinge solely on the funds
and the rise and fall of the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time goes on, the fund business may turn out to be their
loss leader,'' Lowell said.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, that hardly seems to matter. At the end of June,
Fidelity said it had earned a stunning $1.2 billion for the first
six months of the year, more than double last year's first-have
earnings. Revenue was $5.8 billion, up 41 percent, largely on
online trading fees, as investors bought and sold heavily until the
Nasdaq Stock Market's dive in April.
</P>
<P>
   FRC isn't writing off Fidelity's fund efforts. The research firm
recently named Fidelity one of the five firms to watch in the
coming decade. Cummings, the analyst, maintained, ``The are the
company to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SLOWING THE FLOW &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Through the first seven months of the year, Fidelity Investments
has taken in less than a quarter of the new money it took in last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Fund family !  &UR;  &LR; Net inflows, (billions) ! &UR;  &LR;  1999 &QL; 
Janus ! $36.5 ! $20.4 &QL; 
Putnam Investments ! $13.3 ! $4.0 &QL; 
AIM Distributors ! $8.8 ! $1.1 &QL; 
Vanguard Group ! $8.0 ! $36.1 &QL; 
INVESCO Funds Group ! $7.3 ! $1.0 &QL; 
MFS Investment Management ! $7.1 ! $6.8 &QL; 
Alliance Fund Distributors ! $6.1 ! $7.6 &QL; 
PIMCO Advisors ! $5.0 ! $7.8 &QL; 
SEI Corp. ! $4.9 ! $3.4 &QL; 
Fidelity Investments ! $4.0 ! $17.7 &QL; 
SOURCE: Financial Research Corp. &QL;
</P>
