<P>
   NY-FOSTER-CARE (New York) _ When a child is troubled, the range
of options available to the privileged _ military-style private
schools, private psychiatric treatment _ are not readily available
to poor parents. So instead, every day, dozens of them stream into
a courtroom in Manhattan designated for so-called voluntary
placements into the foster-care system. These children represent
about 10 percent of the children who enter foster care every year.
Many are teen-agers, either delinquents or emotionally troubled
children in need of mental health services. A look at such
voluntary placements and how they affect parents, the already
flooded city agency and especially the teen-agers themselves. By
Somini Sengupta. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.)
</P>
