<SLUG> BC-SECT-RIGHTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S RIGHTS ADVOCATES DISTURBED BY JDUGE'S RULING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With Sect-Arrest)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first, the decision seems clear: a woman whose strict
religious sect forbids modern medicine _ but whose previous child
could have been saved by a routine medical procedure _ is ordered
to serve out the remainder of her current pregnancy in a locked,
state-run medical facility.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's decision by Judge Kenneth P. Nasif in the case of
Attleboro, Mass. sect member Rebecca Corneau sent a shock wave
through the women's rights community, and raised a profound
question: How much control should the government have over the
health decisions of a mentally competent person?
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do we draw the line here?'' asked Andi Mullin, president
of Massachusetts chapter of National Organization for Women. ``Are
we going to start incarcerating women who drink during pregnancy,
who smoke during pregnancy or don't wear their seat belts in a
car?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jetta Bernier, executive director for Massachusetts Citizens
for the Children said given Corneau's disturbing history, the judge
made the best decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Limiting her rights for a period of a few weeks seems far less
disturbing then denying her child's basic right to be born in a
safe and protective setting,'' said Bernier.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago Judge Kenneth P. Nasif ruled that Corneau _ one of
13 members of the ultra-conservative Christian sect suspected of
burying the bodies of two infants in a Maine park last fall _ was
an unfit mother who must surrender her unborn baby to the state
after birth.
</P>
<P>
   While the fundamentalists file no birth records and shun modern
medicine, prosecutors now say they have evidence the infant,
Jeremiah Corneau, lived for several minutes, and his death could
have been prevented. They also believe Samuel Robideaux, a
10-month-old baby, died when he stopped nursing.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week the judge seemed willing to give Rebecca
Corneau the benefit of the doubt, allowing her to remain free if
she allowed a court-appointed nurse into her home for daily
checkups on her pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Corneau refused, insisting that the conventional medical system
is ``under the direction of a pagan God.'' Thursday, the top
prosecutor in Bristol County, Mass., mindful of the two earlier
deaths, urged the judge to put Corneau in state custody. The judge
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   The case involving Corneau is unusual because the government
rarely involves itself in the decision of a mentally-competent
pregnant woman, said Madlyn Freundlich, policy director for the
Children Rights, a national advocacy organization in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In those rare cases, she said, the court usually struck down the
state's decision. But Freundlich said the state's job in this case
is to focus on the baby's health, not the legal rights of the
mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a difficult area when you are trying to respect the
rights of the woman and the rights of the child. That becomes even
more complicated when you don't have the little person in front of
you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But legal and child welfare experts say the case could have
broad implications on all people, regardless of their gender, by
removing an individual's power to choose based on his or her
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is outrageous,'' said Sarah Wunch, staff
attorney for the ACLU in Massachusetts. ``The implications are very
serious. And I believe there is no basis for it. I think the judge
is the outlaw in this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Paltrow, director of the New York-based National Advocates
for Pregnant Women, said that when the state gets involved in
childbirth issues ``they often get it wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   She recalled that a court once ordered a pregnant woman in
Washington, D.C. to have a Casearian birth over her objections,
believing they could save an endangered fetus. The fetus died,
Paltrow said, and the operation contributed to the woman's death.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling in Corneau's case `` sets a dangerous precedent to
both women and their future children,'' Paltrow said. ``It risks
frightening women from establishing good relationships with health
care providers, out of fear they will be forced to undergo unwanted
medical procedures and examinations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
