</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORESTFIRES-CAUSE-360&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO CONNECTION SEEN BETWEEN REDUCED LOGGING AND RAMPANT FOREST
FIRES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Mont.)   By TIMOTHY EGAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There appears to be no link between reduced logging on national
forests over the last decade and the wildfires now raging through
much of the West, a report by a bipartisan research group for
Congress has found.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, heavy logging from earlier years may have
contributed more to the conditions that have made Western forests
ripe for big fires, because more flammable small trees and heavy
brush are often left in the forest after the larger stands of
timber have been taken out, said the report, by the Congressional
Research Service, which does policy analysis for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last month, leading Republicans in the West, as well as
House Speaker Dennis Hastert, have said that logging reductions
under the Clinton administration have been a contributing cause of
fires that have burned more than 6 million acres this year. Logging
in national forests has been reduced by more than 75 percent since
1989.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Oregon earlier this month, Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, the Republican presidential nominee, said Clinton
administration policies that restrict logging ``made the forests
more dangerous to fire,'' although he did not blame the fires on
the president.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the years with the most fires over the last two
decades were those in which logging was at record high levels, the
report states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timber harvesting removes the relatively large diameter wood
that can be converted into wood products, but leaves behind the
small material, especially twigs and needles,'' wrote Ross W.
Gorte, author of the report. ``The concentration of these `fine
fuels' on the forest floor increases the rate of spread of
wildfires.''
</P>
<P>
   The report was done at the request of Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore.,
but it was conducted by the agency that conducts policy analysis
for all of Congress. Some Western Republicans who have linked
Clinton forest policies to the fires say the report is not
conclusive enough to determine future policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It presents a mixed picture,'' said Gov. Marc Racicot, R-Mont.
``This year is the lowest ever for timber harvesting and it could
be the worst fire year in decade.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Next week, the Clinton administration plans to release its
recommendations on how to manage more than 40 million acres which
are considered to be at extreme risk of major wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt said the congressional report
would not help the argument of either side of a growing political
debate over the fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``These fires are being used by both the timber industry and
environmentalists,'' said Babbitt. ``One side says increase
logging, the other side says no logging, even thinning. Neither
position is the accurate way to address forest health problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said the commercial logging program on national forests
will not play a significant role in the plan presented next week.
The plan will try to restore forest health through controlled burns
and some thinning, and attempt to get people who live in
high-fire-risk forested areas to clear the hazards near their
homes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional report looked at logging and fires for each of
the last twenty years. The two highest years for logging _ 1987 and
1988 _ were two of the highest years for acres burned on national
forest lands. The report does not address this year, when logging
has been at a historic low, and the fires are at near-record highs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assertion has been that we're getting more acres burned as
we have reduced the timber harvesting levels,'' said Gorte, author
of the report, in an interview. ``In fact, for the most part, we
were getting fewer acres burned.''
</P>
<P>
   The fires have been at the heart of a clamorous political debate
in the West. On Tuesday, on the day that Vice President Al Gore,
the Democratic presidential nominee, made a campaign stop in
Oregon, a number of groups which favor higher logging took out
full-page ads in the state that blamed the fires on the vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say no to Al Gore's big burn,'' was the headline in a
full-page ad which ran Tuesday in the Oregonian, the biggest paper
in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., has been highly critical of Clinton's
timber policies, saying forest neglect and mismanagement have
contributed to the fires. Thursday, after the congressional report
was released, Smith continued to criticize the administration,
though he softened his tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at things on a short term basis, we could concede
some of the points made in this report,'' said Joe Sheffo, a
spokesman for Smith. ``But the fact is we have a cumulative
problem. And the Clinton administration has known about it for
years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
