A7698 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BEAR-VS-ALPACA0901-CO     08-31 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAR-VS-ALPACA0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bear kills breeder's alpaca
 &HT;    By Michael C. Bender
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ A $10,000 alpaca was found half-eaten
just outside of Grand Junction Thursday morning, the victim of a
young bear's exquisite midnight snack.
</P>
<P>
   The bear attacked and devoured Mac, one of Kathy McKinley's
alpacas, then leaped the corral fence and headed across the street
into a corn field. The Division of Wildlife set a bear trap in the
corral later in the afternoon, hoping the bear would return to
finish its treat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't afford to have a bear eat all my animals,'' McKinley
said. McKinley and her husband, Steve, own Mesa Llamas and Alpacas.
They own 17 llamas and alpacas worth a total of more than $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   An alpaca looks like a smaller version of its cousin, the llama,
and is bred for its expensive fur.
</P>
<P>
   A late spring freeze and dry conditions this summer have bears
coming down from the mountains in a search for food.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Division of Wildlife has relocated 22 bears from
the Grand Valley this year and 10 others have been killed by
private property owners. The department receives about 12 phone
calls a day reporting bears in the city, said Steve Yamashita, area
wildlife supervisor for the DOW.
</P>
<P>
   This bear, however, was the first to kill livestock or cause
serious damage in the valley.
</P>
<P>
   McKinley did not hear anything during the night, but her
neighbor, Don Hauer, did.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was five or six seconds of fairly intense noises but
they always fight like that,'' Hauer said. ``It stopped after a few
seconds and I thought, 'That's the end of that.'''
</P>
<P>
   McKinley found the carcass about 7 a.m. and called the Mesa
County Sheriff's Department. She was referred to the DOW.
</P>
<P>
   The DOW ``said they wouldn't come because I didn't see the
bear,'' McKinley said.
</P>
<P>
   What McKinley did see was one of her favorite alpacas, minus
nearly the entire right side of its body.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken him to parades and to birthday parties, it's
really sad,'' McKinley said. ``Even the fur and the bones are
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   A coyote also could have killed Mac, but McKinley was convinced
the killer was a bear because of a large scat pile, about 50 feet
away from the carcass, surrounded by bear prints.
</P>
<P>
   Hauer, a manager in U.S. Rep. Scott McInnis' Grand Junction
office, said he called Russell George, the DOW's incoming new
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a bear that's come this close and with all the
reported sightings, you would think the Division of Wildlife would
be out here quick,'' Hauer said. ``She's got insurance on these
animals. Common courtesy would be for the sheriff's department to
at least come take a look.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is no immediate threat of a visible bear, the DOW will
not rush to the scene, Yamashita said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a two-strike policy here,'' Yamashita said. ``If we
have to relocate a bear we tag it and if it's found again we
euthanize it. If at all possible we try not to give it its first
strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Yamashita and Joe Gumber, district supervisor for the
department, arrived at McKinley's house about 11:30 a.m. They
determined it was indeed a bear that killed the animal. If trapped,
they will tag it and relocate it near Silt.
</P>
<P>
   The bear was probably in the area because neighbors are leaving
food out to feed all the bears coming into town, said Linda O'Neal,
a neighbor and friend of McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think the bears are so cute and adorable,'' O'Neal said.
``It's stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Yamashita agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fed bear is a dead bear,'' Yamashita said. ``The law
prohibits feeding wild animals. It encourages this bad behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
