u a BC-RAMSEY-WEB0901-COX     08-31 0280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-WEB0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JonBenet mystery `addictive' to Net surfers
 &HT;    By Maurice Tamman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even when the JonBenet Ramsey case largely disappeared
from television and newspapers, the story continued bubbling
online.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's addictive once you start exploring all the twists and
turns,'' said Susan Bennett. ``It's what I do all day, everyday.''
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina-native created a Web site a couple of years
ago to document developments in the case and explain why she
believes John and Patsy Ramsey did not kill their daughter in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   She has traveled all over the country to meet witnesses and has
posted lengthy challenges to published accounts of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's people like me that keep it alive online,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When Boulder police interviewed the Ramseys at their
Atlanta-area lawyer's office this week, visitors flocked to her Web
site and posted dozens of messages interpreting what happened.
Bennett, who uses the name Jameson online, said she welcomes
anyone's opinion but the site does have a slant.
</P>
<P>
   JonBenet's name appears in thousands of Web pages, including
this sampling from the week's events:
</P>
<P>
   _ Susan ``Jameson'' Bennett's pro-Ramsey Web site.
www.webbsleuths.com
</P>
<P>
   _ Crime Lynx's Ramsey case history.www.crimelynx.com/ramsey.html
</P>
<P>
   _ NBC ``Today'' show recording of a portion of the Ramseys'
interview with Boulder
police.www.websleuths.com/media/0830ramsey.html
</P>
<P>
   Transcript of Larry King interview with a prosecutor and Ramsey
attorney. www.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0008/30/lkl.00.html
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
