<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7701 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-OUTLOOK-$ADV     08-31 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-OUTLOOK-$ADV03-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONGRESS RETURNS WITH A FOCUS ON VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Sept. 3)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress returns to Capitol Hill Tuesday for a
fast-paced final month of work in which members will jockey to
showcase an agenda designed primarily to win votes in November.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative goals are taking a back seat to political strategies
as polls are showing a tight presidential race between Texas Gov.
George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Eyeing the election, Democrats will push popular legislation to
boost the minimum wage and grant patients a bill of rights against
managed care providers.
</P>
<P>
   With the same focus, Republicans will try to override President
Clinton's veto of the so-called marriage penalty tax as well as his
veto last Thursday of a plan to phase out the federal estate tax.
They will also push a measure to expand Individual Retirement
Accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some members of both parties will fight behind closed
doors to stymie legislation, hoping to keep certain issues alive
for the campaign. For instance, measures to make prescription drugs
more affordable for seniors are not expected to advance simply
because the two parties' plans are too far apart and not enough
time remains to resolve the differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be much sound and fury but very little actual
lawmaking because each side has an incentive to posture rather than
legislate,'' predicts Jack Pitney, a political scientist at
Claremont McKenna College in Claremont, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, says David Rohde, a political scientist at
Michigan State University, ``nobody wants to be seen as an
obstructionist, and each side wants the other side to be seen as
obstructionist.''
</P>
<P>
   Relations between both ends of Pennsylvania Avenue are already
tense. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott fired off a letter last
week charging that President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore
``are engineering `a train wreck' to affect the political
environment'' by vetoing spending bills. So far, only two of the 13
measures that fund the federal government have been signed into
law.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jake Siewert shot back, saying Congress is
``well behind in its work,'' and that ``it's time to stop making
excuses and get a budget together.''
</P>
<P>
   That will probably happen _ with plenty of last-minute
compromises _ since no one wants another government shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are still stung by the bruising House losses they
suffered after getting blamed for two partial federal government
shutdowns in late 1995 and early 1996 that resulted from budget
stalemates between them and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to avoid a repeat, Republicans in 1996 and 1998 made
major concessions to Clinton to complete the federal budget. Later
many GOP strategists blamed those concessions for additional
Republican losses in the House in 1998. Now Republicans have a
seven-vote majority there and a five-vote majority in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats remember all too well the legislative gridlock, plus
Clinton's failed health care overhaul, that swept congressional
Republicans to power in 1994. Voters blamed both sides for the
stalemate but punished Democrats at the polls that year.
</P>
<P>
   As the targeted adjournment date of Oct. 6 nears, horse-trading
between Republican leaders and the White House will go into high
frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything depends with how vulnerable the Republicans feel
and what they make by way of concessions without alienating their
conservative base,'' says Thomas E. Mann, a senior fellow at the
Brookings Institution, a Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   And, in the final month of the 106th Congress, President Clinton
will seek to burnish his legacy and drum up support for Gore and
for Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is running for a U.S. Senate seat
from New York.
</P>
<P>
   The following legislation will take center stage as Congress
returns:
</P>
<P>
   _ CHINA TRADE. The Senate will soon consider the landmark,
House-passed bill that would grant China permanent trading
privileges with the United States, which most other countries
enjoy, without an annual review. Since the measure, opposed by
organized labor, is a top priority for Clinton and Lott and is
backed by Gore and Bush, it will likely pass. But the outcome is
unclear on a controversial companion measure by Sens. Fred
Thompson, R-Tenn., and Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., which would prod
the White House to impose sanctions if China fails to stop giving
weapons of mass destruction to rogue nations.
</P>
<P>
   _ MINIMUM WAGE. House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., with
Lott's approval, offered a deal to Clinton last week. He said
Congress would agree to the president's plan to raise the minimum
wage by $1 over two years in exchange for a GOP proposal to provide
$76 billion in tax breaks over 10 years for small businesses. While
the House approved the minimum wage boost over two years, the
Senate has insisted on implementing it over three years. A
compromise version has stalled for months, but now, with Clinton
indicating he could accept the tax measure, passage looks likely.
</P>
<P>
   _ RETIREMENT SAVINGS. Lott has pledged to push legislation that
would expand contributions to Individual Retirement Accounts from
$2,000 to $5,000 over three years. The measure passed the House
with 401 votes in July, but the Treasury Department opposes it and
has said it will recommend a veto. Outlook: possible.
</P>
<P>
   _ MARRIAGE PENALTY. House Republican leaders will try to
override Clinton's Aug. 5 veto of the so-called marriage penalty
tax, a quirk in the tax code that causes some couples to owe more
income taxes if they marry than if they live together but remain
single. An override is doubtful but has a slim chance.
</P>
<P>
   _ ESTATE TAX. Hastert will try to override President Clinton's
Aug. 31 veto of a bill that would phase out the estate tax over 10
years. The speaker says it forces family farms and businesses to
break up. But in 1998, only 47,500 estates, 2 percent of the total,
paid the tax, and most of the revenue came from estates worth more
than $5 million. Republicans have been vulnerable to charges they
are catering to the wealthy, and their override attempt is likely
to fall short of the two-thirds majority needed.
</P>
<P>
   _ PATIENTS' BILL OF RIGHTS. Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., will
look for chances to attach to spending bills a measure that would
pay for emergency care, allow patients to see certain specialists
without prior health plan approval and let them sue a health plan
in state courts. Democrats claim they have 50 votes, which with
Gore's tie-breaker would allow them to pass the measure. But they
couldn't muster 60 votes to quash a GOP filibuster, and since the
Republicans are not likely to give Gore such a plum, the measure
will probably die.
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
</P>
<P>
   Judy &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
