<SLUG> BC-CARE0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CARE mounts relief for Eritrea
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ CARE, the Atlanta-based international relief and
development agency, announced Thursday that it is launching an
emergency relief program in Eritrea, where more than a quarter of
the population has been displaced by drought or by war.
</P>
<P>
   In a country that has not always welcomed International aid
agencies, CARE will help local institutions in managing food
distribution, providing seeds for planting, removing land mines and
educating people about them, and providing health care for women
and children who have been driven from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea has a strong tradition of self-reliance, and in the
mid-1990s the country asked a number of international agencies to
leave the country. But a brutal border war earlier this year saw
Ethiopian troops penetrate deep into Eritrean territory, sending
thousands of civilians fleeing. And a drought that has parched the
Horn of Africa has left many Eritreans unable to plant crops or
find food.
</P>
<P>
   Late in July, the deputy commissioner of the Eritrean Relief and
Refugee Commission, Teclemichael Woldegiorgis, met in Washington
D.C. with representatives of a number of non-governmental
organizations. He spoke about deteriorating conditions facing the
country's 1.1 million internally displaced people _ more than
one-fourth of the country's 4.1 million inhabitants _ and asked the
aid agencies how they thought they could help.
</P>
<P>
   In response, CARE sent a team of four people to Eritrea to work
with government ministries to assess the needs and figure out what
niche CARE might fill, said Susan Farnsworth, the CARE official who
led the team.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, CARE has worked with donors _ primarily the Italian
government and the U.S. Agency for International Development _ to
secure funding for what is projected to be a one-year emergency
intervention, Farnsworth said.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern part of the country, the CARE team visited
refugee camps, which, Farnsworth said, were populated primarily by
woman, children and old men _ the younger men having gone either to
the front or to the city to look for work, since the crops cannot
be planted this year. In the southern Debub zone, or province, the
Alba refugee camp has 24,000 people living in it, and more are
arriving daily, she said.
</P>
<P>
   CARE will help there with hygiene, malaria treatment and trying
to provide antiseptic tools and sheeting for births, as well as
education for traditional birth attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Displaced people who try to return home sometimes find their
houses damaged, the area's social services devastated, and the land
too strewn with mines to be inhabitable.
</P>
<P>
   CARE plans to move quickly. In the south, the planting season
has been missed. But in the north, the rains are just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an opportunity this week and next to get seeds in the
ground,'' Farnsworth said.
</P>
<P>
   CARE's plan, Farnsworth said, has been developed with officials
from Eritrea's relief agency, health ministry and agriculture
ministry participating every step of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eritrea has this very strong principle of self-reliance,'' she
said. ``I think that's something to really be respected.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
