 PERSONALS: Rock 'n' Roll and Bad Dirty Fun 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Spin magazine's October list of the 100 Sleaziest Moments in Rock
gives rise to much debate. The No. 1 moment is a 1969 Led Zeppelin
incident ``involving fornication with fresh seafood.'' Among the
other highlights:
</P>
<P>
   No. 12: `` &UR; Bill Wyman &LR;  of the Rolling Stones marries a
13-year-old girl; his son later dates the girl's mother.'' No. 17:
`` &UR; Eminem &LR;  includes daughter's voice in a song about killing her
mother.'' No. 24: ``When a member of the Bay City Rollers nearly
OD'd, their manager called the press before an ambulance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; PERSON TO PERSON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Interior designer  &UR; Ann Jones &LR;  of San Francisco was talking to
her husband in Seattle on Aug. 30 when he mentioned that  &UR; Al Gore &LR; 
was outside, participating in a photo op.
</P>
<P>
   He proved it by taking his cell phone outside, making his way
through the crowd and handing it to Gore, who greeted her with
``Hi, this is Al Gore,'' chatted a bit and then put  &UR; Joe &LR; 
 &UR; Lieberman &LR;  on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, Ann,'' said Lieberman. ``God bless you. Let me give you
back to your husband.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHEN YOU'RE NOT SMILING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   How trendy are trendy dentists?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Steven Butensky &LR;  of New York, who does the veneers of
photographer  &UR; Peter Beard &LR; , provides patients with a TSE cashmere
throw while they're in the chair, reports Vogue magazine.  &UR; Lana &LR; 
 &UR; Rozenberg &LR;  of New York offers aromatherapy massage and orange-spice
neck wraps to dental patients. And the Steliotes Dental-Medical Spa
in McMurray, Pa., refers to dental crowns as ``personalized
porcelain sculptures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's more,'' says this important medical story, ``teeth are
suddenly fashionable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; HOW TO SUCCEED AT THANK- &LR; 
 &UR; YOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by  &UR; Helen Gurley Brown &LR; 's advice about starting a
thank-you note with a question,  &UR; Les Albert &LR;  suggests:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``What were those little greenish things you served as an
appetizer? They tasted funny.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Did you know that wine stains will probably come out of the
rug if you use club soda?''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Is your cat all right?''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Rumor has it that it's all over between  &UR; Russell Crowe &LR;  and
 &UR; Meg Ryan &LR; , whose husband,  &UR; Dennis Quaid &LR; , has already filed for
divorce. Online gossip Fox411 says she's hoping to reconcile with
him despite the filing.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; M.W. &LR;  was intrigued by the Palo Alto Weekly ad placed by
someone selling an Encyclopedia Britannica. ``No longer needed,''
says the ad. ``Recently married and wife knows everything.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE ACORN AND THE TREE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Martha Stewart &LR;  Living's latest issue focuses on decorating,
featuring the New York apartment of  &UR; Alexis Stewart &LR; , Martha's
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lali Maly &LR;  points out that although Alexis' decorating style is
different from her mom's _ ``a clean, modern apartment in which . .
. every line has to be straight, every plane flat, every corner a
perfect right angle, or the effect is ruined,'' says the magazine _
certain aspects of their approaches to decorating are similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I used to go to my friends' houses,'' says Alexis,
describing her childhood, ``I had to throw everything under the
couch so the room would look clean before we could play.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. A poll taken by Rowenta irons has found that San Francisco
is fourth in the country in the percentage of people who iron their
pajamas but not even in the top 10 of people who iron their jeans.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``John Waters' `Serial Mom' was the graveyard for Kathleen
Turner, his `Pecker' finished off Edward Furlong and Martha
Plimpton, and now `Cecil B. DeMented' is the death knell for
Melanie Griffith and Stephen Dorff. . . . Andy Warhol tried to make
boring self-parodies and produced triumphs. Waters tries to be a
trailblazer and just copies himself into oblivion. Waters be
still!''
</P>
<P>
   _  &LR; Actor  &LR; Taylor Mead &LR; , who apparently doesn't expect to star
in &LR;   &LR; any  &LR; John Waters &LR;  movies, to &LR;  Baird Jones  &LR; at the closing
party &LR;   &LR; of the New York Fringe Festival. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
