u p BC-NADER-NYT &LR;      08-31 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NADER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NADER BRINGS HIS CAMPAIGN TO NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ralph Nader, running for president as the Green Party
nominee, railed against big business from the heart of corporate
America Thursday, crisscrossing Manhattan to condemn environmental
pollution, the exploitation of workers and the abuse of taxpayer
dollars through ``corporate welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   He also dismissed his opponents, Vice President Al Gore and Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, as candidates whose similarities (favoring
businesses over workers, in Nader's view, and taking millions from
corporate donors) outweighed their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Nader, the consumer advocate whose long-shot candidacy has
received comparatively little national media attention, began his
salvos from a prominent platform: a morning interview with Matt
Lauer on NBC's ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are different in a few areas, but the rhetoric is more
different than the reality,'' Nader said of Bush and Gore on
``Today,'' as about 300 people milled about on a Rockefeller Center
sidewalk outside the studio. Some held signs demanding that the
major candidates open the presidential debates to Nader and the
Reform Party candidate, Pat Buchanan. Two men made the point by
wearing chicken suits to represent Bush and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Today,'' Nader gave a separate interview on NBC's cable
cousin, MSNBC, then crossed the street to the headquarters of the
network's corporate parent, General Electric, where he criticized
the company for polluting the Hudson River. He also attacked Gore
and Bush for taking contributions from the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for General Electric to obey the law and pay for
its poisoning of the Hudson River and stop lying and deceiving the
public about the dangers,'' Nader said, referring to GE's legal
discharge of PCBs into the Hudson until 1977, when the chemicals
were banned by the federal government. He called for Bush and Gore
to give back the money their campaigns had received from GE.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Nader went to the Bowery, where he protested with
union workers at the New Silver Palace Restaurant, a 900-seat dim
sum parlor and banquet hall that once was the only unionized
restaurant in Chinatown. Former employees have waged a three-year
battle with the restaurant's management, which has been accused by
federal labor officials of antiunion hiring practices.
</P>
<P>
   Nader finished his campaign day on Wall Street, where he
criticized the city and state of New York for offering
multimillion-dollar tax breaks and other incentives to persuade
companies like the New York Stock Exchange to stay in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is this bastion of global capitalism on welfare,'' Nader
said, after taking a private tour of the Stock Exchange. ``Hundreds
of millions of taxpayer dollars in order to build them a new
building, at the same time hundreds of neighborhoods are suffering
from inadequate funding of their vital needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader said that such ``corporate welfare'' was emblematic of the
problems of America's current two-party political system. Nader's
candidacy is widely seen less as an attempt to capture the White
House in November than an effort to influence the public debate.
</P>
<P>
   At various points since announcing his candidacy, it appeared
that Nader could garner a high enough percentage of the vote _
mostly from Gore _ in several key states, including California and
Michigan, to push Bush ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But recent polls have suggested that Nader's moment appears to
be fading, given Gore's surge in the polls after the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a Field poll released last week showed that Nader
was supported by 4 percent of California voters, compared with 7
percent in a similar survey in June.
</P>
<P>
   Nader's swing through New York City Thursday followed a series
of fund-raisers and appearances on the East End of Long Island on
Wednesday. Earlier in the week, he and his running mate, Winona
LaDuke, staged a boisterous rally in Portland, Ore., that drew more
than 10,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   At his Manhattan appearances, Nader was trailed by small but
loyal bands of supporters: college and high school students,
environmentalists and those who said they were concerned about the
influence of large corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care how much of a threat he is to Bush and Gore,''
said David Joseph, 33, a master's student in French at Hunter
College, outside the NBC studios Thursday morning. ``I want to see
something new, something fresh in the debates.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Welfare reform, for example, would not be discussed in the
same fashion if Nader were not in the debates,'' said Joseph, a
registered Democrat who said he would vote for Nader in November.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Rogovin, 59, of River Vale, N.J., who moved off the steps
of a building for Nader's Wall Street news conference, said he
would probably not vote for Nader, but was happy to see him in the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is man for the people,'' Rogovin said. ``I don't believe he
will get elected or get a chance to debate the two power brokers.
Think, he would act as devil's advocate.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why, Rogovin said, he answered, ``By all means'' when
Nader asked if he could use the steps.
</P>
</TEXT>
