<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7720 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TIRE-DEALERS0901-COX     08-31 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-DEALERS0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chorus rising for broader tire recall
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tire dealer Andy Maughon said he initially doubted the
need for a recall on millions of Firestone tires but not any
longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to get worse. This is escalating,'' said the owner
of Bulldog Tire Co. in Snellville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the way Bridgestone/Firestone and Ford Motor Co. see
it.
</P>
<P>
   They maintain they've identified the 6.5 million tires that
needed replacing in a voluntary recall announced Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Like other metro Atlanta dealers, Maughon said the pace of tire
replacements slowed this week. But he predicted that may reverse.
</P>
<P>
   He said he recently replaced 16-inch Firestone tires _ which are
not part of the recall _ on a Ford Explorer. He said he did so
because they showed separating tread similar to the recalled tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mouth flew open. You could see the steel belt actually
protruding out of the tire,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I was skeptical. Now, yes, I think there's a
problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The recall covers certain 15-inch ATX, ATX II and Wilderness AT
tires that were installed on Ford sport-utility vehicles and
pickups.
</P>
<P>
   The models are all P235/75 R15 Firestone ATX and ATX II tires
made since 1991 and P235/75R15 Wilderness AT tires manufactured
since 1996 at Firestone's Decatur, Ill., plant.
</P>
<P>
   The latter tires are identified by a code number starting with
``VD.'' The serial number is only visible on the tire sidewall from
underneath the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Those tires ``are considerably over-represented'' in incidents
of tread separations and blowouts involving the Ford vehicles, said
Bridgestone/Firestone spokesman Walt Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   He said other models and sizes did not show abnormal numbers of
failures, according to Firestone's and Ford's analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep in mind that tires are consumable products. All tires
fail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer safety advocates such as Public Citizen and
Safetyforum.com (www.safetyforum.com) say the problems may be due
to a wider design defect.
</P>
<P>
   They have called for Firestone to expand its recall to include
16-inch tires and all 15-inch Wilderness tires, not just those made
at the Decatur factory.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Transportation Safety Administration,
Georgia and other states say they are investigating and haven't
ruled out ordering a wider recall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are receiving calls on other tires,'' said NHTSA
spokeswoman Liz Neblett.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to do the investigation despite the fact that
Firestone has done the recall. We are investigating to ensure that
the scope of the recall is adequate and that it addresses all the
safety issues with all of the tires.''
</P>
<P>
   According to complaint data on the Firestone tires from NHTSA's
Web site (www.nhtsa.gov), tire sizes other than 15 inches account
for about 5 percent of the 739 complaints the agency received
through Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wilderness and ATX tires accounted for the large majority of the
complaints, but the tire size was not identified in almost 80
percent of the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   California, Texas and Florida had the largest number of
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
