<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7721 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-EXPERIMENTSHALTED-HNS     08-31 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPERIMENTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 HALTED-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    (EDS NOTE: SLUG IS A MISNOMER ... experiments have not been
halted; only new prisoner enrollment has been halted.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    U.S. agency orders UT Medical Branch to halt prisoner enrollment
in 195 research projects
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By LEIGH HOPPER
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Under orders from the federal agency that oversees patient
safety, the University of Texas Medical Branch at Galveston has
halted prisoner enrollment in 195 research projects because of
alleged lapses in procedures that protect inmate patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interpretation was we were in compliance (with federal
regulations) and their interpretation questions whether we were in
compliance,'' said Wayne Patterson, director of UTMB's ethical
oversight committee on patient research. ``We look forward to
discussing that with them and we will make whatever revisions are
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   UTMB said the investigation was prompted after university
officials attended a conference at Brown University on ethical
guidelines for research involving prisoners. An attendee wrote to
the Office for Human Research Protections (OHRP) questioning
whether current clinical trials involving prisoners comply with
federal guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   All of the research projects, which are open to nonprisoners as
well, are continuing; only enrollment of prisoners has been
suspended, Patterson said. He said he knew of no inmates being
dropped from current studies. Twenty-five studies involving 99
prisoners with HIV infection were allowed to continue because the
studies were deemed to be in the best interest of the inmates'
health.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent July 10, the OHRP sharply criticized the
university on several fronts. UTMB provides health care to the
majority of Texas prison inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said the university provided ``scant
evidence'' that it thoroughly reviews medical research involving
prisoners. The letter also stated that UTMB's effort to include a
suitable prisoner representative on the ethical oversight committee
was ``insufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials also pointed out an instance where an informed
consent form for an ovarian cancer project ``appeared to overstate
the ... benefit to the subjects.''
</P>
<P>
   UTMB has since responded to the allegations by letter and is
preparing for an on-site evaluation Sept. 12-14 conducted by the
OHRP, which is part of the U.S. Department of Health and Human
Services.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the criticism, UTMB installed a member of the
Texas Inmate Families Association on its 35-member ethical
oversight committee, or institutional review board, last month.
Institutional review boards (IRBs) are based at research
institutions and are responsible for ensuring that people who agree
to participate in studies fully understand the nature of the
research and willingly consent to participate.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulations require that one member of the IRB ``be a
prisoner, or a prisoner representative with appropriate background
and experience.'' In the past, UTMB has used university doctors who
care for prisoners to fulfill that role.
</P>
<P>
   UTMB also forwarded additional documents in August to federal
authorities to illustrate the four-step process by which it reviews
new study proposals. Under UTMB's system, a study proposal is
assigned to a primary reviewer, who presents his or her findings to
a study group. The study group discusses it further and makes a
recommendation to a subcommittee. The subcommittee then reports to
the entire IRB which then votes on whether to approve the study.
</P>
<P>
   As for the criticism that UTMB overstated the benefits to
patients in an ovarian cancer study, the OHRP said that UTMB's
consent form states ``I understand that the potential benefit of my
participation in this study is the control of my disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said it would have been more appropriate to
say ``subjects are unlikely to benefit from this research.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Patterson said the second half of the sentence on
UTMB's consent form states ``but it is possible that my condition
my worsen despite treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a difference of opinion,'' Patterson said. ``These are
not unusual questions for discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson said UTMB hopes to resume research involving prisoners
after the site visit, and after study proposals have been
re-reviewed with the new prisoner representative.
</P>
<P>
   UTMB is not the only research institution under fire for its
studies involving prisoners. Federal investigators have uncovered
oversight lapses at the University of Miami, University of Florida
and Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   Miami was ordered to suspend new enrollment of inmates in one of
its projects and Florida and Yale were told to clean up their
patient-protection systems.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
