<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7724 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DOWDOW0901-COX     08-31 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWDOW0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Across-the-board increases cap a big month for stocks
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The stock market ended its best monthly performance of
the year with a broad-based rally on Thursday, prompted in part by
investment-favorable economic news.
</P>
<P>
   August was the first month in which all four major stock market
indexes were in plus territory. The Nasdaq composite gained 11.7
percent, the Russell 2000 small-stock index 7.4 percent, the Dow
Jones industrial average 6.6 percent and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The government's report on Thursday that factory orders plunged
a record 7.5 percent in July reinforced Wall Street's conviction
that the Federal Reserve will have no reason to raise interest
rates again this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're past the Fed's rate-hike cycle, and ahead of us is a
healthy economy,'' said Alfred Goldman, chief market strategist for
A.G. Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has boosted short-term interest rates six times over the
last 14 months to slow what it regards as inflationary economic
growth, and the strategy seems to be working.
</P>
<P>
   While the economy expanded at a still-strong 5.3 percent annual
rate in the second quarter, much of the important economic news for
July and August reflected a definite slowing of activity in
manufacturing, home building and retailing, and a slip in consumer
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, inflation moved only slightly higher amid news
of stronger-than-expected productivity growth and stable wages.
</P>
<P>
   The government's important monthly job growth and unemployment
reports for August are due for release today. But their impact on
the market is likely to be subdued given the early departure of
many traders for the three-day Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   With a month to go, the third quarter is shaping up as the best
three-month period of the year for the stock market, with a
favorable outlook for the fourth quarter as well.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to prospects that interest rates have peaked,
analysts base that outlook on upbeat third-quarter corporate profit
forecasts and the seasonal increase in year-end trading.
</P>
<P>
   And depending on how it goes, the presidential election in
November could give an added boost to stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The six months before an election are usually pretty good. But
since the market sputtered in June and July, that may lead to
increased momentum in the next two months,'' said Legacy South
strategist Phillip Larkins.
</P>
<P>
   Once the election is over, he added, the market will be in a
seasonally upbeat part of the year typically marked by tax-related
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Technology and financial stocks paced the market in Thursday's
trading. The tech-loaded Nasdaq composite index rose 2.5 percent,
while the blue chip Dow Jones industrial average and the broader
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 1 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens from this point on, analysts doubt that the
stock market will end the year anywhere close to the double-digit
gains that were routine in the last half of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   All the major stock indexes have rebounded from their spring
lows, but they are still just ahead for the year, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq, for example, has rebounded 33 percent from its low
point in May but is just 3.4 percent above last year's close. The
Dow has rallied 14 percent from its earlier low and is still down
2.5 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, analysts who believe the stock market's worst
problems are over now look for the bull market to resume later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are correct by stating that the summer rally is not
over, then the stage will be set for an eventual upside
follow-through,'' technical analyst Ralph Acampora told Prudential
Securities clients on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This rally will be an integral part of the presidential
election cycle, which suggests that the market makes new highs,''
he added. ``Thus any hesitation is a buying opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
