<HEADER>
A7727 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-PAC10-LADN     08-31 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PAC10-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTSIDE CONFERENCE, PAC-10'S BEEN NOT SO ROSY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's the new national pastime - dump on the
Pacific- 10 Conference. Take your best shots now, because truth is,
they're fairly defenseless.
</P>
<P>
   Just how are you supposed to defend yourself after last year's
1-4 bowl record, which included losses to Wake Forest and Hawaii? A
postseason record that just happened to match the previous year's
mark.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to rally the troops around a 20-18 nonconference record,
which included victories over Boise State, Idaho and Nevada. The
conference champ, Stanford, was pasted 69-17 by Texas and also was
knocked off by not-so-mighty San Jose State.
</P>
<P>
   Conference spirit waned. If Pac-10 morale was any lower, it'd be
the Russian Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty apparent the whole conference didn't do very well
last year,'' said Cal coach Tom Holmoe. ``It was a down year. I
think you can't just say, 'Hey, don't worry about it. It's
something that will change.' It's won't automatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Things got off to an oh-so embarrassing start last year when
Arizona, ranked fourth going into the Kickoff Classic against Penn
State, was pummeled 41-7 on national TV. Think the East Coast was
sneering?
</P>
<P>
   ``The tough thing for us last year was, we didn't get off to a
very good start,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``What happened to
Arizona, everybody kind of looked at and made more out of than they
probably should have. Then, of course, the Rose Bowl game at the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, at least Stanford gave Michigan a game. Losing in the Rose
Bowl, however, is nothing new for the Pac-10. It hasn't won one
since 1995. It's lost seven of the last eight.
</P>
<P>
   Already, though, there is reason for optimism. On Sunday, USC
went to the Kickoff Classic to play Penn State and returned the
favor of last year with a 29-5 thumping.
</P>
<P>
   Beano Cook, ESPN college football analyst, said last year was
simply a temporary condition, not a permanent conference
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody gets too excited if a conference has one great year,
and gets down if a conference has one bad year,'' Cook said.
``Before you do trends, you have to wait five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pac-10 had a bad year, that's all. The year before they
had pretty good year. UCLA was in the running to play for the
national title until they lost to Miami - a game they probably
would have won if played when originally scheduled.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook said there are simply too many good athletes in California
for the Pac-10 to suddenly start looking like the Mid-American
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Pac-10 coaches can't help noticing top California kids who
sign with out-of-state schools. Last year, highly regarded
California prospects D.J. Williams (Miami), Chris Rix (Florida
State), Travis Johnson (Florida State), Casey Clausen (Tennessee)
and Zac Wasserman (Penn State) all spurned the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the one thing that's important is that we have not
been able to keep the West Coast players on the West Coast,''
Hackett said. ``That's something that has been disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It really starts with recruiting,'' Holmoe said. ``We're
losing too many kids from California and L.A. specifically - to
outside the West.''
</P>
<P>
   It's part chicken-and-the-egg material, though, because it's a
lot easier to recruit when you're winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the recruiting lists and see some good athletes from
the West Coast leaving to go to the Midwest, East or the South,
which always leads to a cry here,'' said assistant Pac-10
commissioner Jim Muldoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you really take a close took at it, you see it happen
the other way, too, where people are coming in here from Texas and
the South. I don't think you can say there's a talent drain. It's
become much more fluid nationally than it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but last year no school in the Pac-10 made most of the
national top-10 recruiting lists. The conference mostly treaded
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably somewhere in the middle of the pack, as far as the
nation is concerned,'' Hackett said. ``It's not on the bottom end
at all, but I don't know that we'd be in the elite area.''
</P>
<P>
   Muldoon said part of the reason for last season's failures can
be attributed to the schedule. Most of the top nonconference
opponents Ohio State, Texas, Michigan, Penn State, Notre Dame -
came on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year that reverses a little bit,'' he said. ``We have the
likes of Michigan and Ohio State and Texas coming here. So that
might help.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, the answers about Pac-10 rebound could be coming in the
first month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find out early,'' Cook said. ``USC plays Penn State and
Colorado. UCLA plays Alabama and Michigan. Washington plays
Colorado. Arizona plays Ohio State. We find out early.''
</P>
<P>
   And another thing, coaches say: Two years ago, the Pac-10 was
awash in top quarterbacks Akili Smith, Cade McNown, Brock Huard,
and just a year removed from Ryan Leaf. Last year, babes led them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had good teams led by good quarterbacks, and the Pac-10's
always been a conference where the quarterbacks have a lot to do
with the success of the offense,'' Holmoe said. ``Last year was a
down year for quarterbacks. Todd Husak was a very good one, and
there's a few others that had decent years, but none at a national
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, last season Stanford's Husak was the only Pac-10
quarterback to crack the top 25 in national passing efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Pac-10 supporters say, the conference looked worse than it
actually was last year because it has so many good teams. Or at
least, pretty good. All this equality doesn't sell nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a national perspective, from a ranking perspective,
you're much better off to have three or four dominant teams just
kick the hell out of the others,'' Muldoon said. ``Your strength is
perceived by your top teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmoe said some teams annually ranked in the Top 10 may benefit
from playing in a lopsided league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe some of the schools in their conference are not very
good,'' he said. ``I know in our conference, the coaches feel that
they go into every game thinking it's a battle. I think the Pac-10
Conference might be more balanced than any conference in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow during this Pac-10 decline, some coaches have decided
the training table is an issue. In most conferences, players are
allowed to be fed a meal throughout the school year. In the Pac-10,
it is only during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think it's not even an issue, they're saying it's
an excuse,'' Holmoe said. ``But when we go into a home against a
school, they'll use it against us - so that is an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   This season the Pac-10 again has the look of a balanced
conference set to underwhelm voters. In the preseason Associated
Press poll, Washington (13th) and USC (15th) were the only
conference selections. Sports Illustrated, in a ranking of
conferences, listed the Pac-10 fifth, behind the ACC and ahead of
the Big East.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously lost a lot of games last year,'' Muldoon said.
``We are hopeful it is a one-year aberration and a cyclical type of
deal rather than a trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Few, though, are predicting some kind of dramatic turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm not sure there's a corner being turned,''
Hackett said. ``I don't sense that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a little cause for concern,'' Holmoe said. ``I
feel we do need to look at it as more than just something that was
an illusion, something that was maybe cyclical.''
</P>
<P>
   No one questions, however, the way to turn things around: Make
like USC against Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to make up a lot of excuses,'' Holmoe said. ``We
just have to win games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand there are some issues that will help, but that's
not why we've struggled. We've just go to do it, and there's no one
else to blame but ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
