r s BC-FBC-UCLA-PREVIEW-LADN     08-31 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS CONTINUE TO MAKE MOVES IN RIGHT DIRECTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There is no Heisman campaign. There are few TV
cameras and only a handful of print reporters at Spaulding Field.
There is no talk of national championships; in fact, there's little
talk of rankings.
</P>
<P>
   And there is positively no buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Can it be just two years since the UCLA football team was
captivating the Southland by rolling to 20 consecutive victories
with its high-scoring offense and its high-wire defense?
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were big box office back then.
</P>
<P>
   Actor James Caan attended practices, ESPN brought its ``Game
Day'' crew to the Rose Bowl for a UCLA game for the first time, and
lampposts around West L.A. were adorned with Cade McNown banners.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins sold 20,000 walk-up tickets for a game against
Washington - a development so unexpected it tied up pregame traffic
for hours - and in 1998 they shattered the school's
season-attendance record.
</P>
<P>
   After each home victory, UCLA coach Bob Toledo marveled at how
great it was to have a home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when the Bruins open the 2000 season Saturday at the Rose
Bowl against No. 3-ranked Alabama, there will be so many Crimson
Tide fans - perhaps as many as 25,000 - that it may be hard to tell
if the game is in Pasadena or Tuscaloosa.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year and a half, UCLA has been devastated by
injuries, endured the messy departure of defensive coordinator Nick
Aliotti and been scarred by the handicapped parking scandal. If
Florida or Nebraska have a down year, it's 7-4. But since the
Bruins strutted into the Orange Bowl to play Miami less than 20
months ago, they've won just four of 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA has gone from burgeoning national power to a basketball
school.
</P>
<P>
   So, as Toledo fields the first team comprised entirely of his
recruits, the question facing his program is this: Can the Bruins
get their groove back?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's headed in the right direction,'' Toledo said,
pointing to recruiting classes that were rated 24th, 6th and 1st in
the nation the past three years by SuperPrep magazine. ``If you
look at our seniors, 11 seniors were on scholarship until I gave
some of the walk-ons scholarships (in fall camp). And if you look
at the depth chart, only five or six are going to play a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of good young people in the program who have
played and are going to play this year. We have the quarterback
established and, if we keep improving, I think we have a chance to
make a heck of a run this year and next year.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no questioning the talent. Tailback DeShaun Foster,
receivers Brian Poli-Dixon and Freddie Mitchell, tight end Mike
Seidman, linebacker Robert Thomas, defensive end Kenyon Coleman and
defensive tackle Ken Kocher have the skills that the NFL covets.
</P>
<P>
   But Coleman is the only senior among the group, the only one who
has played an entire season and the only one who has achieved so
much as all-Pac-10 second-team status.
</P>
<P>
   If that group is injury free, gives the Bruins veteran
leadership and plays to its ability, the Bruins could be much, much
better.
</P>
<P>
   But even quarterback Cory Paus, a sophomore whom the Bruins are
counting on heavily for leadership and steady play, isn't sure
where the program stands.
</P>
<P>
   He concedes it's probably not where it was two or three years
ago when the Bruins were a Skip Hicks fumble against Tennessee and
a couple of official's calls - Jermaine Lewis spotted short of the
goal line against Washington State and Brad Melsby's fumble against
Miami - from playing in back-to-back national championship games.
</P>
<P>
   But neither are they as bad as last season when they scored more
than seven points just once in the final five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where we are because we haven't played yet,''
Paus said. ``Last year was really bad. You're always going to have
injuries, but we had so many and we weren't that deep. I know we're
better than last year, but only time will tell how much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Poli-Dixon kept a newspaper photo of himself - down on a knee
staring at the mad celebration by Miami players and fans - on his
bedroom wall last year as motivation. It's gone now and so, too, is
the hangover.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team's right on the bubble,'' he said, dismissing the
notion that underclass-laden Bruins are a year away from returning
to national prominence. ``We've got a lot of potential, all the
keys, all the tools. It's a matter of how much we want it and how
well we execute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time is now. We said last year how we had a young team.
Now we've got everybody coming back. There's no excuses. We're not
a young team anymore. We're ready to come in and kick some butt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
