<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7729 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USC-PREVIEW-LADN     08-31 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT NOW FOR USC?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A few minutes after getting throttled by USC 29-5,
Penn State coach Joe Paterno quickly pulled out one of his favorite
cliches to describe his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not as good as you think you are when you win, and not
as bad as you think you are when you lose,'' the venerable coach
said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe USC should be listening, too. The Trojans are sky-high
after routing the Nittany Lions, but it's still just one game, much
like last year's 62-7 victory over Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   USC proceeded to lose six of its next eight games following that
dominating performance.
</P>
<P>
   The Penn State victory was clearly an excellent launching pad to
the season, but more will be known when USC faces Colorado on
Saturday at the Coliseum. It's something coach Paul Hackett has
been stressing all summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't really have an idea of where we are until two or
three games into the season,'' Hackett said. ``It's going to take
that long.''
</P>
<P>
   With that said, let's analyze the Trojans' position-by-position
as they enjoy a bye week following the Kickoff Classic. &QL; 
Quarterback
</P>
<P>
   No one should get too anxious about Carson Palmer's sluggish
start. He's still the single most important player on the team, and
the unspoken leader. Everyone draws extra confidence when he's
playing, which is something that immediately disappeared when he
became injured last season.
</P>
<P>
   Once the rust goes away from sitting out last season, Palmer
should be fine. As usual, Mike Van Raaphorst is the backup and true
freshman Matt Cassel of Chatsworth High will be the No.3
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Cassel is headed for a redshirt season, but he will make every
road trip in case of emergency. &QL; 
Running backs
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest question mark on the team before the season,
but sophomore Sultan McCullough's MVP performance in the Kickoff
Classic (128 yards) seems to have allayed fears USC would not have
a reliable tailback.
</P>
<P>
   But the Trojans still have not seen junior Malaefou MacKenzie at
his best, limited to three carries because of an injured hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Petros Papadakis is back as the short-yardage specialist,
meaning true freshman Chris Howard will probably redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   A surprise this season could be sophomore Chad Pierson running
the ball out of the single-back formation. Junior Charlie Landrigan
is the blocking back and will occasionally catch a pass out of the
backfield. &QL; 
Wide receivers
</P>
<P>
   Kareem Kelly, the Pacific-10 Conference Freshman of the Year,
will be double-teamed all season. But he's still the offense's
jewel, a game-breaker who must see the ball at least 10 times a
game.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Marcell Allmond has locked up the other starting job
and has the hands to become a dependable receiver. After that,
things become more muddled. Sophomore Steve Stevenson is just now
coming back from a hamstring injury, and senior Matt Nickels earned
a scholarship in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't surprise anyone, though, if true freshman Keary
Colbert becomes the No.3 receiver. &QL; 
Offensive line
</P>
<P>
   Besides running back, this is the other major concern, but
again, the Penn State game turned out to be nice opening effort.
They certainly committed fewer penalties in the opener than has
been normal for USC linemen the previous four years.
</P>
<P>
   Senior center Eric Denmon is the heart of the line, while
sophomore guard Zach Wilson might be the most talented. Junior
Faaesea Mailo has emerged as an impact player, stealing the right
tackle position.
</P>
<P>
   The key will be whether the inspirational high of the opener can
be sustained over the course of the season. And whether the false
starts and holding penalties will also remain memories. &QL; 
Defensive line
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans have six players who have started in their career.
Senior defensive tackle Ennis Davis is clogging up the middle and
demanding double coverage, while junior Ryan Nielsen was one of the
Trojans' most improved players last season.
</P>
<P>
   On the outside, senior Matt Childers says little but plays hard
and is the most consistent of the ends. He's backed up by senior
Shamsud-Din Abdul-Shaheed, who has been a part-time starter in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   The other end spot is even stronger, as senior Sultan
Abdul-Malik returns after a year at linebacker, and junior Lonnie
Ford is coming off his best season and will split time with Malik. &QL; 
Linebackers
</P>
<P>
   Senior Zeke Moreno might be the best player on the team, and
most dominating. He's also the Trojans' team leader. Senior Markus
Steele is also hoping to have a big season to propel him into the
NFL draft, but needs to stay healthy.
</P>
<P>
   The one mystery is junior Kori Dickerson, who is still learning
the position but is considered an upgrade over last season.
</P>
<P>
   The problem here could be if an injury occurs, and then the
talent and experience drops considerably. Otherwise, this group is
considered the heart of the defense's excellence. &QL; 
Defensive backs
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans can substitute so much here that it's difficult to
tell at times who is playing. Troy Polamalu and Ife Ohalete are the
starting safeties, but Frank Strong and DeShaun Hill could just as
easily be in the game, or even true freshman Matt Grootegoed.
</P>
<P>
   It's a depth problem that secondary coach Dennis Thurman loves
having. Cornerback is a similar story. Kris Richard and Darrell
Rideaux are the starters, but Chris Cash and Kevin Arbet play
nearly as much, and Cash will be battling Rideaux for a starting
spot all season. &QL; 
Coaching
</P>
<P>
   Hackett knows it's time to produce or else. The feeling is that
he needs nine victories and a major bowl bid, or USC could be
looking for another coach.
</P>
<P>
   But Hackett thinks he took care of any potential problems by
revamping his coaching staff, bringing in newcomers Kennedy Pola
(running backs), A.J. Christoff (linebackers) and Brian
Schottenheimer (tight ends) and placing highly respected Steve
Morton on the offensive line, which he coached for 10 years at
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   After these moves, there won't be anyone else to blame if the
Trojans don't perform.!dlim!!tvspt2!Ego Check:!off! The Trojans are
bursting with confidence after Penn State, but better not be too
cocky heading into game with Buffaloes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
