<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSUN SEEKS TO LEAVE CONFERENCE ON HIGH NOTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They're exactly where they always are in the Big
Sky Conference preseason football rankings: Nowhere near the top.
</P>
<P>
   That's just fine with the Matadors of Cal State Northridge, who
are picked to finish sixth in the Big Sky.
</P>
<P>
   They intend to use the ranking as a rallying cry in their final
season in the conference. CSUN is moving to the Big West next
season - a nonfootball conference - leaving one final attempt to
make its mark on the Big Sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Sky (rankings) are nothing new to me,'' junior
linebacker Cos Abercrombie said. ``They always put our chips down.
Plus, we didn't have a great season last year. And especially with
the probation thing. But that makes us more hungry. I always like
the underdog. Being the underdog makes you want to prove everybody
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would be better than getting the Big Sky ring now when
supposedly we can't?''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN can win the ring, all right. However, it can't accept the
postseason berth that comes with it.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors were placed on probation in June for NCAA
violations under former coach Ron Ponciano. CSUN has been
scrambling to recover ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a blow with that,'' running back Alan Taylor said.
``But as a team, we don't really think about it that much. We look
at the Big Sky championship. That's what we're after.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Kearin, in his second season as head coach, has his team
believing anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope at the end of the year we're 11-0 and disappointed as
heck,'' Kearin said. ``I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN will be a huge underdog when it opens against Division I-A
Air Force on Saturday. And then there's defending Big Sky champion
Montana, not to mention Portland State, Northern Arizona and
Sacramento State.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kearin believes his team will contend in what he believes
will be a more balanced conference.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is the return of quarterback Marcus Brady and a solid
receiving corps. Brady, a junior, threw for 3,326 yards and 24
touchdowns last year. His favorite target, Drew Amerson, is back.
Amerson led the team in receptions (74) and yards receiving (897).
Three more receivers, returnee Gil Rodriguez and transfers Jason
Stone and Ryan Felix, also are reason for optimism. Six starters
return on offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is by far the best conditioned team I've ever been on,''
Rodriguez said. ``The commitment is there. Coach Kearin has made
that commitment and we have something to look forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   Only three starters return on defense, which surrendered 431.1
yards per game. An early strength appears to be a linebacking corps
that includes Abercrombie, Pieter Keus and Lewis Blanton.
</P>
<P>
   The glaring weakness is depth, particularly on both the
offensive and defensive lines. Serious injuries would be
devastating. Many linemen already are nursing minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depth is more obvious every day,'' Kearin said. ``But that's
the normal wear and tear of camp.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN was 6-5 overall and finished fourth in the Big Sky at 5-3
last season. The Matadors were 4-4 on the field but earned a
forfeit victory over Northern Arizona, which used an ineligible
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe that four teams could easily go undefeated,''
Kearin said. ``Montana, Portland State, I think Sacramento State
can do really well and I think we can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it could be a long season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I'm not going to say we're going to win because
I don't know for sure,'' fullback Crayton Milton said. ``But we'll
go down in the alley with all our starters.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana is ranked second in the Sports Network's Division I-AA
preseason poll while Portland State is ranked 12th. CSUN received
votes and is 37th.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're after the Big Sky this year,'' Abercrombie said. ``The
Big Sky hasn't been givin' us no love. They're lovin' Montana and
those teams that barely beat us. I think we can do big things. They
shouldn't count us out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
