u f BC-FORD-VENEZUELA-765&AMP;AD     08-31 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-VENEZUELA-765&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELAN AGENCY REQUESTS CRIMINAL CHARGES AGAINST FORD AND
BRIDGESTONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TIRE-RECALL, TIRE-LABOR) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Accusing Ford Motor Co. and Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. with
conspiring to hide tire defects that caused dozens of deaths,
Venezuela's consumer protection agency Thursday asked that nation's
prosecutor to bring criminal charges against both companies.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies ``had concealed vital information from
Venezuelan consumers,'' said Samuel Ruh Rios, chairman of the
Venezuelan consumer agency. He said the companies were aware that
``a macabre combination of a soft suspension and an inadequate
tire,'' was to blame for at least 80 accidents in which 47 people
had died.
</P>
<P>
   The tires involved in Venezuela are similar to those being
recalled in the United States because they are suspected of tearing
apart at high speeds and contributing to roll over crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. National Highway Traffic Safety Administration in
Washington Thursday increased by 26 the number of deaths that have
been linked to the recalled Firestone tires. That brings to 88 the
total number of deaths being investigated by the agency, along with
more than 250 injuries in 1,400 complaints the agency has received
concerning tire separations on Ford's popular sport utility
vehicle, Ford Explorer, among others, which has been equipped with
the suspect tires.
</P>
<P>
   In Dearborn, Jacques Nasser, the president of Ford, defended the
company's actions in Venezuela and denied any attempt to mislead
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accusation from the Venezuelan government that Ford
Venezuela lied is absolutely unfounded,'' he told reporters during
a conference call. He added, however, that Ford would cooperate
with any Venezuelan investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser insisted that the problem ``was a tire issue, not a
vehicle issue,'' and said that 1.5 million tires had already been
replaced, representing about 22 percent of the 6.5 million
Firestone tires being recalled. Bridgestone/Firestone officials,
speaking in a conference call , said they had not yet had time to
translate the report from Venezuela, but said they did not believe
they had done anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe there was a conspiracy,'' said Christine
Karbowiak, a Firestone vice president. ``We are working closely
with Ford however to identify the cause or causes of the problems
that have been evident.''
</P>
<P>
   The stream of accusations and news reports have hurt both
companies on Wall Street. Shares of Ford dropped 7 percent, or
$1.75, to $24.25, closing at a 52-week low. In Japan, where
Bridgestone is based, shares of Bridgestone closed down 98 yen at
1380 yen.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelan consumer authorities contended that after the first
reports there in 1998 of Firestone tire blowouts causing Ford's
Explorers to roll over, the two companies held a series of secret
meetings to determine what was wrong. Evidence led them to suspect
the original equipment Wilderness model tires from Firestone were
failing, investigators said, and instead of initiating a costly
recall, Ford asked Firestone's parent company, Bridgestone, to
redesign the tire by adding a new, fifth ply.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone officials Thursday confirmed that they had discussed
redesigns with Ford Venezuela starting in January 1999, but said
such discussions were normal.
</P>
<P>
   After those meetings between Bridgestone and Ford, new tires
produced at Firestone's plant in the Venezuelan city of Valencia
were marked to indicate they contained five plys, but most
contained no more than four, investigators said. Firestone
acknowledged that all but a few of the tires had been mistakenly
stamped as having five plys, but that they always met Ford's
specifications.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford engineers who examined some of the Venezuelan tires
made at that time found that their treads separated at a rate 500
times greater than Firestone's ATX tires made in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Venezuelan investigators also charged that Ford's doorjamb
decals recommended lower tire pressures than those set by
Firestone. And they said original shock absorbers were not strong
enough to handle a fully loaded Explorer, making them dangerous to
operate. Instead of recalling the vehicles and replacing the shock
absorbers, the investigators charged that Ford told dealers to
quietly change them without notifying regulators or consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The Venezuelan agency, the Institute for Consumer Protection and
Education, does not have the power to file criminal charges.
Therefore, the agency recommended that the Venezuelan federal
prosecutor do so. It also requested that Bridgestone/Firestone
recall all the defective tires and that Ford replace all suspect
shock absorbers on Explorers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For American lawyers representing victims of Explorer rollovers
and their families, the Venezuelan report may help build a case
that the manufacturers had deliberately withheld information about
the tire problem.
</P>
<P>
   For Venezuela, the action by the consumer agency, which was
created in 1995, Thursday's announcement marks the country's
attempt to carve out a more influential role in international
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   However, the poorly funded and understaffed Venezuelan agency
has never undertaken a case like this before, and its investigation
may face challenges to its credibility. The evidence presented in
the agency's report includes examinations of Explorers parked in
public lots and American newspaper articles taken from the
Internet. Also, the consumer agency's chief investigator is an
agronimist, and the technical expert heading the tire inquiry is a
former Goodyear tire salesman and race car driver without
engineering qualifications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
