<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7739 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-RAMSEY0901-COX     08-31 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ramsey case shows no sign of end
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The police interviews were over and Patsy Ramsey was
answering the final question at an Atlanta news conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Will the Ramseys now fade away, she was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never fade away until we find who did this,'' she
said. ``So there.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments earlier, the much-hyped interviews had ended in an odd,
yet somehow predictable way.
</P>
<P>
   Odd in that the attorneys exploded, released tapes to the media
and made outrageous challenges to one another. Predictable in that
nobody walked away in handcuffs, and nobody walked away cleared of
suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   In this nearly four-year saga of the 1996 murder of JonBenet
Ramsey, the odd has become the predictable. And it's kept us on the
edge of our seats, tuned into America's No. 1 whodunit. Not
necessarily with news _ just something new.
</P>
<P>
   Now a weeklong onslaught of Ramsey news has the story again
dominating the media and the Internet, TV talk shows and dinner
table chats.
</P>
<P>
   Every time it seems like the final chapter, it turns out to be
just the next one.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Patsy Ramsey, speaking as though to the police,
told USA Today, ``If you think I did it, let's have a trial and get
it over with.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Ramseys have provided police with boots they
say may have been worn by her killer. Boulder, Colo., police, for
their part, say the boots are being tested. But they stressed that
the boots belong to a man who had committed suicide, and that his
DNA already had been tested and did not match any evidence found at
the crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   If that's not enough, the attorneys are talking about releasing
transcripts from the grand jury proceeding on the case.
</P>
<P>
   To the delight of television viewers, the Ramseys' attorney
released a 22-minute video segment from the police interrogation.
On it, prosecutor Mike Kane verbally attacks Ramsey attorney Lin
Wood for not letting Patsy Ramsey answer some questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sham,'' Kane says to Wood, as the prosecutor rises
as though threatening to walk out on the talks. ``This is a big
publicity stunt on your part.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the attorneys have promised to release the full tape of this
week's 10 hours of police interviews with the Ramseys in Atlanta,
which were the first interviews with them in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Hooked? Much of America is.
</P>
<P>
   But as the latest Ramsey drama reaches a fevered pitch, the
question remains why we're so stuck on this story.
</P>
<P>
   Even the O.J. Simpson story didn't hold people's attention so
intensely for so long, and that had an arrest and two trials. The
Ramsey story is somewhat of a national Rorschach test _ the ink
blot test where you see in it whatever you want. From soap opera
drama, to legalistic debate on the evidence, to cynicism on the
wealthy, to cries of the media's falling into the tabloid abyss,
there is something for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has all the elements _ the money, the exclusivity, the
little girl,'' said Robert Butterworth, a Los Angeles clinical
psychologist who has discussed the media on ``CBS This Morning''
and ``Larry King Live.''
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't O.J. The Ramseys were not famous beforehand. They
were just an upwardly mobile family in Boulder, Colo., when their
6-year-old daughter, JonBenet, was found strangled and beaten the
day after Christmas 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in this tale of the golden-haired princess' death, the
bungled police probe, and the ravenous media, John and Patsy Ramsey
became celebrities. And that changed everything in terms of news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Joey Buttafuoco syndrome _ that somebody could become
famous just for being in the news so long,'' said Matthew Kerbel,
the author of the media book, ``If It Bleeds, It Leads.''
</P>
<P>
   News judgment can become slippery around celebrities. Stories
becomes not so much about events, as about the people involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Ramseys have to do is open their mouths,'' and the
cameras start rolling, Kerbel said. Their ascent into the pantheon
of pop culture figures was secured, he added, when they became the
butt of jokes by Jay Leno on late night television.
</P>
<P>
   ``She could be Tammy Faye Baker,'' Kerbel said.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is on the street. Patsy Ramsey, among the most
recognizable women in America, and her husband were walking down
Atlanta's Peachtree Street when a truck carrying construction
workers rode by. ``John! Patsy! John! Patsy!'' they called.
</P>
<P>
   Patsy smiled and waved, the wave of one acknowledging fame.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the Ramseys' increasing public presence is
bringing people to their side, depends on whom you talk to.
</P>
<P>
   For some people, Patsy Ramsey's character has evolved from a
strange woman who thrust her daughter into bizarre tiny-tot beauty
pageants, to a tragic figure twice victimized _ by the loss of her
child and her tribulations in the public spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   But others can't shake their first impression of two parents who
avoided police early in this investigation while hiring a public
relations firm.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the story these days is being driven by the Ramseys,
who live in Atlanta. They have taken on any comers who challenge
their innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem on a public relations offensive, trying to convey
that they're willing to cooperate and have nothing to hide,'' said
Kerwin Swint, an assistant professor of political science at
Kennesaw State University.
</P>
<P>
   The latest front-page grabber came Wednesday when the Ramsey's
attorney Wood and prosecutor Kane, continuing their battle from
days ago, sparred on CNN's ``Larry King Live.'' After Wood
challenged Kane to explain why a grand jury did not indict his
clients, they discussed seeking the release of the grand jury
transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   That's not likely to happen, said Christopher Mueller, a law
professor at the University of Colorado. The release would require
the approval of a judge. The secrecy provision for grand jury
proceedings, he said, is aimed at protecting everyone interviewed
and discussed before the grand jury, especially those who might
have been investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Customarily, the transcripts would only be released to the
prosecutor or witnesses, and for their eyes only. Since the Ramseys
were not called as witnesses, they would have no right to even
request the transcripts _ unless they were charged with the crime,
said Mueller.
</P>
<P>
   For now, people keep talking. Place a dozen strangers at a table
and mention JonBenet, and they can all talk about the little girl
as if they knew her. They know the color of her hair and eyes, and
they can discuss in detail the facts of her death. They've heard
gossip about her mother and father, and they've complained about
the police not solving the crime.
</P>
<P>
   On a larger scale, that's what this story does for people across
America. In computer chat rooms, for instance, people's familiarity
with the case has them conversing as though they all live in the
same small town. And they're all worried about one little girl's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
