r s BC-CAR-MOTORS-COLUMN-LAD     08-31 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORS-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST PLACE NO PIECE OF CAKE FOR DRAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM HADDOCK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USAC Sprint car driver Jay Drake caught and passed
series leader Tony Elliott in Attica, Ohio, on Aug. 25. Then he
lost his lead in Lawrenceburg, Ind., the following night.
</P>
<P>
   Drake, a graduate of Buena High in Ventura, won the race at
Attica Raceway Park to take the lead in the series standings. But
Elliott won the Danny Milburn Classic at Lawrenceburg Speedway and
now holds a 14-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably how it's going to be for the rest of the
races,'' Drake said. ``If I don't win, Tony probably will.''
</P>
<P>
   With four races to go in the Sprint car season, Drake knows he
has to win more than Elliott if he wants the points championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Sprint cars return to action at Cedar Rapids, Iowa, tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Drake missed the Sprint cars' first trip to Cedar Rapids earlier
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I hadn't,'' Drake said. ``The points would be all
wrapped up by now.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to racing his Sprint car at Cedar Rapids, he will
also be racing a USAC Midget at Indiana on Saturday and at
Wisconsin on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Drake is also second in points on the Midget
circuit, he has all but surrendered his pursuit of series leader
Kasey Kuhn.
</P>
<P>
   Drake's Midget car owner, Ralph Potter, decided to quit running
the car last month and he missed a race because of it. Now Drake is
back on the Midget circuit in a car owned by Keith Kunz, who also
owns his Sprint car.
</P>
<P>
   But Drake says he's too far back to catch Kuhn.
</P>
<P>
   Hornaday listens to advice from owner Earnhardt: NASCAR Busch
Series driver Ron Hornaday Jr., coming off a 15th-place finish in
the Food City 250 at Bristol Motor Speedway, is paying attention to
what his team owner, Dale Earnhardt, has to say about his next
race.
</P>
<P>
   The Busch Series drivers head to Darlington Raceway on Saturday
for the Duralube 200.
</P>
<P>
   Hornaday's history at the South Carolina track has not been
good. In his first Busch Series race there, as a substitute for
Steve Park in 1998, he failed to qualify. Earlier this year at
Darlington, Hornaday, driving the Earnhardt-owned NAPA Auto Parts
Chevrolet, made the field, but fought to stay in the top 20 during
the race.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, who was racing in the NASCAR Winston Cup race at
Darlington the next day, came over the radio and told Hornaday to
change his line on the track. The advice led to an eighth-place
finish for Hornaday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have never thought that the line he wanted me to run
would work considering how the car felt, but it did,'' Hornaday
said. ``That's the great thing about having Dale as an owner. He
has so much track experience. He knows every bump on every track.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornaday, who has won two Busch Series races and has five
top-five finishes, is fifth in the series standings and second in
rookie points.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Series heads to Madera Speedway: Auggie Vidovich of
Lakeside has won the last two NASCAR Featherlite Southwest Series
events and will look to extend his winning streak in the Food 4
Less MDA 100 at Madera Speedway on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   With two straight wins, Vidovich is 87 points out of first place
in the series standings. Matt Crafton of Tulare leads the series
with 1,910 points.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Woodside of Saugus is fourth in points; Greg Pursley of
Newhall is fifth; M.K. Kanke of Frazier Park is sixth and Frank
Maronski Jr. of Quartz Hill is eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Winston West races in Utah on Labor Day: The NASCAR Winston West
Series heads to Rocky Mountain Raceways on Monday for the Bank One
250.
</P>
<P>
   Series leader Brendan Gaughan of Las Vegas holds a 210-point
lead in the standings and is in search of his first championship.
The Bank One 250 is the ninth race of the 12-race Winston West
Series schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Sedgwick of Acton, who finished second in the Aug. 19
Winston West Series race at Irwindale Speedway, is sixth in points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-00 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
