<DOCNO> NYT20000831.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7744 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NY-LAZIO-FUNDRAISING-     08-31 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-FUNDRAISING-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO'S FUND RAISING IS SETTING RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT23 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio may be less well known than his opponent in the
New York Senate contest (not to mention the Republican who dropped
out), but in terms of fund-raising, he has already entered their
league. Lazio collected $10.7 million in just seven weeks this
summer, his aides said Thursday, leaving little doubt that he will
have the means to battle for the seat despite his late start.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has taken in a total of $19.2 million since jumping into
the Senate race in May, nearly as much as Hillary Rodham Clinton,
who has been raising money for more than a year and has collected
$21.9 million. She raised $3.3 million in the seven-week period
this summer: July 1 to Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's success with donors suggests that no matter who is on
the Republican line _ mayor, congressman, school board member _ the
checks will pour in because of hostility among some people across
the country to the Democratic candidate, Clinton. And Lazio, a
once-obscure congressman from Suffolk County, has readily harnessed
that sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Rick Lazio,'' he wrote in an unusually short, one-page
fund-raising letter this summer. ``It won't take me six pages to
convince you to send me an urgently needed contribution for my
United States Senate campaign in New York. It will take only six
words: I'm running against Hillary Rodham Clinton. Sincerely, Rick
Lazio.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Clinton's financial edge so far, Lazio has more money on
hand, an important indicator. Lazio began the race with $3.5
million left over from his House campaigns, and then collected
$15.7 million. After expenditures, largely for television
advertisements and direct mailings, he has $10.2 million in the
bank. She has $7.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns released summaries of their finances Thursday,
but not lists of donors and expenditures. They are required to
submit those lists to the Federal Election Commission this month.
</P>
<P>
   Before exiting the race to focus on his treatment for prostate
cancer, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani repeatedly set fund-raising records
with a campaign that appealed to the distaste of conservatives and
others for Clinton. With the same strategy, Lazio is surpassing
even Giuliani's records.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three months of this year, for example, Giuliani
took in $7 million, less than Lazio's total for the recent seven
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is historic,'' said Bill Dal Col, Lazio's campaign manager,
a longtime political consultant who led Steve Forbes' presidential
campaigns. ``I have never seen numbers like this.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   These totals would have been unthinkable in previous races. In
the seven-week summer period in the 1998 Senate contest in New
York, the eventual winner, Charles E. Schumer, raised $627,000,
while the incumbent, Alfonse D'Amato, raised $1.7 million,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer spent $16.7 million on the entire race.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who raised $23.3 million for his aborted run, and
Clinton have both surpassed the record for fund raising by a
nonincumbent in a Senate race, the $21 million taken in by Oliver
North, a Republican, in his failed race in Virginia in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The record for spending will not be known until November: Jon
Corzine, a Wall Street multimillionaire, spent $35.5 million,
nearly all of it his own money, to win the Democratic Senate
primary in New Jersey. He is expected to spend more in the general
election against the Republican, Rep. Robert D. Franks.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The New York contest is likely to be the most expensive Senate
race in the nation's history, and that is without taking into
account so-called soft money: large donations raised and spent by
party committees. Clinton has raised soft money, and while Lazio
has not, outside groups not connected to his campaign have bought
ads to help him.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Clinton, Giuliani took in more money from donors
outside the state than a typical Senate candidate, and Lazio is
expected to focus more on such contributors this month. He has
scheduled fund-raising visits next week to Alabama, Texas and
California. The Lazio campaign said it did not know what percentage
of its recent donations were from out-of-state.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has raised about 60 percent of her individual donations
out of state.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides, who long ago resigned themselves to the idea
that she is reviled by politically active (and check-writing)
conservatives, said they were not daunted by Lazio's tally. ``We
are not surprised that Congressman Lazio outraised us given his
ability to tap into a well-funded national network of conservative
donors,'' said Cathie Levine, a Clinton campaign spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's aides attribute some of their success to a sense of
urgency among Republicans around the country after Giuliani dropped
out. Many Republican contributors consider the New York Senate race
their second priority after the presidential one, because defeating
Hillary Clinton would end the reign of both Clintons.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lazio holds several fund-raisers, often weaving them into his
schedule as he travels around the state. Campaigning one Monday in
mid-August in the Jamestown area, in the southwest corner of the
state, he held a breakfast fund-raiser, then toured a sprawling
furniture factory, and then held a luncheon fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has benefited from the groundwork laid by Giuliani's
campaign, especially its direct-mail operation, which compiled a
list of more than 200,000 donors nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, and there is no secret about this, there is a great
deal of resentment towards Mrs. Clinton,'' said Bruce J.
Teitelbaum, who led the Giuliani campaign. ``No matter who is going
to run, they are going to raise big money. That said, Rick Lazio
and his team are doing a superb job.''
</P>
<P>
   For some Democrats, the numbers released Thursday confirmed
their fears that Lazio would quickly catch up to Clinton in fund
raising and probably surpass her by November. That does not mean
that he will win, but it does make him less of an underdog, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could run a tree against her, and it wouldn't matter,''
said Hank Sheinkopf, a Democratic political consultant not involved
in the Senate race. ``The Republicans will do anything to stop
her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
