<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 AD-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Unwelcome surprises shaking Bush's confidence
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON
 &HT;    and R.G. RATCLIFFE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two weeks of sliding poll numbers and unwelcome surprises have
shaken the confidence of Gov. George W. Bush's presidential
campaign for the first time since his January loss in the New
Hampshire Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Aides and associates in Austin and on the road with Bush are
expressing concern privately that the road to the White House may
be rockier than they once expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a roller coaster ride,'' said one aide, who
expressed confidence that things will turn back around.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told reporters Thursday that he plans to come out of the
Labor Day weekend focusing attention on Vice President Al Gore to
eliminate the bounce that Gore got from the Democratic National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to continue to hear the failed leadership
theme,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to keep reminding the American people that it's one
thing to give flowery speeches and talk big about issues, but
they've had a chance to get something done on prescription drugs
and the Medicare program, for example, and they haven't
performed.''
</P>
<P>
   While national tracking polls show Bush with a narrow lead over
Gore, state polls are starting to indicate electoral college
trouble for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But informal conversations with staff suggest that some of the
more experienced political operatives view the rough patch as
simply a typical development in a close campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A poll in the battleground state of Ohio, where Bush was
campaigning Thursday, showed Bush with a slight lead but in a
statistical tie with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, where Bush's brother Jeb is governor, was once
considered solid Bush country. But a new poll there shows Bush has
gone from leading by 8 percentage points to trailing by 8 points.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is striking fire in Florida with his promise to make
prescription drugs affordable for seniors. Bush plans to lay out
his own prescription drug plan next week, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   A loss in Florida would undermine Bush's electoral college
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's decision to focus more on Gore's record next week may be
a reflection of a Rasmussen Research tracking poll that found the
two candidates' favorable and unfavorable ratings are now almost
identical.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was viewed favorably by 46 percent of those surveyed and
unfavorably by 41 percent. Bush's rating was 49 percent favorable,
38 percent unfavorable. Up to this point in most polls, Bush's
unfavorable rating has been much lower than Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction by Bush and his aides has played out visibly in
Austin and on the road.
</P>
<P>
   On the road, Bush's campaign had announced plans to focus
attention on education for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, Bush was knocked off message by questions over
whether he would debate Gore in prime time and by renewed focus on
health care in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor and his staff have been reacting nervously
and sometimes angrily.
</P>
<P>
   They were especially annoyed with state Attorney General John
Cornyn for not warning them about a federal judge's ruling that the
state's Medicaid system is inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise ruling by U.S. District Judge William Wayne Justice
seemed to give additional ammunition to Gore's charges that health
care in Texas has been inadequate during Bush's administration as
governor.
</P>
<P>
   As he has for much of the week, the governor played offense and
defense on the campaign trail in Ohio Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to question the motives of Justice for ruling during
the campaign that Texas has failed to adequately care for
low-income children in its Medicaid program.
</P>
<P>
   He said, though, that ``William Wayne Justice is a well-known
activist, liberal judge in the state of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aug. 14 order, which caught Bush and his campaign staff by
surprise, is being used by Democrats to reinforce their attacks
against the Texas governor. Bush first learned of the order on
Wednesday from a news report.
</P>
<P>
   Justice, a 1968 appointee of President Johnson, has issued
several controversial and landmark decisions during his long
career, including an order 20 years ago for massive improvements in
the Texas prison system.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit over children's health care that prompted the
federal court ruling in Texas was filed in 1993, when Democrat Ann
Richards was still governor. In the latest development, Justice
held that Texas has not lived up to terms of a consent decree
entered in 1996 under Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Texas will appeal the latest ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working hard to sign up as many children as we can to
the children's health insurance program as well as to Medicaid,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Justice's ruling concerns an early diagnostic and
treatment program, which the judge determined wasn't being
adequately carried out by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said that Texas had improved its
record of screening children's health care needs under that program
since Bush has been governor. She said that Texas now screens 61
percent of the children eligible for the program, compared with a
54 percent national screening rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the vice president wants to complain about this, then he
better go complain about America. We do a better job on this in
Texas than Al Gore does in America,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Thursday, Bush notched his campaign's 100th visit to a
school, this time the Springfield High School in Holland, near
Toledo, in northwest Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   In his most pointed speech of the week, he told several thousand
students and adults packed into the school's gymnasium that the
Clinton-Gore administration failed to deliver on a 1992 campaign
promise to cut taxes for the middle class and failed to help senior
citizens obtain prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``After seven and a half years of empty rhetoric, I can
understand why the young become disillusioned (with politics),''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
