<SLUG> BC-GORE-PATIENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Gore tells Seattle voters to reject cynicism and embrace his
plan
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JULIE MASON
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Closing out a week of campaigning on the Democratic
agenda for health care, Vice President Al Gore on Thursday urged
more than 2,000 supporters at a downtown rally to reject cynicism
and ``ironic detachment,'' and embrace his plan for America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open your hearts and allow yourselves to really, sincerely
believe without reservation that we can do the right thing in
America, redeem the promise of our democracy and be the better for
it,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who for the past several days has seemed invigorated by a
surge in the polls and the burgeoning crowds turning out to greet
him, campaigned with running mate Joseph Lieberman in support of a
patient's bill of rights. They addressed the crowd in a downtown
plaza and picked up the endorsement of the American Nurses
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the Democratic running mates took a ferry
ride to Bainbridge Island to meet voters. Gore served coffee to
reporters, and Lieberman told one ferry commuter that the campaign
is still enjoying momentum from the party's national convention two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels real good,'' Lieberman said, ``it feels like we've
got some wind behind us.``
</P>
<P>
   Later, at the campaign rally downtown, Lieberman complained
about new Republican ads that began airing Thursday that tweak Gore
on his past fund-raising at a Buddhist temple and exaggerations
about his role in the development of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry to say George Bush's promise to change the tone of
American politics has run into the reality of a troubled
Bush-Cheney campaign,'' Lieberman said. ``These attack ads break
his promise not to launch personal attacks in this campaign, and
they drag us back to the worst politics of the past.``
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee ad is airing in 17 states.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, spokeswoman for Texas Gov. Bush, the Republican
presidential nominee, said the ad's message _ suggesting that Gore
is dishonest _ is no worse than Democratic ads that ``call the
governor a polluter or suggest he doesn't care about kids.``
</P>
<P>
   The escalating rhetoric comes as polls tighten and the close
race heats up for key states heavy with electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our opponents have been trying to tell the country that we are
worse off today than we were eight years ago, but I don't think
so,'' Gore said. ``We've got a lot of problems that need to be
addressed, but eight years ago there were many more.''
</P>
<P>
   In calling for passage of a patient's bill of rights, Gore and
Lieberman are pushing a plan they say would assure patients access
to specialists, emergency room care, an appeals process and more
responsive health maintenance organizations. Throughout the week,
the Democrats have been touting aspects of their health care
agenda, including plans for Medicare, prescription drug benefits
and children's health care coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is to detail his own health care agenda next week, has
said he supports a patient's bill of rights that would allow
patients to sue their HMOs, but he opposes any federal legislation
on the subject that would supersede state's laws.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his objective is to move power in the health care
equation from insurance companies and HMOs and back to the
patients.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle rally coincided with the unveiling of a new campaign
ad recorded during Gore and Lieberman's recent four-day campaign
trip down the Mississippi River. The 30-second spot shows Gore at a
rally in Bellevue, Iowa, complaining about HMO ``bean counters''
who try to play God. &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
