<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TISSUE-SELLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOTECH FIRM TO SELL LEFTOVER SURGICAL TISSUE FOR GENE STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Beginning next week some surgery patients at Beth
Israel Deaconess Medical Center will be asked to allow leftover
tissue from their operations to be delivered to a Massachusetts
biotech company that will attempt to sell it to genetic researchers
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The pioneering agreement between the hospital and biotech
startup Ardais Corp., of Lexington, marks the latest effort to make
sense of the deluge of information coming from the Human Genome
Project, which traced much of the human genetic map but did not
tell scientists exactly what each gene does.
</P>
<P>
   Ardais hopes to eventually create a massive tissue catalog,
allowing researchers to place Internet orders for tissue samples
from patients with the specific diseases they are studying.
</P>
<P>
   Both the hospital and the tissue bank want to help scientists
match genes to particular diseases, then develop gene-based cures.
Hundreds of conditions, from cancer to schizophrenia are thought to
have genetic roots. However, genetic research is often plodding
because of the difficulty in obtaining tissue samples.
</P>
<P>
   Four area hospitals are in talks with Ardais to enter into
similar arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Israel owns a small part of Ardais, and said Thursday that
all profits from the arrangement would be put back into medical
research.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was approved by Beth Israel's internal ethics board, as
well as a host of outside medical ethicists. Duke University
Medical Center signed a similar deal this week with Ardais. Several
other out-of-state hospitals are in negotiations with the private
company, which is financed by a small group of venture capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   Tissue samples from the hospital will be sent to Ardais
accompanied by detailed records on patients' family medical
history, age, prescription drug use, and numerous other criteria
relevant to genetic research. But the samples will be anonymous,
containing an alpha-numeric code understood only by Ardais
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, we will protect the rights and
confidentiality of patients,'' said Eric Gordon, president and CEO
of Ardais.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said his company was aware of the ethical questions
involved, and spent weeks with outside ethicists working through
the issues. One of them, Rabbi Meir Sendor of the Young Israel of
Sharon synagogue, said he was impressed with the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They certainly seem to conform with very high standards of
confidentiality and privacy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of Beth Israel patients asked to participate will
be cancer patients, said hospital officials, and some of the top
cancer researchers in the country also consulted with Ardais.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed with their program,'' said Dr. Richard
Klausner, director of the National Cancer Institute, who met
briefly with company executives.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that Ardais must be ``clear and transparent and
absolutely committed to making sure that all the normal steps of
patient confidentiality are even higher than usual because of their
commercial motives.''
</P>
<P>
   Ardais was founded in 1999 with the sole purpose of creating a
tissue bank for genetics researchers. The company has 24 employees.
Gordon said he wants to sign up 20 hospitals by the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning next week, nurses paid for by Ardais will ask some
Beth Israel patients, before they are operated on, if they wish to
participate. Surgeons will be shielded from their decisions to
ensure their performance will not be affected. If a patient agrees,
the excess tissue _ which otherwise would have been thrown away _
will be transferred from the operating room to Ardais' freezers in
Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only arrangement that goes right into the OR to
collect the samples. I haven't heard of that before,'' said Boston
University medical ethicist George Annas.
</P>
<P>
   Annas said the program appeared sound but expressed concern with
a portion of the confidentiality agreement that patients will be
asked to sign, which says: ``The research that is done with your
tissue may not help you directly but it may very well help you or
others in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You may benefit. Those are magic words to patients. You can't
say that. The only people that will benefit are the company and
researchers,'' Annas said.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Israel officials said the hospital's only motive is
furthering genetic research. All profits from the hospital's shares
in Ardais will be put back into the hospital's own scientific work,
said hospital officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
