A7753 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS-WHITFIELD     08-31 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-WHITFIELD0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amiable Falcons tackle reaches milestone for consecutive starts
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLOWERY BRANCH, Ga. _ The time has come to ask, `What's up with
Bob?' Not that Falcons left tackle Bob Whitfield will give you a
straight answer.
</P>
<P>
   But when a 6-foot-5, 318-pound man is about to set a franchise
record by starting his 113th consecutive game _ every game since
the beginning of the 1993 season _ it's worth a special look.
</P>
<P>
   The guy who plays left guard next to Bob is named Bob, too. But
everybody calls him Hallen. He knows there can be only one Bob.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really gets me is how with his vision, with one good eye,
he's able to play left tackle so well,'' Hallen says. ``I think
when everybody thinks of a Bob, it's going to be Bob Whitfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolina quarterback Steve Beuerlein had five surgeries in the
offseason. Bob, who has a cross-eyed stare, has had one in his 28
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was on my dead eye,'' Bob says. ``I was born with a
underdeveloped right eye. The optic nerve never developed. I don't
have full control of it. That's why it will cross sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that a problem on the field?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Bob says. ``That's why the Creator gave you a neck _ so
you can turn your head.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob began turning heads when he was a starter at age 17 at
Stanford. The Falcons made him the eighth pick of the first round
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Three of Atlanta's starting linemen missed at least one start
last season because of injury. Bob hasn't missed one since his
rookie year, and that was because he was a backup.
</P>
<P>
   And Bob doesn't even tape his ankles. So, how does a guy stay
upright so long?
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I give a lot to being lucky,'' Bob says. ``And I
tell people I can't pull a muscle because I'm mostly fat. You learn
certain reactions. You . . . can feel something start to go and you
pull out your ankles or elbows and stuff. And keep your feet
moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the time, Bob doesn't move quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking for the water cooler, look for Bob,'' kicker
Morten Andersen says. ``He'll have his leg up on it. And he's got
that jog down pat.''
</P>
<P>
   What's up, Bob, with the water-cooler pose, and that slow
``speed'' walk at practice?
</P>
<P>
   ``That started (in the mid-1990s) when my back started bothering
me,'' he says. ``I said, `I'm going to put my leg up and take the
pressure off my sciatic nerve.' But . . . now that . . . is so
comfortable. That's just my stance now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
