<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARSMART-TOYOTA-SOLARA-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYOTA SOLARA: ADULT FUN IN THE SUN THAT YOU CAN DEPEND ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 3) 
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toyota is a very successful automaker and it got that way by
making its brand synonymous with dependability.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the Corolla, built in a joint-venture factory with
General Motors in California; the car's Toyota nameplate has made
it a far better seller than the virtually identical (and slightly
cheaper) Chevy Prizm built on the same production lines by the same
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many foreign automakers, Toyota has recognized that many
Americans really do like the kinds of cars that Detroit offers. It
set out to make them, and to make them better.
</P>
<P>
   Want a comfortable family sedan? Try the Camry, a quieter and
far more reliable version of Mom's old Fairlane. You want to
recapture the sense of arrival that Dad had when he got the big
raise and moved up from an Impala to a LeSabre?
</P>
<P>
   Try the Avalon, with its cloudlike ride and optional bench
seats. Want a hushed, soothing luxury car without the firm
suspension and serious road feel of the Mercedes E-Class? The Lexus
LS is waiting quietly for you.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Toyota is back with another marketing marvel: a
midsize convertible at a reasonable price. It won't knock the socks
off serious drivers. Indeed, it won't knock off anybody's socks,
but that's just the point. The Toyota Camry Solara convertible
captures the sense of effortless, tamely glamorous fun in the sun
that so many middle-aged, middle-class adults yearn for.
</P>
<P>
   The Solara convertible is, literally, a variation of the Solara
coupe. Each convertible begins as a semifinished coupe, just off
the production line at Toyota's factory in Cambridge, Ontario. Then
it is shipped to a nearby plant of the American Sunroof Co., a
parts supplier that makes more than a million convertible tops
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Once the well-designed power top is installed, complete with
glass rear window, and some metal is added to stiffen the frame,
the car goes back to Cambridge for painting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since any freshly minted Solara is, in effect, available for
factory conversion, ever-eager-to-please Toyota offers the
convertible in all three Solara trim levels. The base SE model
($25,550 for 2001, including delivery charge) comes with a
2.2-liter 4-cylinder engine borrowed from the Camry, with 16 valves
and a horsepower rating of 135. Standard are a 5-speed manual
transmission, air-conditioning, halogen headlights, a stereo system
with cassette and CD players, power windows, power locks and what
Toyota calls ``wood grain-style accents.''
</P>
<P>
   The SE V6 ($28,490) gets you, no surprise, the 3-liter V-6 from
the Camry, with 24 valves and 200 horsepower. It has antilock
brakes and a four-speed electronically controlled automatic
transmission, both options on the base car. The top-line SLE V6
($30,970) adds leather, a power driver's seat, 16-inch aluminum
wheels (instead of 15-inchers), a JBL sound system, remote locking
and (alas) a stubby spoiler on the rear deck.
</P>
<P>
   Side air bags are a $250 option, and traction control ($300) is
an option only on the SLE.
</P>
<P>
   The black-leather interior of the SLE V6 test car was handsome
and functional, if a little fussy and old-fashioned-looking
compared with the latest designs of several European manufacturers.
The front seats are nothing special, but the rear seating is a
marvel of ergonomic design. Access is easy and egress even easier,
thanks to a foot pedal that one can use to slide the front seat
forward. Two adults can sit back there in relative comfort, in
spite of the space commandeered for the power-roof machinery.
Still, the trunk is adequate for a couple of suitcases and a set of
Callaway clubs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About that convertible top: The American Sunroof Co. did its job
very well. Flip two levers, press a button and there is the sky.
Getting the top back up and locked in place is just as carefree.
With the roof up, visibility is, by the standards of convertibles,
excellent. Again measured in relative terms, the wind noise with
the top closed is subdued. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But this is a car, not a cabana, and the driving experience
counts, too. The V-6 in the SLE has enough power, but is nothing to
brag about. I wouldn't have high hopes for the 4-cylinder version.
Toyota doesn't publish acceleration times, but the 8.2-second
figure that Car and Driver recorded for a 0-to-60 sprint in the
Solara coupe seemed about right.
</P>
<P>
   The handling, too, was adequate but not overwhelming. The Solara
convertible is no embarrassment at the speed limit on a curvy road,
but front-wheel drive, all-weather tires and a relatively soft
suspension make it quick to protest attempts at hard cornering. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My guess, though, is that these shortcomings will matter little
to potential buyers. The real competition to the SLE V6 is not the
lithe (and roughly $6,000 more expensive) BMW 325Ci convertible,
but the very American (and roughly $3,000 less expensive) Chrysler
Sebring JXi convertible. Nobody buys a Sebring for the way it
handles.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota certainly knows how to build serious cars for serious
drivers _ think of the Lexus GS 400. The Solara convertible shows
that the company also knows how to build a car for baby boomers who
just want to add a little sunshine to their long commutes and their
weekends in the country. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
