<HEADER>
A7767 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BRAVES-RACE0901-COX     08-31 0319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-RACE0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Braves, Mets again in the way
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the race in the National League East goes down to
the wire, the six games the Braves and New York Mets play in
September will be doubly important.
</P>
<P>
   In case of a tie, the season series _ not a playoff game _ will
determine the NL East winner, as long as the other team is going to
be the NL wild card.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Braves have the edge. Atlanta leads the series 4-3
after splitting a four-game series in New York and winning two of
three at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams, with the best records in the National League,
play a three-game series in Atlanta on Sept. 18-20 and three games
in New York on Sept. 26-28.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves dominated the Mets the past two seasons, especially
at Turner Field. In winning the season series 9-3 each year, the
Braves were 6-0 at home in 1998 and 5-1 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Mets trailed Atlanta by just one game in the NL
East when they opened a three-game series at Turner Field on Sept.
21. But the Braves swept the series and clinched their eighth
consecutive division title the next weekend in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves play 15 of their 28 September games at home, while
the Mets have only 12 of their 29 at Shea Stadium. The Mets,
however, have easier opponents. New York plays a three-game series
at St. Louis beginning tonight, but then meets teams with losing
records, except for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In the NL playoffs, one best-of-five series will start Oct. 3
and the other Oct. 4. At the moment, the NL East winner would open
at home against the division winner with the worst record _ St.
Louis. The wild card would start on the road against San Francisco.
The team with the home-field advantage gets Games 1 and 2 and, if
necessary, 5.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
