<HEADER>
A7768 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-ART-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      08-31 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH APPROVES NEW AD MOCKING GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BUSH-AD, DEMS-REACT) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT6 and NYT7 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ After struggling for a week to seize the
offensive from Vice President Al Gore, aides to Gov. George W. Bush
said Thursday that they had approved a new and sharp attack
commercial that strikes directly at the Democratic nominee's
character and mocks his appearance at a Buddhist temple
fund-raising event four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-second spot, paid for by the Republican National
Committee, will go on the air on Friday in 17 states, and comes
just a week after Bush personally blocked another commercial
sponsored by the party that also questioned Gore's truthfulness.
The move exposed rifts within the Republican camp over how to
attack Gore without violating Bush's vow to keep his campaign
positive.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides said they had wholeheartedly approved the contents
and tone of the new spot, which they described as
``tongue-in-cheek.'' They said it was a response to critical
advertisements run by the Democrats against Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial shows a television set on a kitchen counter with
Gore on the screen and an unseen woman complaining that the vice
president is ``reinventing himself on television again.'' At one
point the commercial shows an image of Gore at the Buddhist temple
event in 1996 and another segment shows him saying, ``I took the
initiative in creating the Internet.'' At that point, the narrator
says sarcastically, ``Yeah, and I invented the remote control.''
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, the commercial sparked a series of accusations and
counteraccusations between the two campaigns over which one had
``gone negative'' first. Gore's camp wasted no time responding to
the commercial, which was widely shown on television news programs
and on the Internet during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also switched gears on his campaign day, scaling back plans
to focus on a patients' bill of rights in the belief that the
Republican advertisement would backfire and that the Democrats
should not create news that would distract public attention from
it.
</P>
<P>
   The new commercial is part of a broader, coordinated effort by
the Republicans to raise doubts about Gore's ethics and integrity,
which the Bush campaign clearly views as the vice president's
greatest vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   All this week, Bush has criticized Gore as being a weak leader
who broke promises made during the 1992 campaign to cut taxes and
expand prescription drug coverage. And Thursday, in a speech at a
high school in Holland, Ohio, Bush accused Gore of using ``empty
rhetoric'' that had disillusioned young people.
</P>
<P>
   But this more aggressive strategy also comes at the end of a
two-week period in which Gore, clearly enjoying a postconvention
bounce in the polls, has forced Bush to defend himself on issues
like tax cuts, prescription drug prices and when the candidates
would be debating. Since the Democratic National Convention last
month, Gore has pulled even with Bush in many national polls, and
he is even ahead in some swing states where he had previously
trailed.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Democrats asserted Thursday that Bush was
turning negative in an attempt to stanch weakening poll numbers and
reinvigorate a lackluster campaign. They also accused Bush of
hypocrisy, citing his pledge at the Republican National Convention
in early August ``to change the tone of Washington to one of
civility and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Hattaway, a spokesman for the Gore campaign, said Bush
had ``broken his own promise not to engage in personal, negative
attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen this from Bush before, in the primaries,'' Hattaway
added. ``When his back was against the wall, he went negative on
John McCain. Now he's talked out of both sides of his mouth about
changing the tone of the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides have said they had every intention of endorsing
commercials that raised questions about Gore's ethics. But the
content of such advertisements has been a subject of debate among
Bush's top advisers and among Republican officials.
</P>
<P>
   While campaign officials said they viewed questions about the
vice president's credibility as an important part of their message,
they have also been mindful of their candidate's pledge to run an
uplifting, positive campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, on Thursday afternoon, as the Republican Party was
releasing the new commercial, Bush was telling a boisterous
audience at a high school here that ``politics doesn't have to be
ugly and mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Strategists in the Bush campaign and in the Republican Party
have said that the best way to deliver a tough advertisement
questioning Gore's ethics was to employ humor, so as to avoid
appearing mean-spirited.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good-natured way of making a very important point,''
Karen P. Hughes, Bush's director of communications, said of the new
Republican spot. ``That is: the gaping credibility gap between what
Vice President Gore says and what Vice President Gore does.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts were divided about whether the honey-thick
sarcasm of the advertisement would help soften its negative
message, or turn voters off. Ken Goldstein of the University of
Wisconsin, who specializes in analyzing political ads, argued that
a lighter touch could make a negative message more palatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ad gets at what Al Gore's weaknesses are, but it doesn't
do it in what I think some people would consider an unfair way,''
Goldstein said on Political Points, a joint Webcast of ABC News and
the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Carrick, a Democratic consultant, said the commercial
would undermine what has been one of Bush's prime selling points:
his genial personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's biggest asset is his sunny, hopeful presentation of
himself,'' Carrick said. ``Since the Democratic convention, the
Bush people have been trying to become the very mean-spirited
Republicans they have been trying to run away from.''
</P>
<P>
   In the spot, titled ``Really,'' a woman can be heard commenting
on various television images of Gore. Gore is then shown standing
alongside Buddhist monks in saffron robes at the Hsi Lai Temple
near Los Angeles in 1996. Gore contends he did not know the
luncheon was a fund-raiser. But two Democratic fund-raisers were
later found guilty for their roles in soliciting illegal campaign
contributions from people, including monks, who attended the event.
</P>
<P>
   The woman narrator then says, ``Who's he gonna be today? The Al
Gore who raises campaign money at a Buddhist temple? Or the one who
promises campaign finance reform?''
</P>
<P>
   The spot will start running on Friday in closely contested
states, including Ohio, Michigan, Arkansas, Pennsylvania, Missouri
and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican commercial that Bush ordered canceled last week
featured excerpts from a six-year-old interview in which a
stammering Gore said President Clinton had never lied in his
political career.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial, which was never broadcast, suggests that Gore
was refusing to acknowledge that Clinton had made deceptive remarks
about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky. But the advertisement
was actually based on an NBC News interview in which Gore was
talking about his criticism of Oliver North, then a candidate for
Senate from Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Bush later said he objected to the commercial because Gore's
comments had been taken out of context and ``had nothing to do with
the affairs of the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   The last two weeks have been difficult for Bush. Last week, Bush
acknowledged that he needed to do a better job selling his proposed
across-the-board income tax cut _ and then struggled to provide a
coherent explanation of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Bush's aides had pledged he would stick to his
education agenda. But almost every day, other issues have intruded
to dilute his message.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush has been able to ratchet up his criticisms of Gore's
character. In two rousing speeches Thursday Bush laced time and
again into Gore's character and credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``After seven and a half years of empty rhetoric, I can
understand why the young of America become disillusioned,'' he told
3,000 raucous students, parents and Republican partisans in a high
school gymnasium in Holland. ``It's time to put somebody in office
who will do in office exactly what he tells the American people he
intends to do. And that is what I'm going to do should I become the
president of the United States.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
