<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7770 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOP-AD01-COX     08-31 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-AD01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP airs first TV ad attacking Gore's credibility
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new Republican ad begins airing today in 16
states that for the first time attacks Vice President Al Gore's
personal credibility.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-second spot features a woman in her kitchen with
snapshots of Gore flickering across her television screen.
``There's Al Gore reinventing himself on television again,'' the
woman says. ``Like I'm not going to notice. Who's he going to be
today?''
</P>
<P>
   The ad questions Gore's claim that he is committed to campaign
finance reform by raising his controversial visit to a Buddhist
temple in California to raise campaign funds in 1996, an event that
Gore says he did not know was a fund-raiser. The ad also digs at
Gore's claim that he ``took the initiative in creating the
Internet'' while in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee produced and is paying for the
ad, but it is running with the blessing of GOP presidential nominee
George W. Bush, said RNC spokesman Clifford May.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign immediately denounced the ad and accused the
Bush campaign of resorting to the very type of negative campaigning
that Bush vowed to avoid. The Gore campaign turned to running mate
Joe Lieberman to respond to the ad's claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than focusing on the serious issues before our country,
our opponents have hit the airwaves with paid political negative
personal attack ads,'' Lieberman said. ``These new attack ads break
(Bush's) promise not to launch personal attacks in this campaign.
And they drag us back to the worst politics of the past. It seems
to me today, that Governor Bush has sadly changed his tune about
changing the tone.''
</P>
<P>
   In a gambit that voters will be turned off by the ad's negative
tone, Democratic Party officials said they do not plan to respond
with an ad of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are going to reject this,'' said Jenny
Backus, a spokeswoman for the Democratic National Committee. ``We
are not going to respond to this, because we don't think this is
what the American people want to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for both the RNC and Bush defended the advertisement
as a legitimate way to raise questions about Gore's truthfulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's a really good-natured way to make a fundamental
point, which is that there is a difference between what Al Gore
says and what Al Gore does,'' said May. ``I don't think there is
anything personal about it. When you talk about campaign finance
reform, you are clearly talking about issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Bush and Republicans had steered clear of such
pointed attacks on Gore's credibility while Bush was leading in the
polls. The decision to run the ad now, after Gore emerged from the
Democratic National Convention with a healthy bounce in the polls,
showed that Bush and the Republicans are worried about Gore's
surge, Democrats said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When George Bush's back is against the wall, he will do
anything to get elected,'' said Mark Fabiani, Gore's communications
director. ``In the primaries, he visited Bob Jones University and
saluted the Confederate flag. Now, Bush, in an act of desperation,
is breaking his own promise not to engage in personal, negative
attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad, which May described as ``tongue in cheek,'' attempts to
poke fun at Gore with a healthy dose of sarcasm. In response to
Gore's claim about creating the Internet, the woman in the ad says,
``Yea, and I invented the remote control, too. Another round of
this and I'll sell my television.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his claim about creating the Internet, made on CNN in
March of last year, Gore has sought to explain himself by saying
that he promoted the funding from Congress that helped the Defense
Department develop the Internet into what it has become today. Gore
also has repeatedly made jokes about the comment in an effort to
defuse the issue as a potential point of attack.
</P>
<P>
   Republican sources said the ad would run for about one week in
16 battleground states, all of which have already seen a deluge of
advertising from both Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The states are: Arkansas, Florida, Iowa, Kentucky, Louisiana,
Maine, Maryland, Michigan, Missouri, New Mexico, Ohio, Oregon,
Pennsylvania, Washington, West Virginia and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
