<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7771 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-DAVIS-LONGHORNS09     08-31 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-DAVIS-LONGHORNS0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FBy Olin Buchanan
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It looks like a dachshund following a Great Dane.
</P>
<P>
   The photo, which has become a staple for University of Texas
promotions, shows huge Leonard Davis leading diminutive Hodges
Mitchell through a hole during a football game last season. And
although it was an image of the past promoting the present season,
it also hinted to Davis' future after football.
</P>
<P>
   When the 6-foot-6-inch, 360-pound giant stops leading smaller
running backs, he hopes to guide smaller people. He's already
prepared for that by doing volunteer work with middle school
students as part of one of his UT classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some kids get intimidated by my size and then they are perfect
angels,'' Davis said. ``We talk about just life in general and how
if you work hard you can have good things in life. I tell them
nothing comes free or easy.''
</P>
<P>
   For Davis, talking to kids is almost as satisfying as making a
big block, like the one Ricky Williams cut behind on the run in
1998 and broke the NCAA career rushing record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like doing it. You can see a difference being made in
someone's life,'' Davis said. ``I tutor them and monitor them and
you can see them open up. When we talk one-on-one they get
comfortable. If they have problems they can talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis has always spawned plenty of conversation. When he first
walks into a classroom, students are first amazed, then curious.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're like, `Whoa.' They're amazed and they ask, `How tall
are you? What do you weigh? What's your shoe size?' '' Davis said.
``Then they're amazed that I'm just a regular person.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive ends would be amazed, too. In most eyes, Davis is
definitely not a regular person.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN draft analyst Mel Kiper Jr. rates Davis the No. 2 senior
professional prospect, and Davis also was named Preseason
All-America by Playboy, The Sporting News and Street &AMP; Smith's. The
Sporting News listed him as the No. 3-rated Outland Trophy
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially impressive considering that Davis is still
somewhat of novice as offensive tackle. He played defense as a
freshman and was a backup as a sophomore. Last year, his first as a
starter, he was hampered by a sprained ankle _ a considerable
injury when you take into account that his ankle must support 360
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a tender ankle, Davis earned second team All-Big 12
recognition. This year he's healthy, more experienced and in better
shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of Leonard's best playing is ahead of him,'' Texas
Coach Mack Brown said. ``He had by far his best spring this year.
Hopefully, we'll see the Leonard that I know is there. I know he'll
have a great pro career. I just hope he starts this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion of lining up opposite Davis might spur the same
response from defensive ends that comes from kids who want Davis'
autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a little shy when they look at me,'' Davis says of the
students. ``They think I'm a monster. (Teammates) Shaun (Rogers)
and Casey (Hampton) always make fun of me. They say, `You big
monster, you're going to scare those little kids.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There's no need to be scared. Well, at least not the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most interesting thing is the little kids are so cautious
when they approach him,'' Texas publicist John Bianco said. ``We
were about to leave a game at the Cotton Bowl and these tiny kids
are shaking because they want to get an autograph from Leonard. But
he puts that big hand on their head, and he's a gentle giant. They
walk away saying, `You're nice. Can you come to my party?' ''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Cory Redding practiced but without contact Thursday
night. Lee Jackson, Derrick Dockery, Courtnee Garcia and Ervis Hill
were held out, but are expected to be back in action when the
Longhorns resume practice on Monday. . . . Brown gave the team off
today, Saturday and Sunday and encouraged them to watch football
and relax. ``We encouraged them to get off their feet. We purposely
gave them the time off because it takes 24 to 48 hours to get their
legs back after two-a-days,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
