<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORDSTROM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORDSTROM FAMILY TAKES BACK EXECUTIVE POSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After several years of anemic sales growth, the chairman and
chief executive and the chief financial officer of Nordstrom's Inc.
resigned, the company said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Two members of the Nordstrom family, which controls roughly
one-third of the company's stock, have been named to top executive
positions. Blake Nordstrom, 39, will be president, while Bruce
Nordstrom, 66, will be chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released after the stock market closed Thursday,
Enrique Hernandez Jr., a new board member who analysts call the
catalyst for the change, said the board has been disappointed in
the company's performance for the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now at the point where we believe the company would
benefit from a different style of leadership,'' he said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
   For some time, there had been rumors of quarrels between the
Nordstrom family; John Whitacre, the outgoing chairman and chief
executive; and Michael Stein, the departing chief financial
officer. Whitacre, who took the helm of the company in 1997, was
the first nonfamily chief executive in the company's 100-year
history, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Whitacre's tenure did not produce dynamic sales
increases at the department store chain, which is based in Seattle,
many stock analysts were not happy to see the company return to
family management.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disappointed,'' said Michael Exstein, a retail analyst
with Credit Suisse First Boston. ``I think Nordstrom had a problem,
and John Whitacre and the team he had assembled had started a
process to bring the store toward the realities of retail today.
They took steps that were utterly necessary, like pooling
purchases, reducing costs, not resorting to selling on price.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitacre and his team were also widely credited by analysts with
bringing Nordstrom's notorious inventory overstocking problems
under control.
</P>
<P>
   Exstein raised concern that the family would not make the hard
decisions needed to right the stalled retailer. He pointed to
Dillard's, another company where the founding family has a similar
stake, which has been struggling in the current competitive retail
climate.
</P>
<P>
   Nordstrom's stock has been in decline for almost a year and a
half. Until the announcement last night, it had been trading at
about $17.50 a share, almost 50 percent below its 52-week high of
$34.50 a share. At the end of July, Nordstrom warned that earnings
would fall short of forecasts and the stock plunged. Nordstrom
stock closed Thursday at $17.25, down $1.13.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Lakner, a retail analyst with CIBC World Markets, was
more positive about the management changes: ``It was under Bruce
Nordstrom and his generation that Nordstrom saw its greatest years,
in the 1980s,'' she said. Still, Lakner is not recommending the
stock. ``Nordstrom is still a company in search of an identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Nordstrom said it hired a national search firm before settling
on Blake Nordstrom to take the role of president. Nordstrom started
working for the company in 1974. He has worked as a stocker,
salesperson, buyer, merchandise manager and store manager. In 1995,
Blake Nordstrom and his five brothers and cousins were named
co-presidents of the company.
</P>
<P>
   In February 2000, the company eliminated the office of the
co-presidency after John Whitacre reorganized the company into five
units. He named Blake Nordstrom president of the Nordstrom Rack
Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
