<P>
   (NYT37) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- TEN-U.S.-OPEN-6 -- On the
day after her father was thrown out of the National Tennis Center
for yet another outburst, Jelena Dokic returned to the court
Thursday for a second-round match at the U.S. Open. No scenes, no
distractions. Just solid tennis. Playing on a side court that was
less than full, Dokic prevailed over Miriam Oremans 6-1, 6-4.
(Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- TEN-U.S.-OPEN-5 -- Martina
Navratilova made a triumphant return to the U.S. Open Thursday,
pairing with Spain's Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario to defeat Linda Wild
and Sabine Appelmans 5-7, 6-2, 7-6 (7/3) in a first-round match.
The American left-hander, who turns 44 in October, retired from the
WTA in 1994 with 19 career Grand Slam titles in singles and
doubles, one shy of Billie Jean King's all-time record. (Vincent
Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- DRUG-REPORT -- The use of
illegal drugs by children ages 12 to 17 dropped sharply from 1997
to 1999, the federal government said Thursday. And while drug use
among people 18 to 25 went up, it was still far below what it was
two decades ago. Discussing a new survey on drug use, Donna
Shalala, the secretary of health and human services, said that
``the heartening trend among those 12 to 17 is the most important
finding of the National Household Survey on Drug Abuse.'' (Susana
Raab/The New York Times) NO SALES
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) BRUNSWICK, Maine -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- MAINE-MUSEUMS-3 --
With its wealth of woods, water and mountains, Maine has always
lured artists, among them Winslow Homer, Martin Johnson Heade,
Marsden Hartley, Childe Hassam and Maurice Prendergast. And where
there are artists, there are museums to reap their work. Seven
museums have banded together to form the Maine Art Museum Trail
inspired by the tourist-luring Connecticut Impressionist Art Trail
set up by a group of museums a few years ago. 1805 portrait of
Sarah Bowdoin, wife of James Bowdoin III, by Louis-Leopold Boilly
at The Bowdoin College Museum of Art. (The New York Times/Bowdoin
College)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) WATERVILLE, Maine -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- MAINE-MUSEUMS-2 --
With its wealth of woods, water and mountains, Maine has always
lured artists, among them Winslow Homer, Martin Johnson Heade,
Marsden Hartley, Childe Hassam and Maurice Prendergast. And where
there are artists, there are museums to reap their work. Seven
