set up by a group of museums a few years ago. Alex Katz's ``Pari''
(1990) at the Colby College Museum. (The New York Times/Colby
College Museum of Art)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) PORTLAND -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- SUB-MAINE-MUSEUMS-1 -- With
its wealth of woods, water and mountains, Maine has always lured
artists, among them Winslow Homer, Martin Johnson Heade, Marsden
Hartley, Childe Hassam and Maurice Prendergast. And where there are
artists, there are museums to reap their work. Seven museums have
banded together to form the Maine Art Museum Trail inspired by the
tourist-luring Connecticut Impressionist Art Trail set up by a
group of museums a few years ago. ``Chignon Woman'' (1949), by
Alberto Giacometti at the Portland Museum. (The New York
Times/Portland Museum) Subbing for art piece identificaation
correction
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- CARS-SPONSORS -- Two
California companies are playing Daddy Warbucks, but their
generosity has strings attached: The cars serve as eye-catching
mobile billboards for corporate sponsors. FreeCar Media says it has
given away 30 cars. It plans to have 2,000 cars on the streets by
the end of 2001. Autowraps, a San Francisco-based company, pays
their participants $100 to $400 a month to wrap cars that they
already own. Shad Interligi turns a Chevy Blazer into a Head &AMP;
Shoulders billboard for Autowraps. (Jack Manning/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) WARSAW, Poland -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- POLAND-SOCIALISM -- A
re-creation of a ``milk bar,'' complete down to the ``surly
waitress,'' is one of several installations in a Warsaw exhibition
at the Galeria Zacheta dedicated to the art and culture of the
Communist period, 1956 to 1970, in Poland. The exhibition called,
``Gray in Color: 1956-1970,'' tries to show the life of the period,
that was filled with intellectual and artistic energy and ended
with enormous disillusion. (Alan Chin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) GETTYSBURG, Pa. -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- GETTYSBURG-MUSEUM-2
-- The National Park Service recommends on its Web site that
visitors to the Gettysburg National Military Park spend at least
four hours touring the battlefield and museum, ``though an entire
day is more desirable.'' As understatements go, this is a keeper. A
re-enactment of the final day's assault Gettysburg battlefield, led
by Gen. George E. Pickett. (Salvatore DiMarco Jr./The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- TEN-US-OPEN-4 -- Frenchman
Arnaud Clement upset defending U.S. Open champion Andre Agassi 6-3,
6-2, 6-4 Thursday at the U.S. Open. The top-seeded Agassi, who
completed the career Grand Slam last year and won this year's
Australian Open, failed to get past the second round on the
hardcourts of the National Tennis Center. Agassi signs authographs
as he leaves the court following his defeat. (Ozier Muhammad/The
New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- TEN-US-OPEN-3 -- Frenchman
