<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- NY-LAZIO-FUNDRASING -- Rep.
Rick Lazio may be less known than Hillary Rodham Clinton, his
opponent in the New York Senate contest, but in terms of
fund-raising, he has already vaulted into the major leagues. Lazio
raised $10.7 million in just seven weeks this summer, his aides
said Thursday, leaving no doubt that he will have the means to
fight for the seat despite having entered the race late. Lazio,
left, talks with waiter Fred Morgan about picking up the tab for
his entourage after they had breakfast at Junior's Restaurant in
Brooklyn, Tuesday. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- NY-FOSTER-CARE -- The range
of options available to the privileged; military-style private
schools or private psychiatric treatment; are not readily available
to poor parents with troubled children. So instead, every day,
dozens of children stream into the city's foster care system. A
woman, who refused to be identified, with her son whom she fought
to have returned from foster care. (Chester Higgins Jr./The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) DATONG, China -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- CHINA-DOGMEAT-COX-2 --
Whereas American palates rarely venture beyond the staples, Asians
are far more adventurous diners, enjoying countless dishes that
would make Americans squeamish. In Beijing and many other cities in
China, dog meat is not commonly eaten and is available only at a
few restaurants. Still, in Datong, China, the site of China's
largest Saint Bernard breeding center, and the only one that is
state-run, the famed mountain rescue dog is is being mated with
local dogs to produce mixed-breed dogs that can then be sold for
meat. (Julie Chao/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) DATONG, China -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- CHINA-DOGMEAT-COX-1 --
In Beijing and many other cities in China, dog meat is not commonly
eaten and is available only at a few restaurants. Still, in Datong,
China, the site of China's largest Saint Bernard breeding center,
and the only one that is state-run, the famed mountain rescue dog
is is being mated with local dogs to produce mixed-breed dogs that
can then be sold for meat. So far the farm is only breeding dogs,
not slaughtering them. But plans are in the works to build China's
first large-scale dog meat factory. (Julie Chao/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- COWBOY-GRUB-2-LADN -- The
stampede is on. Texas-style Cowboy cooking has arrived in Los
Angeles in a big way at Reata Restaurant in Beverly Hills which
opened six months ago. A favorite of chef Grady Spears is grilled
strip steak with cilantro butter, with sides of mashed potatoes and
fresh green beans. (David Crane/The Los Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- COWBOY-GRUB-1-LADN -- The
stampede is on. Texas-style Cowboy cooking has arrived in Los
Angeles in a big way at Reata Restaurant in Beverly Hills which
opened six months ago. One of the popular items on the menu is this
entree which includes Ranch Beans, Buttermilk Biscuits and Corn
Bread Muffins. (David Crane/The Los Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- CLINTON-ESTATE-TAX-2 --
Saying the nation's prosperity should not be squandered, President
Clinton on Thursday vetoed a bill to repeal the federal estate tax,
all but assuring a classic election-year showdown over taxcuts and
how best to spend the surplus. Clinton amidst honor guards in the
East Room of the White House after vetoing the bill. (Susana
Raab/The New York Times) NO SALES
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- CLINTON-ESTATE-TAX --
President Clinton speaks with John Sumption during a ceremony at
the White House on Thursday where Clinton vetoed a bill which would
end the federal inheritance tax. Sumption, a farmer in Frederick,
South Dakota, spoke about how the repeal of the tax would benefit
larger farms and businesses. (Susana Raab/The New York Times) NO
SALES
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ARLINGTON, Mass. -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- HOME-MURALIST-BOS
-- Arlington, Mass., artist Joshua Winer studied painting at Yale
and architecture at Harvard, and today is a prominent Boston
muralist and public artist known for his trompe l'oeil decorations
on buildings. In a strange reprise of his childhood, Winer's latest
project will be painting a childhood friends castle in France named
Picomtal, a storybook-like medieval edifice on a hillside in a
small village in the southern Alps. (David L Ryan/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BURLINGTON, Mass. -- Aug. 31, 2000 --
HOME-EXPO-DESIGN-BOS -- Need a bathroom fixture for the ultimate
shower? Then maybe a visit to Expo Design Center is in order. At
this huge new showroom store in Burlington, Mass., the claim is
that customers can find just about everything they possibly could
want for indoor remodeling projects, including ``shower towers,''
whirlpool baths and steam cabinets. Children check out some of the
wares at a public preview of the Expo Design Center created by Home
Depot Inc. to help sustain company growth. (Pam Berry/The Boston
Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- AUTHOR-DANTO-BOS --
Philosophers, at least in theory, are seekers after truth. Truth,
the poet says, is beauty. Thus it makes perfect sense that Arthur
Danto, who philosophizes by day, should moonlight as one of
America's best-known art critics. ``It's been such a joy,'' Danto,
76, says of writing about art. ``I never knew there was anything so
good as that.'' Danto, the award-winning art critic for The Nation
Magazine, with a Brillo box illustration from his 1992 book
``Beyond the Brillo Box,'' in his New York apartment. (Janet
Knott/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- NADER -- Consumer advocate
and Green Party presidential candidate Ralph Nader blitzed
Manhattan on Thursday, bashing General Electric for polluting the
Hudson River, George W. Bush and Al Gore for failing workers and
the city for subsidizing ``corporate welfare.'' Nader adjusts his
seatbelt before heading to a campaign appearance, Thursday. (James
Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NASHVILLE, Tenn. -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- TIRE-LABOR --
Tricia Arnold, center, whose husband works at the local
Bridgestone/Firestone tire plant, during a labor rally outside the
company's headquarters in Nashville, Thursday. Union workers
rallied Thursday as a countdown to what they say is an inevitable
strike this weekend. Bridgestone/Firestone and negotiators for the
International Steelworkers union have been working on a new
contract since March. (Christopher Berkey/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- TEN-US-OPEN -- Once Lindsay
Davenport got her game in gear Thursday, she raced into the third
round of the U.S. Open tennis championships. Davenport reacts to
early frustrations before moving on to defeat 17-year-old Kim
Clijsters of Belgium 4-6, 6-2, 6-2, Thursday. (Ozier Muhammad/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SEATTLE -- Aug. 31, 2000 -- GORE-2 -- Vice President Al
Gore, the Democratic presidential candidate, right, and Sen. Joe
Lieberman, his running mate, look towards downtown Seattle while
riding the ferry across Puget Sound, Thursday. Gore and Lieberman
greeted commuters arriving to Seattle from Baybridge Island across
Puget Sound by ferry on Thursday then got aboard for a ride. Gore
used the occasion to urge additional funding for alternate forms of
mass transit. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
