<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-31 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7781 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-GORE-INTERVIEW-SPI &LR;      08-31 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-INTERVIEW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TAKES ON INSURANCE INDUSTRY, DEFENDS LIEBERMAN IN SEATTLE
VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Vice President Al Gore brought his call for a strong
patients' bill of rights to thousands of cheering supporters at a
downtown Seattle rally Thursday, and in a later interview defended
the right of public officials to discuss their religious beliefs
and to give a human response to ``the emotions of the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has used a four-day swing with vice presidential nominee
Joe Lieberman to hit hard at the issue of health care. But the
Democrats' ticket is also facing questions about Lieberman's strong
profession of his religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore has been dealing with a very public expression of his
own feelings. Comics' barbs, usually directed at his stiffness,
have shifted to ``The Kiss,'' Gore's prolonged buss of wife Tipper
on the closing night of the Democratic Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been asked if I was sending a message: Yes, I was sending
a message to Tipper, and she received it,'' Gore said in the
interview, repeating a line he has been polishing since the
convention ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was overwhelmed with the emotions of the moment,'' he added.
``It was a moment for which Tipper and I worked for many years. I
wanted to share it with her. I just kissed her.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, aside from referring to the Northwest as ``God's
country,'' steered clear of spiritual talk at the rally at Westlake
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The vice presidential nominee, a devout Jew, has spoken freely
of his religious beliefs in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Gore defended him, indicating that personal values were a major
factor in his decision to put the Connecticut senator on the
Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a man of great faith,'' Gore said in the interview. `It
is a faith that motivated him to fight for civil rights in the
1960s, and in the 1990s to protect this country's environment. ...
He and I agree on the separation of church and state.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that ``expression of religious beliefs is protected in
the Constitution, even if you are in public life.'' In American
government, he added, the president must serve as more than just a
political leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our system of government, the president is both head of
state and head of government,'' he said. ``As head of state, the
president has duties that include presenting a vision of the
country's future.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington and other battleground states, Gore is doing a
dicey political walk.
</P>
<P>
   He is claiming credit for America's prosperity while separating
himself from the personal conduct of Bill Clinton, the president he
has loyally served for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman indirectly pointed out differences between Gore and
Clinton in a succession of carefully worded sentences at the rally.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Al and Tipper Gore have been married for 30 years,
and described the Gores' life as ``anchored in faith.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is not an award for past performance,'' Gore
declared as he took the microphone. He ticked off goals of a
Gore-Lieberman administration: ``Attack global warming. Reduce
pollution. Stop sprawl. ... Get guns out of the hands of kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic ticket, appearing on a workday, drew far fewer
people than the throng of 15,000 that greeted Bill Clinton on a hot
July Saturday in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton crowd was largely curious. The rally Thursday
consisted largely of party faithful, including many union
activists.
</P>
<P>
   At times, chants of ``Let Ralph Debate!'' could be heard from a
small group of Ralph Nader supporters, kept beyond the fences.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats sounded populist themes Thursday, with America's
insurance companies taking a pounding at the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing for a patients' bill of rights, Gore declared that
medical decisions should not be made by ``some bean counter sitting
behind a computer terminal who doesn't have a license to practice
medicine and a right to play God.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman told of meeting an elderly stroke victim in San Diego,
forced to use a walker because a managed care provider had refused
to pay for medicine that would have relieved his pain.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gary Locke, preceding Gore and Lieberman, made a mocking
reference to ``insurance company CEOs and numbers crunchers.''
American Nurses Assn. president Mary Foley, whose union endorsed
Gore Thursday, added: ``Treatment decisions should be made by
health professionals, not insurance bureaucrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has renounced the traditional partisan hit-man role of
a vice presidential nominee. Thursday, however, he showed that he
can go after a foe with words of admonishment.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party began airing a TV spot in 17 states that
questions Gore's credibility. It shows his 1996 fund-raising visit
to a Buddhist temple in Los Angeles, and Gore's statement that he
took the lead in inventing the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Al Gore reinventing himself,'' says an announcer.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman argued that the ``politically negative personal attack
ads'' violate GOP nominee George W. Bush's promise not to launch
such TV assaults.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sad to say, George Bush has changed his tune about changing
the tone (of the campaign),'' Lieberman told the Westlake rally.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, Gore and Lieberman engaged in what has become a
election-eve ritual for many Washington state politicians _ shaking
hands at a ferry terminal, and riding with commuters to and from
Bainbridge Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is mass transit in Seattle,'' Gore joked of the commute
by boat.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president entered the coffee shop aboard the Wenatchee
and aksed: ``Is there any unhealthy breakfast food here?''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Siddons, who was traveling to Bainbridge, asked Gore what
he would do to restore salmon to the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The salmon represent the linchpin of this whole region's
balance between the economy and the environment,'' Gore said. ``The
focus on the salmon works for everybody because when you do the
right thing, (you) keep the economy strong, and keep the
environment healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Siddons described himself as a likely Gore voter,
saying: ``His response was helful to me. At least he knows what's
going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in the interview, Gore reiterated his pledge to hold a
regionwide ``salmon summit'' early in his administration to work
out a program to restore salmon runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to bring all parties together,'' he said. ``I intend to
consult first before deciding where and when.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting would be patterned after the 1993 Northwest forestry
summit, at which Clinton and Gore spent a day hearing from all
sides on the future of the region's old-growth forests. It produced
a plan that reduced national forest logging by more than 80
percent, but allowed some cutting to go ahead.
</P>
<P>
   As president, Gore added, he will hold town meetings around the
country on a variety of topics, as a device to stay in contact with
``the person on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president promised never to let the majesty of the
nation's highest office turn his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had the opportunity to see that job from a close-up
viewpoint,'' he said. ``I think I have some immunity from the
trappings of the office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
