<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOFTBALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. HEAVY FAVORITE FOR SOFTBALL GOLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Over the past 10 years, the United States women's
softball team has lost just five games in international
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Four of those losses have been against Australia.
</P>
<P>
   It's an obvious source of concern for the Americans as they
prepare for the 2000 Olympics in ... Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 Atlanta games, Australia spoiled U.S. pitcher Lisa
Fernandez's perfect game when Joanne Brown smashed a two-strike,
two- run homer to beat the Americans in the opening round. The
Americans regrouped to win the gold in Atlanta, but the memory of
that loss lingers. The fact they'll face Australia on its home soil
makes the loss even more significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I live with everyday,'' said Fernandez, who
sobbed after the `96 loss. ``After I'd given up the home run and we
win the gold medal and everything's fine, and you think it's over
and you're ready to move on. Then the postcard comes around
Thanksgiving, and it brings up a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the postcard. Four months after the Americans won the gold
medal in Atlanta, Fernandez got a postcard - postmarked from
Australia - with a picture of Brown waving a flag and riding the
shoulders of her teammates after hitting the home run to beat
Fernandez and the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it was someone on the team or a fan,''
Fernandez said. ``But it was someone obviously trying to stick a
knife just a little bit deeper into an open wound. I felt
definitely as if it were a personal attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Fernandez and the U.S. will use the loss, the
postcard and the fact that they'll have to win the gold away from
the United States as motivation in Sydney. Obviously, Fernandez is
prepared. During a pre-Olympic tour she pitched five consecutive
perfect games, and in the fifth she struck out all 21 batters.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, who are closing in on a 100-game winning streak,
were dominant during the tour, outscoring their opponents 364-3 in
the first 51 games.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Americans take anything for granted. Certainly they
are favorites to win the gold in Sydney, but as the Australians
proved in 1996, the U.S. is by no means unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-team tournament is more balanced than four years ago,
and each team has made significant improvements. In addition to the
U.S. and Australia, the rest of the field consists of Japan, China,
Canada, Cuba, Italy and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all have, in their minds, the feeling that they are
improving,'' U.S. second baseman Dot Richardson said. ``As usual,
every country guns for us. That's the way we've always had it, and
the way we want it. We actually welcome the challenge. It's easy to
get to the top. The true challenge is staying there.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan is a threat because it plays solid defense, and China lost
two one-run games to the U.S. before falling 3-1 in the gold-medal
game in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And of course there's the Australians, who have emerged as the
biggest threat to the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the U.S. is favored to repeat. Fernandez is the
best player in the world, and shortstop Crystl Bustos (Canyon High)
is quickly catching up, using her potent bat and spectacular
strength to pound opposing pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable power,'' Fernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   At catcher, UCLA standout Stacey Nuveman is a remarkable
defensive player and a solid hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge for the U.S. might be playing in front of
8,000 Australian fanatics when the two countries square off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're actually looking forward to being in a hostile
environment,'' Fernandez said. ``To have fans booing you and you
throw the first pitch 80 mph. There's nothing better than hearing
the silence of the crowd. That's something that internally lights
out fire.''
</P>
<P>
   ships, the Pan American Games and the 1996 Olympics.!dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
