<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSUN FACES UNCERTAIN FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- There are no visible signs. Nothing you can see.
Nothing you can feel. Still, you know they're there.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of NCAA sanctions imposed on the Cal State
Northridge football program in June linger, even though those
associated with the program say it's not something they talk about
much.
</P>
<P>
   And probation is just the beginning. Many more impending changes
are in store for CSUN, changes that leave people wondering what the
future holds for the Matadors football program.
</P>
<P>
   The team's home - North Campus Stadium - is scheduled to be
demolished after the season and CSUN is scheduled to play at Pierce
College for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   This season is CSUN's farewell tour in the Big Sky Conference.
The Matadors move to the Big West - a conference without football -
next year.
</P>
<P>
   An independent schedule in a foreign stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the same thing everybody else sees,'' linebacker Cos
Abercrombie said. ``They're taking the stadium away. We do wonder
what the program is going to be like down the line. But I know
there will be a season this year. I live for today.''
</P>
<P>
   And today, there is football. But what about next season? Or the
season after?
</P>
<P>
   CSUN has contracts for games with UC Davis, Sacramento State,
Cal Poly San Luis Obispo and Southwest Texas State for 2001.
Matadors coach Jeff Kearin is filling the rest of the schedule,
which will include a game against a Division I-A opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, CSUN has a contract with UC Davis though 2003, and
Sacramento State and Cal Poly San Luis Obispo probably will be
regulars on the schedule, too.
</P>
<P>
   Athletic director Dick Dull said he doesn't want people to read
anything into the fact CSUN has yet to fill its schedule for next
season. He said it's never booked this far in advance.
</P>
<P>
   And he doesn't believe a stadium is the key to any program.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take the ball as it lays,'' Dull said. ``That's
our situation. It's not a perfect world. What's more important is
not where they play but the people that direct this program. They
look at Jeff Kearin and say that overrides the 'Hey, maybe we don't
have a big, beautiful stadium.'
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always more important than facilities, from my
vantage point.''
</P>
<P>
   A new stadium has been discussed for years, but no decisions
have been made. Other facilities are taking precedence, according
to Dull.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't sat down and specifically come up witha game plan
(for a stadium),'' Dull said. ``There are other facilities I have
in the short-term that are more important than the football
stadium. The reason is we have a safety valve with Pierce College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more concerned about making changes to the baseball
stadium - it's really not adequate - and (changes) for softball and
the seating at The Matadome (CSUN's gym). Those are the priorities.
It doesn't mean we've given up on the football stadium, but we have
another set of priorities that I'm going to address.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN plans to add seats to the gym (which has a capacity of
1,600) to keep in line with other Big West schools. Dull hopes to
have another 850 seats or so in place (on the upper level of one
side) by the time the basketball season opens.
</P>
<P>
   Even if CSUN had plans for a football stadium, major issues
would remain, such as financing and location. Again, all this
remains in the discussion stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly a general commitment to talk about what it
is we need,'' CSUN president Jolene Koester said. ``I don't have,
in my drawer, plans. I also want to affirm we have a commitment to
look at what it is we need.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearin, always the optimist, doesn't appear to be upset about
the stadium. He's operating under the assumption that Pierce will
be his team's new home, although he's heard talk the Matadors might
play at North Campus Stadium for another season.
</P>
<P>
   If Kearin's worried about anything, it's not where his team will
play on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy,'' Kearin said. ``We just want to play. Probably
the bigger question is where we're going to practice. People here
are working on that.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN practices on a field adjacent to the stadium that also is
on the site where the MiniMed biotechnology project is being
constructed.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty over stadium plans undoubtedly will scare away
some recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you where (the stadium) hurts us is recruiting,''
senior receiver Gil Rodriguez said. ``When you don't have a
stadium, you have to find guys who aren't interested in looks and
big money. When you see this stadium, you've gotta find players who
want to play football. Guys who play with heart.''
</P>
<P>
   And players who aren't scared off by ever-present rumors that
the athletic department will drop football.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty difficult to respond to rumors,'' Koester said.
``A rumor is a rumor. And universities like all complex
organizations are filled with rumors. I respond to it substantively
by saying that we're playing football and we're setting up a
schedule for next year. I look at football in context of the entire
intercollegiate athletic program. We're playing football. What can
I say?''
</P>
<P>
   But the rumor of the program's demise persists. For example, a
couple of players said other schools made reference to it on
recruiting visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people ask me about it,'' fullback Crayton Milton
said. ``I try not to think about it. I hope (the program) doesn't
end. As long as the program is here, I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Rodriguez: ``For the guys that have been here three or
four years - myself and others - we're used to it. Every year
there's talk about cutting football and demolishing the stadium.
This year it's another setback - not letting us go to the playoffs
(if they win the conference title because of probation).''
</P>
<P>
   As an independent, CSUN will not be required to offer 55
scholarships, as it is now in the Big Sky. University officials
haven't said whether they'll cut back for the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   That, along with the direction of the program, is something CSUN
will address this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there needs to be dialogue with interested
constituents about football, the level of football we want and
direction from the new president,'' Dull said. ``I'm not in a
position to drop sports and add them.... We haven't begun the
dialogue of football after 2001.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
