<HEADLINE>
NAVRATILOVA HAS FANS, BUT A TEST IS LOOMING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  By SOPHIA HOLLANDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Martina Navratilova and Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario
advanced to the second round in women's doubles Thursday with a
dramatic victory over Sabine Appelmans and Linda Wild, 5-7, 6-2,
7-6 (3), before an overflowed crowd on the Grandstand Court.
</P>
<P>
   Only organ music was missing as it seemed the spirit had seeped
across the boardwalk from Shea Stadium. The spectators became
rowdier and and more emphatic after each point, leaping to their
feet and four times bursting into rhythmic clapping that strongly
implied a ``Let's Go, Marty'' chant.
</P>
<P>
   Even the scoreboard was swept away. `Nice Work Guys!!!' it
blared after match point, as fans stood whistling and clapping
furiously, while Navratilova and Sanchez-Vicario embraced.
</P>
<P>
   Navratilova turned to the crowd, raising her hand, then patted
it over her heart. That was close.
</P>
<P>
   With the crowd so overwhelmingly against them, Appelmans and
Wild could only shake their heads and smile. But fan loyalties will
be sorely tested in the second round, when Navratilova and
Sanchez-Vicario take on the popular 14th-seeded team of Jennifer
Capriati and Anna Kournikova.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat Suits Her
</P>
<P>
   Lilia Osterloh used to stand in her back yard in Canal
Winchester, Ohio, and hit tennis ball after ball off the side of
her family's garage. Though her parents played recreationally and
her sister competed at DePaul, she was captivated by the images
playing across her television, by Chris Evert and Martina
Navratilova as they danced across courts and powered past
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   One day, she said to herself, that will be me.
</P>
<P>
   Now she is ranked 57th in the world and playing in her fifth
straight U.S. Open. Thursday, she upset 14th-seeded Dominique Van
Roost, who retired because of heat illness even though she had won
second set, 6-3. Osterloh won the tight first set, 7-6 (7).
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Osterloh advanced to the fourth round at
Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my third year on the tour, and I really want to make the
jump to the top 50,'' said Osterloh, 22, who won the 1997
collegiate singles title in her one year at Stanford before turning
pro.
</P>
<P>
   She said that her victory against Van Roost was an important
step, but was clearly uncomfortable with the way she won.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the second set, I was like, `OK, let's battle it out,'''
Osterloh said, frowning slightly. ``I noticed her face was really
red. But it was really humid out. I didn't know it was that
severe.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunlight seared through haze in the Grandstand, as the smell of
sunscreen wafted onto the court. After the second set, a flushed
Van Roost disappeared down the ramp for what appeared to be a
bathroom break. She would not play again, withdrawing from the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heat felt pretty brutal,'' Osterloh said. But, she added,
``I like the heat, even though I grew up in Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she will have a chance to play in it more.
</P>
<P>
   Hard Feelings
</P>
<P>
   An emotional and slightly defensive Billie Jean King spoke about
her decision to leave the No. 1 doubles player, Lisa Raymond, off
the Olympic team in favor of Serena Williams, who has no doubles
ranking.
</P>
<P>
   At a morning news conference regarding the U.S. Olympic teams,
King discussed the saga that began when she selected the top four
singles players for the U.S. team _ Lindsay Davenport, Monica
Seles, Venus Williams and Serena Williams _ instead of following
the recent Olympic tradition of picking the top doubles player for
the fourth position. Raymond challenged the decision but lost in
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have known Lisa since she was 12 years old,'' said King, who
seemed to be on the verge of crying several times. ``I absolutely
adore Lisa. This was probably the most difficult call I ever made,
definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning her singles match in the afternoon, Raymond
discussed the mentoring role King had played in her life. For
Raymond, King's decision was a personal and a professional
betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   The two have not had a conversation since King called Raymond
after Wimbledon to tell her she had been left off the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very frustrated, angry, very disappointed, both in Billie
and the USTA,'' said Raymond, who breezed through her second-round
match against Ruxandra Dragomir, 6-4, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   King said: ``It's been very painful. I think I went through a
lot of anxiety and pain about it, trying to figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   But she defended her selection and insisted that she had fought
for Raymond, first by lobbying unsuccessfully to have the Women's
Tennis Association vote in favor of counting Olympic matches in
ranking, which would have allowed the women to take more than four
players, and then by approaching the International Tennis
Federation twice, asking the sport's international governing body
to make a special allowance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made an incredible effort to try to make it happen,'' King
said. ``We were unable to.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
