<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD CLOSE TO COMING BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ The Los Angeles Dodgers leaned on left fielder Gary
Sheffield for most of the season and were one game over .500.
Illness and suspension cost Sheffield the past 11 games, but it
brought the Dodgers eight wins.
</P>
<P>
   The end of Sheffield's inactivity is close. But after his first
workout since becoming ill Aug. 22, he wasn't ready to say he would
return to the lineup today, when the Dodgers begin a three-game
series with Philadelphia at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm going to return, that's undetermined,'' Sheffield
said via telephone after working out at Dodger Stadium. ``It'll
probably be when I'm feeling like I can go score from first on a
hit and I can get in the outfield and chase two fly balls down. I'm
not that far away. About a day or two, though I should be fine
after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield said he felt as good as can be expected after the
workout, though he added he's not yet 100 percent. He played catch
for five to 10 minutes and took batting practice for approximately
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a little better,'' Sheffield said. ``Right now I'm just
getting over the aftermath to get right back in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The viral infection has cost Sheffield a chance at the National
League home run crown, but he doesn't care about that. He cares
about winning, and in his absence the Dodgers played solid ball, at
one time winning eight of nine games.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Dodgers lost their past two games and lost much of
the ground they had made up. They are seven games behind San
Francisco in the West with 28 to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched all the games on TV,'' Sheffield said. ``It seemed
like they were playing with passion and with something on the line.
Unfortunately, we have a long ways to go to catch the other teams
ahead of us. Even with the way we were playing, other teams were
winning also.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sheffield's presence should give the Dodgers a jolt. When he
took ill, he was batting .331 and was one homer behind Chicago's
Sammy Sosa at 40 for the league lead. He entered Thursday trailing
Sosa by five and tied with Houston's Jeff Bagwell for second.
Sheffield's 96 RBI are one fewer than Eric Karros for the team
lead.
</P>
<P>
   It'll take time for Sheffield to return to full health - he's
lost about 10 pounds - but manager Davey Johnson said he'll use him
as much as possible. The Dodgers average 5.16 runs per game. They
went 8-3 without Sheffield, and scored 5.55 runs per game in his
absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll get him out of there in the eighth with a lead,'' Johnson
said. ``Sometimes you get guys in the lineup who will count on him,
and he's always doing it. But when he's not there, the other guys
are like, 'Well, I have to do it.' That's the way they have to feel
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Who's in left?: Want a quick synopsis of the Dodgers'
minor-league system? They have no maneuverability on their 40-man
roster and no outfielders ready to contribute at the major-league
level. So, with Sheffield ill and Devon White and Bruce Aven
injured, the Dodgers were left with a sizable gap in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Enter infielder Dave Hansen, who saw emergency action in left
field Friday in Chicago. He started in the outfield for the first
time in his eight-year major-league career Thursday and had three
hits.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen, who played outfield in rookie ball, has started three
games at first and eight games at third this season. With rosters
being expanded today, the Dodgers have no plans to recall an
outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Center fielder Devon White pinch hit Wednesday,
but ran gingerly down the first-base line and said Thursday he
thought he was a few days from being able to play in center field
and handle the defensive load. ... The Dodgers are expected to
recall catcher Paul LoDuca and left-hander Onan Masaoka from
Triple-A Albuquerque and right-hander Luke Prokopec from Double-A
San Antonio as rosters expand to 40 today. Infielder Chris Donnels
is also slated to be activated from the disabled list.
</P>
</TEXT>
