<SLUG> BC-EMULAX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT ARRESTED IN NEWS RELEASE FRAUD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Staff Writer Robert Monroe contributed to this story) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A former employee of an Internet news release
distributor was arrested Thursday, accused of fabricating a news
release that caused a technology company to lose $2.2 billion in
market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities identified the suspect as Mark Simeon Jakob,
23, of El Segundo, Calif., had been an employee of Internet Wire
until a week before the phony release about Emulex Corp. was sent
to Internet Wire for distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Jakob, who had left the Internet Wire on good terms a week
before the announcement, was arrested at his home about 7 a.m. The
investigation continues.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Alejandro Mayorkas said Jakob earned more than
$240,000 from his scheme and has been charged with securities and
wire fraud. If convicted, he faces up to 15 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In a simultaneous action Thursday morning, the U.S. Securities
and Exchange Commission filed a civil lawsuit that seeks to freeze
Jakob's assets, including bank and brokerage accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Jakob is believed to have used a computer at El Camino Community
College in Torrance, Calif., where he was a student, to send the
bogus news release.
</P>
<P>
   While an employee of the Los Angeles-based company, Jakob's job
was to receive press releases from companies and post them on the
Internet Wire Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used his knowledge of Internet Wire to get the release
circulated, not to get back at the company,'' Mayorkas said.
</P>
<P>
   The hoax started with an e-mail sent late last Aug. 24 to
Internet Wire. The notice was widely reported by Bloomberg News,
CBS MarketWatch and other news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The release appeared to be an Emulex announcement that Paul
Folino had resigned as chief executive officer, that the company's
recently reported fourth-quarter results were going to be restated
and that Emulex was under investigation by the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Caproni, the SEC's regional director, said Jakob
borrowed and sold 3,000 Emulex shares on Aug. 17 and 18 at about
$80 per share, hoping to profit by repurchasing the shares at a
lower price.
</P>
<P>
   By Aug. 24, the stock had risen to $113.063, leaving him with
$97,000 in losses. Later that evening, Caproni said Jakob used a
personal computer at the college library to issue the false press
release.
</P>
<P>
   When the Costa Mesa-based company's shares fell 62 percent the
next day based on the false information, Jakob covered his short
position, earning $55,000 and later purchasing 3,500 shares, which
he sold Monday after the stock had rebounded, earning $186,000.
</P>
<P>
   In approximately 16 minutes of trading, 2.3 million Emulex
shares were traded, and the price of the company's stock dropped to
$43 before Nasdaq officials halted trading.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, which resumed trading about three hours later,
recovered to close at $105.75, down $7.313.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a significant increase in the trading volume of
Emulex stock, and many individual traders experienced significant
losses as they sold shares at prices significantly lower than their
purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators traced Jakob by following a trail of electronic
``footprints'' left by the e-mail he sent to Internet Wire. The
trail led FBI investigators to a personal computer at the library
that he had been using, Mayorkas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within several hours of the incident, he was identified,''
said Mayorkas. ``He created the bad news, causing the stock to fall
to cover his losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayorkas warned other investors looking to get rich quick that
they cannot count on the anonymity of the Internet to serve as a
shield for their illegal conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of electronic terrorism cannot be tolerated,'' said
Paul Folino, president and chief executive officer of Emulex, in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quick results from this cooperative effort demonstrate to
others contemplating a similar hoax that the outcome to be expected
is immediate apprehension and prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies have also seen their stock price manipulated by
false information released online.
</P>
<P>
   Caproni said there have been four such incidents, including this
one, in the last 18 months. They involved two Orange County firms,
PairGain Technologies and Bid.com, and Lucent Technologies of
Murray Hill, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is a great tool for investors,'' she said. ``We
will not allow it to become a deadly weapon for those who want to
use it to harm the markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet Wire, a 6-year-old distributor of press releases, says
on its Web site that it serves more than 2,500 clients and is
backed by two of the largest Silicon Valley venture capital firms.
</P>
<P>
   Sequoia Capital and Hummer Winblad Venture Partners are among
the investors in a first round of funding that closed in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet Wire is pleased that the investigation has progressed
so quickly and will continue to cooperate with with the
authorities,'' the company said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Competing press release distributors distanced themselves from
Internet Wire, stressing their source verification standards while
one academic marveled at what he called a high-tech story of
gullibility.
</P>
<P>
   Renu Aldrich, spokeswoman for PRNewswire, a 46-year-old wire
service, said the company has received numerous calls from clients
worried that they could be forced to endure such roller coaster
rides. She said that PRNewswire distributed an announcement to its
clients this week that outline its verification policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be stained by this incident,'' said Aldrich,
who called hers a ``completely different kind of company than
Internet Wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the standards and expertise to ensure that this
doesn't happen,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A. Michael Noll, an Internet watcher and professor at the
University of Southern California's Annenberg School for
Communication, said Jakob's alleged fraud is merely the latest
instance of people irrationally believing sky-is-falling style
rumors.
</P>
<P>
   The difference now is how fast those rumors spread, causing
investors to dump Emulex stocks within minutes of the press
release's appearance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tendency to believe if the computer screen says two
plus two is five, it must be true,'' Noll said. ``It's very scary
the extent to which people fall for these kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Emulex gained $4.188, or 4.1 percent, to close
Thursday at $104.688 on moderate volume of 1,847,900 shares traded
on the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   xxx
</P>
</TEXT>
