A7960 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN     08-31 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIELD HAD EARLY TEST AT ALABAMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Bob Field finished his senior season at
Arkansas in 1970, he walked into the office of coach Frank Broyles
and told him he wanted to become a coach. Broyles asked Field, now
the UCLA defensive coordinator, who he'd like to work for and the
young man didn't hesitate: Bear Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He chuckled,'' Field said of Broyles. ``He said, 'I'll give
you credit for this: you set your goals high.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Broyles went to a national coaching convention the next week and
when he checked in, there was a message from Bryant asking whether
Broyles knew of any young assistants in his program who would be
interested in coaching at Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like an answer to a prayer,'' said Field, who
spent the next two years as a graduate assistant under Bryant,
working with assistants like John David Crow, Pat Dye, Danny Ford
and Bill Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an amazing experience. Coach Bryant was extremely
knowledgeable and a great motivator of individuals and teams. He
expected the same of everybody who played for him or coached for
him, whether you were a walk-on or an All-American or a graduate
assistant or a coordinator.''
</P>
<P>
   Check the pompons at the door: At the start of most major
sporting events, a directive is usually given to the media: No
cheering in the press box.
</P>
<P>
   This could be difficult for ABC-TV analyst Tim Brant, who will
be working the UCLA-Alabama game Saturday with Keith Jackson. Brant
also happens to be the father of Kevin Brant, a UCLA freshman
strong safety who will be in on the Bruins' kickoff and punt return
units.
</P>
<P>
   This won't be Bob Griese choking up when his son Brian led
Michigan to a Rose Bowl win, but it's something father and son are
looking forward to since Tim's work schedule allowed him to see
only one of Kevin's high school games in their hometown of
Bethesda, Md. Tim could work as many as five UCLA games this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to block it out that he's out there,'' said Tim,
who was at practice Thursday. ``If I have to mention him, I'll
probably be harder on him than anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he'll be professional,'' Kevin said. ``Hopefully,
I'll make a few plays and give him something to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   BYU Dreamin': Alabama quarterbacks coach Charlie Stubbs, a
former offensive coordinator at Oregon State in the late `80s, is
one in a long line of candidates for the BYU coaching job after
LaVell Edwards retires at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Bears offensive coordinator Gary Crowton is the
front-runner and Cal coach Tom Holmoe is a strong candidate, but if
Alabama contends for a national title, Stubbs knows it won't hurt
his chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the school and I share the same (religion),'' said
Stubbs, a Mormon who graduated and coached at BYU. ``I know it's
something that's out there, but this is Coach Edwards' year to have
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Webbs tangled: Fifth-year senior Micah Webb, who was expected to
provide veteran depth in the offensive line, has quit the team
because of chronic shoulder problems. His twin brother Josh, also
an offensive lineman, still hasn't recovered from offseason surgery
on both shoulders and his playing status is in doubt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
