<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-BREWERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SLIP BACK AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ It's the first day of September, the day postseason
rosters are set. By all rights, it should be a meaningful day for a
team which has been revamped twice in the past two years at a cost
of $98 million - its payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, after the Los Angeles Dodgers lost to Milwaukee 8-2
Thursday at County Stadium, they're faced with this grim reality:
Any headway they made by starting out a road trip with five wins in
six games was simply tossed away with a pair of losses to the
Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers turned a week of optimism that bred faint hope into
the fact they made up a half game in the standings and another week
has passed.
</P>
<P>
   The latest bit of ugliness, or reality, was the wretched return
of Carlos Perez to the starting rotation. He then gave up six runs
on seven hits in two-plus innings and again made folks wonder just
why he's in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   And it could get worse today since the Dodgers send right-hander
Ismael Valdes, who's 0-2 with a 7.33 ERA since returning to the
Dodgers in late July, out to start against Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as August turned into September and the Dodgers tried to
re-introduce themselves as playoff hopefuls, they sent Perez to the
mound one day and will send Valdes on the next. The two of them are
a combined 7-13 with a 5.61 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys are looking for me to go to a four-man (rotation),''
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``I'm looking to find who my
fourth man would be. I need them to stand up.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez was put back in the rotation partly because he pitched
well in relief, partly because the Dodgers need Matt Herges in the
bullpen, partly because Herges wasn't stellar in four starts, but
mostly because he has a contract that pays him $7.5 million next
season.
</P>
<P>
   For that money, the Dodgers have been willing to give Perez more
chances in the last two seasons than most players get in a career,
namely because they want a return on their investment at some
point.
</P>
<P>
   But after going 0-0 with a 1.78 ERA in relief, and after
allowing one run in 6 innings in a spot start last Friday in
Chicago, the crapshoot that is a Carlos Perez start continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt a little stiff,'' said Perez, who started last
Friday and relieved Sunday. ``I missed the location a lot of times,
and when you miss location some people are going to hit the ball. I
was, most of the time, behind in the count.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez allowed a solo homer to USC product Geoff Jenkins and an
RBI double to Jeromy Burnitz as Milwaukee went ahead 2-1 in the
first.
</P>
<P>
   After an uneventful second inning, Perez was knocked from the
game without recording an out in the third. Mark Loretta led off
with a walk, which was followed by four hits. Herges relieved and
yielded a one-out, two-run single to Luis Lopez as the Brewers took
a 6-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes (Perez) goes out there and pitches great and other
times he goes out there and gets in trouble and can't get out,''
Johnson said. ``We didn't get much offense, but usually when you
fall behind like that it's tough to crank it up.''
</P>
<P>
   And while a mountain of pressure is being heaped upon Johnson's
shoulders, not only is he sending Perez and Valdes out on
back-to-back days to start, the minor-league system is also barren.
So much so that infielder Dave Hansen was asked to play left field
because Devon White and Bruce Aven are injured and Gary Sheffield
remained in Los Angeles, trying to kick a viral infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were doing pretty good (on the trip),'' Hansen said.
``Their guy (Paul Rigdon) kept us off balance and did a nice job.
Our energy was there at the beginning. That guy just got some big
outs. We'll take this time on the (flight) back to focus on where
we need to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
